1. Z0 {‘Your only goal in the opening is to reach a playable middlegame’ - Lajos PortischIn today’s computer era, following the wise advice of the old master proves to be the most sensible approach. Since the height of Kasparov’s reign twenty years ago, getting an objective advantage out of the opening is of the utmost importance. Top players study and analyse main lines to incredible depths, with the assistance of experienced seconds and powerful machines. Some of the openings that were at the forefront of theoretical battles are the Marshall Ruy Lopez, Najdorf Poisoned Pawn, Botvinnik Slav, etc. The forcing nature of these variations means that some of them have literally been analysed “to death” - that is, to an extent when no major discoveries can be made anymore. As a consequence, players began searching for less explored options - finding the “blue ocean” of chess openings.} ({In the same spirit, we explore the Horwitz Attack,} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 {, a rich variation that belongs to the Wild West category of chess openings. White prepares the fianchetto of the queen’s bishop and creates a dynamic battle for the center. You have here the most comprehensive resource available on the Horwitz attack. We present moves and concepts that are both off the beaten path and outside of theory but also provide a solid and sound foundation of plans and themes. After studying this course, you will have a great weapon to combat the French Defence. The journey started in August 2021 - and is by no means over - when we teamed up for this project. It took two whopping years, but finally, by the time you read these words, we are proud that our work has borne fruit. We sincerely hope you will enjoy this course and have a lot of success with the “Wild West” Horwitz Attack! Thank you! Banh Gia Huy and MakkaPakka}) *

