{In this informational we will discuss the structure of the course: what is in each section/chapter, different ways in which you could use the course, etc. Perhaps it will be of use to you, or maybe you will skip it. Your choice!} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 {After reading this Introduction chapter, we have the Quickstarter Guide. In this chapter, we handpicked 14 variations from within the course, with the intent to get you playing the Horwitz Attack as soon as possible! Simply studying our lines is not enough for true mastery of the Horwitz, and it’s important you practice playing our lines in real games. You should not have to study the entire course before playing our lines, and instead, you can quickly learn the Quickstarter and start playing the Horwitz in your games, while simultaneously learning the rest of the course in more detail. For the majority of readers, merely studying the Quickstarter guide will put you far ahead of your opponents with a bit of practice. But we hope you choose to do more :). Moving on, the course is split into three sections, the Open Horwitz, the Closed Horwitz, and Early Deviations. The Open Horwitz is characterised by 1.e4 e6 2.b3 d5 3.Bb2 dxe4 , while the Closed Horwitz arises after 1.e4 e6 2.b3 d5 Bb2 Nf6 , and the Early Deviations section consists of everything else. If you would like more detail, each of these sections are preceded by an Introduction chapter, which we strongly recommend looking at before beginning the theory. In fact, you could even choose to go ahead and look at the Overview of recommendations in each of these Introduction chapters right away, before looking at the Quickstarter Guide. Note that these Intro chapters are not marked as priority - more on this in the next informational - so if you are on Priority mode you will have to temporarily turn off Priority mode to study them. You will see what exactly is in these three Intro chapters soon enough so we won’t go into detail here. However we should mention that they do include key themes, puzzles, and model games, for those of you who were concerned that these wouldn’t exist upon seeing the chapter list! We prefer this approach instead of bunching them all up in one chapter, so you can see the ideas together in one section and in what types of positions they are relevant. It is also part of the learning process, and theory + ideas shouldn’t be split up into two sections where you only do one at a time, neither can exist without the other and should be learnt in synchrony together. At least that’s what we believe :). It should be mentioned that due to the diversity of early deviations, there aren't key themes or model games for this section. Considering how unlikely it is that you will get these, it would be unproductive to analyse themes/model games for each and every one of the possible early deviations. Nonetheless, this was no excuse to slack off in the chapters and we provided our usual quality there, which hopefully by then you will be convinced is high :). We are open to discussion, criticism, and change in this course. We look forward to your feedback, be it praise or condemnation!} *

