1. Z0 {In this informational we will briefly discuss some of the different approaches you can take with this course with some options we have facilitated. We will not go into detail on reviewing lines, perfect chessable settings, etc., as that is outside the scope of this course. Instead we’ll focus on how you could prioritise your time with this course. ~ 1. A Quickstarter Based Approach ~ First of all, we understand that you may not have the time/need to learn almost 200 trainable lines on just responding to the French. As discussed, we have the Quickstarter Guide, consisting of 14 variations, to get you going. Some users could choose to just learn the Quickstarter inside out, and be done with this course, just keeping this course as a reference material. We personally, especially for such a short Quickstarter, recommend going further than this as otherwise you could face a few surprises in your games - this is part of Black's job after all! Instead, you could study the Quickstarter in detail but also briefly look through other chapters in the course (in read mode perhaps) , prioritising breadth over depth. This way you add many new ideas to your toolbox and become more prepared, without dedicating too much more time. However, if you do choose to stick to the approach as outlined in the first paragraph, we at least recommend looking at each of the three Introduction chapters and paying close attention to them. And most importantly, don’t archive and forget this course, but upon finishing a Horwitz game check your opening against what is recommended in the course, and hopefully you will learn something new! ~ 2. A Priority Lines Based Approach ~ Next, there will be others who are still limited in time/need for the full course, but want to go into more detail than the Quickstarter - in terms of concrete moves and not just ideas, as above. For this purpose, we have selected approximately a third of the most important and frequently appearing lines in the course and marked them as ‘Priority’. There is an option in course settings to study only the Priority lines. We expect the most common approach to be to only use the Chessable Movetrainer on Priority lines and use the rest of the course as reference material, as described above. However, if you do this, we still believe it to be important that you look at the three Introduction chapters for some useful ideas and overviews. ~ 3. Eating the Whole Elephant ~ Of course, there will exist the true Horwitz connoisseurs who bravely study the full course, and will join us as part of an elite group of precious few experts on this wonderful opening. French Defence players will fear these people (and rightly so!) and those who achieve this status should definitely reach out to us. This approach could be for those who are higher rated, want to be fully booked up against the French, love this opening, or just enjoy studying on chessable! Those who go this far will probably choose their own way of studying, but we propose a layered approach. By this, we mean you should first study the Quickstarter as mentioned earlier, then the Priority lines as mentioned above, and only then going through the rest of the course. This is our reasoning: if you go through the course chapter by chapter, while playing the Horwitz in games (and it is important you do to truly master it) , you could have finished both the Open and Closed Horwitz sections and know them inside-out, but then someone could spring a Papoo on you (a big theoretical challenge) and without our lines it is likely you will exit the opening with a subpar position. On the other hand, with a layered approach, you would have already studied the Quickstarter/Priority lines on the Papoo and will have a great idea of what to do and probably know it better than your opponent, even without looking at the whole chapter yet. These are just three of the best approaches you could take. Ultimately, it is your choice and others will be chosen by some (such as using the whole thing as a reference tool, or even forgetting all about the course and letting it collect lint in your virtual bookshelf – but better than not getting it at all!) , but nonetheless hopefully this informational was of some use!} *

