{Welcome to the Repertoire Clash! In this file, we address the recommendation of authors writing from Black's point of view, against the Horwitz Attack. If we fail to mention a specific resource, do let us know!} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 (2... b6 {is proposed by GM John Watson in his book 'Play the French'.} 3. Bb2 Bb7 4. Nc3 c5 {and here we recommend white players to open up the position immediately with} 5. d4 $5 {White has a promising Sicilian structure, as we explain here [/variation/22844366].}) 3. Bb2 dxe4 (3... Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 {This simple move passed unmentioned in the book 'Attacking Chess: The French' by Simon 'GingerGM' Williams.} c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 $1 {The key concept against the Closed Horwitz, which you will learn about in this chapter [/course/82991/16]. d3 is the ideal square for the bishop, where it points at Black's kingside. This promising idea was not covered in 'Opening Repertoire: the French Defence’ by IM Cyrus Lakdawala or 'Play the French' (Chess24 video series) by GM Vallejo Pons.}) (3... Nc6 {Being a top choice of the engine this move is on trend to become the new main line. It is recommended in three recent Chessable courses.} 4. e5 d4 5. Nf3 Qd5 {Very concrete chess. Black immediately hits the vulnerable e5-pawn. This variation is briefly covered in 'Lifetime Repertoires: French Defence' by TM (Twitter Master) Anish Giri and 'The Unexplored French Defence by IM Yuriy Krykun'. Most recently, FM Kamil Plichta picked this direction for Black as well in his Lifetime Repertoires.} 6. Bc4 $5 {A venomous pawn sacrifice, giving up the prized central pawn for the sake of fast development. This novelty was neglected by Giri and Krykun, while it is addressed in Kamil's LTR. The specific clash occurs a few moves later down the line, which you can check here. [/variation/17615932] And yes, we also cover the natural and safe option 6. Qe2.}) (3... a6 {appears very infrequently in practice, yet it is not a bad move. It has GM Dmitry Kryakvin's stamp of approval, in his book 'The Modern French Defence'. In the chapter 3rd Move Deviations we devote two trainable lines to this rare bird.}) 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 (5... Nc6 6. O-O-O Nd4 {is referred to as an attempt to equalize by GM Vereslav Eingorn in the book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black'} 7. Qe3 {A fresh idea which contains a nasty trap. Learn about it here. [/variation/21886766]}) (5... Bb4 6. O-O-O Qe7 7. Nxe4 Ba3 {7...Nbd7 The coverage of chessable course 'Master the French' by NM Bryan Tillis ends at this point. Being a repertoire designed for GMs, 'Grandmaster Repertoire - The French Defence' by GM Emanuel Berg gives a few more moves. 8.Kb1 Anticipating ...Ba3 is our recommendation, analysed in three lines starting from this point. 8...a5 9.a4 O-O 10.Nf3 b6 11.Nxf6+ Nxf6 GM Berg's coverage stops at this point. White has the powerful and thematic idea 12.Ne5! In this trainable [/variation/23953384], we explain why White's knight is such a dominant force from the e5 square.} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. d4 Qe7 $1 {9...Bxb2+ is far more popular, but 9...Qe7 is more precise. We believe this is one of Black's best lines in the Open Horwitz. This concept is introduced by the duo GM Jacob Aagaard and correspondence IM Nikos Ntirlis in their excellent work 'Playing the French'.} 10. Nf3 {White has a solid position and can combine playing in the center and kingside with restraining Black's activity on the queenside. This variation is covered in a set of trainables, in this chapter [/course/82991/27].}) 6. Nxe4 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. a4 a5 9. O-O-O b6 {Grandmaster Viktor Moskalenko is a French Defence guru, having played the opening for decades and writing four (!) books about it. In his 2015 work 'The Even More Flexible French', his analysis arrived at this exact position through a small move order twist. In this position, we propose the cunning novelty} 10. Qe1 $5 {Sliding the queen out of harm's way. In the course we checked the development of Black's bishop to b7 and a6, the latter of which is what our text move pre-empts.} *

