{B: 12...Ne5! is the most tenacious, but we have the trick 13.Bxe6+! Bxe6 14.f4! when Black is bound to lose material on the e-file.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: -} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter [/course/82991/17]. -}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and in the theory chapter we begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, there's no magic for Black to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. We don't think the astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database does anything here other than add misery to Black's cause.}) 5... exd3 6. Nf3 $5 ({Black accepts the challenge and grabs yet another pawn. At this point,} 6. Bxd3 {is exclusively played, scoring over 65% for White in the databases. That's an impressive score, isn't it? The task of the authors would be easy in this case: give a few flashy lines backed up by the stats and conclude that White has great compensation there. However, we do anything but recommend continuations that have already been well-established. Similar to Huy's Spielmann-Indian course, we aim to give you unexplored and strong continuations, which will shock your opponents and increase the chance of them going wrong. Fasten your seatbelts, we're going to offer a lovely double gambit!}) 6... dxc2 $6 ({Playing in a romantic style. This continuation hasn't been known to the chess world yet, at least before the publication of this course. We offer the c2-pawn, reasoning that it would accelerate our queenside development and allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring the fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge... yet another time!}) {What can we say? Black has played over-greedily, he must be punished.} 7. Qxc2 {One feature we like about the 4...f5 variation is that it allows White to play based on natural and systematic moves to exploit the weakened kingside, instead of memorizing tons of theory. As castling queenside is denied now, we'll go Bc4 and O-O next followed by Rfe1 and Rad1. With the queen included, we've developed four pieces compared to a whopping zero from Black.} Nf6 8. Bc4 Bd6 {Black tries to block the d-file with the bishop, but it allows us to castle queenside.} 9. O-O-O {White's coordination makes a pleasant picture: every piece is performing at its best. Love your pawns and pieces, play the Horwitz, and they'll bring you such amazing positions!} Nc6 10. Rhe1 Qe7 $1 (10... O-O $2 11. Ng5 $1 {wouldn't be any good for Black. The text move contains a venomous threat: ...Bd7 followed by ...O-O-O when suddenly, Black would be better. Furthermore, Black sidesteps the d-file pin so Ng5 would be met with ...Bf4+, winning the knight. Well, it's not just Black who knows how to play prophylactic moves...}) 11. Kb1 $1 {Getting away from the dangerous c1-h6 diagonal and threatening Ng5 once again.} O-O 12. Ng5 ({The best way to proceed.} 12. Qxf5 $6 {may seem tempting, but Black has the resource} Qf7 $1 {when they will equalise after the exchanges on e6. The text move maintains all the trumps in our position and directs yet one more piece towards e6.}) ({Some sample lines to be enjoyed: A:} 12. Ng5 Nd8 $2 13. Qxf5 {is a winner this time.}) 12... Z0 *

