1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3...dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nc6 $5 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4 etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A barbaric idea that requires investigation, being mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black', with the author quoting the game Gelashvili - Ramon Perez. If we manage to play Nxe4 and Nf3, ninety percent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in this chapter [/course/82991/28].}) 6... Nd4 {The queen hunts begin! Black's minor pieces will act like mosquitoes in the ears, preventing us from recapturing the e4-pawn. And even if we got in Nxe4, Black has the possibility of c7-c5, stabilizing the strong d4-knight at the cost of blocking the f8-bishop.} 7. Qe3 $5 ({We're moving away from the known paths of} 7. Qe1 Bd7 {followed by ...Bc6 with approximate equality. Our suggested}) (7. Qe3 $5 {is much rarer and is a provocation: on e3 the queen is exposed to tricks like Bc5 followed by Nxb3+, Ng4, Nf5, etc. Therefore, care needs to be taken! The good news is that there's no easy way for Black to liquidate the position and we'll keep the pressure in all of the lines. 7...Bd7 is no longer possible since the d4-knight is hanging, so Black must choose another way to deal with the threat of Nxe4.}) 7... Bc5 8. Nxe4 $1 ({The most popular move according to the Lichess Database. Black creates the deadly threat of Nxb3+ winning the queen. At this point, White has two good moves:} 8. Na4 {and}) (8. Nxe4 {. However,}) (8. Nxe4 {is a lot more tricky and gives Black many ways to go wrong, so it'll be our main recommendation! Objectively, White has a clear advantage no matter which option we choose, signalling that 7...Bc5 is not a good line at all!}) 8... Nxb3+ $4 ({Recapturing the lost pawn and setting an EXTREMELY tempting trap!} 8... Nxb3+ $4 {appears to win a clean pawn, but we have a cute trick at the end to win a piece. 8...Nxe4 is a much better alternative, but after 8.Qxe4 White is way ahead in development. Black cannot keep his knight on d4, as we show in the next line.}) {Black uses a 'clever' trick to win the knight on e4 and emerges a pawn up with overwhelming threats at the end of the line. This line ends too quickly!} 9. Qxb3 Nxe4 10. Qa4+ {Oops, it's a fork! We have the last laugh after all :)} *

