[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Bxc3 $5 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) {Black goes for a principled and sharp mode of play. Black prevents the threat of Nxe4 bluntly and signalling his intention to keep the e4-pawn for some time. The cost is that the dark squares are forever weakened with the presence of White's Horwitz bishop, so basically, Black is sacrificing a positional factor for a fat extra pawn. This variation is particularly 'messy', featuring more unclear, complicated chess than most other variations in this course.} 7. dxc3 $1 ({Much more promising than} 7. Bxc3 a5 $1 {or 7...Nc6!? with easy play for Black. The 'fractured' pawn structure is more than welcome since we have the open d-file and the doubled pawns will serve as defenders of White's king. Most likely, White will push the front c-pawn to c4 in order to re-open the long diagonal for the powerhouse on b2. White can play around the e4-pawn with g4 (with or without h3) and threaten to annoy Black with g4-g5. The queen should be put on e3 to free the e2-g3 route for our king's knight. The above guidelines act as a vague picture of White's plans. Generally speaking, we're happy to play a pawn down for 'uncertain' compensation, since the e4-pawn is weak and most likely will fall anyway. If anything, Black should be more careful not to soften his dark squares too much having given up his prized DSB (dark-squared bishop!)}) 7... Qe7 {More sensible than . The d7 square should be reserved for the bishop instead, just in case Black wants to castle queenside.} 8. g4 ({White has a range of options, for example,} 8. c4 {or even go wild with}) (8. f3 $5 {. We decide to be consistent with our other recommendations and start with g4! The idea is, of course, to dislodge Black's knight on f6 with g5 next. In the Lichess Database, White has won an amazing 68% of games that have reached this position, from a sample size of over 100 games!}) 8... h6 9. c4 ({Black wisely prevents g4-g5, thus slowing down White's initiative. The point is that now} 9. h4 {can be met by} e5 $1 {when White cannot push g5 due to the pin on the h-file. We have to switch to a slower plan to win the e4-pawn. The moves White wants to get in are h3 (protecting the g4-pawn), c4, Bg2, Qe3 and Ne2-g3 when all of White's pieces would be ideally placed. If Black develops routinely and allows White to achieve this setup, the first player would have an advantage thanks to the bishop pair after regaining the pawn.}) ({A step in the right direction.} 9. Bg2 {and}) (9. h3 {also support White's plan and are valid alternatives. However, it's good to retain the possibility of pushing h4 in one go, just in case. Black has a myriad of move orders here, but the only thing you need to know is the strategic plan we will show.}) 9... Nc6 (9... b6 {would be ideal, preparing Bb7, if not for the smashing} 10. h4 $1 Bb7 11. Bg2 {when g4-g5 arrives with brute force. 9...Bd7 10.Bg2 e5 11.h3 is similar to what we will be examining now.}) 10. h3 $1 {The next step is to bolster the g4-pawn in order to prepare Bg2-Qe3-Ne2.} e5 (10... Bd7 {can be met with} 11. Bg2 O-O-O 12. Qe3 {, following the grand plan. Next is Ng1-e2-g3-e4, regaining the pawn and keeping the bishop pair.}) 11. Bg2 {Let us remind you once more that we are sticking to the plan!} Bd7 12. Qe3 O-O-O 13. Ne2 Z0 ({Mission completed! Despite being a pawn down, White controls the situation with the power of the bishop pair. Ng3-e4 is available and Nc3-d5 is another idea to increase the pressure. Black is cramped and lacks a target to attack, which makes his position difficult to handle. White is not objectively better against the machine, but Black needs to find many accurate moves -} 13... h5 $1 {a good start - to maintain the balance.}) *

