{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Qe7 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) 7. Nxe4 ({The most logical move, per Black's previous one. Black prepares ...Ba3, trading White's VIB (Very Important Bishop) which weakens our king's cover. After our bishop is traded there is also the idea of ...a5-a4 to endanger our king. This variation is frequently encountered since its ideas are simple and easy to apply. According to theory, the Bb4+Qe7 setup is a safe way to equalize against the Horwitz Attack and it has been recommended by GM Emmanuel Berg as well as NM Bryan Tillis in their respective repertoire works (see the Repertoire Clash [/variation/30221753]). White has three main approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) 7... Ba3 ({This is the mainline. White agrees that Black can exchange two pairs of minor pieces with} 7... Ba3 {and this is indeed what most Black players have done, simplifying the position.}) {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops, which decreases the strength of future kingside attacks by White. Moreover, ...a5-a4 is a possibility White needs to watch out for. 7...Ba3 is the mainline and what many respected theoretical works have recommended for Black. These facts are caused by the simplicity of this variation - Black players are under the impression that they are out of danger after the exchanges. Yes, these positions are equal and sometimes can be dry, but it's always a game. Both sides have to make moves and then there are chances for everyone to outplay their opponent. After a lot of digging, we've created some small ideas that do not drastically change the landscape, but offer a clear gameplan for White and force Black to solve little problems.} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. d4 ({The cheapo is that} 9. Bxa3 Qa1# {is mate - an echo of the famous Englund Gambit trap ( 1.d4 e5 2.dxe5 Nc6 3.Nf3 Qe7 4.Bf4 Qb4+ 5.Bd2 Qxb2 6.Bc3 Bb4 7.Qd2 Bxc3 8.Qxc3 Qc1# ) that chess Youtubers like Eric Rosen and GothamChess have popularized through videos with titles like 'Winning in 8 moves' etc. Anyway, we are not here to discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Bxb2+ ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black exchanges the bishops immediately but allows the white king to take up a good position on b2.} 10. Kxb2 O-O ({The king plays an active role in defending itself! If later we ever play a3/c3, the pawn formation is securely supported by the king. White has a slight lead in development since Black's only developed troop is the not-so-well-placed queen on f6. Our ideal formation is knight to f3, queen to e3 or e4 (to clear the a6-f1 diagonal) then our bishop can get out followed by the h1-rook. In this position,} 10... O-O {and}) (10... c5 {are Black's most popular choices. We'll take a look at both moves.}) {A slow move. The position required more drastic measures. White now has time to develop everything harmoniously. 10...Nc6?! plans Bd7 and O-O-O, but blocks the c-pawn. We can simply follow our plan with 11.Nf3 Bd7 12.Qe3 O-O-O 13.Bd3 when White is controlling the game.} 11. Nf3 {An important question arises for Black: how is he going to create any counterplay at all? He cannot afford to make weak moves, because White has a clear attacking vision on the kingside with Qe4-Bd3, g4, g5, sac, sac, mate!} c5 ({Very logical. Black counters a potential flank attack in the centre. Instead,} 11... a5 12. a4 $1 {blocks everything on the a-file, while}) (11... b6 $2 {intending ...Bb7 is a horrible mistake due to the following important theme:} 12. Qe4 $1 {gaining a crucial tempo} c6 13. Bd3 {and White crushes on the kingside.}) 12. Qe4 $146 {Centralizing the queen and preparing Bd3 to hit the h7 spot. A great thing about White's position is that we are better in sharp attacks... as well as in endgames! Surprisingly, this strong move seems to be a novelty.} cxd4 13. Qxd4 {White has lasting pressure in this kind of late middlegame/early endgame. We have the traditional good bishop and our knight is ready to invade with Ne5 or even Nd4-b5-d6. Our bishop is good on e2 and we are able to quickly double rooks on the key file. In case more pieces leave the board, White's king is also more active - just 2 moves away from the centre. If Black prematurely pushes ...e5 in this type of structure a combination of Nd6 + Bc4 can be devastating, as shown in the model game Rudolf Spielmann - Roberto Grau. [/variation/25618985]} *

