1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} Nbd7 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5-a4-c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {A tricky move. Black leaves the option of ...a5 followed by ...c6 open, so White should not rush with castling. 8.O-O-O?! can transpose to the 7...b6 line [/variation/29257102] after 8...b6 , but superior is 8...a5! 9.a4 c6! and White has been tricked into an undesirable position, as outlined at the start of the chapter.} 8. g4 $1 {We love this move. Go for the throat! This move shows our aggressive intention to play for a kingside attack. Black's last move, ...Nbd7, is quite slow, so Black is not in time to exploit the position of White's king in the centre.} Nxe4 {The critical move to check. Generally, it is inaccurate for Black to exchange on e4, since White's queen will be centralised. However, in this position, Black's other knight is ready to replace its companion on f6. Black even has the option to grab the g4-pawn which would be quite a fun line to analyse, if you are interested.} 9. Qxe4 Nf6 10. Qe2 $5 ({White has to go for it. The tame} 10. Qf4 Bd6 11. Ne5 Nd7 {does not yield anything, so the retreat to e2 is best. We want to play g5 to kick the defensive knight away. It's up to Black whether he'd like to take the pawn.}) 10... Nxg4 $5 {In most lines, Black cannot afford to grab the g4-pawn because keeping the g-file closed is far more important. Therefore it's not likely your opponent would have the courage to go for this line. The computer insists it's best, but only due to a clever tactical point that will be clarified soon.} 11. Rg1 {Lining up the rook on the newly formed semi-open file.} Bf6 $1 {The whole point, otherwise, Black's operation would fail. Exploiting the fact that White has not castled, Black challenges the strong Horwitz bishop and gains control of the long diagonal. 11...Nf6? would be disastrous. 12.O-O-O and we will throw the kitchen sink at Black with Qe3-h6, Bd3, h4-h5-h6.} 12. d4 {No thank you. We need the Horwitz bishop.} Nh6 13. O-O-O Nf5 14. Ne5 {For the sacrificed pawn White has imposed a bind on Black's position. Next, we can consider f4 and Bg2-e4, increasing our control over the position. Another idea is Ng4 followed by the line opening break d4-d5, focusing White's forces on the g7-square. All in all, Black's extra pawn is not felt in this position.} *

