1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} b6 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5-a4-c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {The most popular move. Black develops the bishop actively on the long diagonal, where it puts pressure on our e4-knight.} 8. O-O-O {After Black has played ...b6, he would have to waste another tempo to prepare the ...b5 break (after a5-a4). So we are safe to castle.} Bb7 9. Nxf6+ {The logical move. Our knight is under attack, so we are happy to exchange it. Note that we have a concrete follow-up in mind to avoid the exchange of dark-squared bishops as well.} Bxf6 10. Ne5 $1 {A key move that sets the stage for the middlegame fight. Black's bishop, as we have explained multiple times, is not well placed on f6. White will support the e5-knight with f2-f4. Black is not in time to challenge White's stronghold on the e5-square. Black's b7-bishop puts pressure on our kingside, so we cannot push our kingside pawns casually with g4 (the rook hangs!) Instead, there is an artificial and strong plan available: h4-Rh3-g4. Safeguarding the rook before pushing the g-pawn.} a5 $5 {Should be met with our rule of thumb.} 11. a4 $1 {Meet ...a5 with a4. Simple easy rule.} Nc6 12. f4 (12. d4 {is interesting, but let's stick to our thematic concept. The text position has been reached in a few correspondence games and White has racked up some wins. For example, 12...Qe7 13.h4! Rad8 14.Qf2 is already promising for White in ½-½ (31) Konstantinov, M (2392) - Sanchez, A (2305) ICCF email 2017.}) *

