1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({The second most popular move in the database. Instead of opening the position with} 3... dxe4 {, Black invites 4. e5 with a blocked French structure and a tough strategic battle. The structure indeed resembles the mainline-ish French, with one vital difference - our bishop is on b2! This turns the tide in our favour, since the e5-pawn is exceptionally well-defended, giving us a handy space advantage. If Black tries to challenge our centre with ...f6, the long diagonal would be opened and from an ordinary bishop, the monster on b2 would be the MVP of the game. As of 2023, the traditional}) (3... Nf6 {seems to have moved to the backwaters and we see no sign of it emerging again, especially since Black has found a number of modern methods to deal with the Horwitz Attack.}) 4. e5 {The principled reply, and the only way to highlight the drawback of 3...Nf6 - the knight must move again. Even though the pawn currently blocks the Horwitz bishop, that's not such a big problem as the bishop will act as a supporter of White's pawn chain. Compare to the Advanced Variation of the French, here our centre cannot be destroyed as easily. Black's choices are limited to ( 4...Nfd7 , 4...Ng8 and 4...Ne4 . The former is the mainline by a huge margin (played in roughly 95% of the games), while the latter moves are much rarer. In this chapter, we'll take a look at 4...Ng8 and 4...Ne4 . Both of these lines seem almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there's honestly not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy variations such as 3...Nc6 and 3...dxe4 .} Ne4 $5 {An option that appears very infrequently in practice. The knight looks strong on e4, but it can be easily driven away. White has many ways to claim an advantage and what we chose to recommend is certainly original.} 5. h4 $146 Bc5 ({Controlling the dark horse's escape square g5. The chief point is that the standard French move} 5... c5 $4 {is met by} 6. d3 $1 {and the knight is swiftly trapped in the middle of the board. Also, h4 is generally a useful move for White in this structure, since it gains kingside space. Next, we'll drive Black's knight back with d3 when it turns out that c5 is the only square. If we follow up with d4, Black's sad knight may even find itself on d7. However, what is the point of Ng8-f6-e4-c5-d7 instead of just retreating with 4...Nfd7? Our recommendation is a novelty - maybe you didn't expect us to leave the trodden paths this early, but that's exactly what we did.}) {Most direct, Black is threatening the f2-pawn and forces our next move.} 6. d4 {Pushing the bishop backwards. Black has avoided d2-d3 trapping the knight in the future, but his bishop has wasted a move.} Be7 ({From e7 Black exerts pressure on the h4-pawn, although that pawn is often poisoned. In case of} 6... Bb6 $6 {White has the strong move} 7. Ne2 $1 {, controlling the g3 square and preparing f2-f3, trapping the knight. With the bishop on e7, this isn't an option, since the h4-pawn hangs with check.}) 7. Bd3 (7. Qg4 $5 {is another option, but}) (7. Bd3 {is natural and thematic. In many lines in the Closed Horwitz, we recommend a consistent plan of playing Bd3 after stabilizing the centre (for example 4...Nfd7 5.d4 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Bd3 ) to avoid confusing the readers. We are threatening Bxe4 followed by Qg4 with a double attack on Black's pawns.}) 7... c5 ({Immediately challenging our centre is the most natural and best way to proceed. Note that} 7... Bxh4 $2 {is hardly ever possible in this line, as White has} 8. Bxe4 dxe4 9. Qg4 $1 {winning the house. Also, 7...O-O?! fails to the simple 8.Bxe4! dxe4 9.Nd2 and Black has little to show for the lost pawn.}) 8. Nd2 $5 ({Exchanging the annoying e4-knight for our newly-developed horse.} 8. Bxe4 $5 dxe4 9. Qg4 {is an adventurous option. However, it seems to us that White is getting a more comfortable position after the text move.}) 8... Nxd2 ({Black should exchange knights immediately, since} 8... cxd4 $2 9. Qg4 $1 {is great for White,} Nxd2 10. Qxg7 $1 {is an important intermediate move and White wins material.}) 9. Qxd2 b6 $5 {This positional idea is recommended by Leela. Black wants to play Ba6 and swap his 'bad' bishop for our good one. However, he will have to pay some tempi and a stranded knight on a6 for that.} 10. h5 $1 {Threatening h5-h6 to cramp Black even further.} h6 {Stopping the h-pawn in its track, but now we turn our focus to the g7-pawn.} 11. Rh3 $1 {This rook switch is very common in several lines of the French, intending Rh3-g3 to hit the g7-pawn.} Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Rg3 Z0 ({White owns the initiative. Black's lack of space on the kingside means that it's very tough to defend the g7-pawn. For example,} 13... Kf8 $6 {is met with} 14. Qe2 $1 Nb4 15. c3 Nc6 16. Rd1 {when we have firm control of the centre and can look forward to a decisive invasion on the kingside.}) *

