1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qb6 {This standard move is a must to consider in the French structure. Black hits the d4-pawn, which was well protected by the Horwitz bishop but now vulnerable.} 8. Ne2 {The most logical solution, simply and efficiently protecting the d4-pawn.} cxd4 $6 {One of those bad-timed cxd4s that's very popular online.} 9. cxd4 {Thanks Black for the c3 square!} Bb4+ $6 {This check does nothing other than accelerating our development.} 10. Nd2 {Nc3 drops the d4-pawn this time, so we develop our knight to a less active square. However, the b4-bishop is far from ideally placed, and it will have to move again.} O-O 11. Qc2 $1 ({A nice little move, hitting the h7-pawn and forcing Black's king to h8 or to play a weakening move. At first, we didn't understand why this move is better than the immediate} 11. a3 {, but we managed to find the solution later, and will explain the details soon!}) 11... Kh8 (11... g6 {and}) (11... h6 {are too weakening to be good.}) 12. a3 Be7 13. f4 {We've pushed Black back and secured a decent space advantage. White is a lot better here as Black has no counterplay at all. Next, we'll continue with Nf3 to strengthen our centre. Also, don't forget that the h7-pawn is hanging, or attacking ideas like O-O followed by Rf3!} *

