1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge is awaiting us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2. b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 {)} ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb to remember: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Ng6 {A better square for the knight where it targets the e5-pawn. We cannot let it fall as it would leave Black with a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} O-O {Simple chess, Black castles to see what we do before reacting to our plan. As easy as it seems, the text move proved to be a real nuisance to find something interesting against. After many hours of exhausting analysis on the different options, White has, we can confidently say that a promising direction has been found.} 9. Ba3 $5 ({A switch of plans.} 9. c3 {is what we normally play here, but we couldn't make White's position work after the useful prophylaxis} a5 $5 {, although some other lines are satisfactory for White at least. However, if you're not tempted by the option we're recommending, then} 10. Na3 $5 {followed by Nc2 is the way to handle the}) (9. c3 {line. The text move aims to trade off our passive Horwitz bishop right away, instead of slowly undermining the d4-pawn with c3. A drawback is that Black will win some time with Bxa3, but the closed nature of the position gives us enough time to re-route the knight. As mentioned before, we concluded that}) (9. Ba3 {is the most promising try for White after a long analysis.}) 9... Bxa3 10. Nxa3 {After the exchange, we should be reasonably happy with our position. c3 is coming to resume the battle about the d4-pawn, while the d3-bishop outweighs its counterpart. We'll examine two different ways for Black to handle this line: active mode with ( 10...f5!? or the calm .} b6 {Black plays in a more restrained fashion and patiently prepares Bb7 to develop his worst minor piece. However, the plan contains an evident drawback, namely the weakening of the long diagonal.} 11. Be4 {Exploiting the pinned knight. Our forces don't allow us to win that knight, unfortunately, but it'll be a source of worry for Black.} Bb7 12. c3 $5 (12. Nc4 {is a good alternative, but we have trust in the text move. The point is that our knight might prove useful on either c4 or c2, so let's not commit it just yet! Meanwhile, the opening of the position generally favours the side with more space - that is White. Moreover, our pieces are all developed, leaving us in good shape. The threat is Nxd4, capitalizing on the pin.}) 12... dxc3 ({There is nothing better for Black, since} 12... d3 $6 13. Re3 $1 {leaves the second player a fatty pawn down.}) 13. dxc3 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 {As boring as it looks, the endgame is full of life with four rooks and three pairs of minor pieces remaining on the board. Currently, our bishop is exerting an annoying pin on the Giri knight. Moreover, the rook is eyeing the 7th rank. We plan to continue with Nc4-e3, Nd4 and expand on the kingside with g3, f4 and h4-h5.} Z0 ({Note that the natural} 14... Rfd8 $6 {is punished with} 15. Nb5 $1 {when it's tough to hold on to the c7-pawn.}) *

