1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge is awaiting us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2. b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives that Black has. The text move is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralises his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhaustive investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O d3 $5 ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) {The most dangerous try Black has at his disposal. Despite his lag in development, he opens up the centre with the concrete idea of creating a monster knight on the d3-square. Moreover, the text move is the first choice of the engine - quite an achievement for such a risky move! Both sides have to be precise not to fall into immediate trouble, so do study the theoretical nuances carefully!} 9. cxd3 {There was no other choice since the bishop was hanging. We're at a fork in the road: Black can either capture on f3 or d3.} Nxd3 $1 {Black takes up the gauntlet and occupies the most active position for the knight.} 10. Qc2 $1 {A strong but hard-to-spot nuance when you haven't seen it before. We pin Black's knight at the cost of losing the e2-bishop. However, you'll see that we'll utilise concrete tactics to trap Black's queen in our camp, reaching an unclear position. The alternatives lead nowhere with an annoying knight on d3. You can check yourself that the text move is the only move to yield enough compensation for the pawn.} Qxe2 $1 ({Black must bite the bullet, grab the offered piece and enter a deep dark forest where 2+2=5, à la Tal. Otherwise,} 10... Nc5 $2 {would prematurely retreat the cramping knight and we can punish him with} 11. d3 $1 Qf5 12. b4 $1 {and Black's house is falling. After the text move, aren't we simply a whopping piece down? However, we can prove we have a trick or two up our sleeves.}) 11. Qc4 $1 (11. Nc3 $2 {would be met with} Nb4 $1 {and Black hits our queen, thus escaping with an extra piece. After Black's last move, the only escape square for the queen is e4, so we control it and prepare Nc3, shutting the cage. Moreover, the queen pins the d3-knight, thus not allowing Nb4 tricks as it would hang the queen. Black has two approaches to consider: he might try to get the queen out and sac the knight back, or he can trade the queen on f3 followed by Nxb2, with three minor pieces for the queen. The b2-knight would be trapped in that case, but our wrecked structure (4 pawn islands) surprisingly give Black enough compensation.}) 11... Bd7 {To be honest, Black can play plenty of other moves with the idea of meeting Nc3 with a queen sacrifice. Afterwards, we would have a typical material imbalance in this variation and the specific placement of every piece isn't so relevant. Therefore, we'll cover Black's ideas to sac the queen via the text move.} 12. Nc3 $1 {A deep and sophisticated combination has paid off! Through some accurate manoeuvring, we've cleverly trapped the queen inside our territory. Black has two different ways to sacrifice the queen at this point: either for the f1-rook or the f3-knight.} Qxf1+ ({If you're worried about} 12... b5 $6 {, don't be against this tricky move. The surprisingly cool refutation is} 13. Nxb5 $1 {and Black is powerless to stop the backward move Nc3, trapping the queen again. With the text move, Black sacrifices the queen for a rook, a minor piece (since after Nxb2, the knight wouldn't survive) and a pawn. The trade is quite fair for both sides, leaving us with an imbalanced but equal middlegame. To be honest, we'd be more worried about the dangerous sacrifice}) (12... Qxf3 $5 {, which will be examined next. However, let's see how we should react to the text move first.}) 13. Rxf1 Nxb2 14. Qe2 {An important move, controlling the d3 square to make sure the b2-knight is trapped. Next, we'll play d4 and gobble a whole fat knight. The middlegame is relatively easy to handle for both sides. Afterwards, we'll continue with Ne5, Rd1 and perhaps expand on the kingside with g4-g5 and h4. Black's position is solid enough to offset our queen and we do have a weak pawn on d4, so care has to be taken.} *

