{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 c5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A decently popular move at the master as well as amateur level. Black combines the French with the Sicilian and ambitiously grabs space in the centre. They are preparing d4 to steamroll our Horwitz bishop. However, a clear drawback of this move is that it fails to develop any piece. Black's thrust is also premature in the sense that the strong Bb5+ resource is now available as Black can no longer play ...c6. Huy faced this line once in a rapid game and launched a sudden attack in the middlegame to win. And after doing a lot of analysis, we're convinced you don't need to be worried at all about this option.} 4. exd5 {Similar to the pawn move 3...a6 , we decide to recommend the exd5 approach, which opens up the centre in a principled manner while our opponent is lagging in development. This is an even better option for us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} exd5 {An obviously better choice compared to the Scandi-French hybrid we've just seen. Black captures the centre with their c5-d5 duo, but the legends have it that White will strike back furiously!} 5. Nf3 {A natural move, bringing the king's knight into play in the most active fashion out there. There are many hidden subtleties in the position, like whether Black develops the knight to c6 or f6 and the ways they could react to Bb5+. We'll try to explain them all as convincingly as possible!} Nf6 {The knight jumps may well transpose to each other in case Black plays Nc6 next. However, they also have some independent tries, which we'll examine. The crucial difference between the two lines is our ability to insert Qe2+, to which there is no convincing antidote. ...Be6 isn't always an option given that Bb5+ could be met with ...Bd7, while ...Be7 would allow the Bxf6 resource.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 {Blocking the check this way seems to be the most natural. We'll also take a brief look at some alternatives: A) Buy us a lovely pizza if you cannot refute 6...Qd7 ! B) 6...Nc6 transposes to the 5...Nc6 variation [/variation/18434600].} 7. Qe2+ $1 {An unexpected check, which is rather typical for this structure. We exploit Black's lag in development to prevent them from developing the kingside smoothly.} (7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {gives us nothing, since Black can follow up with Be7 and O-O in time.}) 7... Qe7 $1 (7... Be7 $2 {is refuted with} 8. Bxf6 $1 {and Black's structure represents an ugly creature. And ugly is an 'ugly' word. Remember this trick! The text move is basically the only move for Black.}) 8. O-O {The simplest way to maintain some pressure. Our bishop and queen are protecting each other, so there's no way Black can win material. Our deadly threat is Re1 , so Black should capture on ( e2 immediately. The text move is a lot rare compared to 8.Bxf6 , but it scores much better at a whopping 90%. Meanwhile, 8.Bxf6!? is the way to mix things up. We have the superior structure compared to Black's strong bishop pair, leading to a double-edged fight. Black should play the precise 8...Qxe2! in order to retain the bishop pair (this wouldn't be possible in the notes to ) . 9.Bxe2 Nc6 10.Nc3 followed by d4 when both sides have chances. Personally, we would be quite reluctant with the dark square weaknesses inside our camp.} Qxe2 {Otherwise, we'd play Re1 with a crushing initiative.} 9. Bxe2 Be7 10. d4 {A balanced middlegame has arisen in Bernad Suarez - Sanchez. Although the position is objectively equal, White has won all three games from this point, a convincing sign of how easy our position is to handle. We'll proceed with dxc5, Nc3 and Rad1 to target the isolated d5-pawn. The best statement to summarise the state of this position: equal isn't boring!} *

