{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 b6 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and . Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down.}) {The Copycat variation, championed by John Watson in his legendary book 'Play the French' - a should-have manual for aspiring French players. Black wants to prove that our e4-pawn is a liability by hitting it with Bb7. However, Black does not fight for the centre directly and we can often seize it ourselves with d4 - although objectively speaking we should have done so on the 2nd move ;). We're proud to announce we've found many bright ideas over previous theory (Watson's book for example), and the ideas are as original as they can be.} 3. Bb2 {The point of our previous move. Need we add some more explanations?} Bb7 {No choice for Black either. He threatens the e4-pawn, and now there is more than one way to protect it. We recommend the most logical one, which is} 4. Nc3 {and the pawn is well protected. First of all, we would like to push d2-d4, which is why the various moves Black has tried in this position are directed against it. Secondly, there are also ideas to move our queen and pave the way for queenside castling. The e4-pawn does an awesome job of restricting the poor bishop on b7! In the Owen ( 1.e4 b6 ), it's true that the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop is not the most convenient of ways to gain an edge. However, it's certainly quite a venomous one against the opening that Kramnik considered to be 'no better than 1.e4 a6 '! This is the critical tabiya of the Copycat variation, from which we'll analyse two moves. Grab your popcorn and watch in delight as Black's kingdom falls apart everywhere!} Nf6 ({Firstly, we'd like to mention briefly that} 4... d5 $6 {fails to} 5. exd5 exd5 6. Qe2+ $1 {and Black's coordination is disrupted. There are a lot of details to gain an advantage with White though, and we don't feel it's practical to learn all of them given the rarity of that sideline. With the text move, Black hits the e4-pawn and it's not so convenient to defend it with pawn moves, while 5.Bd3 or 5.Qe2 would block our future development. This concept was played recently by Wesley So against none other than Magnus Carlsen in a game that starts with the unusual move-order 1.b3 b6 2.e4 Bb7 . At this point, 5.e5 Nd5 is the mainline, a possible continuation being 6.Nxd5 Bxd5 7.Qg4 h5!? with highly unclear play in Carlsen, M - So, W, Meltwater Tour Final 2021. What we will be proposing instead is a rare but venomous continuation, let's see it!}) 5. Qf3 $5 {According to our database, this move is a theoretical novelty. Despite the peculiar appearance, it does protect the e4-pawn and is a challenging option due to: - We may transpose to the 4...d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Qf3!? variation as covered previously. - The queen often exerts uncomfortable pressure down the long diagonal while not blocking the f1-bishop. Moreover, Her Majesty supports g4-g5 to dislodge the black knight. - We are now ready to castle queenside! What a multipurpose move! Pretending Black does nothing, we'll play O-O-O and take the whole centre with d4. Black has several playable continuations here, but to our eyes, the most natural ones are 5...c5 and 5...d5 , fighting for the centah!} c5 {Stockfish's favourite move and there are suddenly many games in the database. The reason is that now we've transposed into a sideline of the Sicilian! It starts with 1.e4 c5 2.b3 b6 3.Bb2 Bb7 4.Nc3 e6 5.Qf3 Nf6 and we're back in this position! Black is fighting for control of the d4 square as well as gaining space on the queenside. His next moves will likely be Nc6 and a6.} 6. O-O-O {We see no reason to delay this natural move. We have two basic plans here: Nge2 followed by d4, and g4-g5.} Nc6 {Black threatens to jump his knight onto the juicy d4 square and dislodge our queen. However, the drawback is that we can play} 7. e5 $146 {An obvious and strong improvement to Gelashvili - Ehlvest. Our queen proves its worth on f3, pinning the c6-knight and thus not allowing ...Nxe5. Black's well-placed horse on f6 must move now, granting us the initiative. The sole drawback of the text move is that the e5-pawn is a potential weakness in the long term, but for now, it is doing an excellent job of cramping Black's pieces.} Ng8 ({Not the most pleasant move to make but there is no other good option for Black. For example,} 7... Na5 $2 8. Qf4 Nd5 {is met by} 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Ne2 $1 {and Black is too undeveloped to face d2-d4.}) 8. Ne4 {Activating our knight and protecting the important e5-pawn. It's quite hard to suggest a good plan for Black to develop his kingside given our space advantage. Meanwhile, White has many plans, like Nd6+, Qf4, Nf3 and possibly d4. It cannot be ruled out that we'll cramp Black further with g4 and h4 as well! We'll show you a sample line to demonstrate the ideas we have here!} Nh6 9. Qf4 Z0 ({A prophylactic idea, ensuring that ...Nf5 and ... Nfd4 won't come with a tempo. Moreover, we overprotect the e5-pawn and clear the f3-square for our king's knight to stand on. Re1 is a potentially good idea, while g4 is also possible, taking away the f5 square for Black's knight on the rim. The game may proceed with} 9... Nf5 {Black's threat is surprisingly Nce7-g6 to force our queen elsewhere! We can meet it with the strong} 10. h4 $1 {, preparing h5 and g4 and Black is having extreme difficulties developing his kingside. A gorgeous line discovered by Stockfish is} Be7 $2 11. g4 $1 Nxh4 12. Rxh4 $1 {a bombshell!} g5 13. Qf3 gxh4 {is forced, and now} 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 Rg8 16. Nh3 $1 {followed by Bd3-xh7, Re1 and g5 would give White overwhelming compensation for the exchange. Nice stuff!}) *

