{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 c5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and . Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down.}) 3. Bb2 ({Black grabs his share in the centre and offers White a transposition to an Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Nf3 {. We believe that objectively,}) (3. Nf3 {is the best move; but it wouldn't be wise for us to transpose into a theoretical branch of the Sicilian, which is well-explored already. Let's keep things in uncharted territory!}) ({Mobilising the Horwitz bishop with} 3. Bb2 {is the most logical. In this position, Black has tried} Nf6 {often, but 3...Nc6 is clearly the mainline (according to Lichess Database) and what we will focus on. There are a lot of transpositions here to keep in mind and we'll make sure to highlight them. For a start, 3...d5 is the second most popular move and it brings us to the 2...d5 3.Bb2 c5 variation, a chicken we've roasted in the 3rd move deviations chapter [/course/82991/8].}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 $5 ({Black controls the important d4 square, thus making the d4 break ineffective for us. Over 1300 games have reached this critical tabiya, and the majority of white players are headed for} 4. Nf3 {, moving to Sicilian waters. We have something different up our sleeve!}) 4... a6 $2 ({Creating the lethal positional threat of Bxc6, which seems to be tolerated by Black players all the time!} 4... a6 $2 {is surprisingly the most popular move, and we will demonstrate the punishment. Our recommendation has happened in only 15% of the games, so there's a high chance your opponents will be out of book here, even if 2. b3 didn't surprise them. The drawback of 4.Bb5 compared to 4.Nf3 is that Black has 4...Nd4! available, forcing White to move the bishop again. An observation is that in the first four moves of the game we have broken two classical opening principles: 'Occupy the centre with pawns' and 'knights before bishops'. However, in the 21st century, even the Bongcloud and 1.e4 g5 stuff has entered the rank of legendary openings, so we can chill :)}) {A catastrophic move from a positional point of view. Knowing that Bxc6, damaging Black's structure, is White's main threat, how could it be justified to spend a tempo to provoke its execution? Let's see why the execution is actually even stronger than the threat!} 5. Bxc6 {The structure will be identical to the Rossolimo, but with some powerful differences. Firstly, our knights are still at home, so f2-f4 is available, gaining space on the kingside. The b1-knight will be happy on d2, while the b2-bishop is already perfectly placed! Secondly, Black cannot free his light-squared bishop. The a6-f1 diagonal is unavailable, while Black needs to arrange ...e5 somehow, to activate the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal. This is just impossible given White's superior control of the e5 square with f4 and Nf3.} bxc6 (5... dxc6 $2 6. d3 {is similarly great for White. We can continue with the thematic Nd2, Ngf3 and Qe2. It's astonishing, but Stockfish gives close to +2 for White after 6.d3!}) 6. d3 {It's important to understand where our pieces belong in this structure - there are several good move-orders to reach the same type of position. Our queen's knight will be placed on d2, where it secures the centre and doesn't block the shining view of the b2 bishop. The king's knight goes to f3, controlling the centre. Her Majesty is perfect on e2, and guess what, O-O-O will follow in vintage Horwitz spirit! We've just painted a general picture of White's plan in this structure. Now, let's see how this plan unfolds.} d5 (6... d6 $5 {can be met directly with} 7. f4 $1 {followed by Ngf3, Nd2 and Qe2, etc.}) 7. Nd2 Nf6 8. Ngf3 Be7 9. Qe2 $1 {Queenside castling is much more dangerous than the positional approach of kingside castling, although both are good options. With the broken structure, it's hard for Black to generate any play on the queenside against our king.} O-O 10. O-O-O {White is pleasantly better. g4 and h4 are coming next, supported by Rdg1, and we'll kill on the kingside. The Horwitz bishop is a monster, and if Black blocks the long diagonal with ... d4, our knight would be granted an excellent outpost on c4, not to mention that Black can no longer break with ...c4. Meanwhile, ...a5 will be blocked with a4, shutting down Black's counterplay.} *

