1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {'The best way to refute a gambit is to accept it!' goes a well-known chess adage. White's e4-pawn is unprotected and Black happily grabs it! However, the e4-pawn is vulnerable and unless Black takes extreme risks with ...f5 to maintain the pawn, we'll quickly recapture it with gain of time.} 4. Nc3 {Developing the horsie and hitting the e4-pawn instantly! We've developed two pieces already while Black has been toying around with his pawns. This is the first critical juncture and Black has two moves to choose from: 4...f5 and 4...Nf6.} Nf6 {The classical reply, protecting the pawn the ordinary way.} (4... f5 {This is even riskier than bungee jumping, especially since pawns do not move backward. Black's kingside is forever weakened and in most of the cases, the extra pawn is irrelevant.}) 5. Qe2 {A thematic move, preparing queenside castling and gearing towards an eventual recapture of the e4-pawn. This is the tabiya of the Open Horwitz and will be the topic of four chapters in this course.} *

