{Welcome! In this informational variation, we want to give you a light and easy overview of the variations we are going to cover in the following theoretical chapters.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 ({In his Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense course, Giri considered the position after} 5. Qe2 {to be White's optimal set-up and deviated with 3...Nc6 . Other authors like Yuriy Krykun and Kamil Plichta seem to share this opinion. Black has tried multiple options in this position. They are covered in three chapters: 1) 5th move alternatives 2) 5...Bb4 3) 5...Be7}) 5... Be7 {The most played move by a wide margin. Black sensibly develops the bishop and prepares to castle.} (5... Nc6 {Black intends ...Nd4 to hit the c2-pawn. Leaving White with no time to take the e4-pawn.} 6. O-O-O Nd4 7. Qe3 {A new idea. 7.Qe1 is the traditional way of handling such positions.}) (5... Nbd7 {Threatens ...Nc5 to hold on to the e4-pawn and forces White to recoup the pawn immediately.} 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 {- 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage. - 7.Qxe4 Nf6 Attacking the centralized queen. White has many squares to choose from, but after a process of analysis and elimination we recommend 8.Qh4 The queen is ideally placed to support a future kingside attack. More details are available in the theory chapter.}) (5... Bb4 {Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {falls to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. O-O-O Avoiding the trick and preparing to take on e4. Qe7 Black prepares ...Ba3, swapping off the powerful Horwitz bishop. 6...Bxc3 A highly concrete try. At the cost of allowing us an uncontested dark-squared bishop Black holds on to the extra pawn. 7.dxc3 The right recapture, gaining a tempo on the queen! We'll proceed with g4-g5, h4, c4 and Bg2 with sufficient compensation for the pawn. 7.Nxe4 Ba3 Black manages to swap off the dark squares bishops, but this is not the end of the world. 8.Nxf6+ Qxf6 The a3-bishop cannot be captured on account of the mate on a1. 9.d4 The critical position for the 5...Bb4 variation, which is examined carefully here [/course/82991/27].}) 6. Nxe4 ({Many people are tempted to go} 6. O-O-O {right away, which we believe is a slight inaccuracy. White should grab the e4-pawn first instead of committing the king. We'll explain this nuance in depth in the 5...Be7 chapter [/course/82991/28].}) 6... O-O 7. Nf3 {A logical developing move. Note that White still refrains from castling, although the first player has run out of useful moves now and will likely castle queenside on the next move. We've reached the key starting position of the 5...Be7 variation. Black has numerous options at this point: ( 7...Nc6 , 7...Nbd7 , 7...a5 and 7...b6 . They may even transpose into each other, which makes it confusing for a reader who would like to study this position move-by-move. Instead, we recommend you take a different approach. First, go through this introduction chapter to grasp the basic concepts of the variation. Next, learn all the lines in the theory chapter. Lastly and most importantly, practice and fix! After obtaining knowledge, you should put it into use by playing training games and analysing them afterwards.} *

