1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {The Open Horwitz is a rich battleground. There are many different positional themes, dynamic tactics, guerilla sacrifices as well as subtle nuances and move orders in this variation. Because of the practical relevance (3...dxe4 is by far the most popular move), it's highly important for you to understand both sides's plans and develop a feeling of harmony for White's pieces - basically an intuitive compass that helps us decide where to put a piece, should we start an attack or defend first, exchange or not. In 2023, vague ideas alone are not enough to handle any sensible opening variation though. It needs to be backed up with concrete lines and a lot of details. When presenting a lot of trainable lines, our purpose is NOT to have you memorising everything and gaining loads of XP. Instead, by going through many concrete trainables, we want you to understand the general ideas and fix them in your mind. At the board, no opening course can support you forever. We want you to get a promising position out of the opening. But more importantly, we want you to navigate the arising middlegame well. And that is the purpose of this section - to understand both sides's plans and develop a feeling of harmony in the Open Horwitz.} 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {Because of the opposite-sided castling (White will castle queenside and Black on the kingside), attacking Black's king is a natural theme to consider. In most cases, we need to balance aggression with defending against Black's counterplay at other sectors of the board. However, if the second player plays some senseless moves, a successful attack can be carried out smoothly, as shown in the following model game.} *

