{I want to show you this blitz game, as it's one of the best among my collection of Horwitz games. With this win, I became the Eastern Asia Youth champion, my first international success. In this game, I played with a clear attacking plan and facing slow play from my opponent, I crushed him on the kingside in thematic Horwitz fashion. I'm proud of this game, especially given the 3+2 time control.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 {The Horwitz Attack is a perfect choice for such an important game, since it's blitz and 2. b3 will cost your opponents at least some seconds.} d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {5....Be7 is statistically Black's most popular line against the Horwitz Attack.} 6. Nxe4 O-O 7. Nf3 {Everything has gone according to plan so far...} Nbd7 8. O-O-O {This is a small inaccuracy on my part. I played 8. O-O-O too quickly and automatically, while White should have delayed castling until the best moment.} (8. Nxf6+ {We recommend this move in the theory section, and you can find out the nuances there.}) 8... Nxe4 (8... b6 $1 {is more accurate, when the position is balanced.}) 9. Qxe4 Bf6 {Black prepares an exchange of dark-squared bishops, which is something we dislike in the Open Horwitz. Firstly, our bishop has much more potential and secondly, the bishop isn't well-placed on f6. Black doesn't have the option to meet Bd3 with ...Nf6.} (9... Nf6 {would have prevented White from attacking so easily.}) 10. d4 {Preventing an exchange and I intended to follow up with Bd3, creating a hook for me to open lines on the kingside.} Re8 11. Bd3 Nf8 {Black has managed to defend h7 with extreme passivity. He has defended against our first attacking wave, but has no counterplay on the queenside. It's high time to roll our kingside pawns!} 12. g4 $1 {White's plans in such positions are very straightforward and lethal at the same time. We push our kingside pawns with g4-g5-g6, supported by h4-h5 and smash Black's king cover. If Black does not find counterplay in time, he can go down very quickly, as this game demonstrates.} Qd5 {A queen exchange would ease Black's defensive tasks. Needless to say, I had no intentions of allowing it.} 13. Qe2 Qa5 14. Kb1 Ng6 15. Qe3 {Tidying up our position against ...Nf4. Black's f6-bishop and g6-knight are both clumsily placed. They fail to defend the kingside - in fact, we'll gain lots of time kicking those pieces back.} Bd7 16. h4 $1 {Forward! Note the incredible difference in activity between White's and Black's pieces. Black has not managed to create the slightest hint of play, while White is ready to storm the barricade.} Bc6 17. g5 Be7 18. h5 {In the past few moves, I've launched a powerful and winning attack. It's time to break through.} Nf8 19. g6 {Smashing the kingside!} fxg6 20. hxg6 h6 {Here, I ended the game with a swashbuckling sacrifice. I found, calculated and executed this sac in less than 20 seconds, which is something I am happy about. Hint: White has many wins here, but try to see how we can include the deadly Horwitz bishop in the battle.} 21. d5 $3 {A line-clearing strike that opens up the long diagonal. Next is Bxg7 when Black's kingside collapses.} (21. Rxh6 $1 {Is another pretty win.}) 21... Qxd5 22. Bxg7 Bg5 23. Nxg5 Qxg5 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. Bf6 {The final nail in the coffin. Mate is inevitable, so my opponent stopped the clock. Key takeaways from this game: 1) Black should have a knight on f6 to guard his king. 2) The battery with Bd3 and Qe4 is very strong, threatening checkmate on h7. 3) The plan of g4-h4 is simple but lethal. Black cannot prevent White from opening lines on the kingside. The blow d5!! is pretty as well, but at that point Black's kingside is so weak that many moves win. 4) Black played some random moves (Qd5-a5, Bd7-c6, Nf8-g6) and gave White a lot of time to execute the attack. This game is a great example and demonstrates many thematic ideas for White. Note that except for the final combination 21. d5!!, I didn't even sacrifice a single pawn in the game! However, in most games, Black usually does not allow White to storm the kingside so easily. Therefore, a victorious assault on Black's king sometimes has to include the element of a sacrifice. Let's move on!} *

