1. e4 {In this game, White is the Georgian grandmaster Tamaz Gelashvilli, a supporter of 2. b3 against the French.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 6. O-O-O {We will explain in the dedicated theory chapter why we consider 6. Nxe4 to be a more accurate move-order. The general point is that we should not commit the king so early when not forced to.} (6. Nxe4 {is more precise, as shown here [/course/82991/28].}) 6... O-O 7. g4 $5 {Tamaz launched his kingside forces. The threat is g4-g5, kicking the best defender of the kingside away and allowing White's queen to take on e4. 7.Nxe4 would be the more solid way of handling the game.} c5 $6 {Wasting time and blocking the scope of the e7-bishop.} (7... Nc6 {preparing ...Nd4, hitting White's queen.} 8. g5 {The line continues with a very complex game. Check out this game to see another instructive demolition of Black's kingside.}) 8. g5 {It's a huge success for White to kick this annoying knight away. White is now able to take with the queen on e4, thus setting up the killer Qe4+Bd3 battery.} Nd5 9. h4 {First, stabilizing the g5-pawn before taking on e4. If Black ever plays ...g6 in the future then White has the reply h5, opening up the kingside.} Nc6 10. Qxe4 {The threat is bishop to d3! Because of his inaccurate play in the opening, Black had fallen into serious trouble. At this point, he needed to commit a weakening on the kingside to temporarily prevent White from invading his castle.} f5 {Deep in his bones, the black player must have felt sad about making this move, which allows White to open the g-file and makes the e6-pawn a juicy target.} 11. gxf6 Nxf6 12. Qg2 $1 {Excellent judgement by Tamaz Gelashvili. 12. Qg2! places the queen on a great square, where Her Majesty eyes the sensitive g7-square. Moreover, on g2 it does not obstruct the development of other white pieces. The knight is coming out followed by Rg1 and Bd3. If we count, White has six pieces ready for the attack, which is an indicator of success.} a6 $2 {Too weak too slow. Black's situation is horrible enough, but it truly becomes desperate after this nonsense move.} 13. Nf3 ({There are a number of good choices for White -} 13. h5 {and}) (13. Bd3 {are promising alternatives. The rook is coming to g1 and how is Black going to deal with the threat of checkmate on g7?}) 13... Qc7 14. Rg1 {Qxg7# is on the table.} Ne8 $2 {Black prepares ...Bf6 to hold the kingside together, but there is simply no time. We want to share this 'secret' about the Open Horwitz structure as soon as we can. The so-called Horwitz bishop, the b2-bishop, is White's magical piece. This bishop simultaneously defend our king and points at Black's king. As you will see in this model game - and some of our trainables later on - a clearance sacrifice to open up the long diagonal for the b2-bishop can prove decisive.} (14... Bd8 {Black should have tried this.} 15. Bd3 {However White's attack is already unstoppable. h5 is coming, even as a sacrifice to open up lines.}) 15. Nd5 $3 {This clearance sacrifice is a real thunderbolt. But the follow-up is truly amazing.} exd5 {Black must accept the offer, otherwise White takes on g7 with the bishop for free.} 16. Qxg7+ $3 {(in GothamChess style) And now White sacrifices...THE QUEEN!} (16. Bxg7 $2 {would not do it, since} Bh3 $1 {a cunning deflection sacrifice that wins the game for Black. With this queen sacrifice, White sets up a windmill tactic that will clear up Black's pieces on the 7th rank. By the way, windmill is one of the coolest tactics out there, make sure to study it.}) 16... Nxg7 17. Rxg7+ {Seven, heaven for the rook.} Kh8 18. Rxe7+ {Getting the queen back.} d4 19. Rxc7 Rxf3 {In the next phase of the game, the white player played with great accuracy.} 20. Bg2 Rxf2 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Rxc6 {Black's pawns are being cleared up.} Rf5 23. Rg1 {This seals the deal - cutting Black's king of completely. The main threat is Rxc5, followed by Bxd4+ and if there is no mate yet, White is three connected passed pawns up in the ending. Black's decision to resign here is understandable. Key takeaways from this game: 1) Black drifted into trouble early because he made no attempt to stop White's kingside expansions and later commited a tragic weakening with ...f5, which White exploited. 2) The Horwitz bishop is a magic piece - respect it! 3) 15. Nd5!! followed by 16. Qxg7+!! is a fabulous combination that could only be played by a player with good tactical/ calculation skills.} 1-0

