1... a4 {White's last move, Bf1-d3, contains a nasty tactical threat which Black missed.} 2. Bxh7+ $1 {A standard Greek Gift, destroying Black's king shelter and winning on the spot.} Kxh7 3. Qh5+ Kg8 4. Ng5 {Threatening checkmate on h7. Black's unfortunate queen blocks her own king's escape route via f8-e7, so Black is forced to give up the queen.} Qxg5 (4... Rd8 5. Qh7+ Kf8 6. Qh8#) 5. Qxg5 {And White won easily. As you have seen from these examples, a piece sacrifice on g7/h7 is thematic in the Open Horwitz structure. Especially when White's attack is at an advanced stage, a forcing sacrifice is often the way to finish Black, as we've seen in Huy, B - Hoa, D and Gelashvilli, T - Deniz, M.} 1-0

