{Earlier in the opening, White has sacrificed a pawn with d2-d3 to rapidly get his pieces out, which is indeed a thematic idea. Black has installed a strong knight on d4 which obstructs several lines for the white pieces. How to get rid of this annoying horse?} 10. Nf3 $1 {Challenging the d4-knight head to head. In the opening stage, time is everything. The importance of pawn structure is far too exaggerated. White certainly does not mind wrecking the pawn structure to win crucial time.} Nxf3 $2 {Black overestimated the value of his extra pawn and better pawn structure.} (10... O-O 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nb5 $14 {White gets back the pawn and his position is more pleasant, but at least Black can finish development.}) 11. gxf3 {Discoveries are looming on the d-file. Rg1 is another threat when it's surprisingly difficult to defend g7. White's initiative is very dangerous and he has more than enough compensation for the pawn. The game ended quickly after a blunder by Black. After all it's only a blitz game :(} Qc7 12. Rg1 g6 13. Nb5 (13. Ne4 {Wins the exchange by force.} Qf4+ 14. Qe3 Qxe3+ 15. fxe3 Nxe4 16. Bb5+ Kf8 17. Bxh8 $16) 13... Qf4+ 14. Kb1 a6 $4 (14... O-O 15. Be5 Qxf3 16. Rg3 Qh5 17. f4 $13) 15. Be5 {Oops. White wins thanks to the fork on c7. A clear rook up, White has no reason to complain about his otherwise broken structure on the kingside. This beautiful miniature illustrates the value of development in the opening stage. The greedy black player showed a preference for material and was punished.} 1-0

