{We see grandmaster Tu, one of Vietnam's first GMs, handling the white side in this game.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 {is what we propose.}) 6... O-O 7. g4 Nc6 ({We have just seen Black getting crushed after} 7... c5 $6 {in this model game [/variation/25618978].}) {Black wants to flank aggression with central play - Nd4 is coming.} 8. g5 Nd4 9. Qe1 {Putting the queen on e1 doesn't expose Her Majesty to harassment from the knights, but the queen is a bit passive here.} (9. Qe3 {e3 is a better square for the queen, where it protects the g5-pawn and is ready to swing to g3. It appears that the critical line is} Nf5 10. gxf6 $1 {An inspired positional queen 'sacrifice' for three minor pieces.} Nxe3 11. fxe7 Qxe7 12. fxe3 $13 {A totally unclear situation. It's not clear whether three minor pieces outweigh queen and two pawns.}) 9... Ne8 {The knight doesn't have much to do on e8 at the moment.} (9... Nh5 {is an alternative.}) 10. h4 {Supporting the g5-pawn and creating the threat of Qxe4.} f5 $2 {A positional mistake. Black held on to the extra pawn but neglected his development.} 11. d3 $1 {The turning point of the game. Exploiting Black's clumsy coordination, White pitched a pawn to open up the d-file. The pawn sacrifice is strong and a thematic idea you should definitely be aware of.} exd3 12. Rxd3 c5 13. Nf3 $1 {Removing the obstacle on d4, the knight that is holding Black's position together.} Nxf3 14. Rxf3 $16 {The smoke has cleared and White is clearly better, despite the pawn deficit. With Bc4, Rd3 and Ne2-f4 on the way, Black's kingside is under huge pressure. Black's minor pieces are horrendously placed, especially the c8-bishop. Key takeaway: when Black holds on to the e4-pawn, do not be afraid to simply sacrifice the pawn with d3! The compensation we get is usually worth much more than the investment. Feel free to check out the remainder of this game. Grandmaster Tu's technique was not perfect, but eventually, he won the battle.} Nc7 15. Rd3 Bd7 16. f4 $5 (16. Qd2 $1 Bc6 17. Rxd8 Raxd8 18. Qe3 Bxh1 19. Nb5) 16... Ne8 17. Qe5 Bd6 $2 18. Rxd6 Nxd6 19. Ne4 Ne8 20. Nxc5 {White is completely winning despite the exchange down.} b6 21. Nxe6 Bxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. h5 Qc7 24. Be5 Qb7 25. Rh3 Rc8 26. h6 (26. Bc4 $1) 26... Rc6 27. hxg7+ Nxg7 28. Bxg7+ Qxg7 29. Qxc6 Qa1+ 30. Kd2 Qxf1 31. Qc3+ (31. Qd6 $1 Kg8 32. Re3) 31... Kg8 32. Qc4+ Qxc4 33. bxc4 Rc8 34. Kd3 Rc5 35. Kd4 Ra5 36. Rc3 Rxa2 37. c5 {The rook endgame is winning for White.} bxc5+ 38. Rxc5 Kg7 39. Ke5 Kg6 40. Rc6+ Kh5 41. Kxf5 Ra5+ 42. Ke4 Kg4 43. g6 hxg6 44. Rxg6+ Kh5 45. Rc6 Ra1 46. c4 a5 47. Kf5 a4 48. Rc8 Kh6 49. Kf6 Kh5 50. f5 a3 51. Rh8+ Kg4 52. Rh2 Rc1 53. Kg6 Kf4 54. f6 Ke5 55. f7 Rg1+ 56. Kh7 Rf1 57. Kg8 Rg1+ 58. Kf8 Kd4 59. Rf2 Rb1 60. Kg7 Rb8 61. Ra2 Kxc4 62. Rxa3 Rb7 63. Kg8 Kd5 64. f8=Q Rb1 65. Qf5+ Kd6 66. Qxb1 Kd5 {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

