{The moment of castling is a difficult nuance to understand in the Open Horwitz. As you might have known/will know, after the regular opening moves 1.e4 e6 2.b3 d5 3.Bb2 dxe4 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Qe2 we present a simple rule of thumb: if possible, delay O-O-O by taking the e4-pawn first. We never want to commit the king to the queenside too early, since Black may quickly launch a pawn storm there. A similar problem awaits Black: when should he castles kingside? Obviously, the h8-rook needs to join the game, but ...O-O exposes a clear target for White to attack.} 11... O-O $2 {Castling into the attack?! A huge strategic mistake from Daniel Fridman, a 2600 Grandmaster. With a great queen on e4, White is only one move away from building a battery with Qe4 and Bd3.} (11... Bd7 {Black should have preferred the approach of queenside castling.}) 12. h4 {Strengthening White's position on the kingside and making sure that ...g6 can be met by h5, blasting open the h-file.} Rd8 13. c3 {Carefully covering the d4 pawn.} Bd7 14. Bd3 {As easy as that! White has a decisive advantage while we're not yet at move 15. The threat of Qxh7 forces Black to make some unfortunate decisions on the kingside.} h6 15. Qh7+ (15. g4 {potentially even stronger.}) 15... Kf8 16. Rhe1 {White is planning Ne5 and even Re3-f3. In the game, the first player crashed through on the kingside with a series of spectacular sacrifices. We recommend you to play through the rest of the game. The key takeaway from this example has been made: after a few inaccuracies in the opening, Black's decision to castle kingside was surprisingly fatal. When Black castles kingside in this structure, White should always look out for opportunities to start a kingside attack immediately.} Ne7 17. Ne5 Bc6 18. Re3 Qxf2+ 19. Re2 Qg3 20. Qh8+ Ng8 21. Ng6+ fxg6 22. Rf1+ Ke7 23. Qxg7+ Kd6 24. c4 Bxg2 25. c5+ Kc6 26. Rxe6+ Rd6 27. cxd6 cxd6 28. Rc1+ Kb6 29. Qc7# {1-0 White wins.} 1-0

