1. e4 e6 {Grandmaster Luka Paichadze is a connoisseur of the Horwitz Attack. He is one of the highest-rated players to play 2. b3 against the French on a regular basis. This rapid game was contested in the PRO Chess League, before Covid-19 was a thing. With this win, GM Luka scored a valuable point for his team: Tbilisi Gentlemen.} 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 6. O-O-O {We've emphasised many times earlier that 6.Nxe4 [/course/82991/28] is the 'correct' move.} a5 7. a4 Nc6 8. Nxe4 O-O 9. Nf3 {Playing sensible moves, Black had gottẹn a fine position out of the opening. However, on the very next move he went astray.} Nxe4 $2 {A typical positional error. Black voluntarily traded a key piece and centralized White's queen.} 10. Qxe4 Bf6 {Perhaps this was the point, to exchange the bishops as well?!} 11. d4 {Keeping the bishops on the board to emphasise White's space advantage. Bd3 is threatened, provoking a weakness on the kingside.} Qd5 {Black logically decides to trade queens.} 12. Bd3 {Paichadze decided to allow the queen exchange right away, which is not a bad choice since in the resulting position, White's minor pieces occupy better positions than their counterpart.} (12. Qe3 $5 {By preserving the queens, White maintains attacking possibilities on the kingside.}) 12... Qxe4 13. Bxe4 {Black has one especially bad piece: the c8-bishop. It is locked behind the pawn chain and it is far from easy for Black to activate this piece. Moreover, the c6-knight and f6-bishop are not optimally placed either. White has a useful space advantage and superior piece coordination. Therefore White's position is much better. In the next phase of the game, the grandmaster playing White was patient and accurate, putting pressure on Black's position. It's worth it to watch carefully.} Nb4 14. Rhe1 {Centralization!} Rd8 15. Ne5 {The knight is dominant on e5. Black does not want to play ...Bxe5 and gives up the bishop pair at all.} c6 16. g3 Bd7 17. Kb1 Be8 18. f4 $1 {At the pace of a sculptor, Paichadze strengthened his grip on the position. Black's issue is that he has no active plan at all to pursue. Therefore, there is no need for White to be quick.} Rab8 19. c3 Nd5 20. c4 Nb4 {Black hinted at counterplay with ...b5.} 21. Bc3 {A strong prophylactic move, preventing ...b5 due to tactical reasons.} Be7 {Black prepares the ...c5 break as well as ...f6, driving the strong knight back.} (21... b5 $2 {Black tries to open up the queenside.} 22. Bxb4 $1 {Removing the guard. Thanks to this simple tactic White wins the c6-pawn.} axb4 {22...Bxe5? 23.Bxa5+- nets While a whole exchange.} 23. Bxc6 {Many pieces are hanging in this position! However, simple calculation reveals that White is better. The critical line runs} bxa4 {23...Bxe5 24.Bxe8 Bf6 25.Bxb5+- White is comfortably one pawn up and is completely winning. a4-a5-a6 is coming.} 24. Bxe8 Rxe8 25. bxa4 Ra8 {The critical position that needed to be evaluated when White embarked on the tactical operation starting with 22. Bxb4. Black regains the pawn by force, but his b4-pawn is lost in the long run and White has a powerful c-pawn ready to march down the board.} 26. Kb2 $1 {Preparing mass exchanges on the a-file.} Rxa4 27. Ra1 Rxa1 28. Rxa1 {Black cannot stop the simple idea of Kb3xb4 and c5-c6, simply promoting the c-pawn. White wins the endgame by force.}) 22. c5 $1 {A great positional judgement. Paichadze gave up the d5 square to restrict Black's bishops even further and gain the c4 square for the knight. The a5-pawn is a new target.} f6 23. Nc4 Bh5 24. Rd2 Kf7 25. Nxa5 {White had won a pawn and converted his advantage with good technique.} Nd5 26. Bb2 Rd7 27. Nc4 Rbd8 28. h3 Bg6 29. Bxg6+ hxg6 30. Rde2 Rh8 31. h4 Nc7 32. Bc3 Rh5 33. Ba5 Bf8 34. Bxc7 Rxc7 35. Rxe6 Rd5 36. Nd6+ Bxd6 37. cxd6 Rc8 38. Re7+ Kg8 39. d7 Rf8 40. R1e4 Rd6 41. Kc2 f5 42. R4e6 Rxe6 43. Rxe6 Kf7 44. Re8 {An impressive performance! We can recap the game as follows: 1) Black's ...Nxe4 was premature and is a very popular mistake. 2) White stood better in the queenless middlegame and showed excellent positional chess, provoking one weakness after another before eventually crashing through Black's defence.} 1-0

