{We will end the chapter with a classical masterpiece by Rudolf Spielmann, one of the earliest pioneers of 2. b3 against the French. As a matter of fact, 2. b3 is also known as the Spielmann variation.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Bb4 6. O-O-O Qe7 7. Nxe4 Ba3 {All theory so far.} 8. Nf3 $5 {The German master 'deviated' from our recommendation of 8. Nxf6+. However, the nature of the position remained the same.} Bxb2+ $6 {A strategic error. Black should have kept the bishops so he would have the option of ...a5 later.} (8... Nbd7 {Appears to be a refinement to Black's play.}) 9. Kxb2 Nbd7 10. d4 {White made his claim for the central e5-square!} O-O 11. Ne5 {Spielmann indirectly prevented the ...c5 break, which Black went for anyway.} c5 $6 {The typical French strike to gain freedom in the center. However, in this position, Black's pieces are not ready for the opening of the center.} 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qe3 {White has a huge positional advantage. Black's c8-bishop and d7-knight are both badly placed, while the c5-pawn is hanging.} cxd4 (13... b6 14. Bb5 {Threatening to take on d7 and Black would still be under tremendous pressure.}) 14. Qxd4 {Spielmann has got a great position out of the opening! White's knight is ready to jump into the juicy d6 square. The only open file on the board is firmly under White's control, while the pawn majorities favour White as well since in the endgame, White can create an outside passed pawn.} e5 $6 {A further mistake by Black in a cramped position. This move seriously weakened the f7 point, which would ultimately lead to Black's demise.} (14... Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. Rd6 b6 18. Bb5 $16) 15. Qd6 {We could not believe that White's advantage is 3+ here according to Stockfish.} Qxd6 16. Nxd6 {With the knight on d6, bishop coming to c4 and Rhe1, Black has no chance to survive.} Nf6 17. Bc4 Bd7 18. Rhe1 {Perfect centralisation.} Bc6 19. Rxe5 {White is a comfortable pawn up and the devastating threat is Re7, winning the house.} Rad8 {Black pins the knight on the d-file.} 20. Rd3 $1 {Rudolf was alert and chose the most precise way to eliminate Black's counterplay. The point is that the d3-rook is defended now, so the d6-knight is no longer under a pin.} (20. Re7 $4 {A tempting move to play, but suddenly Black has the resource} Ne4 $1 {Exploiting the pin on the d-file and it turns out that White cannot avoid losses of material, after which the position will be roughly equal.} 21. Bxf7+ Rxf7 22. Rxf7 Rxd6 $13) 20... Bxg2 21. Re7 {Rooks on the 7th rank means money in the bank! Material is equal, but beside the main threat of taking the f7-pawn, White is also ready to chew up b7 and a7.} Bf1 22. Bxf7+ Rxf7 (22... Kh8 23. Rd2 {Does not change the evaluation of the position. White threatens Rxb7 as well as Be6, preparing a nasty check with the knight on f7.}) 23. Nxf7 {Black threw in the towel. White was counterattacking Black's rook on d8 and remained an exchange up. A timeless game by master Rudolf Spielmann!} 1-0

