1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 {)} ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. The astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database only adds misery to Black's cause.}) 5... Bb4 {A possible try to avoid our fierce attack in the mainline. However, we can just capture the e4-pawn with a clear plus due to Black's wrecked structure.} 6. dxe4 {Granted, we should accept the generous offer from Black.} Qxd1+ {What else? Otherwise, we would exchange on d8 ourselves when Black's king would be misplaced.} 7. Rxd1 {Wow! 7 moves into the game, we've managed to bring the whole queenside army out and open the d-file as well as the a1-h8 diagonal for us. Meanwhile, Black would really love to put his f5-pawn back at f7 when he would have some chances of equalizing, but as it turns out, the pawn is just a structural weakness.} fxe4 ({If Black tries to avoid the long-term weakness with} 7... Nf6 {, the punishment would be even more severe:} 8. exf5 $1 exf5 9. a3 $1 {and with Nf3 and Bc4 to come, White has a crushing lead in development. Such lines illustrate the lightning power of the Horwitz: we bring our pieces into the game quickly and furiously in a healthy manner, and then our opponent inevitably crumbles.}) 8. a3 $5 {There are other ways to exploit Black's positional liability, but we prefer this direct continuation as it forces Black to play accurately and reveal his hands.} Ba5 $2 {This passive retreat is quite popular online, even though White has a convincing route to a decisive advantage.} 9. b4 $1 {Against other retreats, we could safely chew up the e4-pawn, but this time Nxe4 would be illegal due to the pin. Therefore, we must kick the bishop offside before grabbing that pawn.} Bb6 10. Nxe4 {White already has a crushing initiative. Black has only developed the dark-squared bishop, but actually, it's doing nothing on b6, and the g7-pawn lacks a defender. Moving the king allows all sorts of Rd8+ and Ng5+ ideas, but otherwise the g7-pawn is simply lost and with it, the game. Actually, the engine's suggestion for Black is to enter a pawn down endgame with} Z0 (10... Nf6 {, but after} 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 {we have a cute trick:} 12. Rd8+ $3 {and White wins in all lines after recapturing the sacrificed material. What a brilliant win after just ten moves! We promise that more than one Francophile has fallen for the trick, so remember it! It shows that the Open Horwitz is full of pitfalls for Black to avoid - while our pieces come out naturally in a flash.}) *

