r pieces into the game quickly and furiously in a healthy manner, and then our opponent inevitably crumbles.}) 8. a3 $5 {There are other ways to exploit Black's positional liability, but we prefer this direct continuation as it forces Black to play accurately and reveal his hands.} Bxc3+ {The only way for Black to survive, but it allows us an uncontested and powerful Horwitz bishop on the long diagonal.} 9. Bxc3 {)} Nf6 ({The most natural and best way to defend the g7-pawn. If you're wondering how to meet the cheeky} 9... Kf7 $2 {, let us deliver the winning recipe:} 10. f3 $1 exf3 11. Nxf3 Nf6 12. Bc4 $1 {and the horribly misplaced king won't survive the assault.}) 10. f3 $1 {Energetically open the centre, so the value of our development lead becomes higher.} exf3 $6 {We expect you to face this kind of overambitious move very often in practice, so this trainable is devoted to how to develop our initiative. Black grabs the pawn and wants to run away with it, but we won't allow that king to escape!} 11. Nxf3 O-O 12. Bc4 {Our bishop is best placed on c4, where it eyes the e6-pawn. We're preparing to castle when the whole army would be ready for the battle. Meanwhile, Black's queenside is struggling to get out and the e6-pawn is a juicy target. There's no doubt White's already better; the only question is the extent of our advantage.} Nc6 13. O-O $16 {White owns a great initiative with Ng5 to come. Black would love to develop the notorious French bishop with 11...Bd7 , but it's clear that the Horwitz bishop is the star of the show when we finish Black off with 12.Bxf6! followed by Rxd7. Instead, ( 11...Nd5!? is a better try with the idea of sacrificing a pawn to neutralize our initiative. We should calmly react with 12.Bd2! covering the e3-square and slowly push Black's pieces back with Rfe1, Bd3 and eventually, expanding with b4 and c4.} *

