t fine; however, we'll prove that his task is much harder than it may appear.} 8. Nge2 (8. Nb5 {is the most popular move, but Black has the nice resource} Bb4+ $1 9. c3 Ba5 {when the c7-pawn is defended while our knight isn't well placed on b5 at all. The text move is much more logical - we're threatening the simple Ng3 to win the pawn. Let's check two ways Black can defend it, either via ...Bb7 or ...Bb4. Otherwise, we should follow the simple plan of Ng3 and Nxe4.}) 8... b6 {Black prepares to fianchetto the light-squared bishop to defend the e4-pawn. However, the plan is practically inaccurate and rather slow. Black indeed holds here after playing with fire for a while, but no one would ever like to defend Black's position in practice.} 9. Ng3 (9. g4 $5 {is a hyper-active idea worth considering. The text move is simple and logical enough.}) 9... Bb7 10. Bc4 $1 {Continuing to put maximum pressure on Black's position. With castling to come, all our pieces would coordinate together wonderfully while Black's are still lagging in development.} Kf7 $1 {Ironically, what Black should do is spend a tempo with the king to hang on to the extra material. Otherwise, we can chew up the e6-pawn when the e4-pawn wouldn't survive for long. After the text move, our trusted silicon friends show 'only' a small edge for White, but the initiative is incredibly tough to handle in practice.} 11. Nb5 {We suggest inserting Nb5 and …Na6 before castling, as Black's queenside knight will become inactive and dim on the rim of the board.} Na6 ({Black doesn't have much choice actually, as} 11... Ne8 $2 12. O-O {is simply disastrous with Rfe1 to follow.}) 12. O-O $13 {White has more than full compensation for the sacrificed pawn. The immediate threat is Bxf6 followed by Rd7, invading the 7th rank. If the bishop comes to c5, a3+b4 will chase it away. Moreover, we have plenty of independent ideas like Nd4, Ngf5 and even f3 to open the dangerous f-file. Overall, even without the queens, White has great chances here to whip up an attacking miniature against Black's king, which is sitting in an unhappy place.} *

