1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. The astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database only adds misery to Black's cause.}) 5... Nf6 {A tame way to return the pawn. Honestly, we think that once Black goes for the greedy 4...f5, it's best to accept a pawn and not play like a wuss afterwards. However, the text move is still practically acceptable and objectively fine.} 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 {It's just a comfortable edge for White after Black captures on e4. Even though our advantage might not be that large according to the engine, Black's position is suspect in the long term and our positional superiority is a trump we can milk for the whole game.} fxe4 $1 {This time, the greedy decision is the correct one. White's structure is preferable in the long-term, but we're a pawn down at the moment. Our goal is to round up the e4-pawn, but Black has his time to support it too. If the e4-pawn falls, then our opening can be considered a success. The battle will revolve around the central pawn, with chances for both sides. Quoting the engine, Black is just fine; however, we'll prove that his task is much harder than it may appear.} 8. Nge2 (8. Nb5 {is the most popular move, but Black has the nice resource} Bb4+ $1 9. c3 Ba5 {when the c7-pawn is defended while our knight isn't well placed on b5 at all. The text move is much more logical - we're threatening the simple Ng3 to win the pawn. Let's check two ways Black can defend it, either via ...Bb7 or ...Bb4. Otherwise, we should follow the simple plan of Ng3 and Nxe4.}) 8... Nc6 {There are other moves, but we're going to put them in the category of …Bb4 lines anyway, as Black cannot let the e4-pawn drop off.} 9. Ng3 Bb4 ({Pinning the knight and preventing Nxe4 for now.} 9... e3 $5 {is a boring attempt to equalize after} 10. fxe3 {. However, White is still leading in development and can count on our superior activity for an edge. Next up is Be2 and Nce4, when Black hasn't fully equalised yet.}) 10. a3 {As usual, we go for the bishop pair immediately.} Bxc3+ {Black should take up the challenge as 11...Be7 12.Ncxe4 is a free positional advantage for White. The e6-pawn is a target in the middlegame and even the endgame.} 11. Bxc3 {Our threat is to play Bb5 and damage Black's structure via Bxc6 and Bxf6. At this point, we can stop the line and claim that White's opening has been a success, as we have great compensation for the pawn deficit and our position is easy to handle. Allow us to show a sample line:} Ke7 12. f3 $5 {Any move that develops the f1-bishop is completely fine, but we cannot resist introducing another gambit to open some lines.} exf3 13. gxf3 Rd8 14. Bd3 {Avoiding the rook exchange as we are a pawn down.} e5 15. Kf2 $13 {We'll combine central play with Rde1 and queenside expansion with b4-b5. The e5-pawn is the point where our attacking forces meet, so it's tough for Black to maintain it.} *

