1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. The astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database only adds misery to Black's cause.}) 5... exd3 6. Nf3 $5 ({Black accepts the challenge and grabs yet another pawn. At this point,} 6. Bxd3 {is exclusively played, scoring over 65% for White in the databases. That's an impressive score, isn't it? The task of the authors would be easy in this case: give a few flashy lines backed up by the stats and conclude that White has great compensation there. However, we do anything but recommend continuations that have already been well-established. Similar to Huy's Spielmann-Indian course, we aim to give you unexplored and strong continuations, which will shock your opponents and increase the chance of them going wrong. Fasten your seatbelts, we're going to offer a lovely double gambit!}) 6... dxc2 $6 ({Playing in a romantic style. This continuation hasn't been known to the chess world yet, at least before the publication of this course. We offer the c2-pawn, reasoning that it would accelerate our queenside development and allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring a fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge...yet another time.}) {What can we say? Black has played over-greedily, he must be punished.} 7. Qxc2 {One feature we like about the 4...f5 variation is that it allows White to play based on natural and systematic moves to exploit the weakened kingside, instead of memorizing tons of theory. As castling queenside is denied now, we'll go Bc4 and O-O next, followed by Rfe1 and Rad1. With the queen included, we've developed four pieces compared to a whopping zero from Black.} Bb4 {Let's see our plan in action.} 8. Bc4 Nc6 9. O-O {Step one is completed: the king is brought to safety. Next, the rooks will come to the open files, and Black will suffer.} Nf6 10. Rad1 Qe7 11. Rfe1 $16 Z0 ({Black's position is in ruins, as the French pawn won't survive much longer. Black's king is caught in the fire, even if he castles. Next, we'll go Ng5 when it's hard to believe Black can do anything to stop the decisive strike. The only detail for you to remember is that the tricky} 11... Ne4 $5 {can be met with the wonderful} 12. Nxe4 $1 Bxe1 13. Ng3 $1 {when despite being a pawn and an exchange down, White has the advantage as the bishop is nearly trapped. If Black goes} Ba5 {,} 14. a3 $1 {is the quiet killer when Black cannot do anything to stop b4 followed by Nxf5 and Re1, winning the queen. What a deep concept!}) *

