t, at least before the publication of this course. We offer the c2-pawn, reasoning that it would accelerate our queenside development and allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring a fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge...yet another time.}) {What can we say? Black has played over-greedily, he must be punished.} 7. Qxc2 {One feature we like about the 4...f5 variation is that it allows White to play based on natural and systematic moves to exploit the weakened kingside, instead of memorizing tons of theory. As castling queenside is denied now, we'll go ( Bc4 and O-O next followed by Rfe1 and Rad1 . With the queen included, we've developed four pieces compared to a whopping zero from Black.} Nf6 8. Bc4 Bd6 {Black tries to block the d-file with the bishop, but it allows us to castle queenside.} 9. O-O-O {White's coordination makes a pleasant picture: every piece is performing at its best. Love your pawns and pieces, play the Horwitz, and they'll bring you such amazing positions!} Nc6 10. Rhe1 Qe7 $1 (10... O-O $2 11. Ng5 $1 {wouldn't be any good for Black. The text move contains a venomous threat: ...Bd7 followed by ...O-O-O when suddenly, Black would be better. Furthermore, Black sidesteps the d-file pin so Ng5 would be met with ...Bf4+, winning the knight. Well, it's not just Black who knows how to play prophylactic moves...}) 11. Kb1 $1 {Getting away from the dangerous