allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring a fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge...yet another time.}) {The most accurate way to proceed, giving up the d3-pawn to get some pieces out.} 7. Bxd3 {There is no alternative, so let's capture the pawn and develop a piece at the same time. Black has a wide range of choices from this point, but they're very likely to transpose to each other. Meanwhile, we can always follow the same plan: Qe2 and O-O-O are our universal next two moves, before deciding whether to bring the h1-rook into the game or not. Understanding of ideas to pressure Black's position is much more critical than memorizing a 20-move long sequence. We hate repeating these not-so-original words as many courses brag about these kinds of 'super simple' positions to handle, but fortunately, this is truly one such position.} Bb4 {Black pins the c3-knight and temporarily prevents us from executing the usual plan. However, let's just kick away the bishop and see what happens.} 8. a3 Bxc3+ $2 (8... Bd6 {is the most accurate move here, but it makes little sense not to play 7...Bd6 [/variation/16191523] at first, as the placement of the a-pawn is irrelevant to the evaluation of the position. However, when Black players go for 7...Bb4, it's usually connected with the suicidal idea of Bxc3, so it's definitely worth checking.}) {Thanks for the free gift! We awarded this move with a huge question mark, because this gross positional blunder deserves it. There is no excuse for giving up the crucial dark-squared bishop and leaving Mr Horwitz with a juicy diagonal.} 9. Bxc3 {We already have a huge advantage due to the strength of the bishop pair, and the advantage can only increase with new moves coming in.} O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 (10... Nd5 {is more active but we can calmly play} 11. Bb2 $1 {when Black's pieces will be pushed back.}) 11. Re1 {Actually, White has several ways to maintain a large advantage, which is a testament to how good our position is. The text move is the most direct, eyeing the vulnerable e6-pawn.} Re8 {Black's position is so bad that even if they had the move here, White would still be better.} 12. Bb2 $16 {Simply tidying up our position. With Bc4, Nd4 and Qe2 - Rd1 as ideas, White has a crushing initiative. Black is struggling to develop while our pieces fire at the e6-pawn.} *

