[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. The astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database only adds misery to Black's cause.}) 5... exd3 6. Nf3 $5 ({Black accepts the challenge and grabs yet another pawn. At this point,} 6. Bxd3 {is exclusively played, scoring over 65% for White in the databases. That's an impressive score, isn't it? The task of the authors would be easy in this case: give a few flashy lines backed up by the stats and conclude that White has great compensation there. However, we do anything but recommend continuations that have already been well-established. Similar to Huy's Spielmann-Indian course, we aim to give you unexplored and strong continuations, which will shock your opponents and increase the chance of them going wrong. Fasten your seatbelts, we're going to offer a lovely double gambit!}) 6... Nf6 ({Playing in a romantic style. This continuation hasn't been known to the chess world yet, at least before the publication of this course. We offer the c2-pawn, reasoning that it would accelerate our queenside development and allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring a fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge...yet another time.}) {The most accurate way to proceed, giving up the d3-pawn to get some pieces out.} 7. Bxd3 {There is no alternative, so let's capture the pawn and develop a piece at the same time. Black has a wide range of choices from this point, but they're very likely to transpose to each other. Meanwhile, we can always follow the same plan: Qe2 and O-O-O are our universal next two moves, before deciding whether to bring the h1-rook into the game or not. Understanding of ideas to pressure Black's position is much more critical than memorizing a 20-move long sequence. We hate repeating these not-so-original words as many courses brag about these kinds of 'super simple' positions to handle, but fortunately, this is truly one such position.} Nc6 {Black simply develops one of his pieces, but we can start bringing our pieces into commanding positions.} 8. Qe2 {) A key move in the Open Horwitz. We bring the queen to the safe e2 square, where it exerts pressure on the backward e6-pawn. Moreover, Bxf5 is an idea if Black isn't careful and castling queenside is on the agenda. Two more moves (O-O-O and Rhe1) and our development would be complete! On the contrary, Black's camp is saddled with weaknesses...} Qe7 {Black tries to get his king to safety via the queenside. We'll also examine the alternative plan later.} 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. Rhe1 {If you only want to have a limited amount of theoretical knowledge, this is a good place to stop memorizing. Our opening strategy has succeeded brilliantly: every one of our pieces is harmoniously developed, with no weaknesses. The same cannot be said for Black, with the e6-pawn as a long-term weakness. We have several plans available, like Bb5, Ng5-e6, or Nb5-d4. According to the engine, White already has the upper hand, and we'll put a sample line on display.} O-O-O 11. Nb5 $5 {A dangerous plan, manoeuvring our knight to the d4 square when Black's pawn chain will crumble.} a6 12. Nbd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 {Our strategy so far has been consistent: the e6-pawn is under fire now. Moreover, the explosive Bxa6 idea is a potential killer.} Re8 {Otherwise the pawn would drop.} 14. Bxa6 $1 {Boom! Black's king sought shelter on the queenside, but our coordinated forces allowed us to strike on both flanks. Stockfish convincingly demonstrated that we're just slightly better with accurate defence from Black, but believe us, that defence is incredibly tough.} bxa6 $2 (14... e5 $1 {is the correct treatment, but after} 15. Nf3 $1 {our attack is still burning. According to the engine, Black needs to find the precise defensive manoeuvre} Qb4 $1 {but after} 16. Bc4 {, we still rate White's chances higher due to Black's hanging centre and poor development. Lastly, we'd like you to enjoy the thoroughly brilliant mating sequence we have after the text move.}) 15. Qxa6+ Kb8 16. Nb5 {All of a sudden, our pieces spring to life against Black's king, who has been stripped off defenders.} Qc5 (16... Bxb5 {loses to} 17. Qxb5+ Kc8 18. Qc6 {and as Qa8+ is threatened, Black is forced to waste another tempo with the king. Next, we'll lift our rook through the 5th rank with a winning attack. The text move is the most tenacious defence: Black covers the a7 square and threatens ...Qxb5, so we must react concretely. Fortunately, we have an amazing resource available that removes Black's last defensive bastion.}) 17. Rxd7 $3 {Simply brilliant. We sacrifice the exchange in order to prevent Qxb5 and give us some more time to make the final kill.} Nxd7 18. Bd4 {That's it! Black's queen is attacked, and after it retreats, Qa7+ will spell the end of the game. Note how our army worked together beautifully: the bishop sacrificed itself on a6, soon followed by the queen. The rook destroys the defensive bishop, before Mr. Horwitz delivers the final blow.} *

