1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is also suggested in many books/courses on the French, a full list of which you may find in the Repertoire Clash file. However, we believe that it's actually a slightly dubious choice for pure French players, at least practically. White has been scoring well here at all levels, and the engine's evaluation isn't in Black's favour either. It has been established that the second player has equality here if he plays precisely; however, we've offered many improvements and crazy novelties to the current theory.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. d3 $1 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) ({In practice, this move stands behind} 5. f3 {in popularity, but we hope after the publication of this course there'll be a shift to}) (5. d3 {. This variation is so harmonious and easy to play: if Black declines the offer, we're just going to capture the e4-pawn with a lasting positional edge. In case Black grabs the offered material, our pieces will easily find their squares with Nf3, Bxd3, Qe2 and castling queenside. Next, bring the other rook to e1 and strike! That's a fairly vague picture of our plan, but we want to illustrate how easy, step-by-step, it is to make the most of our compensation and generate maximum pressure on Black's position until it cracks. The engine already likes our position more, which is a testament to how difficult Black's position actually is. The astonishing score of 65% in the ChessBase Database only adds misery to Black's cause.}) 5... exd3 6. Nf3 $5 ({Black accepts the challenge and grabs yet another pawn. At this point,} 6. Bxd3 {is exclusively played, scoring over 65% for White in the databases. That's an impressive score, isn't it? The task of the authors would be easy in this case: give a few flashy lines backed up by the stats and conclude that White has great compensation there. However, we do anything but recommend continuations that have already been well-established. Similar to Huy's Spielmann-Indian course, we aim to give you unexplored and strong continuations, which will shock your opponents and increase the chance of them going wrong. Fasten your seatbelts, we're going to offer a lovely double gambit!}) 6... Nf6 ({Playing in a romantic style. This continuation hasn't been known to the chess world yet, at least before the publication of this course. We offer the c2-pawn, reasoning that it would accelerate our queenside development and allow us to deliver the kill. A glance at the position should give you an idea how far ahead White is in development: we've developed three pieces and might bring a fourth into the battle soon, while Black has created nothing but some utterly helpless holes on the kingside. Romantic gambits like this are often unsound and refutable with best play, but it's not the case with this one. Black has overextended himself with the committal kingside pushes, so he cannot afford to grab another pawn and get away with it. In fact,} 6... Nf6 {is the best try to keep them alive, but our attacking power is by no means diminished. First, let's check what happens after Black takes up the challenge...yet another time.}) {The most accurate way to proceed, giving up the d3-pawn to get some pieces out.} 7. Bxd3 {There is no alternative, so let's capture the pawn and develop a piece at the same time. Black has a wide range of choices from this point, but they're very likely to transpose to each other. Meanwhile, we can always follow the same plan: Qe2 and O-O-O are our universal next two moves, before deciding whether to bring the h1-rook into the game or not. Understanding of ideas to pressure Black's position is much more critical than memorizing a 20-move long sequence. We hate repeating these not-so-original words as many courses brag about these kinds of 'super simple' positions to handle, but fortunately, this is truly one such position.} Bd6 {We'll examine another strategy Black can try, namely, castling kingside.} 8. Qe2 {Our plan is still as easy and thematic as it can get: after developing the minor pieces, move the queen to e2, castle queenside and crash through! O-O-O is coming and the d6-bishop risks becoming a target on the d-file.} O-O 9. O-O-O Nc6 {Again, we must stress that White already has more than sufficient compensation for the missing pawn due to our superior development and Black's backward e6-pawn. There are several promising choices for us but for the sake of brevity, we'll recommend the one that fits the most with the previous line.} 10. Nb5 {Going for the precious bishop pair followed by targeting Black's d6-e6 duo in the centre.} a6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. Ng5 {Hitting the vulnerable e6-pawn. White has enduring compensation for a mere pawn due to the bishop pair (look, those monsters are striking at the kingside!) and Black's shaky centre. There are several ideas to be aware of, like Rhe1, Bc4 and f4, clamping Black down in the centre. This is a fine point to stop the line and, indeed, if you get as far as this, you are ensured a great game. However, we'll take a look at some sample lines to get an appetizer of how play may proceed.} e5 $6 {Black attempts to solve his problem in the centre radically, but this falls prey to our gorgeous combination.} 13. Bc4+ d5 (13... Kh8 $2 14. Nf7+ {is the end of the game, so Black must push forward.}) 14. f4 $1 {The key move towards an advantage. Our pieces are all striking at that poor king and the crucial idea is to open the long diagonal for the Horwitz bishop to take part in the glorious charge.} h6 {After clicking through the clickables below, you'll soon understand the importance of 'kicking' the g5-knight back:} ({A)} 14... e4 $2 {is met with the shockingly effective blow} 15. Rxd5 $1 Nxd5 16. Qh5 $1 {when believe it or not, it's mate in 9 according to the engine. It's incredibly hard to defend h7, g7 and d5 at once. Beware the firepower of our guns!}) ({B)} 14... exf4 $2 15. Rxd5 {is a copy cat of the above winning line.}) ({C)} 14... b5 {does trap our bishop, but we can simply play} 15. fxe5 bxc4 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Nh3 $1 {+- followed by Nf4, with a crushing positional advantage. Black's structure is in tatters, while the Horwitz bishop dominates its counterpart by a large margin.}) {With the text move, Black tries to avoid that disgusting scenario and kick our knight back from its commanding position. However, we won't ever do Black a favour.} 15. fxe5 {Instead, the best way to proceed is to capture the free pawn and eye the f6-knight.} Re8 {Black prevents exf6 as the queen is pinned. Buckle up, Horwitz fans, you're going to see one of the most fantastic discoveries...the most pleasing combination... you'll ever encounter in this course. We have a winning try here and it's so deep, it's so elegant that we have no choice but to show it in form of a trainable.} 16. exf6 $3 {Wow! We sacrifice a whole queen, but our remaining pieces coordinate so well that it's no surprise that we'll regain the material soon, with interest. Despite the low chance you'll ever get to play this lovely combination, do treat the line carefully. You wouldn't like to miss the once-in-a-lifetime chance to score a memorable victory and bring home the 'Game of the Year' prize, right?} Rxe2 {Simply forced.} 17. Rxd5 $1 {The first point of our combination. The queen is attacked and the bishop is ready to unleash a check, so Black is nearly running out of tricks.} Rxc2+ $1 {The only way to survive. Black relies on the double attack after} 18. Kxc2 Nb4+ {And will regain the d5-rook next move, surviving the first assault. Don't despair, white players: everything you need is to remember the correct positioning of the king and victory will follow.} 19. Kc1 $1 ({The right square! Instead,} 19. Kb1 $2 {allows Black to escape with} Nxd5 20. Rd1 {when he gets to show some brilliancy of his own with} Be6 $1 {A spectacular unpinning, with the point} 21. Nxe6 Nc3+ $1 {and Black captures the hanging rook next, with a better position. Now we believe you've already seen the reason we should put the king at c1: it would protect the d1-rook.}) 19... Nxd5 20. Rd1 {The d5-knight is helpless now, as we can simply capture the free bishop in case of 20...Be6. Look, we only have a minor piece for the queen, but coordination and activity are what matters - Black is a tempo too slow and the game is effectively decided.} hxg5 21. Rxd5 Qxd5 {Black must sacrifice the most valuable trump of his, as allowing Rxd8+ (double check!) is surely not an option.} 22. Bxd5+ Kh7 {If Black chooses another square for the king then Freddie the f-pawn would decide the game with fxg7+ and promotion to another queen. After the text move, another accurate move is needed to clinch the point!} 23. f7 $1 Z0 ({Followed by} 23... Bd7 24. Ba3 {+-, we win the rook and the rest is easy for all of us, we guess. It's a strange coincidence - or intended brilliancy that the Horwitz bishop got the chance to finish the battle. The whole line is one of the most amazing ones in the course, so give yourself a pat on the back if you've gone through it!}) *

