revity, we'll recommend the one that fits the most with the previous line.} 10. Nb5 {Going for the precious bishop pair followed by targeting Black's d6-e6 duo in the centre.} a6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. Ng5 {Hitting the vulnerable e6-pawn. White has enduring compensation for a mere pawn due to the bishop pair (look, those monsters are striking at the kingside!) and Black's shaky centre. There are several ideas to be aware of, like Rhe1, Bc4 and f4, clamping Black down in the centre. This is a fine point to stop the line and, indeed, if you get as far as this, you are ensured a great game. However, we'll take a look at some sample lines to get an appetizer of how play may proceed.} Qe7 {A more solid option, fortifying the shaky e6-pawn.} 13. Rhe1 {Once more, we've reached perfect coordination! All our pieces have been developed and it won't be long before some lines get opened up.} Re8 (13... e5 $2 14. Bc4+ Kh8 {and while the f7 square is well-covered,} 15. Ba3 $1 {is crushing. To put it simply, Black has so many weaknesses that it's an impossible task to cover everything.}) 14. f4 {Creating a grip on the e5 square.} h6 15. Nf3 {Our knight has been pushed back, but we've managed to make the key advance f2-f4 during that time, gaining useful space in the centre. Black desperately needs a constructive plan while we can simply make useful moves like Kb1, Qd2 (switch target to d6!) and g4, probably before h3.} Qf7 {The engine's suggestion, moving the queen away from the dangerous e-file as well as covering the kingside holes.} 16. g4 $5 {An aggressive lunge that contains quite some venom. The point is that our pieces are striking at the kingside and we've tied Black down to the defence of the e6-pawn - it's time to open up a second front and create some more weaknesses.} fxg4 {The correct recapture, temporarily closing the g-file at the cost of loosening the b1-h7 diagonal. 17...Nxg4?! looks natural, but after the strong 18.Rg1! Black is close to busted with h3 and doubling on the g-file coming. There aren't enough pieces to defend the vulnerable g7-pawn, while the Horwitz bishop fires from a distance.} 17. Nh4 $13 Z0 ({White has more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed two pawns. The e6 and d6 pawns are both weak, not to mention the g6 square, which will be a useful base for our pieces. Our bishop pair act as monsters, striking down the long diagonals leading to Black's king, which will come under a fierce assault in no time. The threat is Bg6, and after the engine's} 17... Ne7 {, we'd like to suggest that we venture all-in with the triple gambit} 18. h3 $5 {when} gxh3 {20.Rg1 would give us extremely promising compensation for the three pawns. An absolutely chaotic and computerish line, but it does demonstrate the wealth of possibilities that White has in the Horwitz. We have great/bad news for you guys: this exciting chapter has come to an end! It's not that long, but we hope we've managed to show that 4...f5 is a critically risky option from an objective as well as practical point of view, and it's not a good way to meet the Horwitz as Black. True to the original spirit of the course, we've offered the deadly double gambit 6. Nf3!? which is a novelty and hasn't been known to the chess world before. If you can only remember one thing about this variation, it's the following piece configuration: Nf3, capture the d3-pawn, put the queen on e2, castle queenside, and strike on the e6-pawn. We're incredibly enthusiastic about White's chances in this variation and would be surprised if anyone would like to go into this line as Black. It's the first chapter of the Open Horwitz explanation, and don't worry, the next one is just a few clicks away from you. Good luck!}) *

