1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 {Black announces that he wants to play with an open structure, instead of the typical French one. The option is suggested in many books/courses on the French Defence.} 4. Nc3 f5 ({The only logical way to proceed, going after the vulnerable e4-pawn. At this point, we'll analyse two ways for Black to hold onto the material: ▸} 4... f5 {will be examined in this chapter. ▸}) (4... Nf6 {is the main bulk of the Open Horwitz section and is the topic of the next chapters.}) 5. f3 $5 ({The most ambitious but also riskiest approach for Black against the Horwitz. Black hangs on to the central pawn and forces us to sacrifice material. However, we've already developed two pieces and might well add a third, while Black has only toyed around with his little pawns. You should be very happy to see this move on the board, as we have promising attacking chances against Black's king in all lines. Nowadays, this greedy advance isn't played much anymore as people have understood that it's too dangerous for Black. White scores around 60%, so the whole line has been abandoned at the top level these days. However, it still remains popular within the amateur community. At this point, we have more than one way to turn up the heat and we'll begin by checking the romantic} 5. f3 $5 {, before focusing on}) (5. d3 $1 {, our main recommendation. To end the paragraph, allow us to quote the legendary Yusupov: 'The problem with the Dutch is that Black very often in the middlegame finds that his best available move is f5-f7'. Dear readers, you're going to witness the same thing happening in a completely different opening. However, no matter how strong Black is, he lacks the ability to move his pawn backwards.}) {A romantic, King's Gambit styled gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and the safety of his own king to embark on an all-in assault. The reason we rejected this line is that the play is often too unclear, with our king floating around in the centre. However, the gambit is perfectly sound and we decided that there is no reason you shouldn't witness an amazing line as suggested by the engine.} 5... Bd6 ({Instead,} 5... exf3 6. Nxf3 {is extremely promising for White as we've developed three pieces already while Black has created so many holes on the kingside. The text move is the most problematic one - Black prepares a dangerous check with Qh4+. There is no choice but to go for the deep dark forest with three results possible.}) 6. fxe4 Qh4+ 7. g3 {The start of the madness!} Bxg3+ 8. hxg3 Qxh1 {Black has won a free rook and is threatening the knight, but his pieces are undeveloped and the queen is close to being trapped. However, our kingside isn't so safe and we should also be careful. The position is super complicated and we could produce a hundred pages of analysis on this 0.00 mess - but we have chosen not to do so. Let's see a sample line that can result from it!} 9. Nh3 Nf6 10. Qe2 fxe4 11. O-O-O {More and more pieces are flowing into the action.} Qf3 12. Qh2 $13 {The key move to keep the fight complicated. We keep the queens on the board, and most of our forces are coordinated, while Black's army is dangerously undeveloped. We've been playing like the 19th century masters and, amazingly, up to here, our concept is fully sound. However, it seems that Black holds here with best play from both sides and playing the position would require a tremendous amount of theoretical energy, so we've put this line as an alternative to remind you how beautiful chess is.} *

