1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Bd7 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {is reminiscent of the Fort Knox variation ( 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bd7 ) . Following the exchange on e4, Black brings his bishop to c6, contesting the long diagonal.} 6. Nxe4 ({Avoiding} 6. O-O-O Bc6 {and Black hangs on to his extra pawn.}) 6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Bc6 {This is the position Black likely aims for with 5...Bd7.} 8. Qe3 {On e3 the queen does not obstruct the light-squared bishop. Black's bishop is active on c6 but is vulnerable to Nf3-Ne5. The other bishop, meanwhile, is tied down to the defence of g7.} Nd7 9. Nf3 {Preparing to meet ...Nf6 with the powerful Ne5!.} Bc5 {The most popular move. Black utilises an attack on White's queen to prepare castling.} ({Some alternatives: A)} 9... Nf6 $2 10. Ne5 $1 {puts Black in bad shape. B) 9...Bxf3 10.Qxf3 c6 is a solid option; however White has a clear advantage here because of the bishop pair. 11.O-O-O Nf6 12.Bc4 followed by Rhe1 - perfect centralisation.}) 10. d4 Bb4+ {Provoking c2-c3, thus limiting the scope of the b2-bishop. We need to play c3-c4 in the future to make sure the Horwitz bishop will shine again, but that softens the kingside structure. Therefore, we should change gears, castle kingside and go for a positional game instead.} 11. c3 Bd6 (11... Be7 {can be met similarly.}) 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. c4 $14 {White has the more comfortable game. We'll put the rook on d1 and e1, while Bd3 and Ne5 are some of the ideas that are on the cards.} *

