1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Qd4 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {Tiddalick the greedy Queen embarks on an extremely risky mission to protect the e4-pawn, which will drop anyway. Black will have some difficult moments with his queen so vulnerable!} 6. f3 $146 ({A strong and shiny new idea that blasts open the centre! We can call this a novelty, since: A) 28 games in the ChessBase Database have continued with} 6. O-O-O {so far and none with}) (6. f3 {but we believe the former is a bit inaccurate since it allows Black to bring another piece out before we can play f3. B) On top of that,}) (6. f3 $5 {was played only 6% of the time according to the Lichess Database! Indeed, it's not so relevant when we castle queenside, but every tempo counts when it comes to hunting the black queen.}) 6... exf3 $6 ({In our experience, people who embark on risky moves such as Black's Qd4 usually continue in this greedy fashion and ask us to prove our compensation for the pawn. With some strong moves we can gain the initiative, but that's not always trivial and sometimes we may end up a clear pawn down. Objectively,} 6... Nc6 {is a stronger move. However, why did Black put his queen on d4, then? We can play} 7. fxe4 {followed by Nf3 with a pleasant advantage and chances for a quick crush if the second player isn't careful. An engine-approved sequence is} e5 8. Nf3 Qc5 $1 {Black must protect the e5-pawn.} 9. Qc4 $5 {is now very interesting, followed by exchanging the queens and Bb5 to pin the knight.}) 7. Nxf3 {What could be more natural?} Qg4 ({Black moves the queen away to the kingside where it holds up the g4 break temporarily. However, the drawback is that the c7 spot is softened. Here is a coverage of some alternatives: A)} 7... Qb6 {is met with the thematic resource} 8. g4 $1 {with a powerful attack. Accepting the gambit is extremely risky and bad, as} Nxg4 9. Rg1 Nf6 10. O-O-O {is just crushing for White with d4-d5 and Bh3 to come. Black is too tied up to survive the onslaught. B)}) (7... Qd8 {is way too passive and can be refuted similarly:} 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. g4 $1 {and with g5, h4 and Kb1 to come, Black's extra pawn is much less relevant than the advanced kingside pawns, which will crack a few holes in Black's camp.}) 8. O-O-O {The most flexible move, keeping all of our options like h3, Nb5 and Qe1 open. Black has a large number of setups here and it's logically impossible to cover all of them. Nevertheless, in most cases, we can play Nb5, and Kb1 followed by pushing the kingside with h3. We'll give a sample sequence to demonstrate some possibilities for both sides here.} Nc6 9. Nb5 $5 {Attack! The c7 spot is weakened by Her Majesty's strange journey and we are capitalising!} Bd6 {Forced to defend the c7-pawn. Having secured the bishop pair in the pocket, we can choose when to play Nxd6+. For now, we can make some useful moves first.} 10. Qe1 $13 {With extreme compensation for the pawn. The idea of the text move is to prepare Be2, which would force the queen to move once more. The g2-pawn would be poisoned since Black can't possibly afford to open the g-file. We'll swing our queen to the attack via g3/h4 and it's a one-sided game, since Black has no counterplay on the queenside, not to mention he hasn't castled yet.} *

