1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 b6 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) (5... b6 {doesn't have the reputation of a hot line, but it looks quite logical to prepare the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop. However, the h1-a8 diagonal is weakened and we'll use it in our favour.}) 6. Nxe4 Bb7 ({It turns out that Black is already facing some concrete problems! You'll see that Black faces some tactical issues if he continues with} 6... Be7 {, so}) (6... Bb7 {has been tried more often, allowing a doubling of the f-pawns. There is also a third approach,}) (6... Nxe4 {, but it fails to impress after} 7. Qxe4 {and White's centralized queen is powerful.}) {We're not impressed by this move. Clearly Black has little for the compromised kingside structure.} 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 8. O-O-O $14 {White has a small but clear edge due to the superior structure. There are various sensible ways to proceed, so we're happy to stop here. White can proceed with Nf3-g3-Bg2, neutralizing Black's most active minor piece.} *

