1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 b6 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) (5... b6 {doesn't have the reputation of a hot line, but it looks quite logical to prepare the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop. However, the h1-a8 diagonal is weakened and we'll use it in our favour.}) 6. Nxe4 Be7 ({It turns out that Black is already facing some concrete problems! You'll see that Black faces some tactical issues if he continues with} 6... Be7 {, so}) (6... Bb7 {has been tried more often, allowing a doubling of the f-pawns. There is also a third approach,}) (6... Nxe4 {, but it fails to impress after} 7. Qxe4 {and White's centralized queen is powerful.}) {Black prepares to meet Nxf6+ with ...Bxf6, exchanging two sets of minor pieces. In the 5.Qe2 line we usually want to keep as many minor pieces on the board as possible to organise an attack on the kingside. Therefore, exchanging on f6 is only a viable idea when against ...Bxf6, we can follow-up with Ne5 or d4, preventing the exchange of bishops. At this point White has a nice geometrical motif, disrupting Black's coordination.} 7. Qf3 $1 c6 ({A unique and clever idea! We violate the 'principle' of not moving the queen so many times in the opening, but our concept is justified here. We exploit the temporarily unprotected a8-rook and set up tactical tricks connected with Nxf6+ followed by Qxa8. Black's best try is to block the long diagonal with} 7... c6 {, but it hinders his own development.}) {A sad move to make. White has 'wasted' a move with the queen, but Black also made some not-so-useful pawn moves on the queenside. White has the luxury of choice and we recommend the most straightforward move.} 8. O-O-O {It's the right time to castle! The queen being on f3 instead of e2 is by no means a hindrance. In fact, we have new possibilities like Bd3 and Ne2-c3. The ramming g4-g5 thrust will be a dangerous idea, but only if we time it right. Be careful not to advance kingside pawns too soon and neglect piece development. White can also exchange everything on f6 and leave Black with doubled pawns, but that's not exactly an issue for the second player right now. The king would be perfectly placed on e7 and Black would have an open g-file for his rooks.} a5 {...a5 is often an effective counter against queenside castling. As usual Black wants to soften up our queenside with ...a4 and create counterplay against the king. 8...O-O is dubious due to 9.Nxf6+! Bxf6 10.Bxf6 Qxf6 11.Qxf6 gxf6 . The exchanges are now favourable for White, since Black's king is now misplaced. White should proceed with the strong 12.g4! followed by Bg2, Ne2 and d4, f4, stifling Black's counterplay. 8...Bb7 is another possible move. Black threatens to put pressure on the e4-knight with ...Nbd7, so the prophylactic 9.Bd3!? Nbd7 10.Qg3!? seems quite interesting. We will continue with Nf3 (threat Nfg5) with a full focus on Black's kingside.} 9. a4 {An automatic reaction against ...a5. We block the queenside and if Black wants to open the queenside in the future, it would likely cost a pawn.} Bb7 {Black prepares ...Nbd7 to complete his queenside development. Here we'd like to show you another idea White can try in this structure.} 10. Ne2 $5 (10. Bd3 {is also good and after} Nbd7 11. Ne2 {followed by g2-g4 things are very sharp. The text move is another independent idea made possible by our queen on f3 instead of e2. We want to bring the knight to the c3 square, controlling the ...b5 break. Basically, we want to slow down Black's counterplay before launching our kingside pawns}) 10... Nbd7 11. N2c3 O-O 12. g4 $13 {What we have on the board is a characteristic Open Horwitz middlegame where the master of 2.b3 thrives. We'll proceed with g5-Rg1 and depending on how Black reacts, we'll choose how to continue the attack. A sample line is ( 12...Nxe4 13.Nxe4 b5! Black must break for counterplay. We ignore, with 14.g5 bxa4 15.bxa4 c5! 16.Rg1! with a truly wild position. We want to stabilize the queenside with Bb5 and Qc3 is also an idea, threatening checkmate in one.} *

