1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nc6 $5 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A barbaric idea that requires investigation, being mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black', with the author quoting the game Gelashvili - Ramon Perez. If we manage to play Nxe4 and Nf3, ninety percent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in the next chapter.}) 6... Bb4 $6 {A pointless move that shows weak strategic understanding. The bishop has nothing to do on b4 since after} 7. Nxe4 {There are no mating tricks on d2. Black's pieces fail to coordinate and there's huge pressure on the f6-knight (and consequently the g7-pawn). It's hard to dream of such a great position after 7 moves, but this dream has come true 87 times on Lichess, with an astonishing win rate of 70% for White. A sample sequence is} Nxe4 8. Qxe4 O-O 9. Nf3 $16 {White is clearly better, since Black's c6-knight and b4-bishop are out of place. Our goal in this position is to checkmate the king and we're clearly ahead in the race. We can proceed with Bc4/d3, h4-h5, Ng5, etc., with a vicious attack. It's worth mentioning that against ...Qe7, we should reply with Kb1 to keep the monstrous Horwitz bishop alive.} *

