1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nc6 $5 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A barbaric idea that requires investigation, being mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black', with the author quoting the game Gelashvili - Ramon Perez. If we manage to play Nxe4 and Nf3, ninety percent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in the next chapter.}) 6... Nd4 {The queen hunts begin! Black's minor pieces will act like mosquitoes in the ears, preventing us from recapturing the e4-pawn. And even if we got in Nxe4, Black has the possibility of c7-c5, stabilizing the strong d4-knight at the cost of blocking the f8-bishop.} 7. Qe3 $5 ({We're moving away from the known paths of} 7. Qe1 Bd7 {followed by ...Bc6 with approximate equality. Our suggested}) (7. Qe3 $5 {is much rarer and is a provocation: on e3 the queen is exposed to tricks like Bc5 followed by Nxb3+, Ng4, Nf5, etc. Therefore, care needs to be taken! The good news is that there's no easy way for Black to liquidate the position and we'll keep the pressure in all of the lines. 7...Bd7 is no longer possible since the d4-knight is hanging, so Black must choose another way to deal with the threat of Nxe4.}) 7... c5 8. d3 $5 ({Over-protecting the d4-knight, which is clearly an octopus we should challenge with Nf3 sooner than later. We found the text move rather challenging to deal with, since} 8. Nxe4 Be7 $1 9. f4 O-O 10. Nf3 Nd5 {puts Black on the more pleasant side of equality. In the end, we decided to gambit a pawn with}) {A thematic pawn sacrifice in the Horwitz Attack in order to open more lines for our pieces. After Black grabs the d3-pawn, we'll recapture it with Bd3 followed by Nf3 with long-lasting compensation for the pawn. It's hard to make use of Black's extra e-pawn anyway and both of his bishops have limited scope. Meanwhile, we can start a kingside attack with both of our bishops pointed there! While our sacrificial concept is fully sound, you should understand that White isn't going to recoup the pawn anytime soon - so be prepared to live with it!} 8... exd3 {Taking the pawn is the most logical reaction.} 9. Bxd3 {This is an instructive and typical position in the Open Horwitz. White has sacrificed a pawn with no tricks to regain it and no immediate threats, yet we own full compensation with far superior development. The glue holding Black's position together is the d4-knight and we'll challenge it next with Nf3. Afterwards, we start pushing the kingside pawns with Rhg1 followed by g4 and Black lacks a clear plan despite his extra pawn. Let's look at how things may actually unfold.} Be7 ({Preparing kingside castling. Doing it with} 9... Bd6 $2 {is refuted by} 10. Nb5 $1 {and the d6-bishop is caught in the fire.}) 10. Nf3 O-O (10... Nxf3 $2 {is a horrible idea due to} 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Qxf3 {and the threats are Ne4, Rxd7, Qxb7 etc. Knowing that Black is busted there, we come to the conclusion that the knight needs to be on d4!}) 11. Kb1 $13 Z0 ({A useful prophylactic move. The king better not stand in the same diagonal as the queen, although there's nothing concrete. We'll continue with Rhg1+g4 and Ne5! (a great idea to paralyze Black's kingside). For example, a continuation approved by the engine is} 11... a6 12. Rhg1 b5 13. g4 Bb7 14. Ne5 $1 {and Black is already in hot water. The crushing threat is g5 followed by Bxh7+, Qh3+ and g6! We can certainly say that 8.d3!? is a promising gambit.}) *

