1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nc6 $5 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A barbaric idea that requires investigation, being mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black', with the author quoting the game Gelashvili - Ramon Perez. If we manage to play Nxe4 and Nf3, ninety percent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in the next chapter.}) 6... Nd4 {The queen hunts begin! Black's minor pieces will act like mosquitoes in the ears, preventing us from recapturing the e4-pawn. And even if we got in Nxe4, Black has the possibility of c7-c5, stabilizing the strong d4-knight at the cost of blocking the f8-bishop.} 7. Qe3 $5 ({We're moving away from the known paths of} 7. Qe1 Bd7 {followed by ...Bc6 with approximate equality. Our suggested}) (7. Qe3 $5 {is much rarer and is a provocation: on e3 the queen is exposed to tricks like Bc5 followed by Nxb3+, Ng4, Nf5, etc. Therefore, care needs to be taken! The good news is that there's no easy way for Black to liquidate the position and we'll keep the pressure in all of the lines. 7...Bd7 is no longer possible since the d4-knight is hanging, so Black must choose another way to deal with the threat of Nxe4.}) 7... Nf5 {Black continues to fool around with his knight, moving away from the vulnerable d4 spot and attacking our queen once again. We'll take a retreat!} 8. Qe1 $1 ({The best move since} 8. Qh3 $6 e5 $1 {leaves our queen short of squares and}) (8. Qe2 Nd4 {would merely repeat the position. We're threatening the e4-pawn, but Stockfish likes the idea of f2-f3 a lot more, ripping open the centre with powerful compensation for the pawn. With that in mind, we'll take a look at a few sample lines.}) 8... Nd6 {The logical-looking continuation of Black's previous manoeuvres with his knight from c6 to d6. Black officially announces his intention to hold on to the e4-pawn, but he has wasted a lot of time that could have been used for development. Thus, we'll capitalize and strike before Black castles!} 9. f3 $1 (9. d3 $1 {is an equally strong alternative. We forcefully open up the position.}) 9... exf3 {Allowing fxe4 gives White a dream structure and what's more, there's the threat of e4-e5. Therefore, accepting the gambit is mandatory.} 10. Nxf3 {A quick recap of the first ten moves is that we've dropped a pawn out of the opening for 'uncertain' compensation. There's nothing concrete, such as a sequence to regain the pawn, or an immediate attack. Our compensation relies, once more, on superior piece activity. Our pieces work with each other much better compared to their black counterparts. White has several possible plans in this position: g4, Rg1, Ne5 and even Bd3 is sometimes a good idea. Stockfish's opinion can be summarized as equal if Black defends well, but we will have a great initiative (sufficient for an objective advantage, if you care) otherwise. Not all of you will feel like a fish in the water in this kind of pawn-down situation. We suggest analysing the different plans for White with a chess engine and playing out this position in practice to gain a better understanding of White's amazing compensation! Erm... or do you prefer the Exchange French?!} b6 $1 ({This precise move-order isn't easy to find for Black. He intends to develop the bishop to b7, preventing g4 and only then develop the kingside. The problem with the inaccurate} 10... Be7 {is that White can strike immediately with} 11. g4 $1 {exploiting the undefended g7-pawn.} O-O {is met by} 12. g5 Nh5 13. Rg1 {with a ferocious attack for White. There are a million attacking ideas, Bd3, Ne5 and Ne4 being some examples. After}) (10... b6 {, White has several piece configurations to choose from. While the usual plan with Rg1-g4 is playable, it is a bit slow here since we need to spend many tempi preparing the g4 break due to the pressure from the b7-bishop. We'd like to introduce a new setup for White in this structure!}) 11. Bd3 $1 {We don't usually put the bishop on d3, since it would block the d2-pawn from moving. However, our dark-squared bishop is already operating on a great diagonal and the d2-pawn will shield the king. We'll proceed with Rf1 and Qg3 followed by moving the queen to another square e.g h3 and the time is ripe for g4.} Bb7 12. Rf1 Be7 13. Qg3 (13. g4 $5 {is interesting but there's no need to be fancy. We just attack the g7-pawn and force}) 13... O-O {Now, a powerful idea you often see in the Horwitz is} 14. Ne5 $13 {The knight is incredibly strong on the e5 square, where it restricts Black's pieces and controls key squares. We may even play Rde1 next to stabilize the strong knight and then Qh3 followed by g4-g5 is an effective plan. Mate on h7 approaches :) Black has no counterplay in sight and is literally on the defensive. Despite his extra pawn, all guns are blazing toward the king on g8!} *

