1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nc6 $5 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A barbaric idea that requires investigation, being mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black', with the author quoting the game Gelashvili - Ramon Perez. If we manage to play Nxe4 and Nf3, ninety percent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in the next chapter.}) 6... Nd4 {The queen hunts begin! Black's minor pieces will act like mosquitoes in the ears, preventing us from recapturing the e4-pawn. And even if we got in Nxe4, Black has the possibility of c7-c5, stabilizing the strong d4-knight at the cost of blocking the f8-bishop.} 7. Qe3 $5 ({We're moving away from the known paths of} 7. Qe1 Bd7 {followed by ...Bc6 with approximate equality. Our suggested}) (7. Qe3 $5 {is much rarer and is a provocation: on e3 the queen is exposed to tricks like Bc5 followed by Nxb3+, Ng4, Nf5, etc. Therefore, care needs to be taken! The good news is that there's no easy way for Black to liquidate the position and we'll keep the pressure in all of the lines. 7...Bd7 is no longer possible since the d4-knight is hanging, so Black must choose another way to deal with the threat of Nxe4.}) 7... Nf5 {Black continues to fool around with his knight, moving away from the vulnerable d4 spot and attacking our queen once again. We'll take a retreat!} 8. Qe1 $1 {)} ({The best move since} 8. Qh3 $6 e5 $1 {leaves our queen short of squares and}) (8. Qe2 Nd4 {would merely repeat the position. We're threatening the e4-pawn, but Stockfish likes the idea of f2-f3 a lot more, ripping open the centre with powerful compensation for the pawn. With that in mind, we'll take a look at a few sample lines.}) 8... Bd7 {A typical idea for Black in these positions. The second player 'anticipates' the exchanges on e4 in advance and prepares 9.Nxe4 Nxe4 10.Qxe4 Bc6! when the French bishop is very active. Instead, we'll go for the thematic gambit} 9. f3 $5 {Instead of settling for dry equality, we raise the stakes by sacrificing a real pawn for nothing but the initiative. We certainly have sufficient compensation in this kind of position (Black has wasted a lot of time with the f5-knight) and it's surprisingly difficult for Black to navigate the minefield.} exf3 {Positionally forced since allowing fxe4, giving us a huge central majority with tempo, is too easy.} 10. Nxf3 {Our ideas are Rg1+g4 (forcing the clumsy knight to move again), Bd3+Ne4 to exchange the crucial defender on f6, and Ne5 to put more pressure.} Bd6 ({A pretty logical move, controlling the e5 square and preparing O-O. Kingside castling is always risky for Black though, since our pieces are well-placed for a slow-burning but deadly attack. We'll consider some alternatives: A)} 10... Be7 $6 {is a mistake because of} 11. Ne5 $1 {and g4 is on the agenda. For example,} O-O {g5!} 12. Nd5 {h4 and White is close to winning with the threat of (among others) Nxd5 followed by Nxd7 and Qe5, forking g7 and d5. B)}) (10... Qe7 $5 {is the no.1 recommendation of the engine. Black anticipates that the king won't be safe on the kingside and seeks to castle the other way. We suggest you proceed as usual with} 11. Ne5 {O-O g4! with sufficient play for the missing pawn. We have several ideas like Nxd7, h4+Bh3, Bg2 and Rhf1. It's not easy for Black to come up with a plan. The position is dynamically balanced aka 0.00ish :)}) 11. Kb1 $13 (11. Ne5 {immediately is possible as well. However, on this occasion, Black would have the option of Bxe5 to eliminate our strong knight. The text move is a useful prophylactic move. We tuck the king to a safe square and Qe7-Ba3 won't force an exchange of our Horwitz bishop. We now have the option of Nb5 to gain the bishop pair at the right moment! This is a good point to stop the trainable, but for those of you who are interested in seeing the rest of our analysis, we have provided it below: A) 11...O-O Black castles into the storm. We'll 'attack the castled king :)' with 11.Bd3 Bc6 and now 12.Ne4! is a nice resource, exchanging the f6-knight which is Black's best defender of the kingside. White has a strong attack! B) 11...Qe7! is once again the best move. Black prepares queenside castling, so we should react immediately with 12.Nb5! Bxb5 13.Bxb5+ c6 14.Bd3 with typical positional compensation for the pawn. According to the silicon monster, the best play for both sides is 14...O-O-O 15.Bxf5 ( 15.Ne5!? maintains the pressure and can be investigated) 15...exf5 16.Qf2! hitting the a7-pawn and preparing Rhe1. 16...a6 17.Rhe1 Ne4 18.Qf1! with the threats of d3 and Bxg7. There's only one tricky way for Black to achieve equality: 18...Ba3! and it turns out the capture on g7 isn't dangerous at all due to Rhe8. Therefore, we should play 19.Ne5! and there isn't a satisfactory way for Black to defend the f5-pawn. We also have the threat of Nxc6 followed by Qxa6+, so Black should bail out with 19...Bxb2 20.Qxf5+ Qe6! 21.Qxe6+ fxe6 22.Rxe4 Bxe5 23.Rxe5= and the double rook ending is drawish. That's a long line!}) *

