ent of the time the c6-knight would just be misplaced. However, timing is the justification of Black's concept. He will jump his knight onto d4 and force our queen to make a tough decision. Although the knight is often quite active on d4, it's vulnerable to attacks from our Horwitz bishop. After analyzing it for a while, we found some nice ideas that render Black's approach rather risky. A rule of thumb is that if we can grab the e4-pawn without hindrance, Black's opening concept would fail.} 6. O-O-O (6. Nxe4 $6 {is in fact the most popular continuation on Lichess, but} Nd4 $1 {is rather troublesome. The e4-pawn is always there, so we better focus on development before snatching it! At this point, 6...Nd4 is the principled and obvious choice and we're pleasantly surprised to discover that people tend to proceed with Be7 or Bb4 instead. This is one more piece of evidence that many Francophiles are already out of book against 2. b3. We should mention that 6...Be7 transposes to 5...Be7 coverage in the next chapter.}) 6... Nd4 {The queen hunts begin! Black's minor pieces will act like mosquitoes in the ears, preventing us from recapturing the e4-pawn. And even if we got in Nxe4, Black has the possibility of c7-c5, stabilizing the strong d4-knight at the cost of blocking the f8-bishop.} 7. Qe3 $5 ({We're moving away from the known paths of} 7. Qe1 Bd7 {followed by ...Bc6 with approximate equality. Our suggested}) (7. Qe3 $5 {is much rarer and is a provocation: on e3 the queen is exposed to tricks like Bc5 followed by Nxb3+, Ng4, Nf5, etc. Therefore, care needs to be taken! The good news is that there's no easy way for Black to liquidate the position and we'll keep the pressure in all of the lines. 7...Bd7 is no longer possible since the d4-knight is hanging, so Black must choose another way to deal with the threat of Nxe4.}) 7... Bc5 8. Na4 $5 ({The most popular move according to the Lichess Database. Black creates the deadly threat of Nxb3+ winning the queen. At this point, White has two good moves:} 8. Na4 {and}) (8. Nxe4 {. However,}) (8. Nxe4 {is a lot more tricky and gives Black many ways to go wrong, so it'll be our main recommendation! Objectively, White has a clear advantage no matter which option we choose, signalling that 7...Bc5 is not a good line at all!}) ({We should attack the c5-bishop and this is another way to do it. The point is that the Nxb3+ discovery is no longer possible, since we have Qxb3 now. Compared to} 8. Nxe4 {, we keep one more pair of minor pieces on the board at the cost of staying a pawn down.}) 8... Bb6 $1 {The only way for Black to play on.} 9. Nxb6 Nf5 $1 {A crucial intermediate move, since otherwise, the d4-knight hangs.} 10. Qe1 axb6 11. d3 $13 {White has more than enough play for a mere pawn. The d-file is going to be opened up very soon and the black queen is going to feel discomfort. Furthermore, we have the uncontested Horwitz bishop which is a fearsome force.} *

