1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nbd7 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A flexible move, keeping White guessing the placement of Black's dark-squared bishop. One idea to take care of is ...Nc5, holding on to the extra e4-pawn. The light-squared bishop may be developed later with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7. We face the typical dilemma: should White take on e4 immediately or castle queenside?} 6. Nxe4 (6. g4 $5 {is a completely sound and very fascinating alternative, but it looks too complicated and computerish for our taste. And since we either take on e4 or castle against all Black's 5th moves, there's no reason to make an exception this time. As you've seen, 6.O-O-O?! is inaccurate, running into 6...a5!=+ . The text move is the right one, not revealing to Black where will our king be. At this point, 6...Be7 is a transposition to the 5...Be7 chapter [/course/82991/28] All that is left for us to consider is 6...Nxe4 .}) 6... Be7 {Steering the game to the 5...Be7 variation.} 7. Nf3 {And we end up in familiar territory. This is one of the most critical tabiyas in the Open Horwitz. You'll find detailed coverage of this variation here. [/course/82991/28]} *

