1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nbd7 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A flexible move, keeping White guessing the placement of Black's dark-squared bishop. One idea to take care of is ...Nc5, holding on to the extra e4-pawn. The light-squared bishop may be developed later with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7. We face the typical dilemma: should White take on e4 immediately or castle queenside?} 6. Nxe4 (6. g4 $5 {is a completely sound and very fascinating alternative, but it looks too complicated and computerish for our taste. And since we either take on e4 or castle against all Black's 5th moves, there's no reason to make an exception this time. As you've seen, 6.O-O-O?! is inaccurate, running into 6...a5!=+ . The text move is the right one, not revealing to Black where will our king be. At this point, 6...Be7 is a transposition to the 5...Be7 chapter [/course/82991/28] All that is left for us to consider is 6...Nxe4 .}) 6... Nxe4 ({Every black player has either gone for} 6... Nxe4 {or . The idea of this exchange is that Black frees the f6 square for his other knight and he will gain a tempo on our queen. The drawback is that after 7.Qxe4 our centralized queen has many promising squares to go to.}) 7. Qxe4 Nf6 {White has numerous directions here and in practice, White players have tried to put the queen on literally every sensible square. Our dream would be to choose the queen a location where it exerts pressure, isn't vulnerable to attacks and doesn't obstruct the development of the white pieces. However, you can't have it all :)} 8. Qh4 $1 ({After a process of analysis and elimination we decided that} 8. Qh4 {is the strongest as well as the most annoying move for Black to face. Firstly, the queen can only be attacked if the f6-knight, the defender of Black's kingside, moves to another square. Secondly, the queen is perfectly placed to support a future kingside attack with Bd3 or g4-g5. It's surprisingly easy for Black to get in a horrible position by playing 'natural moves' like O-O.}) 8... a5 $146 {Black wants to fight back on the queenside with ...a4. The engine thinks that this is Black's best chance to equalize the position - which is perhaps true. Let me remind you that on 99% of the occasions, we react to ...a5 with a4, blockading the queenside. This position is no exception.} 9. a4 Nd5 $5 ({Block! If Black continues with} 9... Be7 {, the position is similar to 8...Be7 with the a-pawn moves included, which makes little difference.}) {Exploiting the new b4 outpost for the knight. Black argues that a queen exchange benefits him compared to 8...Nd5 (see here [/variation/21886773]), which is true. Black's knight would have a stable square on d5 after ( 10.Qxd8+ Kxd8 and Black has better chances to equalize there compared to 8...Nd5. Agreeing on the queen exchange is just fine, but we propose something trickier.} 10. Qe4 $5 {Confusing Black with the queen dance. Black can't develop the dark-squared bishop due to the hanging g7-pawn, but what if he continues the strategy of harassing our queen?} Nf6 11. Qc4 $5 (11. Qh4 Nd5 {is obviously a repetition so we won't be going there. Let's choose another square for the queen!}) {The queen has travelled through d1-e2-e4-h4-e4 and finally ends up on c4. On one hand, we've violated the opening principle of not moving the queen many times, but on the other hand, Black has been moving around with his knights, so White's queen dance is justified. We could have played Qc4 a few moves earlier, but with the inclusion of a4 and a5 Her Majesty is more favourably placed here. Black cannot drive her away with ...a6 followed by ...b5 anymore. She controls many important squares from c4 and can switch easily to all parts of the board. The devil is in the details, isn't it?} 11... Bd6 12. Nf3 O-O 13. O-O-O {We show our intentions to sharpen up the game by castling on opposite wings. White has typical rich piece play with Bd3, g4-g5 and Rg1 coming next. The Horwitz bishop is worth 3.5 points and if Black goes ...Qe7, we should reply with Kb1 to prevent an exchange via ...Ba3. Black is yet to solve the chronic problem of the French bishop and if he doesn't react with care we will smash on the kingside.} *

