1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({After checking the greedy and risky} 4... f5 {, our microscope is bound to examine the natural knight development, supporting the e4-pawn. This chapter and the next one are the most important chapters of the course, since the sequence of 2...d5, 3. ..dxe4 and 4...Nf6 is very popular. The good news is that White's plans are often quite straightforward and dangerous at the same time.}) 5. Qe2 Nbd7 ({A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling. With the likely presence of kings on opposite wings, the battle is sure to be heated as both sides will try to counter each other's attack while pursuing their own goals. Note that at this tabiya, Black has many similar-looking options. We examine as many as 6 alternatives here for the sake of completeness, but} 5... Bb4 {and}) (5... Be7 {are the major options which you should study more carefully. These two moves are examined in the next chapter, while we'll check the 5th move alternatives here. There are many nuances in this structure - for White, it's whether to push the f, g or h-pawn. It's about the most precise moment to castle queenside and to exchange a few minor pieces. Black faces a similar issue as well since there are so many possibilities out there to consider: develop the bishop to b7 or d7, the knight to c6 or d7, whether to push a5-a4, etc. Besides attempting to give you a full understanding of these subtle details, we've also discovered many new ideas to push the theory of this variation forward. It's worth pointing out that recent French Defence courses from Black's point of view have agreed that this variation is more promising for White.}) {A flexible move, keeping White guessing the placement of Black's dark-squared bishop. One idea to take care of is ...Nc5, holding on to the extra e4-pawn. The light-squared bishop may be developed later with ...b6 followed by ...Bb7. We face the typical dilemma: should White take on e4 immediately or castle queenside?} 6. Nxe4 (6. g4 $5 {is a completely sound and very fascinating alternative, but it looks too complicated and computerish for our taste. And since we either take on e4 or castle against all Black's 5th moves, there's no reason to make an exception this time. As you've seen, 6.O-O-O?! is inaccurate, running into 6...a5!=+ . The text move is the right one, not revealing to Black where will our king be. At this point, 6...Be7 is a transposition to the 5...Be7 chapter [/course/82991/28] All that is left for us to consider is 6...Nxe4 .}) 6... Nxe4 ({Every black player has either gone for} 6... Nxe4 {or . The idea of this exchange is that Black frees the f6 square for his other knight and he will gain a tempo on our queen. The drawback is that after 7.Qxe4 our centralized queen has many promising squares to go to.}) 7. Qxe4 Nf6 {White has numerous directions here and in practice, White players have tried to put the queen on literally every sensible square. Our dream would be to choose the queen a location where it exerts pressure, isn't vulnerable to attacks and doesn't obstruct the development of the white pieces. However, you can't have it all :)} 8. Qh4 $1 ({After a process of analysis and elimination we decided that} 8. Qh4 {is the strongest as well as the most annoying move for Black to face. Firstly, the queen can only be attacked if the f6-knight, the defender of Black's kingside, moves to another square. Secondly, the queen is perfectly placed to support a future kingside attack with Bd3 or g4-g5. It's surprisingly easy for Black to get in a horrible position by playing 'natural moves' like O-O.}) 8... Be7 {Black develops while eyeing our queen. The truth is that while moving the knight away from f6 may annoy White a bit, there is nothing concrete. We shall proceed with development.} 9. Nf3 ({Keeping all options open - as we've explained in the chapter introduction, it's useful to keep Black guessing about the placement of our king. While we go queenside 95% percent of the time, it's recommended to delay} 9. O-O-O {and develop our kingside pieces first. We don't want to invite a5-a4 shenanigans by committing our king too early.}) 9... Nd5 {The best move, annoying our queen. After we move our queen away, Black has two ideas: 1) Bring his king into safety with ...O-O 2) Trade the Horwitz bishop with ...Bf6 Logically, we'll aim to prevent the former by putting the queen on a square where it hits g7. We'll meet ...Bf6 with Ne5, so it's important to keep control of the e5 square as well. White has many queen moves here but following the ideas above, the correct way to proceed is clear.} 10. Qd4 $1 {The queen is brilliantly placed on d4 . She prevents ( 10...O-O??? on account of 11.Qxg7# mate, while preparing to meet 10...Bf6 with 10.Qg3 runs into concrete problems: 10...Bf6 11.Ne5 and now 11...Nb4! is surprisingly tricky to meet.} Bf6 ({Safeguarding the g7-pawn. The other way to do this is} 10... Nf6 {, but Black is just trying to force a repetition. We suggest that you continue with} 11. Qxd8+ Bxd8 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Rg1 $1 {followed by g4 and Ne5 with dangerous kingside play. The queens are off the board but we can still create threats with our remaining pieces! Returning to the diagram position, White has only one good way to repel Black's threat.}) 11. Ne5 $1 {The knight does an excellent job on e5, where it cannot be challenged. Next, we'll finish development and launch a kingside attack, as usual. Note that if Black castles kingside, the f6-bishop wouldn't do much to protect the king compared to a knight on that square. Objectively speaking, White is better and we clearly have the easier game. We'll show you a sample line to demonstrate how quickly Black can fall right into a brutal attack.} O-O ({Not the most accurate move - Black should have delayed committing his king with something like} 11... Qd6 {, when we recommend} 12. f4 $1 {to stabilize the e5-knight. However, castling is a natural move and it's instructive to see how White could start an attack.}) 12. Bd3 {Setting up a battery pointing towards Black's king.} a5 13. Qe4 g6 ({Checkmate in one threatened, so Black doesn't have many choices. The only move is} 13... g6) {The pawn is a 'hook' to open lines and we'll exploit it!} 14. h4 $16 {h5 is coming and a killer assault on Black's king is brewing. Let's take stock: including the h1-rook, White has five (!) pieces participating in the attack, compared to just one defender (f6-bishop) for Black. It's clear that White is having a lot of fun here and the engine confirms that we're clearly better. Conclusion: in this chapter, we've taken a look at the critical position after 1.e4 e6 2.b3 d5 3.Bb2 dxe4 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Qe2 . Specifically, all alternatives to 5...Be7 and 5...Bb4 are covered. Each of them has an independent flavour and we've shown brand new directions for White in many lines. Generally, these 5th move alternatives tend to appear as a result of Black knowing no theory instead of deliberate preparation, so you should be happy facing them. In the next chapter, we'll take a look at 5...Bb4 and 5...Be7 - the crux of the Horwitz Attack. See you there!} *

