{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... O-O ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) {Doesn't fit with Black's previous move. We can safely snatch the e4-pawn having covered d2 and Black's bishop will be misplaced.} 7. Nxe4 Nbd7 {Black prepares meeting Nxf6+ with ...Nxf6, protecting the kingside. His main idea now is Qe7-Ba3, swapping off our strong bishop. 7...Nxe4?! is a popular mistake. 8.Qxe4 Nc6 9.Nf3 and Black's kingside lacks defenders. Bd3 is coming next, forcing a black pawn to move forward and leave weaknesses behind.} 8. g4 $5 ({One of the various ideas we have at our disposal. We are simply launching the g-pawn and ...Nxe4 will be met with Qxe4, activating the queen with tempo. Other possible approaches: A)} 8. a3 $5 Be7 9. Nf3 {is very similar to the 5...Be7 variation. The extra tempo a3 isn't so important. B) 8.Nf3 allows 8...Qe7 when Black's threat of Ba3 and consequently a5-a4 isn't easy to deal with. Our recommendation skips Nf3 for now for quick kingside play. We'll exchange the f6-knight next move and charge forward with g4-g5.}) 8... Qe7 {Trying to trade the dark-squared bishops, which would greatly ease Black's defence. While this exchange isn't always bad for White, we often prefer to avoid it to retain attacking chances. However, you should be flexible in your thinking as well and understand that sometimes, it's worth giving up the bishop pair for positional factors e.g control of the centre.} 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. g5 {Let's kick the knight away!} Nd7 (10... Nd5 {is also possible, but the knight risks becoming a target on d5. We suggest that you switch gears and go for positional control with} 11. Nf3 Ba3 12. c4 $1 Nb6 13. d4 {+=. White has a stable edge and can play on both flanks.}) 11. Kb1 $13 Z0 ({The g5-pawn is poisoned:} 11... Qxg5 $2 12. Nf3 {with Rg1 and h4-h5 to follow is not fun for Black. We're sidestepping the bishop exchange, preparing to meet ...Ba3 with Ba1. Ideally, our next moves are Nf3, Qe4 and Bd3, setting up a killer battery against Black's king.}) *

