{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Bxc3 $5 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) {Black goes for a principled and sharp mode of play. Black prevents the threat of Nxe4 bluntly and signalling his intention to keep the e4-pawn for some time. The cost is that the dark squares are forever weakened with the presence of White's Horwitz bishop, so basically, Black is sacrificing a positional factor for a fat extra pawn. This variation is particularly 'messy', featuring more unclear, complicated chess than most other variations in this course.} 7. dxc3 $1 ({Much more promising than} 7. Bxc3 a5 $1 {or 7...Nc6!? with easy play for Black. The 'fractured' pawn structure is more than welcome since we have the open d-file and the doubled pawns will serve as defenders of White's king. Most likely, White will push the front c-pawn to c4 in order to re-open the long diagonal for the powerhouse on b2. White can play around the e4-pawn with g4 (with or without h3) and threaten to annoy Black with g4-g5. The queen should be put on e3 to free the e2-g3 route for our king's knight. The above guidelines act as a vague picture of White's plans. Generally speaking, we're happy to play a pawn down for 'uncertain' compensation, since the e4-pawn is weak and most likely will fall anyway. If anything, Black should be more careful not to soften his dark squares too much having given up his prized DSB (dark-squared bishop!)}) 7... Nbd7 $6 {The knight just doesn't belong here. It is like a blocker on the road, preventing Black's queenside pieces from getting out.} 8. g4 $1 {Here we go! We never miss the chance to strike. g4-g5 is coming and if ...h6, we'll prepare the thrust with h4! Black's pieces are truly uncoordinated; if he is not careful he may land in an early disaster.} Qe7 (8... h6 9. h4 $1 {followed by Bg2 renews the threat of g4-g5 with a strong effect. Black is trying to cover his dark squares, but it doesn't help much.}) 9. g5 {Forward!} Nd5 10. h4 {Safeguarding the g5-pawn. We have the idea of c4 now to open the long diagonal.} Nc5 {Black defends the e4-pawn, but we couldn't care less about it since it will eventually fall like autumn leaves anyway. The question here is how do we continue the initiative and create threats? We would like to bring to your attention a deep, effective and geometrically pleasing manoeuvre.} 11. Nh3 $1 {The start of a great plan. The knight's normal square on f3 is denied, so it goes to the rim of the board. Next, we'll play c4 to clear the f4 square for the knight.} O-O 12. c4 Nb4 13. a3 Nc6 14. Nf4 $16 {The knight has reached its dream destination! White has a promising attack with Rg1, Qe3 and possibly Nh5 coming. The dark squares f6 and g7 are particularly helpless. If you turn on the computer, you may be surprised with its evaluation of this position :)} *

