{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Bxc3 $5 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) {Black goes for a principled and sharp mode of play. Black prevents the threat of Nxe4 bluntly and signalling his intention to keep the e4-pawn for some time. The cost is that the dark squares are forever weakened with the presence of White's Horwitz bishop, so basically, Black is sacrificing a positional factor for a fat extra pawn. This variation is particularly 'messy', featuring more unclear, complicated chess than most other variations in this course.} 7. dxc3 $1 ({Much more promising than} 7. Bxc3 a5 $1 {or 7...Nc6!? with easy play for Black. The 'fractured' pawn structure is more than welcome since we have the open d-file and the doubled pawns will serve as defenders of White's king. Most likely, White will push the front c-pawn to c4 in order to re-open the long diagonal for the powerhouse on b2. White can play around the e4-pawn with g4 (with or without h3) and threaten to annoy Black with g4-g5. The queen should be put on e3 to free the e2-g3 route for our king's knight. The above guidelines act as a vague picture of White's plans. Generally speaking, we're happy to play a pawn down for 'uncertain' compensation, since the e4-pawn is weak and most likely will fall anyway. If anything, Black should be more careful not to soften his dark squares too much having given up his prized DSB (dark-squared bishop!)}) 7... Qe7 {More sensible than . The d7 square should be reserved for the bishop instead, just in case Black wants to castle queenside.} 8. g4 ({White has a range of options, for example,} 8. c4 {or even go wild with}) (8. f3 $5 {. We decide to be consistent with our other recommendations and start with g4! The idea is, of course, to dislodge Black's knight on f6 with g5 next. In the Lichess Database, White has won an amazing 68% of games that have reached this position, from a sample size of over 100 games!}) 8... e5 $5 ({Black seeks direct play and threatens the g4-pawn. The game is now sharp and concrete. Both sides have to rely on move-by-move tactics instead of just common sense chess. Not surprisingly, Stockfish likes} 8... e5 $5 {very much, suggesting it is the only way to equalize and other options are clearly better for White. We will show you the fun stuff, but beware that}) (8... e5 $5 {isn't something you are likely to face :)}) 9. g5 ({We march on in principled fashion.} 9. h3 $5 {is also possible with more solid play, but we prefer entering the complications, which is very dangerous for Black. Right on the next move, Black faces an important decision regarding the knight.}) 9... Ng4 $1 {Apparently, the only way to hold Black's position together. He prevents Qe4 thanks to the fork on f2. There is a threat to the g5-pawn now which we should address. 9...Bg4? is a tactical mistake, when the easiest refutation is 10.gxf6 !? Bxe2 11.fxe7 Bxd1 12.Kxd1 when we have two minor pieces for a rook and pawn. However, it's likely that Black's king will get stuck in the centre which tips the balance in White's favour. If you dislike this, 10.Qb5+ Nfd7 11.f3 is +2 for White according to the machine, but both sides are walking on a slippery road. 9...Nfd7 is dubious due to 10.h4! and we want to take on e4 next followed by Nf3 and Bh3, crushing Black in the centre. A fancy line Stockfish offered is 10...Nc5 11.b4! Na4 12.Qb5+ Bd7 13.Qxb7 Nb6 14.Qxc7 O-O 15.Qd6 with a large advantage for White. White has captured two pawns and got away with it.} 10. Nh3 $5 {) A great multipurpose move - we defend the f2 and g5 pawns with the knight and threaten Qxe4 as well as introducing Rg1xg4. The knight on g4 is active, but it's also running short of squares. 10.h4 is what we play in similar situations, but with the knight on g4, the position simply demands White to act quickly and vigorously. 10.Nh3!? is a creative idea that sets a lot of tough problems for Black to solve and trust me, Black can fall into a losing position very easily from this point! We also analysed the sharp and computer-like shot 10.f4!? the point is to block the c1-h6 diagonal so ...Qxg5 wouldn't come with a check. 10...exf4 11.Bh3 f3 12.Nxf3! with unclear complications, but ultimately, we decided that our main recommendation is more testing.} f5 $5 11. gxf6 ({A provocative and risky pawn thrust. Black is plonking the knight on g4 and basically forcing a change in the pawn structure with} 11. gxf6 {. The pawn transformation does improve Black's piece coordination but saddles him with a weak pair of doubled pawns.}) {Let's not forget the rule of en passant like patzers. If not for this extraordinary rule of chess, Black's position would be great with a great knight on g4 and the rolling kingside pawn majority.} 11... Nxf6 {Forced, in order to hold on to the e4-pawn. Black hasn't castled yet, so if we're allowed to capture the e4-pawn his king would be in danger. Moreover, there is the sneaky threat of ...Bg4, pinning and winning an exchange.} 12. Rg1 Z0 ({Controlling the g4 square and hinting at some pressure on g7. Next, we can activate the knight on the rim with Ng5. Another thematic idea is the f3 pawn sacrifice to open up lines while Black's king is still struggling for safety. Moreover, if the black bishop moves too early, White has the annoying Qb5+ check. Generally, if we manage to restore the material equilibrium, then Black would suffer since our bishop pair will work powerfully in open positions. Our analysis of the position showed that White has better chances, a few sample lines: A)} 12... Nc6 13. Ng5 Bf5 $6 {can be met with} 14. Qb5 $1 {and Black is in trouble, since} Rb8 15. Qa4 $3 {introduces the paradoxical but deadly threat of Ba3, trapping the queen. B)}) (12... Bf5 13. f3 $1 {is a nice tactical trick, exploiting Black's undefended bishop and b7-pawn. He should return the material with} Nbd7 14. Nf2 O-O-O 15. fxe4 {when White will continue with Qe3 and c4. White has a clear advantage due to the bishop pair.}) *

