sition together. He prevents Qe4 thanks to the fork on f2. There is a threat to the g5-pawn now which we should address. 9...Bg4? is a tactical mistake, when the easiest refutation is 10.gxf6 !? Bxe2 11.fxe7 Bxd1 12.Kxd1 when we have two minor pieces for a rook and pawn. However, it's likely that Black's king will get stuck in the centre which tips the balance in White's favour. If you dislike this, 10.Qb5+ Nfd7 11.f3 is +2 for White according to the machine, but both sides are walking on a slippery road. 9...Nfd7 is dubious due to 10.h4! and we want to take on e4 next followed by Nf3 and Bh3, crushing Black in the centre. A fancy line Stockfish offered is 10...Nc5 11.b4! Na4 12.Qb5+ Bd7 13.Qxb7 Nb6 14.Qxc7 O-O 15.Qd6 with a large advantage for White. White has captured two pawns and got away with it.} 10. Nh3 $5 {) A great multipurpose move - we defend the f2 and g5 pawns with the knight and threaten Qxe4 as well as introducing Rg1xg4. The knight on g4 is active, but it's also running short of squares. 10.h4 is what we play in similar situations, but with the knight on g4, the position simply demands White to act quickly and vigorously. 10.Nh3!? is a creative idea that sets a lot of tough problems for Black to solve and trust me, Black can fall into a losing position very easily from this point! We also analysed the sharp and computer-like shot 10.f4!? the point is to block the c1-h6 diagonal so ...Qxg5 wouldn't come with a check. 10...exf4 11.Bh3 f3 12.Nxf3! with unclear complications, but ultimately, we decided that our main recommendation is more testing.} h6 {This move occurred in both games that reached this position. Black's idea is to challenge the thorn on g5 and free the f6 square for his knight. Needless to say, we have to play with power to prevent this scenario.} 11. Rg1 $1 Nxh2 ({Hitting the knight on g4 and forcing Black to take on h2, since allowing Rxg4 winning material is a big no-no. If Black switches to} 11... f5 $5 {, we can play in the spirits of the 10...f5 line [/variation/23953369] with} 12. gxf6 Nxf6 13. f3 {with promising compensation for the sacrificed pawn, given Black's poor development and exposed king.}) {Grabbing this pawn is best. Besides winning a pawn, Black is ready to eliminate White's light-squared bishop.} 12. gxh6 Rxh6 ({Opening the g-file is beneficial for us since we have a lead in development and our rook will have a great time enjoying the open file. A simple count reveals that while we're temporarily a few pawns down, we have many more pieces developed and ready for action. Black should be fine engine-wise after both} 12... gxh6 {and}) (12... Rxh6 {, but in either case, we can confidently say that the road is full of dirt and potholes for them. It's more than enough for any ordinary player on the streets to know up until this point, however we have gone the extra mile for those who are interested!}) {Black goes for the h3 knight but dangerously weakens his back rank.} 13. Qxe4 {b7 is hanging so Black is unable to take on h3. A nasty surprise White has in store is} Nxf1 14. Rxg7 $3 {Boom! The devastating threat of Rg8+ forces Black's hand.} Kf8 {This wild position is evaluated strictly as 0.00 by the all-knowing Stockfish. We are not sure if Mittens has any objections.} 15. Qg2 $5 (15. Rh7 {is another alternative. The blunt threat of Rg8+ forces an only move. Now the game is a forced draw after a crazy computer sequence.}) 15... Rh8 16. Rd3 Nh2 $1 17. Rd8+ {Clearing the a3-f8 diagonal to force a repetition.} Qxd8 18. Ba3+ Ke8 19. Rg8+ Rxg8 20. Qxg8+ Kd7 21. Qxf7+ Kc6 22. Qc4+ {Neither side can avoid the refutation. Holy Silicon Monster!} *

