welcome since we have the open d-file and the doubled pawns will serve as defenders of White's king. Most likely, White will push the front c-pawn to c4 in order to re-open the long diagonal for the powerhouse on b2. White can play around the e4-pawn with g4 (with or without h3) and threaten to annoy Black with g4-g5. The queen should be put on e3 to free the e2-g3 route for our king's knight. The above guidelines act as a vague picture of White's plans. Generally speaking, we're happy to play a pawn down for 'uncertain' compensation, since the e4-pawn is weak and most likely will fall anyway. If anything, Black should be more careful not to soften his dark squares too much having given up his prized DSB (dark-squared bishop!)}) 7... Qe7 {More sensible than . The d7 square should be reserved for the bishop instead, just in case Black wants to castle queenside.} 8. g4 ({White has a range of options, for example,} 8. c4 {or even go wild with}) (8. f3 $5 {. We decide to be consistent with our other recommendations and start with g4! The idea is, of course, to dislodge Black's knight on f6 with g5 next. In the Lichess Database, White has won an amazing 68% of games that have reached this position, from a sample size of over 100 games!}) 8... Bd7 $6 {Black ignores our kingside expansions and goes on with his queenside development. In this case though, he should have at least prevented our g5 thrust with 8...h6 [/variation/23953379] before proceeding with ...Bd7.} 9. g5 {Let's kick the poor knight around for a chase.} Nd5 10. Nh3 $1 ({A retreat to g8 would be way too embarrassing :) Both} 10. h4 {and}) (10. Nh3 {work wonders for White now, with the threat of c3-c4, not to mention Qxe4 in both cases. However, for some subtle details}) (10. Nh3 {is slightly stronger.}) 10... f5 ({This weird-looking knight sortie has been seen once before in a 8...e5 line [/variation/23953368]. The point is that we're defending the g5-pawn and threatening c4 as well as Qxe4. Black's only way to address both threats is} 10... f5 {, when the knight will be amazing on f4. 10.h4!? is also clearly better for White, as a matter of fact.}) {If Black allows us to regain the e4-pawn it would be a disaster. Black needs a pawn to partially compensate for his troubles. The text move also defends the g7-pawn indirectly by freeing the 7th rank.} 11. c4 {Kicking the centralized knight back and creating a magnificent outpost for our own horse on f4.} Nb6 12. Nf4 $1 {Pawns never move backwards. With every pawn move, weak squares are left behind - a patzer chess player once claimed. Black's 10...f5 pawn break seriously weakens his camp and we sneak into our enemy's territory. Among several killing threats, the most dangerous is 13.Qh5+ Qf7 14.g6+- winning material.} Qxg5 {The best move, removing the thorn that annoyed Black so much.} 13. Qh5+ {Exchanging Black's best piece and the only defender of the kingside! Now our bishop + knight combo teams up brilliantly to destroy Black's kingside.} Qxh5 14. Nxh5 $16 Z0 ({A picturesque position. White is temporarily two pawns down, yet he is clearly dominating. White's activity is simply monstrous with the Bb2 sniper combined with Nh5 and Rd1, not to mention an eventual Rg1. For example,} 14... Rg8 {can be met by either} 15. Nxg7+ {or inserting 15.c5!? Nd5 first before 16.Nxg7+ , with a powerful initiative.}) *

