{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Qe7 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) 7. g4 ({The most logical move, per Black's previous one. Black prepares ...Ba3, trading White's VIP bishop and weakens our king's cover. After our bishop is traded there is also the idea of ...a5-a4 to endanger our king. This variation is frequently encountered since its ideas are simple and easy to apply. According to theory, the Bb4+Qe7 setup is a safe way to equalize against the Horwitz Attack and it has been recommended by GM Emmanuel Berg as well as NM Bryan Tillis in their respective repertoire works (see the Repertoire Clash). White has three main approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) {A theoretical novelty which we've spent a lot of time analysing. However, it looks totally unimpressive, a good way to confront White's play being} 7... Ba3 {Simply proceeding according to plan.} 8. g5 Nd5 9. h4 a5 {Black's counterplay is quick, so White is advised to bail out.} 10. Qxe4 a4 11. Nxd5 Bxb2+ 12. Kxb2 exd5 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {All of this is supported by the machine. With natural moves, Black is standing strong in the endgame and White really has nothing here. There are alternatives along the way - but in conclusion, 7. g4 does not challenge Black enough.} *

