{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Qe7 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) 7. Nxe4 ({The most logical move, per Black's previous one. Black prepares ...Ba3, trading White's VIB (Very Important Bishop) which weakens our king's cover. After our bishop is traded there is also the idea of ...a5-a4 to endanger our king. This variation is frequently encountered since its ideas are simple and easy to apply. According to theory, the Bb4+Qe7 setup is a safe way to equalize against the Horwitz Attack and it has been recommended by GM Emmanuel Berg as well as NM Bryan Tillis in their respective repertoire works (see the Repertoire Clash [/variation/30221753]). White has three main approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) 7... Nbd7 ({This is the mainline. White agrees that Black can exchange two pairs of minor pieces with} 7... Ba3 {and this is indeed what most Black players have done, simplifying the position.}) {Black supports the knight on f6 but misses the chance to force a favourable bishop exchange.} 8. Kb1 {We logically avoid ...Ba3, which can now be met with Ba1, preserving White's superior bishop.} O-O {A slightly misguided decision. While Black's move may be 'fine' in engine terms, it is not 'good' because it makes White's play focused on one target - the king.} 9. Nxf6+ {Forcing the other knight to go to f6 when g4-g5 will gain time on the knight.} Nxf6 10. g4 {Charging forward at full speed. The reason White should often delay g2-g4 in favour of piece development is that in most cases when Black hasn't castled, the pawn thrust achieves little. Here Black has castled so White's aggressive g4 is justified. We'll follow up with g5, Nf3 and Qe4-Bd3, setting up a deadly battery.} a5 ({Black creates some counterplay.} 10... Ba3 11. Ba1 $1 {is the point of Kb1 earlier, keeping the dangerous bishop.}) 11. g5 {The knight is stable on f6, guarding numerous key entrances to Black's king. However, its time has ended.} Nd5 (11... Nd7 12. Nf3 $1 {protecting the g5-pawn} a4 13. Qe4 $1 {reaches a thematic and poisonous piece formation for White. Bd3 is coming next when White's attack comes first. We would refer you to this model game to see how White's attacking plans can be applied in this kind of position. Back to . The knight move is natural but it allows an artificial resource immediately pointed out by the engine.}) 12. c4 {Kicking the knight to a passive square where it is temporarily out of play.} Nb6 13. Qe5 $1 {The surprising point behind White's concept. For the time being, Black has no defender of the g7 square and the threat of Qxg7 checkmate forces the second player to commit a sad weakening.} f6 ({Forced, to stop the threat of mate in one.} 13... f5 {can be met in the same way, if you remember the rule of en passant.}) 14. gxf6 Rxf6 15. Bd3 {A final accurate move ensures White's advantage. We are controlling the key light squares on the kingside. White's bishops are terrifying monsters! We will follow up with Nf3 and Qe4, creating more threats on the kingside. Black's e6, g7 and h7 pawns are juicy targets as well as the king himself.} *

