{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Qe7 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) 7. Nxe4 ({The most logical move, per Black's previous one. Black prepares ...Ba3, trading White's VIB (Very Important Bishop) which weakens our king's cover. After our bishop is traded there is also the idea of ...a5-a4 to endanger our king. This variation is frequently encountered since its ideas are simple and easy to apply. According to theory, the Bb4+Qe7 setup is a safe way to equalize against the Horwitz Attack and it has been recommended by GM Emmanuel Berg as well as NM Bryan Tillis in their respective repertoire works (see the Repertoire Clash [/variation/30221753]). White has three main approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) 7... Nbd7 ({This is the mainline. White agrees that Black can exchange two pairs of minor pieces with} 7... Ba3 {and this is indeed what most Black players have done, simplifying the position.}) {Black supports the knight on f6 but misses the chance to force a favourable bishop exchange.} 8. Kb1 {) We logically avoid ...Ba3, which can now be met with Ba1, preserving White's superior bishop.} a5 {A rule of thumb is that we always meet ...a5 with ( a4! - that is unless a Black bishop on a3 blocks the way. 8...Ba3 will be examined next.} 9. a4 {Stopping Black's queenside expansion in its tracks.} O-O 10. Nf3 ({Black has failed to create a ruckus on the queenside with ...a5-a4, and if he wants to attack our king, it will take some time.} 10. g4 {is perfectly fine, but in this situation, we see no need to rush. Meanwhile, our traditional kingside attack - Nxf6+ followed by g4-g5 - is coming. The following sample line is a good demonstration of White's resources.}) 10... b6 {Black prepares smooth development of the light-squared bishop via either b7 or a6. The drawback of this move is the weakening of the c6 square, which White should exploit immediately.} 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. Ne5 $1 {An exclamation mark for this classy idea. White anticipate ...Ba6 and is ready to sneak in the c6 square. Moreover, we anticipate ...Bb7 as well by removing pieces from the long diagonal!} Bb7 {Covering c6 and preventing g2-g4 on account of the hanging rook. 12...Ba6?! 13.Qf3! Bxf1 14.Nc6! is the shot, forcing a clearly better middlegame for White following 14...Qd6 15.Bxf6! gxf6 16.Rhxf1 . Black's rooks are unable to reach d8 while his pieces are disconnected.} 13. Rg1 ({The best strategy to deal with a fianchettoed bishop? Remove all pieces from the long diagonal! Having removed the rook from the vulnerable h1 square, White is all set for g4-g5.} 13. h4 $5 {with the idea of h5 and Rh3 is very promising for White as well. Generally, in this kind of fluid position, knowledge of standard attacking methods is more valuable than concrete lines. By going through a lot of 'typical' variations like this and the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter, you will (hopefully) handle the 3...dxe4 variation better in practice.}) *

