 discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Bxb2+ ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black exchanges the bishops immediately but allows the white king to take up a good position on b2.} 10. Kxb2 c5 ({The king plays an active role in defending itself! If later we ever play a3/c3, the pawn formation is securely supported by the king. White has a slight lead in development since Black's only developed troop is the not-so-well-placed queen on f6. Our ideal formation is knight to f3, queen to e3 or e4 (to clear the a6-f1 diagonal) then our bishop can get out followed by the h1-rook. In this position,} 10... O-O {and}) (10... c5 {are Black's most popular choices. We'll take a look at both moves.}) 11. c3 $146 {)} ({Black hits directly in the center, planning cxd4 and Nc6 with a lot of exchanges on the d4 square. In his own practice, Huy faced this position in a classical game and went for the tame} 11. Qf3 {, after which he exchanged queens and a draw was quickly agreed upon. Now we know better and are pleased to recommend something different.}) ({A nice, brand-new idea.} 11. Nf3 {isn't ideal because of} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. Qe3 Bd7 {and in our opinion, Black just equalizes with ...Nxd4 coming. The point of}) (11. c3 {is to keep more pieces on the board and shield the king from the black queen. dxc5 is now a threat.}) 11... cxd4 12. Rxd4 Nc6 {The best line for Black. He gains some time on the rook.} 13. Rd2 {We should retreat the rook to d2 and NOT d1 because in the future the other rook can easily come to the d-file as well. We will achieve a totally harmonious setup with Nf3 and Qe3 (where the queen protects the dark squares and cannot be attacked) before deciding on a square for the bishop and sliding the other rook to d1. White has a comfortable edge, especially if he follows the plan described above. If it sounds too vague, we'll show a sample line.} O-O 14. Nf3 e5 ({Trying to develop the bishop the other way backfires horribly:} 14... b6 $2 15. Qe4 Bb7 16. Rd7 $1 {is a cute tactical motif, winning instant material.}) 15. Qe3 $14 {The bishop can come to b5 next, exerting pressure on the e5-pawn. If Black prevents it, put the bishop on e2. We'll quickly double rook on the d-file and invade through d6. A very important point is that all piece exchanges tend to favour White because in the endgame White has the more active king and is able to create an outside passer. With such annoying pressure White is definitely better here. We don't think the popular 9...Bxb2+ equalizes at all.} *

