 approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) 7... Ba3 ({This is the mainline. White agrees that Black can exchange two pairs of minor pieces with} 7... Ba3 {and this is indeed what most Black players have done, simplifying the position.}) {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops, which decreases the strength of future kingside attacks by White. Moreover, ...a5-a4 is a possibility White needs to watch out for. 7...Ba3 is the mainline and what many respected theoretical works have recommended for Black. These facts are caused by the simplicity of this variation - Black players are under the impression that they are out of danger after the exchanges. Yes, these positions are equal and sometimes can be dry, but it's always a game. Both sides have to make moves and then there are chances for everyone to outplay their opponent. After a lot of digging, we've created some small ideas that do not drastically change the landscape, but offer a clear gameplan for White and force Black to solve little problems.} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. d4 ({The cheapo is that} 9. Bxa3 Qa1# {is mate - an echo of the famous Englund Gambit trap ( 1.d4 e5 2.dxe5 Nc6 3.Nf3 Qe7 4.Bf4 Qb4+ 5.Bd2 Qxb2 6.Bc3 Bb4 7.Qd2 Bxc3 8.Qxc3 Qc1# ) that chess Youtubers like Eric Rosen and GothamChess have popularized through videos with titles like 'Winning in 8 moves' etc. Anyway, we are not here to discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Qe7 $1 ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black holds up the annoying bishop on a3 and reserves the idea of ...a5. To our knowledge, this fine nuance was first recommended as a novelty by GM Jacob Aagaard and Nikos Ntirlis in their excellent 2013 book 'Playing the French'. Turned out that after ten whopping years, this hasn't become common knowledge, since 9...Qe7 happens in only 5% of the games in the ChessBase Database.} 10. Nf3 {Black's queen coming to a3 would be annoying indeed, so we don't rush to exchange the bishops either. In fact, both sides want the other to release the tension!} O-O {Castling feels like a small inaccuracy - committing the king too early. In any case, White starts an attack immediately now!} 11. Qe4 $1 {This is a recurring motif in the Open Horwitz. When Black castles, we prepare a battery with Qe4+Bd3. This battery is particularly effective when Black's kingside lacks defenders.} Nd7 {Black sends a knight to help protect h7.} 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. Qh4 $13 {In positions with opposite-sided castling, time is a crucial factor and there is often no space for retreats. White is planning g4-g5, removing the guardian on f6. There is also Ne5, putting the knight on an excellent central square. Black is likely to commit a weakening with ...g6 when White has plans of h4-h5 opening up the kingside, or g5 and manoeuvring the knight to f6. To slow down Black's ...a5-a4 break there is the c3 resource, preparing to meet ...a4 with b4, shutting down the queenside. White may not have enough pieces to checkmate Black, but by organizing a kingside attack we will induce some positional weaknesses and distract Black from playing in other sectors of the board.} *

