{Hello! We welcome you to the second chapter where we deal with the position after 5.Qe2 . In this chapter, we'll deal with 5...Bb4 , a respectable variation against the Horwitz Attack.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A multipurpose move: we put the queen on an active square, prepare a recapture of the e4-pawn and pave the way for queenside castling.} Bb4 6. O-O-O ({Black defends the e4-pawn indirectly, since} 6. Nxe4 $4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 $4 {loses immediately to} Qxd2# {mate. This trick has happened in numerous online games so it's worth knowing it. Another idea is that when we castle queenside, ...Qe7 followed by Ba3 exchanges off our dynamic Horwitz bishop. Additionally, Black can capture on c3 and maintain his extra e4-pawn, although positionally, it would be a risky decision due to White's uncontested dark-squared bishop.}) 6... Qe7 ({We would love to take on e4 on the 6th move, but if that's not possible we castle. The threat is Nxe4, and Black's bishop would find itself misplaced on b4 with nothing to do. Therefore, the two sensible approaches Black can try here are: 1)} 6... Bxc3 $5 {is a radical attempt. Black sacrifices the dark squares in hopes of maintaining the glorified extra e4-pawn. 2)}) (6... Qe7 {is more thematic, preparing ...Ba3 and later even ...a5-a4. This has been the recommendation of most authors going for 5...Bb4 from the black side.}) 7. Nxe4 ({The most logical move, per Black's previous one. Black prepares ...Ba3, trading White's VIB (Very Important Bishop) which weakens our king's cover. After our bishop is traded there is also the idea of ...a5-a4 to endanger our king. This variation is frequently encountered since its ideas are simple and easy to apply. According to theory, the Bb4+Qe7 setup is a safe way to equalize against the Horwitz Attack and it has been recommended by GM Emmanuel Berg as well as NM Bryan Tillis in their respective repertoire works (see the Repertoire Clash [/variation/30221753]). White has three main approaches to combat 6...Qe7: A)} 7. g4 Ba3 8. g5 {is interesting, but White's one-pawn attack is too tame to even cause the slightest damage. B)}) (7. Kb1 $5 {avoids the exchange of dark-squared bishops with} Ba3 8. Ba1 {being the idea, preserving the valuable Horwitz bishop. C)}) (7. Nxe4 {is the classic line that people have played for decades. After} Ba3 {two sets of minor pieces are exchanged, reducing dynamic possibilities for both sides. Despite the simplified nature of the position, we will show you little ideas to continue posing problems. We've decided to concentrate energy on the mainline with}) (7. Nxe4 {, although the above alternatives are explained as well.}) 7... Ba3 ({This is the mainline. White agrees that Black can exchange two pairs of minor pieces with} 7... Ba3 {and this is indeed what most Black players have done, simplifying the position.}) {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops, which decreases the strength of future kingside attacks by White. Moreover, ...a5-a4 is a possibility White needs to watch out for. 7...Ba3 is the mainline and what many respected theoretical works have recommended for Black. These facts are caused by the simplicity of this variation - Black players are under the impression that they are out of danger after the exchanges. Yes, these positions are equal and sometimes can be dry, but it's always a game. Both sides have to make moves and then there are chances for everyone to outplay their opponent. After a lot of digging, we've created some small ideas that do not drastically change the landscape, but offer a clear gameplan for White and force Black to solve little problems.} 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. d4 ({The cheapo is that} 9. Bxa3 Qa1# {is mate - an echo of the famous Englund Gambit trap ( 1.d4 e5 2.dxe5 Nc6 3.Nf3 Qe7 4.Bf4 Qb4+ 5.Bd2 Qxb2 6.Bc3 Bb4 7.Qd2 Bxc3 8.Qxc3 Qc1# ) that chess Youtubers like Eric Rosen and GothamChess have popularized through videos with titles like 'Winning in 8 moves' etc. Anyway, we are not here to discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Qe7 $1 ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black holds up the annoying bishop on a3 and reserves the idea of ...a5. To our knowledge, this fine nuance was first recommended as a novelty by GM Jacob Aagaard and Nikos Ntirlis in their excellent 2013 book 'Playing the French'. Turned out that after ten whopping years, this hasn't become common knowledge, since 9...Qe7 happens in only 5% of the games in the ChessBase Database.} 10. Nf3 {Black's queen coming to a3 would be annoying indeed, so we don't rush to exchange the bishops either. In fact, both sides want the other to release the tension!} a5 {Black's flank attack is more poisonous than it may appear. If given time to play ...a4, it's likely that Black's queen would be able to invade through a3, forcing White's king out of the 'safe zone'.} 11. c3 {Taking a move to neutralize Black's bayonet attack. We prepare to meet ...a4 with b4, stabilizing the queenside.} a4 ({White's last move is precisely directed against} 11... a4 {.}) 12. b4 $1 {The triangle b4-c3-d4 makes a nice geometrical impression :)} Bxb2+ 13. Kxb2 $14 Z0 ({White has successfully coped with the first attacking wave. We have the positional threat of a3, completely locking down the queenside. Therefore Black must try} 13... a3+ $1 {when} 14. Ka1 {or 14.Kc1 are possible. In this unusual position, White will try to expand on the kingside with Qe5, h4-h5 and even Rh3. The pawn structure on the queenside looks weird, but in the short-term, it protects White's king well.}) *

