 discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Qe7 $1 ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black holds up the annoying bishop on a3 and reserves the idea of ...a5. To our knowledge, this fine nuance was first recommended as a novelty by GM Jacob Aagaard and Nikos Ntirlis in their excellent 2013 book 'Playing the French'. Turned out that after ten whopping years, this hasn't become common knowledge, since 9...Qe7 happens in only 5% of the games in the ChessBase Database.} 10. Nf3 {Black's queen coming to a3 would be annoying indeed, so we don't rush to exchange the bishops either. In fact, both sides want the other to release the tension!} a5 {Black's flank attack is more poisonous than it may appear. If given time to play ...a4, it's likely that Black's queen would be able to invade through a3, forcing White's king out of the 'safe zone'.} 11. c3 {Taking a move to neutralize Black's bayonet attack. We prepare to meet ...a4 with b4, stabilizing the queenside.} O-O {With the inclusion of ...a5 and c3 castling makes more sense. Nevertheless, White's reply remains the same.} 12. h4 Nd7 13. h5 h6 14. g4 {Followed by Rg1. White probably has nothing, but at least it's a complicated game.} *

