 discuss the merits of Internet gambits, so back to the Horwitz Attack. The text move is automatically played - if Black doesn't see this in advance he wouldn't go for 7...Ba3 at first. He would go for stuff like 7...Nxe4 as covered here [/variation/23953382].}) 9... Qe7 $1 ({Blocking the long diagonal and finally Bxa3 is - technically - a threat. At this point,} 9... Bxb2+ {is almost exclusively played. However, White can count on a positional advantage after recapturing with the king. 9...Qe7! is much more accurate, as we'll explain later.}) {Black holds up the annoying bishop on a3 and reserves the idea of ...a5. To our knowledge, this fine nuance was first recommended as a novelty by GM Jacob Aagaard and Nikos Ntirlis in their excellent 2013 book 'Playing the French'. Turned out that after ten whopping years, this hasn't become common knowledge, since 9...Qe7 happens in only 5% of the games in the ChessBase Database.} 10. Nf3 {Black's queen coming to a3 would be annoying indeed, so we don't rush to exchange the bishops either. In fact, both sides want the other to release the tension!} a5 {Black's flank attack is more poisonous than it may appear. If given time to play ...a4, it's likely that Black's queen would be able to invade through a3, forcing White's king out of the 'safe zone'.} 11. c3 {Taking a move to neutralize Black's bayonet attack. We prepare to meet ...a4 with b4, stabilizing the queenside.} O-O {With the inclusion of ...a5 and c3 castling makes more sense. Nevertheless, White's reply remains the same.} 12. Qe4 (12. h4 $5 {pushes Harry the h-pawn forward and is another way to create pressure on the kingside.} Nd7 13. h5 h6 14. g4 {White probably has no advantage here, but still, this caveman approach is worth a try. We decide to recommend the text move because Qe4 against ...O-O has been a recurring theme throughout the Open Horwitz and it makes sense to fix these patterns in your mind. The idea is Bd3 threatening checkmate.}) 12... Nd7 ({Black brings the knight in for defence.} 12... a4 {yields nothing on account of} 13. b4 {, blocking the queenside.}) 13. Bd3 Nf6 14. Qh4 $13 {The position is very similar to the 10...O-O variation [/variation/23953389] with the inclusion of ...a5 and c3, which are moves both sides would like to play anyway. We recommend that you check this line for more in-depth explanations for this type of position. Conclusion: In this chapter, we've tackled 3...dxe4 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Qe2 Bb4 , which is one of Black's best replies against the Horwitz Attack. After 6.O-O-O Black has two main options: 6...Qe7 and 6...Bxc3 With 6...Bxc3 Black wins a pawn but surrenders the dark squares. The critical tabiya arises after 7.dxc3 Qe7 8.g4! , which we've explored in great detail. 6...Qe7 is the most respected choice, preparing ...Ba3 and swapping off White's key bishop. We recommend the simple 7.Nxe4 which contains many tricky nuances. Aagaard and Ntirlis's suggestion of 9...Qe7! equalizes for Black, but the popular 9...Bxb2+ gives White a stable edge in the upcoming middlegame.} *

