1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. O-O-O ({Many have been and would be tempted by this move, but it is a slight inaccuracy. The reason is that in the phase from the 6th-10th moves, Black needs to decide how he wants to arrange his queenside pieces.} 6. O-O-O {commits the king while Black has not moved anything on the queenside. Therefore Black can choose an optimal set-up to create danger for the king.}) 6... a5 7. a4 O-O 8. Nxe4 c6 $1 {The key idea which makes White's position suspicious. Black prepares ...b7-b5 in one go, even as a pawn sacrifice. This idea would have been pretty much pointless had White's king stayed on e1. Black's position is preferable and in a practical game, it's a headache to deal with an attack on White's king. Please make a mental note of this position, because it shows exactly the scenario White should avoid in this variation.} *

