1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} Nxe4 $6 {Black exchanges off a key defender of his kingside, while his other knight isn't on time to reach f6. 6...Nbd7 7.Nf3 Black has nothing better than 7...O-O which transposes to 6...O-O .} 7. Qxe4 Bf6 8. d4 Qd5 (8... O-O $2 9. Bd3 $1 {is crushing for White.} g6 10. h4 {with a ferocious attack.}) 9. Qe3 $1 {Keeping the queens on} Nc6 10. Nf3 $14 {Black's pieces will be kicked back after we castle queenside.} *

