1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the other knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} Nbd7 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5, a4, c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {A tricky move. Black leaves the option of ...a5 followed by ...c6 open, so White should not rush with castling. 8.O-O-O?! can transpose to the 7...b6 line [/variation/29257102] after 8...b6 , but superior is 8...a5! 9.a4 c6! and White has been tricked into an undesirable position, as outlined at the start of the chapter.} 8. g4 $1 {We love this move. Go for the throat! This move shows our aggressive intention to play for a kingside attack. Black's last move, ...Nbd7, is quite slow, so Black is not in time to exploit the position of White's king in the centre.} b6 {When Black plays ...b6, the goal in mind is usually to challenge the knight on e4. Alas...} 9. g5 $1 {...Black is not in time! The knight is threatened and if Black takes on e4, White recaptures with the queen and is the first to seize the important diagonals.} Nd5 {The line we talked about is 8...Nxe4 9.Qxe4 Rb8 10.Bd3! strongly weakening the kingside. 10...g6 11.Qd4! threatening checkmate and further destroying Black's king shelter.} 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Rg1 {Some possible ideas are Kb1, c4, Ne5 and Rg3-h3. White has active pieces and a commanding position. Our pieces are pointing towards the kingside, so logically, a full-scale attack on the king is on the radar.} *

