1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the other knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} Nbd7 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5, a4, c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {A tricky move. Black leaves the option of ...a5 followed by ...c6 open, so White should not rush with castling. 8.O-O-O?! can transpose to the 7...b6 line [/variation/29257102] after 8...b6 , but superior is 8...a5! 9.a4 c6! and White has been tricked into an undesirable position, as outlined at the start of the chapter.} 8. g4 $1 {We love this move. Go for the throat! This move shows our aggressive intention to play for a kingside attack. Black's last move, ...Nbd7, is quite slow, so Black is not in time to exploit the position of White's king in the centre.} Nxe4 {The critical move to consider. Generally, it is inaccurate for Black to exchange on e4, since White's queen will be centralised. However, in this position, Black's other knight is ready to replace its companion on f6. Black even has the option to grab the g4-pawn which is quite a fun line to analyse.} 9. Qxe4 Nf6 10. Qe2 $5 ({White has to go for it. The tame} 10. Qf4 Bd6 11. Ne5 Nd7 {does not yield anything, so the retreat to e2 is best. We want to play g5 to kick the defensive knight away. It's up to Black whether he'd like to take the pawn.}) 10... a5 (10... b6 $6 {is again slow.} 11. g5 $1 Nd5 12. Rg1 {followed by Qe4, and Bd3 with a promising attack. We can meet Black's a-pawn advance in many ways, but let's stick to our rule of thumb.}) 11. a4 ({Block the queenside. We shall note that} 11. g5 $5 {is another way to treat the position.} Nd5 12. Rg1 a4 13. Qe4 {White may not ever castle, but we gain time for the kingside attack.}) 11... Nxg4 {Other moves can be met thematically with g5, O-O-O, Rg1, and so on.} 12. Rg1 {Leads to similar play to 10...Nxg4 , which we will examine next.} *

