1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the other knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} Nc6 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5, a4, c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {A logical developing move that fights for the centre. We should note that Black's knight isn't exactly well placed on c6, since it obstructs the future development of Black's c8-bishop. Black should aim to either transfer the knight to b4 (to develop the bishop to b7) or develop the bishop via a6.} 8. O-O-O {Black's dangerous ...a5 and ...c6 plan has been hindered, so White can castle. If Black does nothing, a pawn storm is coming.} a5 {Black wants to secure the b4 square for his knight. Otherwise, the knight on c6 makes no sense.} 9. a4 {According to our rule of thumb.} Nb4 {Black takes over the outpost created by 9.a4 and introduces the idea of ...c6-b5, among others.} 10. Nxf6+ ({We reckon with the ...b5 idea by swapping off a few pieces and preparing to put our queen on e4.} 10. g4 $6 {is the typical Horwitz move, but Black has the stunning} b5 $1 {grabbing the initiative.}) 10... Bxf6 11. Qe4 Bxb2+ 12. Kxb2 {White has a comfortable position. Our queen is nicely centralized and we are ready to kick back Black's best piece with c3. The knight is ready to jump into e5 while White can also consider d4-Bd3, provoking weaknesses on the kingside. The position is objectively equal, but if you understand the ideas better than your opponent you will get a competitive edge.} *

