the e5-square. Black's b7-bishop puts pressure on our kingside, so we cannot push our kingside pawns casually with g4 (the rook hangs!) Instead, there is an artificial and strong plan available: h4-Rh3-g4. Safeguarding the rook before pushing the g-pawn.} c5 (10... Nd7 {can be met, as usual, with} 11. f4 {followed by h4.}) 11. f4 {Supporting the e5-knight. h4 and Rh3 are coming.} Nc6 12. h4 {In case Black goes ...Nd4 to attack our queen, we can move Her Majesty to f2. Re1 is a useful move to solidify the e5-knight. And of course, White wants to get Rh3 and g4 in. With these guidelines in mind, let's follow the course of a correspondence game.} Nd4 13. Qf2 Rc8 14. Re1 Nc6 15. Rh3 Rc7 16. Bc3 $16 {Black has played some dubious moves while White followed through with his thematic plan. After all these preparatory moves, the first player can start a kingside initiative with Bd3 and g4. 1-0 (36) Milde,L (2340) -Cipolla,A (2222) ICCF email 2019.} *

