 f6. At the end of this chapter} 9. Kb1 $5 {is covered as a more fighting alternative.}) 9... Bxf6 ({Black fights for the e5-square. If} 9... Nxf6 {,} 10. Ne5 $1 {is a typical device. White's powerful knight controls the centre and supports a future kingside onslaught. Thematic moves like g4, g5, and h4 are coming.}) 10. d4 ({In the notes to 8...Nbd7 we have mentioned that} 10. Ne5 {is harmless. The text move is the other way to prevent the desirable (for Black) exchange of dark-squared bishops.}) (10. d4 {also controls the e5 square, so on the next turn, White can consider plonking a knight there. If Black does not challenge the h1-a8 diagonal, Qe4 is a strong idea, followed by Bd3.}) 10... c5 11. Ne5 {)} ({Black challenges our centre immediately. The natural} 11. Qe4 {turns out to be not a refutation because Black has the stunning reply} Qc7 $3 {preparing} 12. Qxa8 Bb7 {when White's queen is trapped. In the resulting middlegame Black's queen would be stronger than White's rooks.}) {Putting pressure on the d7-knight and threatening dxc5.} 11... cxd4 12. Ng4 $1 {A nice idea, preparing to butcher the black bishop. Black has ...e5 to support his pawn centre, but White has concrete resources to attack it. White has a promising position. We will include a sample line.} e5 $1 13. f4 $1 {Counterattacking immediately.} Re8 {Black does his best to maintain his one-pawn advantage and central control.} 14. Qd2 {We have ideas like Bb5, Nxf6+ and fxe5. Black also has to find concrete moves to avoid trouble.} Bh4 {We can't take on e5 because ...Bg5 costs the queen.} 15. g3 Bb7 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Qxg2 Be7 {The engine says this is the best move. Black transfers the bishop to ...c5 when needed.} 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Rxd4 Qc7 ({Nice in-between move. Black can't keep the extra knight, since} 19... Nd7 20. Rhd1 {regains the material with interest.}) 20. fxe5 Qxe5 21. Rd5 Qc7 22. Kb1 $14 {White has the more active pieces and a potential queenside majority. Black is yet to fully equalise.} *

