1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the other knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} b6 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5, a4, c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {The most popular move. Black develops the bishop actively on the long diagonal, where it puts pressure on our e4-knight.} 8. O-O-O {After Black has played ...b6, he would have to waste another tempo to prepare the ...b5 break (after a5-a4). So we are safe to castle.} Nbd7 9. Nxf6+ ({A smart move order. Black controls the e5-square in advance, which means after} 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Ne5 {Black is able to exchange everything on e5.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxe5 {White is not in time to support the knight with f2-f4. We believe 8...Nbd7 is Black's best attempt to equalise.}) ({Same as the 8...Bb7 line [/variation/29257102], we recommend releasing the tension immediately and asking Black which piece captures back on f6. At the end of this chapter} 9. Kb1 $5 {is covered as a more fighting alternative.}) 9... Bxf6 ({Black fights for the e5-square. If} 9... Nxf6 {,} 10. Ne5 $1 {is a typical device. White's powerful knight controls the centre and supports a future kingside onslaught. Thematic moves like g4, g5, and h4 are coming.}) 10. d4 ({In the notes to 8...Nbd7 we have mentioned that} 10. Ne5 {is harmless. The text move is the other way to prevent the desirable (for Black) exchange of dark-squared bishops.}) (10. d4 {also controls the e5 square, so on the next turn, White can consider plonking a knight there. If Black does not challenge the h1-a8 diagonal, Qe4 is a strong idea, followed by Bd3.}) 10... c5 11. Ne5 {)} ({Black challenges our centre immediately. The natural} 11. Qe4 {turns out to be not a refutation because Black has the stunning reply} Qc7 $3 {preparing} 12. Qxa8 Bb7 {when White's queen is trapped. In the resulting middlegame Black's queen would be stronger than White's rooks.}) {Putting pressure on the d7-knight and threatening dxc5.} 11... Qc7 {Moving the queen out of the firing line. Now we start a forcing operation.} 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13. dxc5 Bxb2+ 14. Kxb2 {Black must capture back with the pawn, which 'breaks' his pawn structure. A factor that may become relevant later on.} bxc5 15. Qe3 {The queen is well placed on e3, controlling different sectors of the chessboard. White has the maneuver Rd3-c3 available, targeting the c5-pawn. The bishop can come out via e2 and f3. In the long term, we will push the kingside pawns to generate some weaknesses. It is important to understand the nature of this middlegame. White has the better structure and better king in the endgame. However, Black currently owns the more active pieces, while our f1-bishop and h1-rook have not joined the game. Therefore Black needs to act dynamically before the static advantages turn the position in White's favour. In this chapter, we've analysed 5...Be7, one of the most respectable and popular ways to meet the Horwitz Attack. The variation, with all the subtleties, has rarely - if ever - been covered in depth before in chess literature. We are confident that equipped with the concepts we present, you will be able to reach promising positions with clear plans out of the openings. Afterward it's your job to take it from there!} *

