1. e4 {Welcome aboard! In this chapter, we shall tackle 5... Be7, one of Black's most respected methods to combat the Horwitz Attack. We highly recommend that you check out the Open Horwitz Introduction chapter [/course/82991/21] (if you have not already) before proceeding to study anything in this chapter.} e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2 Be7 {You will definitely face this line during your journey with 2. b3 against the French. It is natural and logical to put the bishop on e7, intending ...O-O. Black stays flexible with the queenside pieces, keeping Nbd7/Nc6 and b6-Bb7 options open.} 6. Nxe4 {First subtlety. By avoiding castling, White discourages the ...a5-a4 raid followed by ...c7-c6 as we've seen here. Next, we'll play Nf3 (another useful waiting move) to force Black to show his hand.} O-O 7. Nf3 {Developing the other knight and delaying queenside castle one more move. Before delving into the various alternatives, we want to offer a summary of White's battle strategy:} b6 (7... Nc6 {and}) (7... b6 {are good moves, but they obstruct the ...a5, a4, c6 plan mentioned at the start of the chapter, so White happily castles. 7...a5 and 7...Nbd7 keeps the aforementioned plan [/variation/29257092] available for Black, so White insists on delaying O-O-O.}) {The most popular move. Black develops the bishop actively on the long diagonal, where it puts pressure on our e4-knight.} 8. O-O-O {After Black has played ...b6, he would have to waste another tempo to prepare the ...b5 break (after a5-a4). So we are safe to castle.} Nbd7 9. Kb1 ({A smart move order. Black controls the e5-square in advance, which means after} 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Ne5 {Black is able to exchange everything on e5.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Bxe5 12. Qxe5 {White is not in time to support the knight with f2-f4. We believe 8...Nbd7 is Black's best attempt to equalise.}) ({This is the alternative option.} 9. Kb1 {is a prophylactic move which puts our king in a secure position. However, the true concept is that we are planning to meet ...Bb7 with Nc3!? , keeping more pieces on the board.}) 9... Bb7 10. Nc3 {The big idea. We refuse the exchange on f6 and leave Black's knights stepping on each other's toes. The knight has moved three times which is wasting time, but it's likely that in the near future Black will play ...Nd5 to ease his position, thus returning the tempo.} c5 11. g4 $13 {Garry the g-pawn leads the parade. With g5 and Rg1 coming White has the initiative. Black's queenside play is slower than usual with the presence of our knight on c3.} *

