1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({Black develops his knight and tempts our e-pawn to move forward, creating a center with blocked pawn chains - definitely something French players love to see on the board. Regardless of the objective evaluation :) This is traditionally the second most popular move. However, its popularity is decreasing, since White has many good lines to choose from. A quick note. We use the word 'Closed Horwitz' to classify the} 3... Nf6 4. e5 {variation, with reference to the closed pawn structure. In contrast, the mainline}) (3... dxe4 {leads to a more dynamic, open type of game, so we call it the 'Open Horwitz'.}) *

