{The text move is an original path travelled by only 5 out of the 70 explorers! White's idea is that the bishop is optimally placed on d3 and we can bring the king's knight out via the e2-square, leaving the f2-f4 option open. The other knight may travel to f3 via d2 if needed! Our stronghold on e5 means that there will be plenty of attacking options involving queen swings to g4 or h5 while Harry the hacking pawn will roar with h4-h5-h6! However, they are only the vague ideas. The whole 7. Bd3 variation is full of subtleties, madman tactics and deep positional manoeuvres. Get yourself a drink and study the 4...Nfd7 chapter carefully!} 1. e4 {Definitely the battle-hardened and Fischer-approved way to start the game - 1. e4!} e6 {This is called the French Defence. Black adopts a light-squared strategy and will set up a brick wall in the centre with d7-d5 next. Little do the Francophiles know that their defences will be breached soon!} 2. b3 $1 {The energized and lightning-fast Horwitz Attack!} d5 3. Bb2 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first!} Nf6 {The second most popular move in the database. Instead of opening the position with 3... dxe4, Black invites 4. e5 with a blocked French structure and a tough strategic battle. The structure indeed resembles the mainline-ish French, with one vital difference - our bishop is on b2! This turns the tide in our favour, since the e5-pawn is exceptionally well defended, giving us a handy space advantage. If Black tries to challenge our centre with ...f6, the long diagonal would be opened and from an ordinary bishop, the monster on b2 would be the MVP of the game.} 4. e5 {The principled reply, grabbing space in the centre with tempo. Black has three sensible knight moves and we'll devote a chapter to each of them.} (4. d3 $5 {The perfect weapon to surprise your opponent! White insists on gambiting a pawn for fast development and attacking chances against Black's king. The gambit has been employed by the 'creative genius' Danill Dubov, so it's no surprise that we name the gambit after the Russian star. More details are available in the corresponding theory chapter! [/course/82991/5]}) 4... Nfd7 {The overwhelmingly popular move, which has been tested in over 1000 games in the ChessBase Database as well as on Lichess. Black's knight exerts influence on the e5-pawn and the second player is preparing ... c5. At this point, 5. f4 and 5. Qg4 are both very popular and are the usual options mentioned by French Defence authors from the black side. We'd like to bring your attention to a logical yet (surprisingly) rare idea!} (4... Ne4 $5 {An outlandish knight jump into the centre! After this rare continuation, there are only 274 games in the Lichess Database. Not satisfied, we decided to cut it down with a novelty that brings the game into fresh grounds as early as the 5th move!} 5. h4 $146 {Hurry up, Harry! We're controlling g5, the escape square of the dark and evil e4-knight. We dedicated a whole chapter to demonstrating White's resources in this brand-new position!}) (4... Ng8 {This knight retreat is positionally well-founded, Black argues that the knight is a bad piece on d7 and his idea to manoeuvre the knight to the better e7 square, at the cost of two full tempi. It's a huge waste of time and we ensure after} 5. Nf3 {White has the clearly easier play. We'll often blow up the centre with sacrificial thrusts left, right and centre while Black blames himself for wasting his best years moving around with the knight! Black has actually done well in the few encounters that have reached this position. However, we have trust in White's position, and the potentially random stats should not deter you from studying the 4...Ng8 lines!}) 5. d4 {What can be more natural than conquering space in the centre? Most Horwitz experts like Paichadze and Gelashvili have preferred 5. f4 and 5. Qg4 with evil kingside intentions, but we feel that such concepts are too rushed. Instead, our recommendation is to stabilize in the centre first, develop our pieces to good squares (and there is no lack of such squares!) and only then strike! Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage [/course/82991/29] of the 5. f4 line at the end of this section, as an alternative if you are interested.} c5 (5... b6 $5 {Is a typical idea but perhaps it is too slow. In any case, we have given it a brief coverage here.}) 6. c3 Nc6 {The previous two moves for Black are universally played. We're at a crossroad here: Black is exerting strong pressure on the d4-pawn and we must decide on a particular set-up!} 7. Bd3 $5 {The more popular alternatives all have drawbacks:} ({A)} 7. Nf3 f6 $1 {undermines our proud centre. We've lost the Qh5+ option 'thanks' to the knight on f3!}) ({B)} 7. Nd2 {feels premature due to} a5 $1 {and the weakness of the b5 square cannot be exploited by a knight anymore.}) *

