1. Bb2 {This pawn structure is the core to understanding the closed Horwitz. It looks very similar to the French Advance variation, with the important difference that White puts his bishop on b2. This makes the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain well-protected and not easy to break down. In this pawn structure, there are some key breaks you should be aware of: - c3-c4 is a typical idea to blast open the centre, and unleash the Horwitz bishop. You will see this theme is in action later on in this overview chapter. - dxc5 followed by b4 is another instructive sequence, clearing the d4 square for our pieces and driving Black's pieces back. You will find this sequence often. - Since the base of our pawn chain is very solid, Black may attack it with ...f6 instead. However, this committal thrust often weakens the kingside, as you'll see in the theory section. - Black has the idea of ...a5-a4, disrupting our development. However, he loses time and weakens many squares in the process. We can respond to this by blocking the queenside, as you'll see in this overview chapter. Besides learning which pawn breaks to apply, you should know the optimal squares to put your pieces on as well! Here are a few guidelines: - The f1-bishop always comes to d3 to hit the kingside. - The g1-knight may come to f3 depending on circumstances, but it's often best to leave the square for the other knight (Nb1-d2-f3) and put the king's knight on e2 instead. - h4-Rh3 is a thematic rooklift to supercharge the kingside attack. We see this idea in action a few times in this section.} *

