1... a5 {In the closed Horwitz structure (see the overview) , we should know that ...a5 is a typical pawn break for Black. The second player logically wants to push the pawn all the way to a3, hitting our bishop and softening our kingside. Note that we never want to play a4 in this structure, since the b4 square would be permanently weakened. We either let the pawn go all the way to a4/a3, or play a3 ourselves to meet ...a4 with b4, closing the kingside.} 2. a3 {The recipe to contain Black's counterplay is to block the queenside!} a4 3. b4 {Blocking the queenside. White has a space advantage due to the e-pawn, granted by Black's 3rd move. White enjoys a continuing initiative while Black's counterplay will take a million light years to succeed! You can see the variation this puzzle was taken from here. [/variation/16095558]} *

