1... a5 {After a thematic dxc5 Bxc5 exchange we arrive at this position. White is preparing b4, hitting the bishop, and eventually c3-c4, opening up the position with great effects (the d6 square for a start) . Therefore, Black prevents this plan with In this particular scenario, Black is not only going for counterplay, but preventing our own threat of b4, shortly followed by c4, which would emphasise the d6 weakness.} 2. a3 {We simply respond by taking control of b4. This is a typical position for the 4... Ng8 variation, where Black is terribly cramped with little counterplay. White should be better, even though it's not easy to break through Black's defensive fortress.} *

