{Let's take a quick look at an inspirational win by grandmaster Daniil Dubov over the GingerGM Simon Williams in the 4. d3 variation [/course/82991/5].} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. d3 $5 {An extremely rare gambit idea that we devoted a chapter to, which can be found here. [/course/82991/5] In MrDodgy-organised tournaments there is a much higher scope for creativity than in usual competitions.} dxe4 5. Nd2 {White is ready to pitch a pawn to accelerate the development of the pieces.} Bc5 {Declining the pawn on offer.} (5... exd3 {is the critical move.} 6. Bxd3 {White will proceed with Ngf3, Qe2 and O-O-O. You can see more here. [/course/82991/5]}) 6. dxe4 Nc6 7. Bb5 {Threatening to compromise Black's structure.} O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Ngf3 a5 10. O-O a4 11. c4 $14 {White has a nice position out of the opening. The Horwitz bishop is a force on a long diagonal, while the c8-bishop is hemmed in by Black's pawn chain. In the upcoming phase of the game, both players made numerous mistakes, caused by the rapid time control. However, in the end, the stronger player prevailed.} Nd7 12. e5 Be7 13. Ne4 Nc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Qc2 Qe7 16. Rad1 Bb7 17. Bc1 f6 18. exf6 Qxf6 19. Rfe1 axb3 20. axb3 Bb4 21. Ng5 Qf5 22. Qxf5 Rxf5 23. Rxe6 h6 24. Nf3 c5 25. Be3 Bxf3 26. gxf3 Rxf3 27. Re7 Rf7 28. Rxf7 Kxf7 29. Rd7+ Kf6 30. Rxc7 $16 {White has won a pawn with great winning chances.} Ra3 31. Rb7 g5 32. Rb6+ Kf5 33. Rxh6 Rxb3 34. Rh5 Rc3 35. Rxg5+ Ke4 36. Bxc5 Kf4 37. Bxb4 Rc1+ 38. Kg2 Z0 ({Black resigned, because} 38... Kxg5 39. Bd2+ {wins the rook.}) 1-0

