1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} Be7 {This uninspiring move is actually quite popular online. Our 'bluff' made Black scared enough that they refrain from accepting the gambit.} 5. Nd2 {Defending the pawn.} O-O 6. g4 $5 {Immediately launching an attack is the most dangerous way to proceed. The Horwitz bishop works rather well with Garry (and soon, Huy!)} d4 ({Trying to restrict the bishop. However, Black also closes the centre, which gives us a free hand on the kingside.} 6... h6 7. h4 $1 {puts Black on the ropes, as the engine believes White is already better with such unorthodox play.}) 7. h4 {Preparing g5 followed by Bh3.} e5 8. g5 $1 {Kicking the knight away from the kingside.} Nfd7 9. Bh3 Nc6 10. Qf3 $1 {Before developing the knight, it's useful to bring the queen to the kingside.} Nc5 11. Ne2 $13 {White has fair chances in this complicated middlegame. Next, we will play Rg1, a3 (to prevent a5-a4) and h5 with a potentially dangerous kingside attack. Our king is perfectly safe in the centre, and the now 'bad' bishop on b2 can be relocated via Bc1 later.} *

