1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} c5 {This option is also rather popular. Black wants to play d5-d4 to restrict our bishop.} 5. Nd2 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Qc7 (6... Be7 7. g3 Qc7 {transposes to the mainline.}) 7. g3 {Double-fianchettoing the bishops.} Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O {The tension in the centre is likely to be released soon. Black would love to play ...d4, but that move isn't without its drawback.} dxe4 (9... d4 {can be met by} 10. a4 $1 {stabilising the situation on the queenside, with Nc4 and Bc1 to come.}) {Releasing the tension in this way is also fairly logical.} 10. dxe4 Rd8 11. e5 $5 ({Fighting for more than an equal middlegame, which is all we have after} 11. Qe2 e5 $1) 11... Ne4 12. Qe2 {Getting out of the pin and forcing Black to capture on d2.} Nxd2 13. Nxd2 $14 {The engine shows equality here, but in our opinion White should be slightly better due to our space on the kingside and the passivity of the c8-bishop. Next, we will play Nc4, Rd1 and even h4/a4 to strengthen our control over the board. A kingside attack may be threatening, but it's most likely that White should play on both flanks.} *

