1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} c5 {This option is also rather popular. Black wants to play d5-d4 to restrict our bishop.} 5. Nd2 Nc6 6. Ngf3 dxe4 {Compared to the last line, here Black releases the tension too early and allows White a more active square for the bishop.} 7. dxe4 Be7 8. Bb5 $1 {This is the difference. Bxc6+ is a big positional threat, so Black is forced to defend the knight.} Bd7 9. O-O (9. Bxc6 $5 {is also an interesting idea, but the text looks most natural.}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 Qc7 11. e5 $1 {Removing a kingside defender and gaining space.} Nd5 12. Bf1 $14 {A useful prophylactic move. The bishop realises it has no more future on b5 and drops back to the original square. White will patiently but surely build up on the kingside with Ne4, g3, Bg2 and h4 while Black is cramped and lacks counterplay.} *

