1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} c5 {This option is also rather popular. Black wants to play d5-d4 to restrict our bishop.} 5. Nd2 Nc6 6. Ngf3 d4 {Immediately blocking the bishop is the most accurate option.} 7. g3 e5 8. Nc4 {Hitting the e5-pawn. We will examine two ways Black can defend the pawn.} Bg4 {Pinning the f3-knight and thus indirectly protect the pawn.} 9. Be2 Bxf3 {The only way to justify the bishop move.} 10. Bxf3 b5 11. Nd2 g6 12. a4 {Undermining the b5-pawn in order to gain the c4 square for the knight.} a6 ({The only move. Stockfish believes} 12... bxa4 {leads to a 'slightly' better position for White, but the truth is that White is strategically dominating with the bishop pair and healthier structure. It seems our silicon friend doesn't understand closed positions too well.}) 13. Bc1 {This position is balanced. White's bishop pair is compensated by Black's space advantage and the closed position. Next, we will play Bg2, O-O and f4.} *

