1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged us from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it. 5...exd3 is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... Bb4 6. a3 $1 ({Pinning the d2-knight. Black's cheap idea is that} 6. dxe4 $4 {can be met with} Nxe4 {winning the horse. However, we are not forced to fall for that trap, of course.}) {Chasing the bishop away. As you will see, each option has its own drawback.} 6... Bxd2+ $6 {Black greedily goes after a mere pawn, but why didn't he do so with 5...exd3 then? In this version of the Dubov Gambit Accepted, White is a lot better as Black is lacking a crucial defender, the dark-square bishop. That means the Horwitz bishop is unopposed!} 7. Qxd2 O-O (7... exd3 $6 {is far too greedy. After} 8. Bxd3 O-O 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nf3 Qe7 {White has the line-opening resource} 11. g4 $1 {with a decisive initiative.}) 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qe3 $1 {We shouldn't rush to recapture the pawn. Instead, it's more favourable if we can force Black to capture on d3 and accelerate our development.} e5 ({As you might have understood by now,} 9... exd3 {is far too greedy. The text move aims to close the long diagonal, but White is clearly better after…}) 10. dxe4 Qe7 11. Nf3 $16 {And the bishop pair will dominate the board. We can combine central play with Bc4 and kingside aggression with h3 followed by g4-g5.} *

