1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged us from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it. 5...exd3 is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... Bb4 6. a3 $1 ({Pinning the d2-knight. Black's cheap idea is that} 6. dxe4 $4 {can be met with} Nxe4 {winning the horse. However, we are not forced to fall for that trap, of course.}) {Chasing the bishop away. As you will see, each option has its own drawback.} 6... Ba5 {The lesser evil. Black gives back the pawn in order to maintain the important bishop.} 7. b4 {Freeing the knight from the pin.} Bb6 8. dxe4 e5 $1 9. h3 ({The best move, gaining space in the centre. Other moves would have allowed e4-e5 with a nagging space advantage and Black would be left with a boxed in bishop at c8. The text move seemingly hangs a pawn, but Black's tactical justification is that} 9. Bxe5 $2 {is met with} Bxf2+ $1 10. Kxf2 Ng4+ {winning back the bishop with a dominant position.}) {A prophylactic move, preventing the potential Ng4 jump.} 9... O-O 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Ngf3 $14 {White has a slightly better position, thanks to a space advantage. Moreover, in practice, our position is also easier to play, with the immediate threat being Nc4 picking up the bishop pair.} *

