1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged us from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it. 5...exd3 is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... exd3 {Bravely grabbing the offer.} 6. Bxd3 {6 moves into the game we've lost a pawn with no compensation in sight. However, the reality is that White has rich compensation due to the following factors: - We have two pieces developed, compared to one Black piece. - Our bishops are looking eagerly at the kingside, waiting for the moment to strike. - Our pieces will flow easily into action with Qe2, O-O-O and Nf3. Of course, we shouldn't forget the fact that Black is still a pawn up. White should play energetically in order to prove compensation for the pawn. As Nigel Short said, it's checkmate that ends the game, and you are in no way short of checkmates with this repertoire.} Be7 {Black simply develops the bishop and prepares castling.} 7. Qe2 O-O 8. O-O-O {The opposite-sided castling guarantees an exciting battle ahead!} Nc6 9. Ne4 $1 {Getting rid of the defensive knight and opening the d-file for the rook.} Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Bd6 11. Nf3 $13 {White has dangerous compensation for the pawn in the form of kingside attacking chances. We wouldn't be surprised if in the future White wins the majority of games from this novel position.} *

