1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged us from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it. 5...exd3 is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... exd3 {Bravely grabbing the offer.} 6. Bxd3 {6 moves into the game we've lost a pawn with no compensation in sight. However, the reality is that White has rich compensation due to the following factors: - We have two pieces developed, compared to one Black piece. - Our bishops are looking eagerly at the kingside, waiting for the moment to strike. - Our pieces will flow easily into action with Qe2, O-O-O and Nf3. Of course, we shouldn't forget the fact that Black is still a pawn up. White should play energetically in order to prove compensation for the pawn. As Nigel Short said, it's checkmate that ends the game, and you are in no way short of checkmates with this repertoire.} Nc6 $1 {The strongest move, intending Nb4 to swap off the d3-bishop.} 7. Qe2 Bc5 ({Preparing to castle queenside. At this tabiya of the whole Dubov Gambit, we will examine two options for White. First, we will take a quick look at} 7... Bc5 {before examining the critical knight jump}) (7... Nb4 {in-depth.}) {Black's idea is to play ...Nd4 and exchange some minor pieces, which will ease their defensive task.} 8. Ngf3 Nd4 9. Qe5 $1 {Keeping the Horwitz bishop on the board is the only way for White to maintain a playable middlegame with one pawn less.} Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 $1 (10. Nxf3 $6 Bxf2+ $1 {, justified by Ng4+, is a useful trick to avoid. The text move does ruin our structure, but in return we get the open g-file.}) 10... Qd6 {Offering the queen exchange.} 11. Qg5 {Which we of course decline.} Bd4 {Finally, our much-needed Horwitz bishop is forced to go off the board. Rest in peace, the mighty bishop! Your friends will do it for you.} 12. O-O-O Bxb2+ 13. Kxb2 {At first, our position looks suspect; after all, we are a pawn down with a ruined structure. However, matters aren't so simple. Apart from the h1-rook, all of the White pieces are nicely placed and ready for action. The g7-pawn is under pressure and Nc4 will hit the queen hard.} Rg8 14. Nc4 Qe7 (14... Qd4+ $2 {takes greediness to a whole new level. After} 15. c3 Qxf2+ 16. Rd2 Qxf3 17. Rf1 Qh5 18. Qg3 {Black is busted with poor development and threats coming from all directions.}) 15. Rhe1 {Centralizing all pieces! It's unclear how the Black king can reach safety now.} Bd7 (15... b6 $6 16. Ne5 $1 {threatens Bb5+ and Black's position is falling apart. The text move is played with the intention castling queenside. However, there is a resource in our bag of tricks to stop that.}) 16. Qa5 $1 b6 ({As} 16... O-O-O {would be met by} 17. Qxa7 {, Black has no choice but to weaken their position.}) 17. Qd2 {After the queen manoeuvre, the light squares in Black's camp are weakened.} O-O-O 18. Ne5 $13 {White has sufficient compensation for the pawn. We'll see what happens if Black is careless enough and make a random move.} h5 $2 19. Ba6+ Kb8 20. Qc3 {And the two simple threats of Nc6+, and Rxd7! followed by Nc6+ cannot both be stopped at once.} *

