 a pawn with no compensation in sight. However, the reality is that White has rich compensation due to the following factors: - We have two pieces developed, compared to one Black piece. - Our bishops are looking eagerly at the kingside, waiting for the moment to strike. - Our pieces will flow easily into action with Qe2, O-O-O and Nf3. Of course, we shouldn't forget the fact that Black is still a pawn up. White should play energetically in order to prove compensation for the pawn. As Nigel Short said, it's checkmate that ends the game, and you are in no way short of checkmates with this repertoire.} Nc6 $1 {The strongest move, intending Nb4 to swap off the d3-bishop.} 7. Qe2 Nb4 ({Preparing to castle queenside. At this tabiya of the whole Dubov Gambit, we will examine two options for White. First, we will take a quick look at} 7... Bc5 {before examining the critical knight jump}) (7... Nb4 {in-depth.}) {Hunting down the bishop pair.} 8. Be4 $1 {If we are to give up the bishop pair, it's definitely preferable to exchange it for the crucial f6-knight rather than its sidelined partner.} Nxe4 9. Nxe4 {Our position already looks quite threatening, and Black will find it hard to untangle his pieces. The development of the f8-bishop is a problem which is hard to solve.} Be7 $2 {Black is too tired of defending and decides to give up a pawn to relieve their position. At least, that's what they thought.} 10. Bxg7 Rg8 11. Rd1 $1 {Forcing the bishop to walk into the pin.} Bd7 12. Bb2 Rxg2 {Black regains the pawn, but White is already winning due to our overwhelming activity.} 13. Nf3 {Threatening Ne5.} Nc6 14. h4 {The easiest way to wrap up the game. The immediate threat is Nfg5 when the rook find itself trapped inside the enemy's territory. Black's pieces are so passive that we have time to slowly build up our position and win with ease.} *

