1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged us from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it. 5...exd3 is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... exd3 {Bravely grabbing the offer.} 6. Bxd3 {6 moves into the game we've lost a pawn with no compensation in sight. However, the reality is that White has rich compensation due to the following factors: - We have two pieces developed, compared to one Black piece. - Our bishops are looking eagerly at the kingside, waiting for the moment to strike. - Our pieces will flow easily into action with Qe2, O-O-O and Nf3. Of course, we shouldn't forget the fact that Black is still a pawn up. White should play energetically in order to prove compensation for the pawn. As Nigel Short said, it's checkmate that ends the game, and you are in no way short of checkmates with this repertoire.} Nc6 $1 {The strongest move, intending Nb4 to swap off the d3-bishop.} 7. Qe2 Nb4 ({Preparing to castle queenside. At this key tabiya of the Dubov Gambit, we will examine two options for White. First, we will take a quick look at} 7... Bc5 {before examining the critical knight jump}) (7... Nb4 {in-depth.}) {Hunting down the bishop pair.} 8. Be4 $1 {If we are to give up the bishop pair, it's definitely preferable to exchange it for the crucial f6-knight rather than its sidelined partner.} Nxe4 9. Nxe4 {Our position already looks quite threatening, and Black will find it hard to untangle his pieces. The development of the f8-bishop is a hard-to-solve problem.} Nc6 {Going back is the best way to proceed.} 10. Nf3 {) Now Black faces a difficult problem: how to develop the f8-bishop without losing the g7-pawn?} Bb4+ $1 {This seems to be the best way to do it, provoking c2-c3 before dropping the bishop back.} 11. c3 Be7 12. Rd1 Bd7 {So far Black has managed to counter White's initiative and according to the engine, our opponent undoubtedly stands better here. While that's true from an objective point of view, we have plenty of ways to spice things up.} 13. h4 $5 {We can't resist pushing one of the co-authors (you guess him) forward in order to create a strong outpost for the knight on g5.} O-O $2 {A natural move, but in fact, a mistake.} 14. Nfg5 $1 {Black is threatened with dozens of combinations.} e5 $6 (14... h6 $1 {may be the most precise move, but after} 15. Qd3 hxg5 16. Qxd7 {our initiative is still going strong. The text move allows us to play an elegant sacrifice that unluckily doesn't result in a winning position, but 'just' a better one.}) 15. Nxh7 $1 {Of course! The knight replaces the bishop in a variant of the Greek Gift.} Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Ng5 $16 Z0 ({Black is forced to give up the queen with} 17... Bf5 {in order to avoid immediate disaster down the h-file. In the resulting position, White is better but should treat the position with care in order to bring home the full point.}) *

