1. e4 e6 {The French Defence, which is known to be a tough nut to crack.} 2. b3 $5 {The Horwitz strike!} d5 {Black replies in normal French fashion, hitting the e4-pawn. However, your opponents are up for a surprise.} 3. Bb2 $5 {We gambiteers don’t care about that pawn, but instead focus on development first. As you will see, White has fantastic compensation for the pawn in every line, and very often Black must return it. We believe Adhiban must regret not recommending 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 e6 3.e4!? in his LTR. His fault, of course!} Nf6 {Black declines the offer and invites us to play 4. e5 with a blocked, typical French structure. However, that's a perfectly viable option for us as the Horwitz bishop stands rather well in that structure, holding our centre together. You can check for more details in the 4. e5 chapters. In this chapter, we're going to cover the nasty Dubov Gambit.} 4. d3 $5 {Insisting on the pawn sacrifice. WARNING: This gambit isn't objectively sound, and Black should emerge with a better position, at least according to the engine. However, we find it very dangerous practically and not every Black player expects it. This gambit is played at your own risk, so don't protest if the engine screams at you with some unimpressive evaluations! Having said that, it scores rather well in practice, and the always creative Daniil Dubov used it to devastating effect against GM Simon Williams. For that reason, we decided to name the gambit after him.} dxe4 $1 {The only way to question the soundness of every gambit is to accept it! The Dubov Gambit isn't an exception.} 5. Nd2 $5 (5. Nc3 $5 {is an alternative gambit, but the fact that the powerful Horwitz bishop is blocked for no concrete reason discouraged me from recommending it. After the text move, we are attacking the e4-pawn so Black must do something about it.} exd3 {is the critical move, but we'll examine the pin 5...Bb4 first.}) 5... exd3 {Bravely grabbing the offer.} 6. Bxd3 {6 moves into the game we've lost a pawn with no compensation in sight. However, the reality is that White has rich compensation due to the following factors: - We have two pieces developed, compared to one Black piece. - Our bishops are looking eagerly at the kingside, waiting for the moment to strike. - Our pieces will flow easily into action with Qe2, O-O-O and Nf3. Of course, we shouldn't forget the fact that Black is still a pawn up. White should play energetically in order to prove compensation for the pawn. As Nigel Short said, it's checkmate that ends the game, and you are in no way short of checkmates with this repertoire.} Nc6 $1 {The strongest move, intending Nb4 to swap off the d3-bishop.} 7. Qe2 Nb4 ({Preparing to castle queenside. At this tabiya of the whole Dubov Gambit, we will examine two options for White. First, we will take a quick look at} 7... Bc5 {before examining the critical knight jump}) (7... Nb4 {in-depth.}) {Hunting down the bishop pair.} 8. Be4 $1 {If we are to give up the bishop pair, it's definitely preferable to exchange it for the crucial f6-knight rather than its sidelined partner.} Nxe4 9. Nxe4 {Our position already looks quite threatening, and Black will find it hard to untangle his pieces. The development of the f8-bishop is a hard-to-solve problem.} Nc6 {Going back is the best way to proceed.} 10. Nf3 {Now Black faces a difficult problem: how to develop the f8-bishop without losing the g7-pawn?} Bb4+ $1 {This seems to be the best way to do it, provoking c2-c3 before drop the bishop back.} 11. c3 Be7 12. Rd1 Bd7 {So far Black has managed to counter White's initiative and according to the engine, he undoubtly stands better here. While that's true from an objective point of view, we've plenty of ways to spice things up.} 13. h4 $5 {We can't resist pushing one of the co-authors (you guess him) forward in order to create a strong outpost for the knight on g5.} Qc8 {Unpinning the French bishop is also a logical continuation.} 14. h5 $1 {There is no way back now.} e5 {This is by no means forced, but the resulting sequence is so amazing that we must share it with you.} 15. h6 $1 {First undermining the g7-pawn and weakening the f6 square.} g6 16. Ba3 $3 {We would love it if we could give more than two exclamation marks to this brilliant and creative deflecting sacrifice.} Bxa3 (16... Bf5 {is a try to keep the game going, but after} 17. Bxe7 Kxe7 18. Nc5 {we no longer stand worse as Black's king is terribly stuck in the centre.}) 17. Nxe5 $3 {Ripping open the e-file. Black has no choice but to accept the offer.} Nxe5 18. Nf6+ Kf8 $1 ({The only move, as} 18... Ke7 $2 19. Qxe5+ Be6 20. Nd5+ $1 {is winning for White.}) 19. Qxe5 {The d7-bishop is threatened, so Black must move it. Amazingly, only one move can save them while others lose.} Bc6 $1 (19... Bg4 $2 {is refuted in a spectacular fashion:} 20. O-O $1 {21.Nd7+!! Qxd7 22.Qxh8+ Ke7 23.Re1+! and huge material losses is unavoidable and 19...Be6 is met with the incredibly quiet 20. 0-0! with the shockingly simple idea ofRfe1 followed by Nd7+ . Black is so paralyzed that he cannot do anything to stop it. The text is the only move to hold as 20...Qe6! activating the queen. Now, White has two ways to hold the draw, but we prefer the more direct one.}) 20. Rd7 $5 {A splendid rook sacrifice with the point of preventing Qe6, even at the cost of a full rook.} ({The engine also suggests} 20. O-O $5 Qe6 21. Qd4 {with the idea of continuing as normal a whole piece down. While that concept is definitely playable, we find it to be quite risky, since if Black manages to kick the knight away from g6, it's all over. Nevertheless, Black must act quickly before White can consolidate, so it's fair to say that both sides are walking on very thin ice with high risks of blundering. We would not venture into that world without any preparation, though.}) 20... Bxd7 21. b4 ({Another route to the draw is} 21. Nxd7+ Qxd7 22. Qxh8+ Ke7 23. Qxa8 Qe6+ {as our king cannot escape the checks.}) 21... Qe8 $1 {However, the text leads to a draw much more quickly, and you might even score the full point against an unsuspecting opponent! What we mean by this is that your opponent might play some random moves, for example 21...a5 and you reply with 22.Qc5# . A nasty and easy to overlook mate, isn't it? Is the best way to force the draw, pinning us on the e-file.} 22. Nxd7+ Kg8 (22... Qxd7 {allows us to win both rooks, so Black is forced to go for a perpetual.}) 23. Nf6+ {A draw is inevitable, unless we lose our mind and capture the queen.} *

