1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({The second most popular move in the database. Instead of opening the position with} 3... dxe4 {, Black invites e5 with a blocked French structure and a tough strategic battle. The structure indeed resembles the mainline-ish French, with one vital difference - our bishop is on b2! This turns the tide in our favour, since the e5-pawn is exceptionally well-defended, giving us a handy space advantage. If Black tries to challenge our centre with ...f6, the long diagonal would be opened and the ordinary bishop would be transformed to a monster on b2 , the MVP of the game. As of 2023, the traditional 3...Nf6 seems to have moved to the backwaters and we see no sign of it emerging again, especially since Black has found a number of modern methods to deal with the Horwitz Attack.}) 4. e5 Ne4 $5 ({The principled reply, and the only way to highlight the drawback of 3...Nf6 - the knight must move again. Even though the pawn currently blocks the Horwitz bishop, that's not such a big problem as the bishop will act as a supporter of White's pawn chain. Compared to the Advanced Variation of the French, here our centre cannot be destroyed as easily. Black's choices are limited to} 4... Nfd7 {,}) (4... Ng8 {and}) (4... Ne4 {. The former is the mainline by a huge margin (played in roughly 95% of the games), while the latter moves are much rarer. In this chapter, we'll take a look at}) (4... Ng8 {and}) (4... Ne4 {. Both of these lines seem almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there's honestly not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy and important variations such as the Papoo, the Open Horwitz and the Superior Knight Jump covered in the next chapter.}) {An option that appears very infrequently in practice. The knight looks strong on e4, but it can be easily driven away. White has many ways to claim an advantage and what we chose to recommend is certainly original.} 5. h4 $146 Be7 ({Controlling the dark horse's escape square g5. The chief point is that the standard French move} 5... c5 $4 {is met by} 6. d3 $1 {and the knight is swiftly trapped in the middle of the board. Also, h4 is generally a useful move for White in this structure, since it gains kingside space. Next, we'll drive Black's knight back with d3 when it turns out that c5 is the only square. If we follow up with d4, Black's sad knight may even find itself on d7. However, what is the point of Ng8-f6-e4-c5-d7 instead of just retreating with 4...Nfd7? Our recommendation is a novelty - maybe you didn't expect us to leave the trodden paths this early, but that's exactly what we did.}) {Black develops his bishop modestly and threatens the h4-pawn. However, more often than not that pawn is poisoned since we have the strong reply of Qg4, attacking the bishop and the g7-pawn.} 6. d3 {Following the game plan - we're pushing the knight back.} Nc5 7. d4 Ncd7 ({Gaining even more time on the knight. We've moved the d-pawn twice, but it's nothing compared to the journey of that knight. In case of} 7... Ne4 {, we'd have an unusual transposition to this variation [/variation/23856878], except with an extra move for both sides. All that is left for us to consider is}) {Let's take stock: we've managed to gain kingside space with h4 and created a stable d4-e5 pawn chain in the centre, while Black has retreated the knight to d7 after all and developed his bishop to e7. Compared to the starting position of the ( 4...Nfd7 variation, White has played two moves (d4 and h4), while Black has played one (...Be7). In addition, ...Be7 is not the most useful of moves, since Qg4 will come with tempo.} 8. Bd3 {You'll see a theme occurring again and again in the Horwitz structure: the light-squared bishop is best on d3, where it eyes Black's kingside. Black should be very reluctant to castle kingside as a Bxh7+ sacrifice might be a killer.} c5 (8... Bxh4 $4 {is met by} 9. Qg4 $1 {hitting both h4 and g7.} Bg5 10. Nf3 Bh6 11. Rxh6 $1 {is the most elegant way to finish the job. After} gxh6 12. Qg7 Rf8 13. Qxh6 {White is just completely winning, and we won't even be down on material after capturing on h7. Moreover, the dark squares in Black's kingside are forever weakened. The text move is much more natural, undermining White's centre in the classical French style.}) 9. c3 {It's true that the b2-bishop isn't doing an impressive job right now, but it's holding our structure together. Without the support that the bishop provides, the c3-d4-e5 pawn chain would collapse. This pawn chain is White's most powerful asset, since it gives White attacking prospects on the kingside.} Nc6 10. Qg4 Z0 ({Forcing a concession on the kingside. Castling into the storm with} 10... O-O {is risky, but committing a weakening with ...g6 or ...Kf8 isn't ideal either. White's next move is Nd2 to prevent ...cxd4 followed by Nb4, bagging the strong d3-bishop. We would have a square on b1 in that case! The rook can lift into the action with Rh3 while the king's knight will be well-placed on e2, supporting the centre. Our king needn't castle - very often it will be safe on e1, shielded by the army of pawns and pieces!}) *

