h4 $146 Bc5 ({Controlling the dark horse's escape square g5. The chief point is that the standard French move} 5... c5 $4 {is met by} 6. d3 $1 {and the knight is swiftly trapped in the middle of the board. Also, h4 is generally a useful move for White in this structure, since it gains kingside space. Next, we'll drive Black's knight back with d3 when it turns out that c5 is the only square. If we follow up with d4, Black's sad knight may even find itself on d7. However, what is the point of Ng8-f6-e4-c5-d7 instead of just retreating with 4...Nfd7? Our recommendation is a novelty - maybe you didn't expect us to leave the trodden paths this early, but that's exactly what we did.}) {Most direct, Black is threatening the f2-pawn and forces our next move.} 6. d4 {Pushing the bishop backwards. Black has avoided d2-d3 trapping the knight in the future, but his bishop has wasted a move.} Be7 ({From e7 Black exerts pressure on the h4-pawn, although that pawn is often poisoned. In case of} 6... Bb6 $6 {White has the strong move} 7. Ne2 $1 {, controlling the g3 square and preparing f2-f3, trapping the knight. With the bishop on e7, this isn't an option, since the h4-pawn hangs with check.}) 7. Bd3 (7. Qg4 $5 {is another option, but}) (7. Bd3 {is natural and thematic. In many lines in the Closed Horwitz, we recommend a consistent plan of playing Bd3 after stabilizing the centre (for example 4...Nfd7 5.d4 c5 6.c3 Nc6 7.Bd3 ) to avoid confusing the readers. We are threatening Bxe4 followed by Qg4 with a double attack on Black's pawns.}) 7... c5 ({Immediately challenging our centre is the most natural and best way to proceed. Note that} 7... Bxh4 $2 {is hardly ever possible in this line, as White has} 8. Bxe4 dxe4 9. Qg4 $1 {winning the house. Also,}) (7... O-O $6 {fails to the simple} 8. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 9. Nd2 {and Black has little to show for the lost pawn.}) 8. Nd2 $5 ({Exchanging the annoying e4-knight for our newly-developed horse.} 8. Bxe4 $5 dxe4 9. Qg4 {is an adventurous option. However, it seems to us that White is getting a more comfortable position after the text move.}) 8... Nxd2 ({Black should exchange knights immediately, since} 8... cxd4 $2 9. Qg4 $1 {is great for White,} Nxd2 10. Qxg7 $1 {is an important intermediate move and White wins material.}) 9. Qxd2 O-O $2 {This allows us to release the central tension favourably. Castling straight into the attack is a bad idea :)} 10. dxc5 $1 {Luring the bishop to the c5-square.} Bxc5 (10... Nd7 11. b4 {is just a pawn up for White.}) 11. Nf3 Z0 ({Surprisingly, White's advantage is already decisive according to Stockfish! However, this may indeed be true if we look at the potential of White's kingside attack. The immediate threat is} 11... Z0 12. Ng5 $1 h6 13. Nh7 $1 {with a killing attack.}) *

