on. However, it seems to us that White is getting a more comfortable position after the text move.}) 8... Nxd2 ({Black should exchange knights immediately, since} 8... cxd4 $2 9. Qg4 $1 {is great for White,} Nxd2 10. Qxg7 $1 {is an important intermediate move and White wins material.}) 9. Qxd2 cxd4 {Most sensible, avoiding dxc5 tricks.} 10. O-O-O {We are in no rush to recapture the pawn as it will eventually fall anyway. Moreover, it's preferable for us to recapture that pawn with the knight, as Bxd4 will be met with Nc6 harassing the valuable Horwitz bishop. White wants to first support the centre pawn wedge with f2-f4 before rounding up the d4-pawn with Nf3 and Qf2. For example} Nc6 11. f4 h5 $1 {Black has managed a kingside blockade, and now we should content ourselves with a small edge after capturing the d4-pawn.} 12. Nf3 Bb4 13. Qf2 Qa5 {The dark squares in our camp are indeed weak, but the Horwitz bishop is present there to take care of the matter.} 14. Kb1 {Protecting the a2-pawn.} Bc3 15. Be2 $14 {After some massive exchanges on d4 we'll be left with a classic good bishop vs bad bishop clash. We have the better bishop thanks to our pawns being placed on dark squares and therefore own a stable edge. Conclusion: After the principled 4.e5 , Black has several knight moves, 4...Ne4!? being a cheeky option. It has not occurred frequently in practice and has no theoretical relevance, so we didn't spend a lot of time on this line. In the end, our proposal is 5.h4!? , a novel concept that prevents Black from tricky problems regarding the e4-knight. In the next few variations of this chapter we will explore the meek retreat with 4...Ng8.} *

