1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 ({The second most popular move in the database. Instead of opening the position with} 3... dxe4 {, Black invites e5 with a blocked French structure and a tough strategic battle. The structure indeed resembles the mainline-ish French, with one vital difference - our bishop is on b2! This turns the tide in our favour, since the e5-pawn is exceptionally well-defended, giving us a handy space advantage. If Black tries to challenge our centre with ...f6, the long diagonal would be opened and the ordinary bishop would be transformed to a monster on b2 , the MVP of the game. As of 2023, the traditional 3...Nf6 seems to have moved to the backwaters and we see no sign of it emerging again, especially since Black has found a number of modern methods to deal with the Horwitz Attack.}) 4. e5 Ng8 $5 ({The principled reply, and the only way to highlight the drawback of 3...Nf6 - the knight must move again. Even though the pawn currently blocks the Horwitz bishop, that's not such a big problem as the bishop will act as a supporter of White's pawn chain. Compared to the Advanced Variation of the French, here our centre cannot be destroyed as easily. Black's choices are limited to} 4... Nfd7 {,}) (4... Ng8 {and}) (4... Ne4 {. The former is the mainline by a huge margin (played in roughly 95% of the games), while the latter moves are much rarer. In this chapter, we'll take a look at}) (4... Ng8 {and}) (4... Ne4 {. Both of these lines seem almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there's honestly not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy and important variations such as the Papoo, the Open Horwitz and the Superior Knight Jump covered in the next chapter.}) {A peculiar knight move. This variation resembles the 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 Bf8!? variation in the Winawer. Black's idea is that in this closed structure, he has time to manoeuvre the knight to e7, even though at the cost of two full tempi. However, this is very slow and violates a basic opening principle of not moving a piece several times in the opening. Nowadays, the 4...Ng8 line seems almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there is not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy variations such as 3.. .Nc6 and 3...dxe4.} 5. Nf3 ({This move-order and} 5. d4 {have equivalent value. Some players might prefer}) (5. d4 c5 6. c3 {with a closed game, but we prefer the chosen option as it allows Black to exchange on d4 and force our knight to d4. While the e5-pawn would be a bit weak, it's in our favour to open the position as we are leading in development.}) 5... c5 {There is hardly any sensible alternative to this move.} 6. d4 cxd4 ({Gaining space in the centre and overprotect the e5-pawn. At this point, we'll first examine the tempting} 6... cxd4 {before moving on to the main line of}) (6... Nc6 {.}) {Black exchanges his c-pawn for our d-pawn, thus reaching a 2 vs 1 majority in the centre. However, it also opens up the position for our energetic, ready-for-action pieces. For that reason, we think this approach is playable but doesn't fit well with the 4... Ng8 variation at all.} 7. Nxd4 (7. Qxd4 $5 {is a creative idea to bring the queen over to the kingside. After} Nc6 8. Qf4 {White will slowly build up on the kingside with a promising position. However, we prefer the 'classical' recapture and hold Her Majesty on its original square for now.}) 7... Ne7 $5 ({Black's intention is to either play Ng6 or Nbc6 to attack the e5-pawn. In the latter case, he makes sure that after White takes on c6, Black can recapture with a knight. We should mention that} 7... Qc7 $6 {is highly suspicious due to} 8. Nb5 $1 {followed by c4, ruthlessly opening up the centre to exploit White's superior piece development.}) 8. Bd3 Nbc6 ({Developing the bishop like this cannot be wrong. We are at a branch: Black must choose between} 8... Ng6 {and}) (8... Nbc6 {.}) {Revealing one of the aforementioned points behind Black's 7th move.} 9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10. O-O {The tension in the centre has cleared and it's time to take stock of the position. Black has a central majority (2 vs 1) but he is slightly behind in development and the c8-bishop is blocked behind its own pawns. You might argue that the e5-pawn cannot be properly defended by a pawn (f4 would be risky) but actually, it's doing a fine job of cramping Black's pieces. Furthermore, we can always support it with Qe2, Re1 and Nbd2-f3. And never forget the boss sitting at b2!} Be7 11. a3 $1 {The key move to gain an advantage, preparing a queenside expansion with b3-b4.} O-O 12. Nd2 {The knight is very flexible here: it can come to either f3 or b3 (after b4). Meanwhile, Black's position is rather stuck. A sample line is} f5 ({Trying to block the kingside.} 12... f6 13. Nf3 {leaves White with a much more harmonious position.}) 13. b4 $16 {White is on the driving seat with c4 to come. The d6-square, lack of space and the bad bishop on c8 are severe problems for Black to solve.} *

