ome with check. The pawn on e5 is indeed hanging, but we've prepared an antidote.}) 8... Nxd4 {Note that 8...Nge7 9.Nxc6 Nxc6 9.Bd3 is likely to transpose to 7...Ne7} 9. Bxd4 Ne7 {The second knight will come to c6 and force us to retreat our Horwitz bishop.} 10. Bd3 {The bishop is usually best placed on d3 in this structure as it exerts pressure on Black's kingside.} Nc6 11. Bb2 $14 {Despite the bishop retreat, our position remains harmonious, with Nf3 to come. Meanwhile, Black still suffers from the typical French's lack of space and the passivity of the c8-bishop. Eventually, we'll slowly push on both flanks with O-O, a3-b4 and Qe2. Black lacks pawn breaks and hasn't solved the notorious problem of the French bishop yet.} *

