t the cost of two full tempi. However, this is very slow and violates a basic opening principle of not moving a piece several times in the opening. Nowadays, the 4...Ng8 line seems almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there is not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy variations such as 3.. .Nc6 and 3...dxe4.} 5. Nf3 ({This move-order and} 5. d4 {have equivalent value. Some players might prefer}) (5. d4 c5 6. c3 {with a closed game, but we prefer the chosen option as it allows Black to exchange on d4 and force our knight to d4. While the e5-pawn would be a bit weak, it's in our favour to open the position as we are leading in development.}) 5... c5 {There is hardly any sensible alternative to this move.} 6. d4 cxd4 ({Gaining space in the centre and overprotect the e5-pawn. At this point, we'll first examine the tempting} 6... cxd4 {before moving on to the main line of}) (6... Nc6 {.}) {Black exchanges his c-pawn for our d-pawn, thus reaching a 2 vs 1 majority in the centre. However, it also opens up the position for our energetic, ready-for-action pieces. For that reason, we think this approach is playable but doesn't fit well with the 4... Ng8 variation at all.} 7. Nxd4 (7. Qxd4 $5 {is a creative idea to bring the queen over to the kingside. After} Nc6 8. Qf4 {White will slowly build up on the kingside with a promising position. However, we prefer the 'classical' recapture and hold Her Majesty on its original square for now.}) 7... Nc6 {Black immediately challenges our d4-knight.} 8. Nd2 $5 ({A knight leap that carries a subtle idea. We would love to play} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd3 {when Black's light-squared bishop is boxed in, but Black would have the amazing and typical resource} Ba6 $1 10. Bxa6 Qa5+ {and our good bishop has been exchanged for its inferior counterpart. Having seen that line, it makes sense to insert a knight on d2 so that ...Qa5 in the above line would no longer come with check. The pawn on e5 is indeed hanging, but we've prepared an antidote.}) 8... Nxe5 {We think by now you should already know how to meet this pawn grab.} 9. Nxe6 $1 {Hitting both the queen and the knight at once. We cannot help but think that this line resembles the 7...Nge7 8. Bd3 Ng6 variation [/variation/23856882], so in case you haven't studied it, check it out.} Bxe6 10. Bxe5 Nf6 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Bd3 {Getting our pieces out and preparing O-O. The position is balanced - Black's only weakness is the IQP, but he has counterplay down the c-file. After castling, White can try to put pressure with Re1 and Nd4-f5.} *

