t the cost of two full tempi. However, this is very slow and violates a basic opening principle of not moving a piece several times in the opening. Nowadays, the 4...Ng8 line seems almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there is not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy variations such as 3.. .Nc6 and 3...dxe4.} 5. Nf3 ({This move-order and} 5. d4 {have equivalent value. Some players might prefer}) (5. d4 c5 6. c3 {with a closed game, but we prefer the chosen option as it allows Black to exchange on d4 and force our knight to d4. While the e5-pawn would be a bit weak, it's in our favour to open the position as we are leading in development.}) 5... c5 {There is hardly any sensible alternative to this move.} 6. d4 Nc6 ({Gaining space in the centre and overprotect the e5-pawn. At this point, we'll first examine the tempting} 6... cxd4 {before moving on to the main line of}) (6... Nc6 {.}) {The most logical move and the only one played so far in the MegaDatabase. Black heats up the battle on the d4-pawn.} 7. c3 ({Strengthening our control of the center. An easy alternative you may consider is} 7. dxc5 $5 Bxc5 8. a3 {followed by Bd3 when White has active piece play. However, we consider the text move to be more ambitious. The position after}) (7. c3 {, as you can expect, is a virgin forest yet to be explored. There have been a mere three games in the databases and a lot of ideas to be discovered.}) 7... cxd4 $6 {Removing the tension is clearly favourable for White as now we can efficiently develop our knight to the active c3-square. Strangely, this has been played often online.} 8. cxd4 Bb4+ $6 {Tempting us to develop our knight isn't the most sensible reaction, but White is better anyway.} 9. Nc3 Qa5 10. Qd2 $16 {White stands better with the extra space and Black has no effective way to break up the centre.} *

