t the cost of two full tempi. However, this is very slow and violates a basic opening principle of not moving a piece several times in the opening. Nowadays, the 4...Ng8 line seems almost forgotten, buried in the ground. Therefore, there is not much point in learning all the lines in this chapter by heart. You better spend your quality time on more trendy variations such as 3.. .Nc6 and 3...dxe4.} 5. Nf3 ({This move-order and} 5. d4 {have equivalent value. Some players might prefer}) (5. d4 c5 6. c3 {with a closed game, but we prefer the chosen option as it allows Black to exchange on d4 and force our knight to d4. While the e5-pawn would be a bit weak, it's in our favour to open the position as we are leading in development.}) 5... c5 {There is hardly any sensible alternative to this move.} 6. d4 Nc6 ({Gaining space in the centre and overprotect the e5-pawn. At this point, we'll first examine the tempting} 6... cxd4 {before moving on to the main line of}) (6... Nc6 {.}) {The most logical move and the only one played so far in the MegaDatabase. Black heats up the battle on the d4-pawn.} 7. c3 ({Strengthening our control of the center. An easy alternative you may consider is} 7. dxc5 $5 Bxc5 8. a3 {followed by Bd3 when White has active piece play. However, we consider the text move to be more ambitious. The position after}) (7. c3 {, as you can expect, is a virgin forest yet to be explored. There have been a mere three games in the databases and a lot of ideas to be discovered.}) 7... Bd7 {The most flexible move. Black plays a move that he normally plays anyway and keeps his cards secret for now. Qb6 is available, as well as Rc8. We'll reply as we usually do and put the bishop on d3.} 8. Bd3 {The bishop almost always goes to d3 in the closed Horwitz structure, and this position is no exception.} Qb6 ({Hitting the centre in typical French Defence fashion. The placement of Black's pieces is strikingly similar to the Advance French, with the significant difference being that White's centre is much, much more secure (note that in the Advance French, White sometimes even need to sacrifice his d4-pawn; the Milner-Barry Gambit being an example).} 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Qa5+ $5 {is a fascinating idea, with the point of} 10. Nc3 Ba3 $5 {undermining the c3-knight. Unfortunately for Black, White has the amazing pawn sacrifice} 11. Bxa3 $1 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 Nxd4 13. Rc1 $1 {and Black is busted. For example,} Qa5 14. Bd6 $1 Nxf3 15. Qxf3 Ne7 16. a4 $3 {preparing Rc7 and Black's position is close to hopeless with severe dark-square troubles.}) 9. O-O {Simple chess. As we explained in the Closed Horwitz Introduction chapter, dxc5! is a dangerous positional threat you should be aware of. The point is that we get rid of the annoying pressure on d4, free the d4 square for our minor pieces and will gain time pushing Black's pieces back.} Nh6 $6 {Allowing us to make the desirable exchange isn't the best of ideas.} 10. dxc5 $1 {Of course!} Bxc5 11. Qe2 {Strengthening our position and preventing Ng4 in advance. Next, we will expand on the queenside, with a promising game.} O-O 12. Nbd2 a5 ({Currently, our threat is to play} 12... Z0 13. b4 $1 Be7 14. a3 $1 {followed by c4 to open the centre. In that case, the d6 square would be Black's vital weakness. For that reason, Black should prevent b4.}) 13. a3 $16 {Covering the b4 square and preparing c4. We've reached a typical position for the 4...Ng8 variation, and the verdict is that Black is terribly cramped with little counterplay. With the pawn on e5 gaining so much space and c4 coming, White is clearly better. Ng5 is also a dangerous idea.} *

