 space advantage and holds on to the d4-pawn.}) 11... Nxd4 {Accepting the pawn is mandatory as otherwise, White can play Ne2! with a dream set-up.} 12. Rc1 $5 ({The immediate} 12. Nxd4 {is certainly an option, but this useful waiting move is our choice as it gives Black more chances to go wrong.}) 12... Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 {White has sufficient compensation for the pawn as Black is badly cramped on the kingside (just look at that knight!). Also, there are a lot of tactical possibilities for the first player, as you'll see.} Bb4 $1 ({Incredibly, this is the only move to maintain a balanced position - that is, according to the engine. The natural} 13... Be7 $6 {fails to} 14. Qg3 $1 {hitting the g7-pawn. The point is revealed after} O-O $2 15. Nxd5 $3 exd5 16. e6 $1 {with a double attack on the d7-bishop and the g7-pawn. Therefore, Black's best attempt is to try 14...Qd4 15.Nb5! Qxb2 with a complicated position. According to the engine, 16.Rc2!? , winning the queen, is the best move. However, play gets unnecessarily messy after 16...Qxc2 17.Bxc2 Bxb5 . We suggest you play 16.Qxg7 instead. After 16...Rg8! 17.Qxh6 Bxb5+ 18.Bxb5+ Kd8 19.Qf4 White is still better, and our advantage is much clearer and easier to convert as Black's king is stuck in the centre.}) 14. Qg3 Bxc3 ({The idea behind Black's previous move - now White no longer has the Nxd5 resource, which would be the case after} 14... O-O $2 15. Nxd5 $1 exd5 16. e6 {.}) 15. Rxc3 (15. Bxc3 {is a fine alternative, but we prefer the text because of a fantastic tactical idea - you'll see it soon...}) 15... O-O ({The only move to parry the threat of Qxg7, as} 15... g6 $4 16. Qf4 {+- is a dark-square disaster for Black.}) 16. Qf4 {Prepare to swing the rook to the kingside.} Bb5 {The most natural move, seemingly 'forces' an exchange of the light-squared bishops and kills most of our attacking forces. But we have a huge surprise ready to be revealed... If your opponent doesn't fall off his chair upon seeing our next move, then kudos to them!} 17. Bb1 $5 {Retreating our valuable bishop back and hanging the f1-rook! However, our remaining pieces will coordinate surprisingly well to tighten the net around Black's king. Let us tell you the truth in advance: it's a notorious 0.00 according to the engine, but the chance that your opponent will play accurately until here AND will find the amazing sequence to force a draw, then a big shoutout to them and we should be satisfied with half a point. Unfortunately, that's what modern chess is like.} Bxf1 18. Rg3 $13 {White has amazing compensation for the rook and a pawn due to our dangerous attack on Black's king.} Kh8 ({Trying to get out of the dangerous g-file.} 18... Nf5 19. Bxf5 exf5 20. Rxg7+ $1 {a brilliant sacrifice, forcing a draw after} Kxg7 21. e6+ f6 22. Qg5+ $1 {= After the text move, it's our turn to find an only move.}) 19. Rxg7 $3 Z0 ({Bang! Black's solid-looking kingside is ripped open in a second. It's Black's turn to show his defensive brilliance with} 19... Nf5 $3 {in order to survive, as the normal}) (19... Kxg7 $2 {loses instantly to} 20. Qg5+ $1 Kh8 21. Qxh6 f5 22. exf6 {with a decisive mating attack. A nice point is} Rf7 23. Bxh7 $1 {when Black's kingside falls apart. After the correct}) (19... Nf5 $1 {, White has several ways to force a draw, the easiest one being} 20. Bxf5 Kxg7 21. Qg5+ {=. If you're desperate for the win, there are alternatives like 21.Bd4 , 21.g4!? and more, but ultimately they're all 0.00 positions. Conclusion: In this rather short chapter, we've begun our investigation of the Closed Horwitz. After the obvious 4. e5 Black has a variety of choices to pick from. 4...Nfd7 is clearly the mainline which will be covered next, but 4...Ne4 and 4...Ng8 are legal moves deserving a mention as well. We like White's position with a space advantage in almost all lines.}) *

