1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... b6 ({Fighting back in the centre immediately with} 5... c5 {is certainly the main option, but we'll quickly check this little pawn move. The idea is known from other variations in the French: Black wants to get rid of their bad bishop via Ba6 and, in their words, get a 'fine' game. However, if an early b6 hasn't ever been considered a good line against the Advance French, then there's no way Black can get away with such slow play here - because the closed Horwitz is a favourable version of the Advance French!}) 6. f4 $1 {We use the extra time granted by Black's manoeuvre to strengthen our centre.} Ba6 7. Bxa6 {Forcing Black's knight to the edge of the board.} Nxa6 8. Qe2 $1 {An energetic and accurate move, hitting the knight and demanding Black to protect their knight.} Qc8 ({Protecting the knight.} 8... Ndb8 {brings the knight, that comes from g8, to b8, which is too much of a waste of time. We can exploit Black's lag in development with} 9. Nc3 c5 10. O-O-O $1 {with a huge initiative. Nf3 and f5 are coming when it's unlikely that Black will survive.}) 9. Nf3 c5 ({Black must strive for activity as they lack space. A slow move like} 9... c6 {can be met by} 10. O-O Nc7 11. c4 $1 {expanding on both flanks, when White has a significant advantage.}) 10. f5 $1 {Striking while the iron is hot! We transform our actively-placed army and space advantage into a direct assault.} Nc7 {Black must try to close the position, while we'll be doing the opposite.} (10... exf5 $6 {would be a risky decision due to} 11. c4 $1 {a shocking and strong blow! White opens the centre and our position is borderline crushing.} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bc5 13. Nxf5 {with a big attack. Note that} O-O 14. Nxg7 $1 {is a neat tactical trick that gives White a winning attack.}) ({If} 10... exf5 $6 11. c4 {and now here the other capture} dxc4 12. d5 $1 {is winning for White, as any human being can understand with a quick glance at the position.}) 11. c4 $1 {We break through in the centre anyway. Note how the power of the Horwitz bishop is released like an atomic bomb. The position is risky for Black and requires precise play, but our position is still preferable. A sample line is} cxd4 12. Nxd4 dxc4 13. fxe6 {Black's king is extremely vulnerable now.} Nxe6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. O-O {White has a close to devastating attack for the price of just one pawn. Black's king is forever stuck in the centre, and White has long-term compensation. We will continue with Nc3-e4, and Black should consider themselves very lucky if they escape at all.} *

