1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} cxd4 $6 {This move is very popular online. However, in general, Black should be very reluctant when making the cxd4 exchange as it gives White the ideal c3 square to develop our knight - the exchange on d4 is only effective once White's b1-knight has reached d2. For that reason, the text move shows a lack of understanding from Black in this structure - a good sign for fans of the Horwitz!} 7. cxd4 Nc6 8. Nc3 {For mysterious reasons only a few White players had exploited Black's inaccuracy on the 6th move and developed the knight to this optimal square.} f6 $5 ({As Black has lost the option of playing on the queenside, they must do something on the other side with the f6 break. An ordinary move like} 8... Be7 {would have allowed White to display our full space power with} 9. f4 $1 O-O 10. Nf3 {when Black's space disadvantage will torture them for a long time.}) 9. Bd3 {Black's last move weakened the h5-e8 diagonal, so we create the devious threat of Qh5+} Be7 ({Black prepares to slide their king to f8 in case of a check. While this approach is the best choice objectively, something must have gone wrong for Black if they are forced to commit their king like that. There is also} 9... g6 {which prevents Qh5+, but it has the drawback of weakening the dark squares, and after} 10. exf6 $1 Nxf6 11. Nf3 {White enjoys a great positional advantage due to the e-file and ugly dark squares in Black's position.}) 10. Qh5+ Kf8 {Black's king has been driven to a poor square, and now there are two ways to continue the offensive.} 11. f4 $5 (11. Nf3 $5 {is also possible, when Black must play} Qe8 $1 {to avoid trouble. The main line of our analysis continues} 12. Qh3 fxe5 13. dxe5 Ndxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bb5 $1 Nc6 16. O-O {followed by f4-f5 with amazing compensation for a worthless pawn. However, the text move seems to be even more appealing. We sacrifice the d4-pawn to clear the diagonal for the Horwitz bishop and gain time on the knight.}) 11... Nxd4 {If Black doesn't accept the sacrifice, chances are that they are going to be squashed as our space advantage is too hard to handle.} 12. Nf3 $1 {Forcing the exchange of the knights, which favours us as the central d4-knight is swapped off for a counterpart that has barely been developed.} Nxf3+ (12... Nc5 13. O-O-O $1 {transposes to the mainline.}) 13. Qxf3 {The queen is standing on the same file as that rusty king. You know what we're implying...} Nc5 $1 ({The best move, angling for counterplay and preparing to remove the ever-dangerous d3-bishop. Note that} 13... fxe5 $2 {simply loses to} 14. fxe5+ Kg8 15. O-O {+- with a decisive invasion on the f7 square.}) 14. O-O-O $1 ({There is also a risky alternative to the text move,} 14. Bc2 $5 f5 15. g4 {as suggested by the engine. However, we do not believe it's easy to handle a Bongcloud king after} Bh4+ 16. Ke2 {, even though Stockfish has been screaming at us that it's a viable approach. The text move is much more natural and leads to positions where we alone have attacking chances. Moreover, this line can be played against both 12...Nc5 and 13...Nc5 .}) 14... Nxd3+ 15. Rxd3 $13 Z0 ({White has powerful compensation for the pawn as Black's king is stuck in the centre and both the c8-bishop and h8-rook aren't doing anything. The 'only move' for Black not to get into serious troubles is} 15... h5 $1 {, an inhuman pawn thrust. Let your opponent spends hours to find this amazing resource, and we'll strike with} 16. f5 $1 {when we doubt whether Black can survive in practice against a strong Horwitz devotee.}) *

