1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qa5 $5 ({This crafty queen move hasn't been tried very many times, but we believe it's quite underrated and contains some venom. There is a minor 7th move alternative too, so we'll take the opportunity to present the brief information with you here in form of clickables: A -} 7... cxd4 {isn't so dubious here as Black has some concrete ideas} 8. cxd4 {and there is a further branch: A1 -} Qa5+ 9. Nd2 {transposes to}) (7... Qa5 {A2 - 8...a5!? Black wants to create an annoying a-pawn with ...a4, so we'll stop them in their tracks with 9.a3!? a4 10.b4 , closing the queenside. Both sides will fight for control of the c4-square now, and a sample line is 10...Nb6 11.Nd2 Bd7 12.Nh3! with better prospects for White on the kingside. Other moves to develop the g1-knight come with drawbacks, for example Nf3 blocks the f-pawn and Ne2 blocks the queen's diagonal, both of which slow down our kingside counterplay. A3 - 8...b5!? is one of the points behind Black's last move, and it's a sound gambit. Black intends to lure our bishop to the b5-square where some tricks are waiting for us. There are some calm alternatives, but we would like to meet fire with fire and bravely accept the offer with 9.Bxb5!? the critical test of any gambit is to accept it! 9...Qa5+ is Black's point and after 10.Nc3 the line divides again: A31 - 10...Bb4? looks tempting, but 11.Qd3!+- protects everything with a winning position. A32 - After 10.Nc3 Ba3! is the best move, luring our bishop away from the defence of the knight and regaining the pawn after the forced 11.Bxa3 Qxc3+ 12.Kf1 Nxd4 However, we have the resources 13.Ne2! preparing to get rid of the strong d4-knight and we're at the last tabiya of the 7...cxd4 variation: A33 - 13...Nxe2?! gives White the bishop pair for just a pawn, and after 14.Bxe2 Nxe5 White can continue energetically with 15.Rc1 Qa5 16.Bd6! f6! 17.h4! followed by Rh3, activating the rook. White's compensation for the pawn is very dangerous. A34 - 13...Qa5! is the best move, as suggested by the engine. Black hits the a3-bishop and captures it after 14.Nxd4 Qxa3 At this point we suggest 15.Qc1! when White has a nagging advantage due to the awkward placement of the d7-knight.}) 8. Nd2 {Black was threatening cxd4, so we wisely block the diagonal and indirectly protect the d4-pawn.} cxd4 9. cxd4 Ba3 $5 {This approach deserves some consideration. Black lacks space so they offer an exchange of the bishops. However, from a positional point of view, it's a bad decision to exchange the crucial dark-squared bishop. The concrete detail is that the Horwitz bishop is providing support to the d4-pawn, and Black wishes to undermine it.} 10. Qc1 $1 ({White's position is rather uncomfortable after} 10. Bxa3 $6 Qxa3 {when the d4-pawn is quite weak. The text move is stronger: we protect everything while forcing Black to release the tension.}) 10... Bxb2 11. Qxb2 $14 {White has a clearly better position. We have a space advantage, while Black has a chronic weakness on the dark squares. We can continue slowly with Ne2, Rc1 and expand on both flanks with h4-h5 and a3-b4.} *

