re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qb6 {This standard move is a must to consider in the French structure. Black hits the d4-pawn, which was well protected by the Horwitz bishop but now vulnerable.} 8. Ne2 {The most logical solution, simply and efficiently protecting the d4-pawn.} cxd4 $6 {One of those bad-timed cxd4s that's very popular online.} 9. cxd4 {Thanks Black for the c3 square!} Bb4+ $6 {This check does nothing other than accelerating our development.} 10. Nd2 {Nc3 drops the d4-pawn this time, so we develop our knight to a less active square. However, the b4-bishop is far from ideally placed, and it will have to move again.} O-O 11. Qc2 $1 ({A nice little move, hitting the h7-pawn and forcing Black's king to h8 or to play a weakening move. At first, we didn't understand why this move is better than the immediate} 11. a3 {, but we managed to find the solution later, and will explain the details soon!}) 11... Kh8 (11... g6 {and}) (11... h6 {are too weakening to be good.}) 12. a3 Be7 (12... Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 $1 {is the critical detail! Had we played a3 instead of Qc2, the king would be on g8 and Black could play} f6 $1 14. exf6 Nxf6 {with good counterplay. However, with the king one square on the right, the evaluation of the position turns around in White's favour - possibly because the king is facing some concrete problems on h8.}) 13. f4 $16 {We've pushed Black back and secured a decent space advantage. White is a lot better here as Black has no counterplay at all. Next, we'll continue with Nf3 to strengthen our centre. Also, don't forget that the h7-pawn is hanging, or attacking ideas like O-O followed by Rf3!} *

