re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qb6 {This standard move is a must to consider in the French structure. Black hits the d4-pawn, which was well protected by the Horwitz bishop but now vulnerable.} 8. Ne2 {The most logical solution, simply and efficiently protecting the d4-pawn.} a5 $5 {The idea of rolling the a-pawn down the board isn't unique in the French, and given that the queen is eyeing the b-file, it's quite a logical plan.} 9. O-O ({We ignore Black on the queenside and complete our development. Having said that,} 9. a4 $5 {is a perfectly valid strategy.}) 9... a4 10. Na3 $1 {This move is rarely seen in the closed Horwitz, so make sure to understand and remember it! White prepares the c4 blow, which wouldn't be so strong if the queen is on d8 as after Black captures on c4, Nxc4 wouldn't come with tempo anymore.} Be7 $1 {Black must try to complete development; otherwise, c3-c4! is going to hit them hard.} 11. c4 $1 {The long-awaited break has finally arrived! The resulting positions are extraordinarily complicated - a mess that the engine evaluated as dead equal, of course - and it's easy for both sides to go wrong. However, it's likely that you know more than your opponents about this position, and will therefore have more fun!} cxd4 ({We've included this natural capture as our mainline, but there are other options: A -} 11... dxc4 $6 {invites} 12. Nxc4 Qc7 13. Nd6+ $1 {with an almost-decisive initiative. B -}) (11... O-O $5 {is also quite sensible. Black keeps the tension for now and dares us to release it. B1 -} 12. Nf4 $5 {leads to murky positions, and a sample continuation is} Nxd4 13. Qh5 $1 g6 14. Nxg6 {with a perpetual. B2 - 12.cxd5! is our main recommendation. We clarify the situation in the centre and open up access to several key squares. After 12...exd5 we should continue with 13.Nc3! cxd4 14.Nxd5 Qd8 when the most ambitious continuation is 15.f4 , protecting the e5-pawn while maintaining that golden knight on d5. The position is rather unclear, but we believe in White's chances.}) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nf4 $1 {Hitting the d5-pawn and forcing Black to play precisely to reach equality.} Ndxe5 ({Perhaps the best move from a practical point of view. Black clears the tension in the centre and puts a knight on the active e5-square. That comes at the cost of leaving the d5-pawn hanging, though... The engine suggests the creative solution} 13... Ra5 $5 {to defend the d5-pawn, but it allows White to go for Black's throat with} 14. e6 $1 {, destroying the king's shelter. Our almighty silicon friends insist that Black's 'fine' after} Nf6 15. exf7+ Kxf7 {, but Black's peculiarly-placed king means that a misstep will have a disastrous effect. Good luck surviving in practice, blind fans of engines!}) 14. Nxd5 Qd8 15. Nb5 $5 O-O ({Setting a mini-trap:} 15... Qxd5 $4 16. Nc7+ $1 {and White forks the queen. Of course, 15.Nxe7+ is a viable alternative, grabbing the bishop pair immediately.}) {Black is forced to surrender the bishop pair as otherwise White can give a check on c7.} 16. Nxe7+ Nxe7 17. Be4 {At the end of the day White is a pawn down, but it's hardly a problem considering that the d4-pawn will drop soon anyway. The position is objectively equal as Black can try to make it as hard as possible for White to regain the pawn and exchange one of the bishops in the process. It's easier said than done though, and if White is allowed to capture on d4 without any concession, then it's just two bishops in an open position - a bishopmare for Black.} *

