1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qb6 {This standard move is a must to consider in the French structure. Black hits the d4-pawn, which was well protected by the Horwitz bishop but now vulnerable.} 8. Ne2 {The most logical solution, simply and efficiently protecting the d4-pawn.} f6 $5 {Black opts for a concrete approach. This undermines our proud centre and forces us to react immediately.} 9. Nf4 $1 {) Let's just ignore the pawn and go for the king! Black's last move has the drawback of weakening the king, and we exploit that fact to our advantage. The threat is Qh5+} fxe5 $6 {Black accepts the challenge and enters the bloody complications. The position becomes razor-sharp now, with a lot of tactical possibilities. While this is an interesting way of playing practically, according to the engine (whose opinion is very important in such sharp positions), White is better.} 10. Qh5+ Ke7 (10... g6 $2 11. Nxg6 $1 {exploits the h-file pin and Black lands in a disaster. The king must Bongcloud itself and take up an 'aggressive' position in the centre. From now on, we will dedicate all our resources to getting at that bare creature!}) 11. dxe5 Ndxe5 {Black's king placement is awkward enough that the extra pawn doesn't help Black. Moreover, the Horwitz bishop strikes on the long diagonal after} 12. c4 $1 {Opening the long diagonal for the bishop to join in the assault! Black's king is incredibly shaky, and a lot of combinations are awaiting it!} d4 $1 ({The best chance to resist; Black must block the centre at all cost! There is no time to go pawn-grabbing with} 12... dxc4 $2 {. We should punish it with} 13. Be4 $1 {and even though Black might be ahead in material, the king is a telling factor. With O-O, Re1 and Nd2 to follow, Black's position is simply losing. Meanwhile,}) (12... Nxd3+ 13. Nxd3 d4 {is an inferior version of the mainline for White as Black no longer has the strong e5-knight to guard their centre. We can simply continue with} 14. O-O g6 15. Qe2 Kf7 16. Nd2 {when there's no doubt White's seriously better as Black's extra pawn is blocked and useless. Moreover, his king is still struggling to find a safe shelter.}) 13. O-O Kd8 {Getting the king out of the dangerous e-file. Against other moves, we can also play Nd2 followed by Rae1 with a scary attack. A typical theme to remember is Nxe6! to exploit the e-file pin.} 14. Nd2 {We slowly but powerfully bring our pieces to the battlefield.} Be7 15. Be4 {A pawn down? Okay. A blocked bishop? Yes. A better position? Sure! Black's king is so weak that White's initiative gives us a better position, even according to the engine. The text move is played with the idea of protecting our light-squared bishop from the threat of Rf8!, undermining the f4-knight, the defender of the bishop. Next on the agenda is Rae1, Bxc6 (to force Nxc6, after which the e6-pawn hangs) and even a re-route of the bishop via Bc1.} *

