re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Qb6 {This standard move is a must to consider in the French structure. Black hits the d4-pawn, which was well protected by the Horwitz bishop but now vulnerable.} 8. Ne2 {The most logical solution, simply and efficiently protecting the d4-pawn.} f6 $5 {Black opts for a concrete approach. This undermines our proud centre and forces us to react immediately.} 9. Nf4 $1 {Let's just ignore the pawn and go for the king! Black's last move has the drawback of weakening the king, and we exploit that fact to our advantage. The threat is Qh5+} g6 $1 {The correct defence! Black prevents Qh5+ once and for all, even though their kingside might be somewhat weakened.} 10. O-O $5 ({We ignore the tension happening in the centre and safeguard our lovely king before the oncoming complications. Note that} 10. Nxe6 {allows the typical trick 11...Ndxe5! regaining the piece with a fine position for Black, while 10.exf6?! Nxf6 is surprisingly good for the second player, who can continue with Bd6, O-O and Bd7 when it's White who struggles for equality.}) 10... Bh6 $1 ({Hitting the knight and begging us to capture the e6-pawn. In engine terms, the text move is the only move to maintain a rough balance in the position. While that information isn't so useful practically, it does show that Black's position is far from easy to handle. For example, after} 10... fxe5 $6 11. Nxe6 {it turns out that Black no longer has that Ndxe5 trick and White stands better positionally after 11...cxd4 12.Nxf8! Rxf8 12.cxd4 e4 13.Be2 with the bishop pair and a well-placed army.}) 11. Bxg6+ $5 ({We aren't satisfied with Stockfish's number one choice,} 11. Nxe6 {, as Black gets a healthy position after the standard tactic} Ncxe5 $1 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. dxc5 Qxc5 {when the engine gives White a tiny edge, but we even prefer Black slightly with active pieces while our Horwitz bishop has limited scope. Note that 11...Ndxe5?? would be a blunder due to 12.dxc5! Qa5 13.b4 and the queen is awkwardly trapped! The text move is an 'impossible' blow: how can we capture such a well-defended pawn? Well, the key is that we wish to exploit the vulnerability of Black's pieces on the kingside with Nxg6 and Qh5 to follow. Our silicon friend doesn't 'understand' the potential of the sacrifice and claims it's a dead equal position. Equal, maybe, but we're throwing ourselves into a lively and chaotic position, not dead!}) 11... hxg6 12. Nxg6 Rh7 ({The first of several only moves Black must play to stay in the game.} 12... Rg8 $2 {looks natural, if not for} 13. Qh5 $1 {with the duel threats of a discovered check and Qxh6.}) 13. Qh5 {Going on full aggressive mode!} Kd8 $1 ({Black should get the king out of the danger!} 13... Nd8 $5 {is a creative solution with the idea of Nf7 to block a potential check, but we don't believe Black's chance of surviving is any higher than in the mainline after} 14. c4 $1 {, furiously opening up the centre where Black's king is located.}) 14. Bc1 $1 {It's our turn to show our precision with this cool move, dropping the bishop back to exploit the h-file pin.} Bxc1 {Otherwise Black would be a few pawns down after Bxh6.} 15. Qxh7 {It's Black's choice where to put the bishop, and only one move saves their position...} Bb2 $1 (15... Bg5 $2 16. h4 {+- traps the bishop, so Black must continue the bishop's journey far from the defence.}) 16. Nf4 $13 Z0 ({Not caring about the rook at all, but instead going for that weak king! The threat is Nxe6+, and Black has a wealth of options, good and bad, to choose from. The engine harshly displays triple zeros, but the position is so complex that any result can happen from this mess. We will show you some sample lines: A -} 16... Bxa1 $4 {is far too greedy, and we can continue with} 17. Nxe6+ Ke8 18. Qg8+ $1 Ke7 19. Nf4 $1 {the key move to win! Now, the threats of Nxd5+ and Ng6+ are unstoppable. B - 16.Nf4 Nxd4!? is played with the idea of preventing Nxe6+ before taking the rook. We should simply proceed with 17.cxd4 Bxa1 and now 18.Qf7!? seems like the most dangerous continuation. Black is certainly walking on a thin rope here to survive. C - 16...Ncxe5!? is another version of the same idea. C1 - 16...Ncxe5!? 17.dxe5?! fxe5! =+ is pleasant for Black, as both the f4-knight and a1-rook are attacked. C2 - 16...Ncxe5!? 17.Qg8+ is the correct way to proceed, not caring about the e5-knight for now. Play continues 17...Kc7! 18.Nd2! to protect the rook instead, and the line branches for the last time: C21 - 18...Bxa1? 19.Rxa1 +- and White is surprisingly winning! The knight isn't running away due to the nasty idea of Nxe6+, and if Black drops the king back to b8, then Qg3+ decides. In the long term, the h-pawn is a potential asset, too. C22 - 18...Bxc3! is the engine suggestion, grabbing a bunch of pawns instead of the exchange. After 19.dxe5 Bxd2 20.Nxe6+ Kb8 21.Rad1 we cannot keep track of the complications that are going on. However, a recurring theme is that White often has various ways to proceed, while Black usually has to find only moves to survive.}) *

