re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} b5 $5 {Black gambits the b5-pawn for the bishop pair and quick development. While this gambit isn't completely sound, it's practically a nuisance to deal with without any preparation. At least, that's what would happen if you click on the 'exit' button right now...} 9. Bxb5 Qb6 $1 {The point behind Black's gambit. Both the d4-pawn and b5-bishop are attacked, so White's forced to hand over the bishop pair.} 10. Bxc6 Qxc6 11. Ne2 {Preparing to bring our king into safety. There is no need to rock the boat now after pocketing a pawn - it's Black's job to do that. We just need to consolidate our extra material!} O-O 12. O-O Ba6 (12... cxd4 $6 {releases the tension too early, and suddenly White has} 13. Nxd4 $1 Qc7 14. f4 $1 Ba6 15. Rf3 {with a kingside initiative.}) 13. Nf3 {There are several methods to defuse Black's bishop pair, but we prefer the simple one.} Rfc8 14. Re1 {Getting the rook from the bishop's line of fire.} Bxe2 $1 ({Last chance to take on e2 as after a normal move like} 14... Rab8 15. Nf4 $1 {is very strong, creating all sorts of threats on the kingside while the a6-bishop looks at thin air.}) 15. Qxe2 (15. Rxe2 {is perfectly playable too.}) 15... a5 $1 {Black must continue the queenside offensive! Here, we'd like to suggest an accurate manoeuvre for White to secure a stable advantage.} 16. Bc1 a4 17. Bd2 $14 {White's position is very harmonious with no weakness in sight. Black has some queenside pressure, but the best he can hope for is an inferior but holdable ending after a liquidation on the queenside. Still, White is playing for two results here with absolutely no chance of losing.} *

