re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} a5 $5 {This pawn thrust, with the idea of a5-a4, is quite original and interesting. As this is among the top engine suggestions and after a careful examination we can find no objective advantage for White, you should be careful upon seeing your opponent execute this move!} 9. Ne2 ({Simply developing in Horwitz fashion.} 9. Qg4 $5 {is a dynamic queen move, but we have trust in Black's position after} O-O {followed by f6 when the queen is misplaced.}) 9... a4 {Black continues the journey of the a-pawn and creates some uncomfortable threats in White's camp.} 10. Nf3 a3 {The pawn finally reached its destiny - chasing the a3-bishop and forcing it to retreat to the original square. However, a drawback is that the a-file won't be opened for the rooks anymore and the a3-pawn may be a weakness in the endgame.} 11. Bc1 cxd4 12. cxd4 f6 $1 {Energetic play by Black! The second player blows up the centre in typical French fashion. We have no choice but to release the tension.} 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. O-O {The position is equal, as both sides have their own strategic trumps. White has the juicy e5 outpost, but the d4-pawn is potentially vulnerable and the a3-pawn is very annoying in the middlegame stage. Next, we should continue with Bg5, Re1 and Nf4/Ne5 to pressure the e6-pawn and occupy the e5 outpost.} *

