re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} a5 $5 {This pawn thrust, with the idea of a5-a4, is quite original and interesting. As this is among the top engine suggestions and after a careful examination we can find no objective advantage for White, you should be careful upon seeing your opponent execute this move!} 9. Ne2 ({Simply developing in Horwitz fashion.} 9. Qg4 $5 {is a dynamic queen move, but we have trust in Black's position after} O-O {followed by f6 when the queen is misplaced.}) 9... a4 {Black continues the journey of the a-pawn and creates some uncomfortable threats in White's camp.} 10. Nf3 O-O $5 {As the 8...O-O variation, castling in this variation is very risky as the king can come under sacrificial attacks from White's well-placed army. The engine couldn't understand that fact - but humans can.} 11. Nf4 $5 ({The knight is getting close to the battle and Black's king must have started to feel the heat.} 11. Qb1 $5 {is an interesting alternative, but the text move is more dangerous according to us. For the record, the main line of our analysis is} Kh8 $1 12. Bxh7 cxd4 13. cxd4 g6 $1 {when White's forced to go for the perpetual with} 14. Bxg6 fxg6 15. Qxg6 {.}) 11... Qa5 $6 ({Black underestimates our initiative and resumes his queenside play. While this decision is inferior, we decided to put this as the main move to illustrate our brilliant attacking ideas. Here is our coverage of alternatives: A -} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 axb3 {, trying to lure White's pieces away from the kingside, is met with the energetic} 13. h4 $1 {and Black should react with care: A1 -} Rxa2 $2 14. Bxh7+ $1 {is a standard Greek Gift that gives White a better position. A2 - 13...g6! is the accurate treatment, when we must play ordinarily with 14.axb3 += There is no attack for now, but our positional superiority ensures us a small edge. B - 11...axb3 is met similarly: 12.h4! with the devastating threat of Bxh7+. The lines are similar to A, with the tiny difference of the c-pawn removed.}) 12. h4 $1 {Gọing all-in for a successful kingside attack!} a3 $2 {This move does nothing other than provoke the inevitable Bxh7+, but the mating sequence is so amazing that we believe it's worth a trainable to show it to you.} 13. Bxh7+ $1 {Ripping the cover of Black's king!} Kh8 (13... Kxh7 14. Ng5+ {leads to a quicker mate.}) 14. Ng5 $1 {Throwing our pieces forward like a mad man, not caring about the queenside pieces at all.} axb2 15. Qh5 $3 {The final, spectacular last move needed for victory! Black might pocket himself a bishop, a rook AND an extra queen, but we're going after the most valuable piece.} bxa1=Q+ 16. Bb1+ $1 {From afar, the bishop goes back, blocks the check and opens the way for the queen to hit that no-defender king.} Kg8 17. Qh7# {Checkmate! After a brilliantly conducted game, White finishes off with a pleasing finale. Have you ever seen such a gorgeous mate before, after just 17 moves? This line is a reminder to us (and hopefully you) why we love chess and specifically, the Horwitz Attack.} *

