morise so many complex lines in such a rare variation.}) 10. Qh5 $1 {Immediately hitting the weak h7 spot.} h6 ({Black creates a big hole on g6, but there is no choice.} 10... f5 {is just a wasted tempi for Black compared to the mainline, while}) (10... g6 $2 {loses to the elegant combination} 11. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 12. Qxg6+ Kh8 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14. Rh3 $1 {and mate is inevitable.}) 11. f4 $1 ({We like this option the most, securing our dominant space advantage with Ngf3 to follow. Note that} 11. Qg6 $6 f5 $1 12. Qxe6+ $2 Kh8 $1 {is actually winning for Black, as there is no good way to stop Ndxe5!}) 11... fxe5 12. fxe5 cxd4 13. cxd4 Rf4 {Black tries hard to undermine our centre, but we can play} 14. Ndf3 $1 ({The idea of this move is to defend the d4-pawn while allowing the other knight to go to e2.} 14. Ngf3 {was our initial idea, but when we check the line again it turned out that after} Nf8 $1 15. g3 Rf7 {Black's position is quite solid and not easy to break.}) 14... Qa5+ $5 {Disrupting our coordination a bit, but we can calmly reply} 15. Ke2 $16 {And amazingly, our king is perfectly safe in the centre as the centre is blocked. We're threatening Nh3 followed by Nhg5! with a devastating attack. That's modern chess, everyone!} *

