1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} O-O {Black refrains from queenside action as seen previously. Instead, he castles kingside and waits to see what we can do. The second player clearly doesn't expect us to kick off the kingside attack immediately!} 9. h4 $5 {Huy the hacking pawn steps forward and initiates the first attacking wave. You might be thinking that such madness cannot be possible and we made the lines work ourselves, but no, this is engine-approved chess! Our pawn thrust, although a super rare guest in practice, has been tested for days with strong engines, so you can be assured of its soundness! In practice, we believe your opponent will be shocked and likely to commit a mistake at this point. Sure, the road to dynamic equality is there, but in all lines it's White who does the attacking, while Black occasionally needs to find several 'only moves' to survive.} b5 $5 {A strange version of 8...b5!? . Black exploits the fact that he has effectively gained a tempi after 9.Bxb5 Qb6! 10.Bxc6 Qxc6 when Black has already castled while h4 seems like an out-of-place weakening move. However, the fact that Black has committed his king allows us to ignore the pawn and go for the bigger prize!} 10. Qh5 $1 {The bishop stays on d3 and White's queen aggressively comes out to set up a mating threat. Actually, the reason this queen sortie is so strange in the French is that often the d4-pawn is poorly defended should the queen leave its post on d1. However, in the closed Horwitz, our b2-bishop is doing a perfect job of holding our structure together, thus allowing us to focus on the kingside attack. After reading our explanation, who dares to say the Horwitz bishop is bad and not participating?} h6 (10... g6 {can be met by} 11. Qh6 $1 {, blocking the kingside with the unstoppable threat of h4-h5; 10...f5 11.Ngf3 just gives White a favourable version of the main line as the b5-pawn doesn't participate in the battle as much as the b6-queen would. Also, make sure to maintain your tactical alertness against a silly move like 10...cxd4!}) 11. Rh3 $1 {Lifting the rook on the 3rd rank and preparing the devastating Rg3.} c4 ({Black must protect the b5-pawn first!} 11... f5 $6 {does stop our attack temporarily, but it allows the simple} 12. Bxb5 {when White is better as Black's f6 break is forever stopped.}) 12. Bc2 f5 $1 13. O-O-O $5 ({Only now this move is correct, and actually, it's the only move to avoid a quick defeat! Note that} 13. exf6 $2 {just loses to} Nxf6 {followed by Bd6 and e5 when White's crushed in the centre. At this point, White has several ways to continue, but the one we like the most is}) {Even though White already has a lot of attacking pieces on the kingside, bringing the 'rookies' to the party cannot hurt! The only drawback is that Black can organise some counterplay against our king, but in this double-edged battle, it transpires that White is better, after hours of analysis.} 13... b4 14. g4 {Opening the kingside as quickly as possible! The position is razor-sharp, and a misstep from either side can turn the tables very quickly. The good news for us is: the engine evaluates this as clearly better for White! That fact is only of relative importance in such a position though, so make sure to train your attacking skills, either by playing with a training partner or the engine.} *

