{or 16...Kh8 17.Nf4 with the deadly threat of Ng6+. Of course, such things are bound to happen when you have five attacking pieces (including the e5-pawn and e2-knight against a bare bishop. By the way, who cares about that poor a1-knight?} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} O-O {Black refrains from queenside action as seen previously. Instead, he castles kingside and waits to see what we can do. The second player clearly doesn't expect us to kick off the kingside attack immediately!} 9. h4 $5 {Huy the hacking pawn steps forward and initiates the first attacking wave. You might be thinking that such madness cannot be possible and we made the lines work ourselves, but no, this is engine-approved chess! Our pawn thrust, although a super rare guest in practice, has been tested for days with strong engines, so you can be assured of its soundness! In practice, we believe your opponent will be shocked and likely to commit a mistake at this point. Sure, the road to dynamic equality is there, but in all lines it's White who does the attacking, while Black occasionally needs to find several 'only moves' to survive.} Qb6 {We believe this is the best try for Black, countering a kingside offensive by playing in the centre. The d4-pawn is attacked, and we must do something...} 10. Qh5 $1 {We've burned the bridge, so we're forced to go forward! 9.Ne2?! (and 9.Nf3 ) would have allowed Black to dismantle our proud centre too easily with 9...f6! when it's White who struggles to get equality. The text move isn't subtle, and hopefully you see White's threat! From a positional standpoint, each of Black's options has its drawbacks. 10...g6 and 10...h6 create weaknesses which we can exploit, while 10...f5 blocks the centre altogether and allows us to build up our play on the kingside without worrying about ...f6 breaks. Of course, for concrete reasons, some options might be better than others, but we present these positional considerations for you to see that it's not 'easy' to prevent White's threat at all. In fact, it's quite the opposite!} h6 $2 ({As mentioned before, this move creates a deadly weakness on h6 which we can exploit.} 10... g6 $2 {is not much better, as we can sacrifice the d4-pawn with} 11. Qh6 $1 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Ngf3 $1 {getting rid of that active knight} Nxf3+ 14. Nxf3 Re8 15. O-O-O {and White is clearly better with h4-h5 to follow. That d4-pawn doesn't really matter, especially considering that the e5-pawn is doing a brilliant job of cramping Black.}) 11. Ne2 {No need to rush things, that h6 weakness isn't going to disappear from the world! Next, we'll introduce the traditional rook lift Rh3-g3, when Black will suffer.} Qc7 12. Rh3 $1 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 {A last-ditch attempt to distract us from the attack by threatening the light-squared bishop.} 14. Bb1 {The light-squared bishop is a strong attacking unit, no need to swap it off...} Nc2+ 15. Kd1 $1 {But not the rook! We're willing to 'misplace' our king and 'sacrifice' the ill rook in the corner for the decisive strike, which will happen far away from where most Black's army is located. However, the most valuable piece is screaming for help...} Nxa1 16. Rg3 Z0 ({Lining up on the g-file and threatening Qxh6. White's attack will crash through after either} 16... f5 17. Nf4 Nf6 18. Qxh6) *

