re: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} O-O {Black refrains from queenside action as seen previously. Instead, he castles kingside and waits to see what we can do. The second player clearly doesn't expect us to kick off the kingside attack immediately!} 9. h4 $5 {Huy the hacking pawn steps forward and initiates the first attacking wave. You might be thinking that such madness cannot be possible and we made the lines work ourselves, but no, this is engine-approved chess! Our pawn thrust, although a super rare guest in practice, has been tested for days with strong engines, so you can be assured of its soundness! In practice, we believe your opponent will be shocked and likely to commit a mistake at this point. Sure, the road to dynamic equality is there, but in all lines it's White who does the attacking, while Black occasionally needs to find several 'only moves' to survive.} Qb6 {We believe this is the best try for Black, countering a kingside offensive by playing in the centre. The d4-pawn is attacked, and we must do something...} 10. Qh5 $1 {We've burned the bridge, so we're forced to go forward! 9.Ne2?! (and 9.Nf3 ) would have allowed Black to dismantle our proud centre too easily with 9...f6! when it's White who struggles to get equality. The text move isn't subtle, and hopefully you see White's threat! From a positional standpoint, each of Black's options has its drawbacks. 10...g6 and 10...h6 create weaknesses which we can exploit, while 10...f5 blocks the centre altogether and allows us to build up our play on the kingside without worrying about ...f6 breaks. Of course, for concrete reasons, some options might be better than others, but we present these positional considerations for you to see that it's not 'easy' to prevent White's threat at all. In fact, it's quite the opposite!} f5 $1 {The correct reply, blocking our proud light-squared bishop. Black also reminds us that the threat to h7 is covered, leaving us to defend the d4-pawn. The main question is: how to do so?} 11. Ngf3 (11. Ndf3 {is also okay, but we prefer the text move as after a potential g2-g4 the g1 square is freed for the rook. Right now, our threat is to play Ng5 with a decisive attack. Black has some options and we'll examine them in turns.}) 11... h6 $6 {Black prevents our threat but unnecessarily weakens some vital kingside squares.} 12. Rc1 $3 ({This quiet move is actually a brilliant one with a very subtle point. After the natural} 12. g4 {Black has the amazing sequence} cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 $3 14. Bxd4 Bc5 $1 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 {when surprisingly Black's compensation for the piece is dangerous. Having witnessed that line, it makes sense to put a rook on c1 so we have the option of Rxc5! at the end of the above line. Furthermore, the bishop now has a safe square on b1, from where it can exert pressure on the b1-h7 diagonal, avoid the annoying Nb4 and not blocking the rook. Because this move is so deep and elegant, it deserves a double-exclamation mark from us.}) 12... Qd8 $1 ({Black realises the danger and prepares an exchange of queens with Qe8. If he plays a nonsense move like} 12... a6 {, we can execute the line mentioned in the annotations to 12.Rc1!! followed by Rxc5! at the end of the line, with a winning attack.}) 13. g4 {Breaking open the queenside.} Qe8 $1 ({Practically this is an only move, even though afterwards Black's position is still worse.} 13... fxg4 $2 {would lose to} 14. Qxg4 Rf7 15. Bg6 Qf8 {and now the clinical finish} 16. Ng5 $1 {opens the h-file with decisive effect.}) 14. Qxe8 {A pity that Her Majesty goes off the board, but our remaining pieces will do the job for her!} Rxe8 15. Rg1 Nf8 16. h5 $16 {The last accurate move needed to secure an advantage, seizing control of the g6 square. After the tension between the f5 and g4 pawns is removed, a hole on g6 will appear and the g7-pawn will be a pain for Black to defend. All in all, it's a challenging task for Black to defend this passive position with no counterplay.} *

