 position is a tough nut to crack. We recommend you to venture fearlessly with 13.Ng5! and Black must make a decision: B1 - 13...Bxg5?! 14.hxg5 is for sure unfavourable for Black due to the opening of the h-file: B11 - 14...cxd4?? is met by a cute trick 14.g6! Re7 15.gxh7+ Kh8 16.Qg5 +- and Black's busted B12 - 14...g6 is better, but the key detail is that we can blast opẹn the centre with 14.dxc5! and even though Black might try to win the crucial e5-pawn with 14...Qc7 15.Qe2 Nxe5 16.c4! unleashes the hidden energy of the Horwitz bishop, with a huge attack for White. Once again, the b2-bishop reminds us of the Stonewall one: sit behind a wall of pawns, defend them, and strike at the appropriate moment! B2 - 13...g6! is the accurate move-order, delaying the exchange of the g5-knight. B21 - 14.dxc5 is an option, but we don't like the look of White's position after 14...gxh5 15.cxb6 Rg7! and with the presence of the dark-squared bishop, Black has great pressure on White's position. B22 - 14.Qe2! is our preferred option, gambitting the d4-pawn for the sake of initiative. The line may continue 14...Bxg5 15.hxg5 cxd4 and now the engine likes taking on d4 followed by exchanging queens, but why don't we keep queens on the board with 16.Nf3!? dxc3 17.Rxc3? In the resulting position, White's compensation might be just slightly above sufficient objectively, but it's very hard to defend such a passive position for Black.}) 13. a3 $5 ({Preparing to meet ...a4 with b4, blocking the queenside altogether. In case you're interested,} 13. Ng5 $5 {is a more aggressive approach to be considered.}) 13... c4 $1 {The only way to exploit our last move - Black hits the vulnerable b3-pawn while we cannot play bxc4.} 14. Be2 {Let's just ignore the b3-pawn! Our point is that after the obvious} cxb3 {We have a key move which decides the doomed fate of the b3-pawn and allows us to resume our kingside attack.} 15. a4 $1 {Preventing ...a4 once and for all! Now it's clear that the b3-pawn is a lone soldier without defender, but we shouldn't rush to capture it immediately. Instead, we suggest you to use it as an 'umbrella', blocking the queenside while we focus on the opposite wing.} Nf8 16. Ng5 $13 Z0 ({White has a strong initiative for the cheap price of a pawn, and the fact that it's gonna drop soon makes our position even more attractive. Some sample lines run: A -} 16... g6 17. Qh6 Rg7 $1 {Black needs to avoid weakening the dark squares too much} 18. Bd1 $1 {we pick up the b3-pawn with a bright future. B - 16...Bxg5 17.hxg5 Ne7 solidifies Black's position to an extent, and now we should switch to playing slowly with 18.Ra1!? Neg6 19.g3 += when White has a stable advantage due to the bishop pair. Please note that White has the nice manoeuvre Ra3-b3 to round up the pawn.}) *

