1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 $1 {After exploring the alternative knight moves, we turn our attention to the most popular move in practice. We also attached an exclamation mark to this move, because it's simply the best move! The knight takes part in the central battle from d7, without worrying about the knight being trapped or inactive, as is the case with the knight moves examined earlier.} 5. d4 ({We are pleasantly surprised to see that this natural move, supporting the centre, is just the third most popular move. For some reason, people like to play} 5. f4 {and}) (5. Qg4 {more, but we hope this will change after the publication of this course. The text move is both stronger objectively and is more original. Oh, and we forgot to mention that several sources ignored this move, for example, Attacking Chess - The French by GM Simon Williams. Having said that, we have offered some brief coverage of the}) (5. f4 {line in the next chapter, as an alternative if you are interested.}) 5... c5 {Any moral French Defence supporters, like us, should know that this move is the best one - without looking at the database and/or engine. Black threatens to dismantle our proud centre with cxd4, so we should support it with another pawn.} 6. c3 {There is no sensible alternative - the pawn chain must be supported. As mentioned before, the Horwitz bishop's passive appearance is deceptive. It is indeed blocked behind a chain of pawns, but the Horwitz bishop is protecting these pawns from afar! Black's goal in the French structure is to destroy our pawn chain, so a bishop supporting it must be a plus for White.} Nc6 {Developing the knight towards the centre and adding more pressure on the d4-pawn.} 7. Bd3 $5 {Putting the bishop on the ideal square in this structure and paving the way for Ne2. We're surprised to see that this natural move is just the third most popular choice in databases, but it scores very well indeed. The chosen option is also not covered in Opening Repertoire: The French Defence by Cyrus Lakdawala as well as GM Vallejo's video series on Chess24. We're at the critical tabiya of the whole 3...Nf6 complex, and Black has several options to proceed. We will check them one by one.} Be7 {Black prepares castling and strikes in vintage French style with ...f6. Warning for the second player: in the lines which he castles, it wouldn't be strange if the king comes under fire!} 8. Nd2 $5 {Generally, we want to play Nd2 as soon as we develop the bishop to d3. The reason is that we want to have the option of Bb1 available in case Black hits our bishop with cxd4 followed by Nb4. Moreover, we can play Ndf3 in case the d4-pawn is severely attacked and this original concept has scored an 'ordinary' 100% in online games. Impressed? Play the Horwitz!} O-O {Black refrains from queenside action as seen previously. Instead, he castles kingside and waits to see what we can do. The second player clearly doesn't expect us to kick off the kingside attack immediately!} 9. h4 $5 {Huy the hacking pawn steps forward and initiates the first attacking wave. You might be thinking that such madness cannot be possible and we made the lines work ourselves, but no, this is engine-approved chess! Our pawn thrust, although a super rare guest in practice, has been tested for days with strong engines, so you can be assured of its soundness! In practice, we believe your opponent will be shocked and likely to commit a mistake at this point. Sure, the road to dynamic equality is there, but in all lines it's White who does the attacking, while Black occasionally needs to find several 'only moves' to survive.} Qb6 {We believe this is the best try for Black, countering a kingside offensive by playing in the centre. The d4-pawn is attacked, and we must do something...} 10. Qh5 $1 {We've burned the bridge, so we're forced to go forward! 9.Ne2?! (and 9.Nf3 ) would have allowed Black to dismantle our proud centre too easily with 9...f6! when it's White who struggles to get equality. The text move isn't subtle, and hopefully you see White's threat! From a positional standpoint, each of Black's options has its drawbacks. 10...g6 and 10...h6 create weaknesses which we can exploit, while 10...f5 blocks the centre altogether and allows us to build up our play on the kingside without worrying about ...f6 breaks. Of course, for concrete reasons, some options might be better than others, but we present these positional considerations for you to see that it's not 'easy' to prevent White's threat at all. In fact, it's quite the opposite!} f5 $1 {The correct reply, blocking our proud light-squared bishop. Black also reminds us that the threat to h7 is covered, leaving us to defend the d4-pawn. The main question is: how to do so?} 11. Ngf3 (11. Ndf3 {is also okay, but we prefer the text move as after a potential g2-g4 the g1 square is freed for the rook. Right now, our threat is to play Ng5 with a decisive attack. Black has some options and we'll examine them in turns.}) 11... Rd8 $1 12. g4 $1 ({Welcome to the world of inhuman chess! This move is the strongest one, yet it's so unnatural that we don't think any human opponent of yours will dare playing it. The cool point (of course discovered by the engines) is} 12. Ng5 {can be calmly met by} Nf8 $1 13. Qf7+ Kh8 $1 {when amazingly, White's attack looks stronger than it is and with some simple developing moves like Bd7, Rac8 and stuff like that, White has no attack. Of course, it's easier claiming that behind a computer than proving that in practice.}) {It's our turn, and we exploit the fact that the f-file is lacking the defender to storm the kingside! Even though the engine rates this as an 'equal' position, any sensible human understands that White's position is a lot more dangerous.} 12... Nf8 ({Black must defend precisely and drop the knight back to f8 to protect the f5-pawn.} 12... fxg4 $2 13. Qxh7+ {would be a huge disappointment for Black.}) 13. O-O-O $5 {There are other approaches to increase the pressure, but again we like this concrete one, bringing the rook over to the heat of the battle.} cxd4 $1 ({Black takes the chance to grab our pawn, as now we cannot recapture due to the idea of Nb4. Note that} 13... Qc7 {can be met by} 14. Kb1 $1 {, safeguarding our king.}) 14. gxf5 ({We've gone too far to come back now, and the only way is to go forward! Of course,} 14. cxd4 $2 Nb4 $1 {-+ would be winning for Black due to the threats of Nxd3, Qc6+ and Nxa2+}) 14... exf5 $1 ({As we're threatening to play f6! to open the kingside further, Black must recapture the pawn. If he plays something like} 14... dxc3 $2 {,} 15. f6 $1 {is the game-winner as after} cxb2+ 16. Kb1 $1 {Black is utterly helpless against the threats of fxg7 and Rhg1.}) 15. Kb1 $5 ({We take a tempi and even sacrifice a pawn to get our king out of the dangerous c-file. The engine also suggests} 15. Nxd4 $5 Nxe5 16. Bxf5 {as playable for White, but with the black queen exerting pressure along the 6th rank White's attacking power is clearly diminished compared to the main line.}) 15... dxc3 16. Bxc3 Nb4 $1 {The best chance for Black is go hunting the bishop and force us to react concretely! If he plays something slowly like 15...Bd7 , then White can just play Rhg1 and/or Bxf5 with a pleasant position due to Black's vulnerable king.} 17. Rhg1 $1 {An amazing, cool, yet effective idea! Our threat is none other than Rxg7+, and it's so dangerous that Black cannot afford to take the bishop without getting mated afterwards.} g6 $1 ({As we mentioned,} 17... Nxd3 $2 {invites} 18. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 19. e6+ {where Black should count themselves lucky if they survive for much longer. The text move avoids the Rxg7+ trick, but our attack isn't over yet by any means.}) 18. Qh6 {White keeps the fire burning and insists on sacrificing the d3-pawn. The point is that we want to play e6 after which the threat of Qg7# is very awkward to meet.} Nxd3 {Black must take the bishop as otherwise, h4-h5 comes with great effect. And White wouldn't be even a piece down!} 19. e6 $13 ({A smashing blow, pushing the pawn forward to an empty square (which Black occupied on move 1) and threatening Qg7 with mate. The Horwitz bishop once again plays a starring role throughout the combination, which is a testament to its power. Fun fact: Both this chapter and the previous one ends with} 19. e6 $1 {, after which Black is holding by the skin of their teeth if they plays all the correct moves according to the engine, but it's an extremely hard task over the board. We feel sorry in case you're annoyed by seeing this sentence so many times, but we sincerely believe you should spend your time to appreciate the practical value of the Horwitz Attack instead. Here are some sample lines to end the chapter: A -} Nxe6 $2 {is far too meek, and White crashes through after} 20. Rxg6+ $1 hxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kf8 22. Rg1 {+- with a winning attack. B - 19...d4! is the correct defence, temporarily blocking the long diagonal. As 20.Bxd4? is met by 20...Rxd4! , we should capture the pawn with the knight 20.Nxd4 and now: B1 - 20...Rxd4? is a typical reaction to swap off our attacking pieces, but we have the cute trick 21.Nc4! ready when it turns out that the d4-rook is pinned due to the threat of Qg7#. For that reason, we're ready to capture the d3-knight next with an overwhelming material advantage. B2 - 20...Bxe6! seems to be the correct defence, getting rid of the thorn at e6. White has several 'discovered checks' with the knight, but the one we prefer is 21.Nc6!? threatening both mate and the g7-pawn. The reason we like it so much is that Black's only way to get out of the trouble is not easy to find at all: 21...Bf6! 22.Bxf6 Rd7! and Black manages to take care of the g7 square. Still, we prefer White's chances in the bloody middlegame after 23.h5! as plenty of sacrifices on g6 are coming. That's it! We have made it through the Closed Horwitz section of the book - though we have one last treat for you after this - and it's time to take stock. Our principled recommendation is 4. e5, even though the 'Dub Dub' Gambit 4. d3!? is covered in some detail. We are confident that our recommendations against each of the knight moves are both original and pack a punch. In short, you should feel more than lucky if your (unprepared, we assume) opponents reach their hand out to the knight on move 3!}) *

