1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 $5 ({White's idea is not to make a huge centre with d2-d4 and c2-c3. Instead, White wants to get the queen out with Qg4 before continuing development with Nf3. The} 5. f4 {variation is highly venomous and unconventional. White has scored over 60% in practice and there is a lot of danger for Black everywhere. Let's take a look!}) 5... c5 6. Qg4 {The entire point of this variation is to mount immediate pressure on Black's kingside. White's queen eyes the g7-square and prevents the development of Black's kingside pieces. Black will have to commit to some weakening move in order to develop the f8-bishop.} Nc6 7. Nf3 {This is the tabiya (the key starting position) of the 5. f4 variation. White's basic scheme of development is Be2 and O-O, with eyes on the f5 break. The b1-knight can try to invade Black's position with Nc3/a3, which will force ...a6, to avoid the knight landing on b5 and d6. The other rook will come into play with Rae1 and that is White's ideal harmonious setup. Black has tried many moves in this position. We'll see how White's plan can be carried out, as well as some typical tricks and quick finishes in this line.} h5 {Annoyed with the presence of our queen, Black kicks it back right away.} 8. Qh3 $5 (8. Qg3 {is another good choice. On h3 the queen cannot be harassed anymore and keeps an eye on the e6 and h5 pawns.}) 8... Be7 9. Be2 {Preparing kingside castling. Black is unable to castle due to the hanging h5-pawn.} a6 10. O-O b5 11. Nc3 {Activating the knight and preparing to bring the rook into play with Rae1. Tactical ideas like f5 and Nxd5 are looming over Black's position. White can also consider a2-a4 to provoke ...b4, then transfer the knight to e3 via d1.} *

