1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 $5 ({White's idea is not to make a huge centre with d2-d4 and c2-c3. Instead, White wants to get the queen out with Qg4 before continuing development with Nf3. The} 5. f4 {variation is highly venomous and unconventional. White has scored over 60% in practice and there is a lot of danger for Black everywhere. Let's take a look!}) 5... c5 6. Qg4 {The entire point of this variation is to mount immediate pressure on Black's kingside. White's queen eyes the g7-square and prevents the development of Black's kingside pieces. Black will have to commit to some weakening move in order to develop the f8-bishop.} Nc6 7. Nf3 {This is the tabiya (the key starting position) of the 5. f4 variation. White's basic scheme of development is Be2 and O-O, with eyes on the f5 break. The b1-knight can try to invade Black's position with Nc3/a3, which will force ...a6, to avoid the knight landing on b5 and d6. The other rook will come into play with Rae1 and that is White's ideal harmonious setup. Black has tried many moves in this position. We'll see how White's plan can be carried out, as well as some typical tricks and quick finishes in this line.} a6 8. Be2 {O-O is coming next.} b5 9. O-O {A typical position for this line. Black has expanded on the queenside, but has not yet managed to mobilise his kingside. Let's take a look at a sample variation.} g6 (9... Nb6 {can suddenly be met with} 10. d4 $1 c4 11. Nbd2 {with very promising chances for White on the kingside. Rf2 followed by Nf1-e3 is a strong idea. The text move prepares the development of Black's dark-squared bishop.}) 10. Nc3 Bg7 11. a4 $1 {A nice positional idea we have talked about. White wants to install the knight on e3, but Black has the annoying ...d4. By inserting a4 and ...b4, White makes sure that ...d4 would give White the c4 outpost.} b4 12. Nd1 a5 13. Ne3 {The knight has reached its ideal place and f4-f5 is the killer threat.} *

