1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 $5 ({White's idea is not to make a huge centre with d2-d4 and c2-c3. Instead, White wants to get the queen out with Qg4 before continuing development with Nf3. The} 5. f4 {variation is highly venomous and unconventional. White has scored over 60% in practice and there is a lot of danger for Black everywhere. Let's take a look!}) 5... c5 6. Qg4 {The entire point of this variation is to mount immediate pressure on Black's kingside. White's queen eyes the g7-square and prevents the development of Black's kingside pieces. Black will have to commit to some weakening move in order to develop the f8-bishop.} Nc6 7. Nf3 {This is the tabiya (the key starting position) of the 5. f4 variation. White's basic scheme of development is Be2 and O-O, with eyes on the f5 break. The b1-knight can try to invade Black's position with Nc3/a3, which will force ...a6, to avoid the knight landing on b5 and d6. The other rook will come into play with Rae1 and that is White's ideal harmonious setup. Black has tried many moves in this position. We'll see how White's plan can be carried out, as well as some typical tricks and quick finishes in this line.} Qc7 {We shall take a look at a blitz game where Black, a 2500 grandmaster, showed little understanding of this structure and was lost after a mere 10 moves.} 8. Be2 a5 $2 {Black chronically and fatally weakens the b5 square - the dream jumping base for White's knight.} 9. a4 b6 10. Na3 {The knight is ready to hop onto b5.} Ba6 11. Bxa6 Rxa6 12. Nb5 Qb8 13. Nd6+ ({proved sufficient for a decisive advantage.} 13. f5 $1 {would have been crushing right away.} Ncxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qh5 {fxe6 is on the way and Black's position collapses.}) 13... Bxd6 14. Qxg7 Rf8 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. O-O {1-0 (55) Mastrovasilis, D (2582) - Stupak, K (2588) Katowice 2017} *

