1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 $5 ({White's idea is not to make a huge centre with d2-d4 and c2-c3. Instead, White wants to get the queen out with Qg4 before continuing development with Nf3. The} 5. f4 {variation is highly venomous and unconventional. White has scored over 60% in practice and there is a lot of danger for Black everywhere. Let's take a look!}) 5... c5 6. Qg4 {The entire point of this variation is to mount immediate pressure on Black's kingside. White's queen eyes the g7-square and prevents the development of Black's kingside pieces. Black will have to commit to some weakening move in order to develop the f8-bishop.} Nc6 7. Nf3 {This is the tabiya (the key starting position) of the 5. f4 variation. White's basic scheme of development is Be2 and O-O, with eyes on the f5 break. The b1-knight can try to invade Black's position with Nc3/a3, which will force ...a6, to avoid the knight landing on b5 and d6. The other rook will come into play with Rae1 and that is White's ideal harmonious setup. Black has tried many moves in this position. We'll see how White's plan can be carried out, as well as some typical tricks and quick finishes in this line.} g6 8. h4 ({Black takes time to safeguard his g-pawn. Now he can develop the dark-squared bishop. This is the most popular move in this position. Before examining our proposed} 8. Be2 {, we would like to draw your attention to an alternative.}) {The Internet's Chess Teacher and famous Youtuber Levy Rozman aka Gothamchess played like this against Tania Sachdev. White does not hide his intentions: h4-h5 is coming. 8. Na3!? en route to b5 and d6 is another option. If Black plays ( 8...a6 White can build a pawn centre with 9.c3 and Nc2-d4.} 8... h5 9. Qg3 Bg7 10. Ng5 Qe7 11. Nc3 b6 12. Nb5 $16 {The horse is about to become an 'octopus' on the d6 square. White won quickly in Rozman, L (2343)-Sachdev, T (2392) Chess.com INT 2020} *

