1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 $5 ({White's idea is not to make a huge centre with d2-d4 and c2-c3. Instead, White wants to get the queen out with Qg4 before continuing development with Nf3. The} 5. f4 {variation is highly venomous and unconventional. White has scored over 60% in practice and there is a lot of danger for Black everywhere. Let's take a look!}) 5... c5 6. Qg4 {The entire point of this variation is to mount immediate pressure on Black's kingside. White's queen eyes the g7-square and prevents the development of Black's kingside pieces. Black will have to commit to some weakening move in order to develop the f8-bishop.} Nc6 7. Nf3 {This is the tabiya (the key starting position) of the 5. f4 variation. White's basic scheme of development is Be2 and O-O, with eyes on the f5 break. The b1-knight can try to invade Black's position with Nc3/a3, which will force ...a6, to avoid the knight landing on b5 and d6. The other rook will come into play with Rae1 and that is White's ideal harmonious setup. Black has tried many moves in this position. We'll see how White's plan can be carried out, as well as some typical tricks and quick finishes in this line.} g6 8. Be2 ({Black takes time to safeguard his g-pawn. Now he can develop the dark-squared bishop. This is the most popular move in this position. Having examined the} 8. h4 {alternative, we will now cover our proposal of}) (8. Be2 {.}) {Going down the usual path. Black faces a choice now: should the bishop be developed to e7 or g7? We will check both moves.} 8... Bg7 9. O-O ({With the bishop no longer controlling the d6 square, again,} 9. Na3 $5 {is worth considering.}) 9... O-O {Now comes the key idea to attack Black's castled king.} 10. h4 $1 {Surprising (?!) and effective! Nowadays an advance of the flank pawn is a thematic idea against a fianchettoed bishop.} h5 ({Blocking the h-pawn right away is sensible. Passive defence with something like} 10... Re8 11. h5 Nf8 {is dubious. White just plays} 12. Nc3 {threatening Nb5-d6, as well as Nd1-e3-g4 (after the queen retreats to h3). Black's position is full of holes. After}) (10... h5 {, Black's kingside is temporarily blockaded. However, it will not last long.}) 11. Qh3 {Making the way for the g-pawn to move forward, ripping open Black's kingside barriers. Thanks to the space advantage created by the e5-pawn, White has a much easier time manoeuvring pieces to orchestrate an attack on Black's king. Conclusion: The 5. f4 line is venomous and scores incredibly for White in practice. You may wish to add it as a weapon to your arsenal of armoury. Our main recommendation is 5. d4, which we have already covered in the previous chapter.} *

