{Against the Horwitz Attack, the mainline is undoubtedly 2...d5 3. Bb2 and accepting the gambit with 3...dxe4. Its popularity is followed by the 'French' move 3...Nf6. However, once in a while, perhaps even thrice in a while, you'll face something other than the two big lines described above. Generally, most French players have no clue about the theory and go their own way early. All of the second players' attempts to escape the mainlines will be covered in the following three chapters: Giri's 3...Nc6, 3rd move deviations and 2nd move deviations. This overview shall act as a guide before diving into the theoretical oceans!} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 {If you've gone this far, no explanation is needed anymore for 2. b3! It suffices to say that we cover five different ways Black can try to combat White's idea of Bb2: - 2...d5 is of course the mainline - 2...Qf6, 2... Nf6, 2...c5 and 2...b6 are covered in this chapter [/course/82991/9]. Just like vanilla and strawberry ice creams, each of them has a completely different flavour. You will face 2...c5 and 2...b6 quite regularly according to the statistics, so we recommend that you spend the majority of your reviewing time on these two moves.} d5 {We fail to challenge the centre in the classical style (with pawns) and do it the hypermodern way instead. On his turn, Black takes a foothold in the centre and attacks our e4-pawn.} (2... b6 {The Copycat variation, championed by John Watson in his legendary book 'Play the French', a should-have manual for aspiring French players. Black wants to prove that our e4-pawn is a liability by hitting it with Bb7.} 3. Bb2 Bb7 4. Nc3 {Defending the e4-pawn. White has many promising plans here at our disposal: d4 (grabbing the centre), Qf3 (preparing queenside castling) and even g4-g5 is an idea in some lines. We don't think Black is able to equalize here and prove it with detailed coverage of 2...b6 starting here [/variation/22844363].}) (2... c5 {Black grabs his share in the centre and offers White a transposition to a trendy Anti-Sicilian with 3. Nf3. We believe that objectively, 3. Nf3 is the best move; but it wouldn't be wise for us to transpose into a theoretical branch of the Sicilian, which is well-explored already.} 3. Bb2 {In this repertoire we aim to keep play in independent paths. Just in case you play the 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 line against the Sicilian and would like to transpose, we endorse Adhiban's 1. e4 repertoire which covers this line. After 3. Bb2, it's worth mentioning that 3...d5 transposes to 2...d5 3. Bb2 c5, which is covered in the 3rd move deviations chapter. Black's most popular move here is 3...Nc6, when our novel idea of 4. Bb5!? avoids the Sicilian at all cost and sets Black a strategic problem of Bxc6. You can study the 2...c5 variation in a set of lines starting here [/variation/22844368].}) 3. Bb2 {Offering a ferocious gambit. You can find more details explaining the move 3. Bb2 in the introduction. This is the second critical tabiya of the Horwitz Attack and we cover many moves for Black at this point.} Nc6 {PAY ATTENTION PLEASE! 3...Nc6 is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri (that famous Chessable author, Twitter chess king and top 10 grandmaster) in his Lifetime Repertoires: French Defence. The move is quickly picked up around the globe and it's recommended in two more sources recently: Edouard's 'Play the French' series on Chess24 and Krykun's 'The Unexplored French Defence' Chessable course. Black's idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. Giri devoted 4 lines to 2. b3 compared to our 33-lines chapter against 3...Nc6. While you may argue that quality trumps quantity, we have an exciting novelty in store to pass the ball back in Black's court.} (3... d4 {Black is combining light squares with dark squares strategy, but the effects aren't as great as when Chess.com buys the Play Magnus Group. The text move is the fourth most popular move according to the ChessBase Database and the Lichess Database as well. Black's idea is to restrict our Horwitz bishop and the game often revolves around the d4-pawn. We'll attempt to undermine it to open the long diagonal for the b2-bishop, while Black will hold on to his centre for as long as possible. Our primary resources in this line to attack the d4-pawn are Nf3, c3 and Bb5 (to pin the knight coming to c6). The 3...d4 line receives detailed coverage in a set of lines starting with this one [/variation/18434593].} 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 $1 {is the right way to undermine Black's centre and we believe White has the better chances here. In the model games section, you can find the classical game Banh Gia Huy - Nguyen Gia Khanh annotated. Black went down surprisingly quickly and resigned after just 11 moves!}) (3... a6 {A strange move to say the least, but it has been employed by several French masters such as Atalik, Bluebaum and Meier. Moreover, it's mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black' as well as being recommended by Kryakvin in his recent French repertoire for Chess Stars. What's the idea behind this little pawn move? Well, it's purely prophylaxis against Bb5, which is often an annoying resource. However, the drawback is that if we open up the position with the lines we recommend, the move a7-a6 seems to be at least partially wasted. Statistics claim that 3...a6 isn't a popular move - you can expect to meet it in less than 1% of your games! However, it's theoretically relevant and objectively White has nothing more than equality.} 4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Anyhow, we'd argue that White's lead in development causes Black some problems. It's a strategically rich middlegame ahead: we'll fianchetto with g3+Bg2, O-O and just play the position! In case Black hits with 5...c5 as in a game of Magnus Carlsen, White can even play 6. d4! with the initiaitve.}) (3... c5 {A decently popular move at the master as well as amateur level. Black combines the French with the Sicilian and ambitiously grabs space in the centre. He is preparing d4 to steamroll our Horwitz bishop. However, a clear drawback of this move is that it fails to develop any piece. Black's thrust is also premature in the sense that the strong Bb5+ resource is now available as Black can no longer play ...c6. Stats confirm that you will face this move on a regular basis. Be prepared!} 4. exd5 {The most logical move. We're preventing Black from expanding with ...d4 while eliminating the possibility of dxe4. It's not that we're bored of offering gambits though! White has a development lead, so it's a principled decision to open up the centre.} exd5 5. Nf3 {White has a pleasant game here and Black should be careful to finish development smoothly. Our chief idea is Bb5+ followed by O-O and Re1+, when sometimes Black even struggles to castle. Another annoying idea is Qe2+ which often leaves Black short of a good reply. We should note that 5...a6 to prevent Bb5+ would transpose to 3...a6 coverage.}) 4. e5 $1 {There are not many useful moves for White as Giri mentioned: 4. Nc3 is met by 4...d4! and the knight must move again, while 4. exd5 exd5 is covered here [/variation/17615905] as a dry alternative. 4. e5! is much more ambitious, gaining space in the centre. The e5-pawn does block the scope of the Horwitz bishop as in 3...Nf6 lines, but things are not that simple. If allowed to play d2-d4, White's pawn chain will be much more secure than usual with the help of the b2-bishop. Furthermore, the c6-knight prevents Black from generating counterplay with c7-c5. It's no surprise that Black's best move here is} d4 $1 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his French repertoire. Black limits the range of our b2-bishop further and saddles it as a bad piece, at least for now. The e5-pawn is under attack as well. 4...d4! is truly Black's strongest move according to our opinion and is the focus of our analysis. In the 3...Nc6 chapter you will find coverage of 4...Nge7 and 4...f6 as well.} 5. Nf3 {Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a plethora of ideas/plans to proceed now: 5...a6 to prevent the Bb5 jump, 5...Bc5 to defend the d4-pawn in advance and 5. ..Nge7 immediately to prepare ...Ng6. There are many subtle positional nuances in these closed positions and we believe we've done a good job of explaining the details. In this overview, we'll only look at Black's most direct approach - one that aims to refute our concept at the cost of violating one of the basic opening rules. One approach has Giri, and later Krykun, as supporters.} Qd5 $5 {A provocative and materialistic move. Black breaks the opening principle of not moving your queen out in the opening, but this 'principle' cannot be blindly followed nowadays, given the huge popularity of the Najdorf Poisoned Pawn, Scandi and such lines. On this occasion, Black is aiming for a direct goal: the important e5-pawn! A key question: how should we react? We provide two alternatives you can choose from. 6. Qe2 is the sane choice, addressing Black's threat at the cost of obstructing the bishop's development. Meanwhile, 6. Bc4!? is our main recommendation and a much more exciting way to proceed.} 6. Bc4 $5 {This is a gambit, given that 6.. .Qe4+ picks up the e5-pawn. For the central pawn, we enjoy a big lead in development since Black's c6-knight is likely to get exchanged and then the queen is Black's only developed piece. We're super excited to present you with the 6. Bc4 gambit here! Black can accept it or not, but if the second player accepts the challenge we're sure you're going to have lots of fun!} Qe4+ {Giri indicated that '6. Bc4 should be met with 6...Qe4+' with no clue for Black on how to proceed next. Meanwhile, it appears that IM Yuriy Krykun has neglected 6. Bc4 in his coverage of the Horwitz Attack.} 7. Be2 $13 {A clever backward move with the bishop. We're already in very fresh territory with almost no games played! Black has two directions here: 7...b6 and 7... Nxe5, both of them are covered extensively. We believe that the 6. Bc4 and 7. Be2 concept asks black players some difficult questions to solve if they want to follow Anish's footpaths. That's the end of the overview for early deviations except for 2...d5 3. Bb2 Nf6 and 3...dxe4. We wish you success in dealing with the early deviations!} *

