1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. exd5 $5 {In case you feel bored and not tempted to go for the critical challenge, this is the choice for you! A safe bail-out approach, going for a dry, symmetrical position.} exd5 5. Nf3 {The position is objectively equal, but certainly not devoid of life! Let's check how play may proceed.} Bg4 $5 ({An interesting way to unbalance the fight.} 5... Nf6 {is recommended by the engine, in which case you can simply continue with} 6. Be2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {followed by d3 and Nbd2. Our position isn't anything inspiring or active, but it is fully playable.}) 6. Be2 (6. Bb5 $5 Qe7+ 7. Kf1 {is a sophisticated alternative, but there's no need for such play here. Let's just develop our pieces!}) 6... Qd7 {Preparing long castling is the name of the game Black has been aiming for. The structure is certainly symmetrical, but as the kings will be on opposite wings we can look forward to a double-edged battle!} 7. h3 {Asking Black a useful question regarding his bishop.} Bh5 (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 {is fine for us with the bishop pair as an asset. The text move is more ambitious and now we suggest}) 8. d4 O-O-O 9. Nc3 $5 {Bringing our knight out actively (the idea is that the knight would replace the bishop with Ne2 in case Black captures on f3 and follows up with Re8+). Next up is castling when White has no problems.} Re8 10. Ne5 $13 Z0 ({Adding a little zest to the calm game. With all the pieces hanging around, it's clear that both sides can easily be frustrated by the complexities of this position. Here are some illustrative lines to remove your doubts: A)} 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Rxe5 $6 {is a tempting continuation, grabbing a free pawn. However, our master plan is revealed after} 12. Qd4 $1 {with a deadly double attack on the rook and the a7-pawn. Black is unable to stop both threats and therefore stands worse. Just remember to kick that bishop back with g2-g4 in case the pressure on e2 becomes too great! B) 10...Bxe2 seems to be a much more safe continuation. After 11.Nxe2 Nxe5 12.dxe5 we've reached an unbalanced middlegame with chances for both sides. Note how our Horwitz bishop has been activated on the long diagonal.}) *

