1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 {)} ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... Nge7 {Following the classical principles, Black moves his knight out first, allowing us to set up a central clamp.} 5. d4 $1 {Gaining space as well as restricting Black's pieces. As Black has committed to an early Nc6, the traditional c7-c5 break is no longer available at his disposal and as a result, f7-f6 will have to be played at some point. This is a psychological win for us, as we've predicted Black's strategy in advance.} Ng6 $6 {A typical strategy to undermine the e5-pawn with ...f6 to follow. However, in modern times, people have rarely chosen to put the knight on the passive g6 square, especially with the increasing popularity of AlphaZero's h4-h5 thrust.} 6. Nf3 {Ordinary development should give us a convincing advantage based on the extra space. The only method for Black to drum up counterplay is the f6 break, so we'll make sure that it won't cause mayhem in our camp.} Be7 7. Nbd2 {The knight is better placed on d2 as it allows the Horwitz bishop to keep an eye on the long diagonal.} O-O {Castling has been the main choice so far in online practice. However, the king is potentially vulnerable on the kingside, given our space advantage and the fact that we haven't committed our king's placement. Fasten your seatbelt, Harry the h-pawn (just crossed it, Huy the h-pawn instead!) is going to hit Black hard.} 8. h4 $1 f6 ({Huy rolls forward and threatens h4-h5, when the sad knight would have to corner itself on the pretty h8 square. Note that capturing on h4 with} 8... Nxh4 $4 {would be a gross blunder due to} 9. Nxh4 Bxh4 10. Qh5 $1 {and our power on the h-file has been demonstrated. Black is dead lost due to the trapped bishop.}) {What else? Black is desperate for counterplay. However, we'll shut him down right in the tracks and prove that he has weakened the centre.} 9. h5 Nh8 (9... Nf4 $2 10. g3 {would be a brutal fate for the knight, so Black did best to keep it in the corner. In a sense, everything Black has done with the knight manoeuvre is putting it on an even more passive square compared to where it starts (g8).}) 10. c4 $16 {A powerful central destroyer. Exploiting our nicely-placed army and Black's out-of-play knight, we blast the centre wide open. Black is close to busted here as almost every one of our pieces are developed. Clearly, Black's horses aren't happy while the French bishop is terribly passive within his own pawn chain. We are close to winning here and there's no doubt our position is the more pleasant to play.} *

