1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... Nge7 {Following the classical principles, Black moves his knight out first, allowing us to set up a central clamp.} 5. d4 $1 {Gaining space as well as restricting Black's pieces. As Black has committed to an early Nc6, the traditional c7-c5 break is no longer available at his disposal and as a result, f7-f6 will have to be played at some point. This is a psychological win for us, as we've predicted Black's strategy in advance.} Nf5 {A more sensible square for the knight where it hits the d4-pawn and cannot be chased away so easily.} 6. Nf3 {) We keep developing regardless. Our next moves will be simple: Bd3 and O-O. Black will be stuck with his inability to break with c7-c5 and we'll work to contain his remaining break.} Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O {It's all normal stuff from both sides and we have emerged from an opening with a decent position. Our space advantage is a handy asset and if Black doesn't do anything, we'll expand with a3, b4 and potentially c4.} Nb4 $5 (8... f6 $6 {is an inaccurate plan due to the idea} 9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Re1 $1) {and White has a positional edge due to our bind on e5. Note the effect the Horwitz bishop is bringing to the position, defending the all-important d4-pawn and controlling the e5 square from afar. The text move is the top suggestion of Stockfish at high depth, so we should consider it carefully. Black's idea is to play c5 then drop the knight back to c6 again.} 9. Be2 {We need to safeguard the bishop pair.} c5 {Black has successfully managed to bring some counterplay, but his plan costs some time, too. White has several ways to maintain an edge, but the one we like the most is} 10. dxc5 $5 {You might be asking, why are we voluntarily giving up a central pawn for a flank one? The reason is that after the inevitable recapture, we're going to win a few tempos with a3 followed by b4. Moreover, the scope of the Horwitz bishop is increased after the text move.} Bxc5 11. a3 Nc6 12. b4 $14 {This is the point behind our machinations. The bishop is kicked away and we'll coordinate our pieces with Nbd2, Bd3 and maybe Rc1. The long-term plan is to open up the centre with c4 and prepare a knight invasion into the sensitive d6 square. White is definitely for choice here with more space and a clear plan as outlined above.} *

