1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... f6 $5 {A tricky move that has proved to be troublesome to handle, especially in online play. When looking at it at first, we weren't convinced such an unusual concept can work but as it turns out, the text move is rather venomous and even with best play we need to settle for dynamic equality.} 5. Bb5 $1 {) The reason most people fall into trouble is that they aren't aware of this important move. We pin the Giri knight, thus indirectly strengthening our control of the e5 square. Next up is Nf3 when we will try to take control of the centre.} Bd7 6. Nf3 {Over-protecting the e5-pawn to prevent Nxe5 shenanigans. Right now,} Qe7 (6... Nxe5 $2 {would be a horrendous mistake due to} 7. Nxe5 Bxb5 8. Qh5+ $1 {and we win the house. Instead, two alternatives will be considered: 6...Qe7 and 6...Nh6 .}) {Black announces his intention to castle queenside and go for our king on the opposite wing. The battle is getting hot, so the value of every decision becomes significantly higher. Be careful when touching the kingside pawns!} 7. Ba3 $5 {There are other ideas for White but we think the text move is the safest, getting rid of Black's dark-squared bishop, a potentially dangerous piece. Afterwards, we'll try to obtain a secure grip on the e5 outpost.} Qf7 {A positive aspect of our last move is that Black's reply is forced.} 8. Bxf8 Qxf8 {Capturing with the king is much worse; in short, His Majesty wouldn't have any future on f8. After the text move, Black's threat is to play Nge7 to support the other knight. If we're forced to play Bxc6 and allow Black to recapture with the knight, it would be a strategic victory for the second player as the e5-pawn is loose, while the Dutch-like manoeuvre Be8-h5 will remove the defensive knight. Therefore, we should release the tension immediately.} 9. Bxc6 $1 {Forcing Black to capture with the bishop.} Bxc6 {Black's current threat is to play d4, blasting open the long diagonal and activating his French bishop. Once more, our best reaction is prophylaxis against Black's idea.} 10. d4 Ne7 {The battle will mainly revolve around the e5 square: Black tries to force us to occupy it with a pawn, while we'd like to maintain firm control with pieces. However, with opposite-sided castling on the agenda, it's not surprising that a pawn race is also about to begin.} 11. O-O O-O-O ({Black can try to delay castling and give us a clear target with something like} 11... Ng6 12. Re1 Qe7 {, but we have the simple} 13. Nc3 {followed by Ne2 and a4-a5 when it's hard to imagine Black's 'attack' would be able to succeed with the g6-knight blocking Garry the g-pawn and the a8-rook is unable to participate.}) 12. a4 {In our opinion, this is the most promising way to continue. We will systematically bring every piece into the attack with b4-b5, Nbd2-b3 and c3 to clear up the first two ranks. We should keep the queen on e2 for the safety of the centre, before the cannons join in with Rfb1. Of course, these are just some vague ideas and we all know chess is a game where both sides move, not just White. However, these are useful guidelines to follow.} *

