1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... f6 $5 {A tricky move that has proved to be troublesome to handle, especially in online play. When looking at it at first, we weren't convinced such an unusual concept can work but as it turns out, the text move is rather venomous and even with best play we need to settle for dynamic equality.} 5. Bb5 $1 {The reason most people fall into trouble is that they aren't aware of this important move. We pin the Giri knight, thus indirectly strengthening our control of the e5 square. Next up is Nf3 when we will try to take control of the centre.} Bd7 6. Nf3 Nh6 $5 ({Over-protecting the e5-pawn to prevent Nxe5 shenanigans. Right now,} 6... Nxe5 $2 {would be horrendous due to} 7. Nxe5 Bxb5 8. Qh5+ $1 {and we win the house. Instead, two alternatives will be considered: 6...Qe7 and 6...Nh6 .}) {Another creative way to bring the knight into the game. As the ever-powerful Horwitz bishop is shooting the f6-pawn, the knight cannot be brought to the game via e7. Therefore, h6 is a pretty natural route.} 7. Bxc6 $1 {Once more, Black's threat of Nxe5 is looming so we did best to hand over the bishop pair. However, it's not all doom and gloom for us with a strong outpost on e5. Moreover, the position is closed and it's debatable whether the bishop pair would help Black that much.} Bxc6 8. Qe2 $5 {The most flexible move, not committing our king's location just yet. Our threat is to play exf6 followed by Qxe6+, so Black should react immediately.} f5 ({Closing the position is the best try according to the engine, even though the more closed it is, the less Black's bishop pair is going to matter.} 8... Bd7 {is a sensible alternative but Black has wasted time with the bishop. We suggest the energetic} 9. c4 $1 dxc4 10. bxc4 {, opening up the position to exploit our development lead. d2-d4 will follow when it's a tough battle between our huge centre versus Black's bishop pair.}) 9. d4 {Limiting the scope of the French bishop even further. We have several plans to proceed from this point: the queen's knight may be re-routed via Nc3-e2-f4, the queen will slide to d2 for that. Meanwhile, a4 and h4 are useful moves to insert along the way, giving us even more space and preventing counterplay. In the long run, our handy space advantage provided by the e5-pawn is going to matter as Black will be forced to shuffle his pieces on the first three ranks.} Be7 10. Nc3 {Following the plan outlined earlier: Qd2 followed by Ne2-f4.} a5 $5 ({There isn't much to do while committing the king isn't in his favour, so Black lashes out with Ary the a-pawn.} 10... g5 $6 {might seem like a tempting try, but the flexibility of our king is revealed after} 11. O-O-O $1 {and with h4 to come, Black's kingside is nothing but weakened.}) 11. a4 $13 {Firmly stopping Black's counterplay in its tracks. We prefer White's plan in this position, especially with Ba3 ideas now available to get rid of the important dark-squared bishop and saddle Black with a tall pawn on c6. However, the position is objectively equal to the engine, so one shouldn't overestimate our chances.} *

