1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 {)} f6 $6 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {If Black wishes to break with f6, probably he has done it a move too late. We have proved a convincing advantage for White here; the remedy will be provided right now.} 6. Bb5 $1 {Pinning the Giri knight. Each of our developed pieces are working in harmony - the d4-pawn is under fire, as well as the c6-knight. Black is struggling to keep his centre together.} Bc5 {Protecting the d4-pawn. There are some alternatives, but none of them would save Black:} ({A} 6... Qd5 $2 {is simply horrible for Black following} 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. O-O {and White is close to winning. Black has been toying around with his queen while we've nearly finished development and the d4-pawn is hanging.}) ({B} 6... fxe5 $6 {is no better due to the simple} 7. Qe2 $1 {, protecting the b5-bishop as well as eyeing the e5-pawn. A sample sequence is} a6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Na3 $1 {when we'll follow up with Nxe5, Nc4 and O-O-O, with perfect coordination. Our knights would cut Black's position in two and the second player wouldn't survive for long with no developed piece.}) ({C} 6... Bd7 7. O-O Bc5 {would be a transposition to the main line.}) 7. O-O {Tucking our king away to safety and preparing Re1, which would hurt Black's poor king a lot. Another devious threat to look out for is b3-b4, driving the bishop away from the defence of the d4-pawn.} Bd7 8. Re1 $1 {Black is desperate to stop the simple threat of Bxc6 followed by exf6, winning a pawn.} a6 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. exf6 $16 Z0 ({We have got a large advantage with the e6-pawn hanging and Ne5 on the air. However, Black still has a few tricks we need to be aware of: A} 10... Qxf6 {should be punished with} 11. Ne5 $1 Bd5 12. Qh5+ $1 {with the tactical point of} g6 13. Nxg6 $1 {[%eval 0,0] followed by capturing the d5-bishop.}) (10... Nxf6 {is the most critical attempt when we should go for} 11. Rxe6+ Kf7 {and now the accurate} 12. Re1 $1 {secures us the upper hand with Ne5+ and d3-Nbd2 to follow. The important thing to remember is that we're a pawn up but Black has the temporary initiative, so we should be careful of a few moves to consolidate our extra material.}) *

