1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 a6 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Strangely enough, this move does have a point and is one of the top suggestions from the engine. As you have seen and will see, the d4-pawn is the crucial point of Black's whole strategy, as it restricts our Horwitz bishop. Our whole plan is usually all about undermining that annoying beast, with Bb5 being a useful idea, pinning the Giri knight and weakening Black's defence of d4. The text move is prophylaxis, preventing Bb5 tricks once and for all. Notably, the correspondence player Lars Milde has faced 3...Nc6 4.e5 d4 twice in his mission to make the Horwitz work. Both games were drawn, which signals that even against the toughest test from strong engines, our trusty Horwitz has proven its total soundness. Kudos to Lars for supporting our opening!} 6. Bd3 $1 {No problem, we're going to find another route for the bishop. Our threat is to play Be4 and renew the threat on Giri's horse. Moreover, c3 would be very strong, opening up further lines for our army.} g5 $5 ({Crazy Garry attempts to unsettle us by rolling itself down the board to create havoc in our camp. Given another move, Black would play g5-g4 and our knight is chased, the crucial e5-pawn is lost and it's nearly over. It's amazing, but modern engines have led to the discovery of many ideas that simply don't look good. If any of your opponents ever unleash} 6... g5 $5 {on you, rest assured that they have prepared this!}) 7. Be4 $1 g4 $5 ({In any case, we follow our plan and bring the bishop to a dangerous square. Bxc6+ is the threat when the d4-pawn would suffer. We'll examine two different moves Black can try:} 7... g4 {is pure madness while}) (7... Nge7 {looks more restrained and human.}) {Didn't we already refute this crazy stuff? Well, this is a purely computerish try and we don't think any of your opponents will go down this way, but we'll include a trainable line regardless.} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxd4 {We've won a fatty pawn and left Black with a crippled structure, but it's not all over, unfortunately.} c5 $1 {Kicking our active knight away and opening the way for the French bishop with Bb7.} 10. Ne2 Bb7 {Cowardly enough, Black has full compensation for the pawn from an objective point of view (you can ask us why but we simply can't make sense the evaluation). However, it's undebatable that White's position is easier to play with our development lead and healthier structure. We would like to propose a surprising but powerful gambit to radically change the nature of the position.} 11. d3 $1 {Clearing the d2 square to get the queen's knight in the game. The g2-pawn wouldn't matter so much as we'll gain a useful tempo on the bishop.} (11. O-O {looks more natural, but Black can simply play} Qd5 $1 12. f3 O-O-O {with a huge attack on our king. Mister Stockfish even demonstrated a clear edge for Black, so let's avoid stepping on that territory.}) 11... Bxg2 12. Rg1 $13 {As usual, 0.00 is Stockfish's favourite evaluation, but we view White's position as the easier one to play. After all, the bishop is hanging and Black will struggle the keep the far-advanced g4-pawn. We'll follow up with Rxg4 in case Black allows it followed by a rook lift to either c4 or a4. Nd2 is an idea as well, activating our queen's knight.} *

