 5. Nf3 a6 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Strangely enough, this move does have a point and is one of the top suggestions from the engine. As you have seen and will see, the d4-pawn is the crucial point of Black's whole strategy, as it restricts our Horwitz bishop. Our whole plan is usually all about undermining that annoying beast, with Bb5 being a useful idea, pinning the Giri knight and weakening Black's defence of d4. The text move is prophylaxis, preventing Bb5 tricks once and for all. Notably, the correspondence player Lars Milde has faced 3...Nc6 4.e5 d4 twice in his mission to make the Horwitz work. Both games were drawn, which signals that even against the toughest test from strong engines, our trusty Horwitz has proven its total soundness. Kudos to Lars for supporting our opening!} 6. Bd3 $1 {No problem, we're going to find another route for the bishop. Our threat is to play Be4 and renew the threat on Giri's horse. Moreover, c3 would be very strong, opening up further lines for our army.} g5 $5 ({Crazy Garry attempts to unsettle us by rolling itself down the board to create havoc in our camp. Given another move, Black would play g5-g4 and our knight is chased, the crucial e5-pawn is lost and it's nearly over. It's amazing, but modern engines have led to the discovery of many ideas that simply don't look good. If any of your opponents ever unleash} 6... g5 $5 {on you, rest assured that they have prepared this!}) 7. Be4 $1 Nge7 ({In any case, we follow our plan and bring the bishop to a dangerous square. Bxc6+ is the threat when the d4-pawn would suffer. We'll examine two different moves Black can try:} 7... g4 {is pure madness while}) (7... Nge7 {looks more restrained and human.}) {A much more sensible course of action. Instead of rushing Garry forward, Black calmly supports the e5-pawn and renews the threat of g5-f4. However, the text move does come with a defect: that is the hanging g5-pawn. Well, we will accept the generous offer, then.} 8. Nxg5 Nxe5 {This is Black's point, regaining the central pawn. There are several strategic features to be aware of in this position, so remember to treat the paragraph below with care! Our Horwitz bishop is blocked, so we should strive to open the long diagonal in the long term. With the exchange of the pawns, Black's kingside has been slightly weakened, a factor we should exploit before he steamrolls us in the centre. With the presence of our aggressive knight and bishop, it's natural that we should strike when the iron is still hot.} 9. Qh5 $5 {The most direct approach, bringing Her Majesty around to create all sorts of attacking ideas.} Bg7 10. f4 {Kicking the centralized knight back. Beware, black players, only a move will prevent an immediate disaster!} N5g6 $1 {In case, Black chooses another square for the knight, Qxf7# would spell the end of the game. Black's kingside fortress looks quite solid now, but our pieces are also well placed and we can just carry out our plans normally.} 11. g3 h6 12. Nf3 $13 {We have several plans available at our disposal: Next up is castling followed by Ne5, throwing ourselves at the weakened black kingside. Black has done a good job of restricting the Horwitz bishop on the long diagonal, but we can activate it with Ba3 when Black's kingside would be shaky. Engines were enthusiastic about Black's position at the start, but at high depth it was demonstrated that White is objectively fine.} *

