 5. Nf3 a6 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Strangely enough, this move does have a point and is one of the top suggestions from the engine. As you have seen and will see, the d4-pawn is the crucial point of Black's whole strategy, as it restricts our Horwitz bishop. Our whole plan is usually all about undermining that annoying beast, with Bb5 being a useful idea, pinning the Giri knight and weakening Black's defence of d4. The text move is prophylaxis, preventing Bb5 tricks once and for all. Notably, the correspondence player Lars Milde has faced 3...Nc6 4.e5 d4 twice in his mission to make the Horwitz work. Both games were drawn, which signals that even against the toughest test from strong engines, our trusty Horwitz has proven its total soundness. Kudos to Lars for supporting our opening!} 6. Bd3 $1 {No problem, we're going to find another route for the bishop. Our threat is to play Be4 and renew the threat on Giri's horse. Moreover, c3 would be very strong, opening up further lines for our army.} Nb4 {This is the continuation of the correspondence game Milde - Semmler and is probably the best way to justify Black's play. After taking away the b5-square from us, he chases our bishop for another time.} 7. Be4 {) Again, we move our bishop to the powerful e4 square, where it controls many squares. The d4-pawn is currently hanging and moreover, a2-a3 to kick the knight back is on the agenda.} f5 $1 {Semmler chose the most aggressive and testing continuation. Unfortunately, our bishop isn't given any respite. However, the text move is by no means the only option Black has:} ({A)} 7... c5 $2 {is natural enough, but Black's development surely hurts after spending two tempos with the knight and the rest with pawns. We can punish him strongly with} 8. c3 $1 {and Black is unable to avoid a decisive opening of the centre.}) ({B)} 7... d3 $5 {is surprisingly tricky and annoying to deal with. While we're alright from an objective point of view, dealing with this unorthodox thrust over the board is far from an easy mission, so our advice is to treat it with care. As Black's threats are looming on c2, the most accurate is} 8. Na3 $1 {and after} dxc2 {we shouldn't allow Black to penetrate the crucial d3-square with} 9. Qe2 $1 {and the fate of the far-advanced c2-pawn is decided. The greedy machine recommends Black to use the cheap tactic} c1=Q+ {(Yes, the pawn has made that far!)} 10. Rxc1 Nxa2 {to win a pawn, but we can simply go} 11. Rc4 $1 {with enormous compensation for the pawn. The Giri knight is terribly offside after eating an unhealthy meal on a2, while almost all of our pieces are working well with each other. Next up is Huy's time with h2-h4, gaining further kingside space and bringing the king's rook into the game.}) 8. exf6 {There is hardly anything better.} Nxf6 9. a3 $5 ({Our bishop is attacked once more, but there is no space for it to retreat now. However, we still have a pleasant choice between two equal alternatives:} 9. a3 {and}) (9. d3 {.}) ({After analysing both options for some time, we became convinced that Milde's choice is the best to get a playable and promising game.} 9. d3 $5 {- a novelty! - is also available, but we feel something has gone wrong with our position after} Nxe4 10. dxe4 c5 $1 {and Black obtains a grip over the centre. So, what's the idea of the text move? We're forcing Black to trade his knight for our bishop, which is being attacked anyway. Moreover, the d4-pawn would be under fire with the removal of one key defender.}) 9... Nxe4 ({Black accepts the offer.} 9... Nc6 $2 {is undesirable due to} 10. Bxc6+ $1 {followed by Nxd4, while}) (9... Nbd5 $5 {is a tricky idea, giving up the d4-pawn after} 10. Bxd5 exd5 11. Bxd4 {. Due to the bishop pair, Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, but it's still a tough mission for him to prove it over the board.}) 10. axb4 {Our b4-pawn proves rather handy in this situation: Black's c5 advance to support the d4-pawn is prevented. Therefore, we've achieved a minor opening success, as Black is unable to stop Nxd4, freeing our deadly Horwitz bishop.} Bxb4 11. Nxd4 $13 {Imbalances are the norm in this position. Black has the bishop pair as well as an active knight on e4, but they're compensated by the horrible French bishop and the broken structure. Our current threat is Qe2 followed by capturing the e6-pawn, so Black should be careful. Alright, after looking at this unbalanced middlegame for some time, Mr Stockfish delivered an ice-cold 0.00 evaluation. There are a lot of possibilities for both sides, but a tricky one to face is} Z0 (11... Nxf2 $5 12. Kxf2 Qh4+ {, with a dangerous attack for the piece. However, we can calmly play} 13. Ke2 $1 Qe4+ 14. Kf2 {when Black has nothing better than repeating with a perpetual, as} O-O+ 15. Nf3 {is completely winning for White.}) *

