1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Nge7 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Qe2 $1 ({The move chosen in the recent correspondence game Milde - Vaughan, which ended in another draw. Instead of bringing the knight out first, Black seeks to play Ng6 quickly.} 6. Bd3 {is no longer effective due to} Ng6 $1 {and we're not in time to defend the e5-pawn. Therefore, our play is more sophisticated compared to other lines. We recommend you pay special attention to this rare continuation!}) {The start of a fine plan! White realizes that castling kingside is way too time-consuming and protects the e5-pawn immediately with the queen. We plan to develop with the surprising Na3 next before breaking up the centre with c3. An artificial plan, but it works! Moreover, as far as we can see, no other alternative is giving White a sound position.} 6... Nf5 {The move played by the correspondence player James Vaughan surely deserves consideration. Black is trying to restrict us to the maximum. Therefore, we have to be accurate when developing the pieces.} 7. Na3 {We continue with the grand plan. As surprising as it is, we've managed to get all of the queenside pieces out of the way and castling will come next! There are several other plans available too: c3 to undermine the d4-pawn, g4 to kick the annoying knight back and Qc4 to open the way for the bishop.} a6 (7... Be7 {is a human alternative, in which case we recommend} 8. g4 $1 Nh4 9. Nxh4 {followed by Bg2 with a huge initiative. With the text move Black plays ambitiously, preparing b5 to bury our knight on the edge of the board. However, we can open a safe square for it immediately with}) 8. c3 $1 {And with the threat of Nc2! coming, Black's centre is clearly under pressure.} Bc5 $146 ({Vaughan chooses the accurate} 8... Bxa3 {to get rid of the knight, but let's check what happens in case Black wants to keep his bishop.}) 9. Nc2 {We continue with our plan. The pieces of the puzzles are beginning to fit: Qe4 will come next, increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn even further.} Ba7 10. Qe4 $1 {We have two threats: capturing on d4 with either knight and the hidden one: Bxa6, exploiting the overloaded b7-pawn! Therefore, Black's best bet is to release the central tension and enters a slightly worse endgame.} dxc3 11. dxc3 $14 Z0 ({White owns the upper hand due to our huge space advantage. Meanwhile, both of Black's bishops are inactive. Our threats include activating the Horwitz bishop with Ba3, Rd1 and g4, kicking the annoying knight back. In fact, Stockfish demonstrates a single way for Black to get out of this mess:} 11... Qd5 $1 12. Bd3 Qxe4+ 13. Bxe4 Bd7 {, with hopes of achieving equality in the long run. However, there is no reason we can't enjoy pressing after the simple} 14. Rd1 {followed by c4, Ke2 and h4-h5.}) *

