 5. Nf3 Nge7 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Qe2 $1 ({The move chosen in the recent correspondence game Milde - Vaughan, which ended in another draw. Instead of bringing the knight out first, Black seeks to play Ng6 quickly.} 6. Bd3 {is no longer effective due to} Ng6 $1 {and we're not in time to defend the e5-pawn. Therefore, our play is more sophisticated compared to other lines. We recommend you pay special attention to this rare continuation!}) {The start of a fine plan! White realizes that castling kingside is way too time-consuming and protects the e5-pawn immediately with the queen. We plan to develop with the surprising Na3 next before breaking up the centre with c3. An artificial plan, but it works! Moreover, as far as we can see, no other alternative is giving White a sound position.} 6... Nf5 {The move played by the correspondence player James Vaughan surely deserves consideration. Black is trying to restrict us to the maximum. Therefore, we have to be accurate when developing the pieces.} 7. Na3 {We continue with the grand plan. As surprising as it is, we've managed to get all of the queenside pieces out of the way and castling will come next! There are several other plans available too: c3 to undermine the d4-pawn, g4 to kick the annoying knight back and Qc4 to open the way for the bishop.} a6 (7... Be7 {is a human alternative, in which case we recommend} 8. g4 $1 Nh4 9. Nxh4 {followed by Bg2 with a huge initiative. With the text move Black plays ambitiously, preparing b5 to bury our knight on the edge of the board. However, we can open a safe square for it immediately with}) 8. c3 $1 {And with the threat of Nc2! coming, Black's centre is clearly under pressure.} Bxa3 {The correct choice, preventing our Nc2-Qe4 plan. However, it mustn't be an easy choice for Black players to allow us an uncontested dark-squared bishop and give up hopes of castling kingside.} 9. Bxa3 {)} b6 {The best way to proceed, preparing Bb7 and Qd7 to castle queenside. The middlegame is strategically complicated, with a lot of tiny details. We enjoy the bishop pair, but that's not so relevant in a closed position. Let us show you the continuation of Milde - Vaughan, a game with exceptionally high quality (as you can expect for correspondence).} 10. Qe4 {Centralizing the queen and threatening the Giri knight.} Bb7 11. O-O-O {It turns out that there is no good discovery with the knight for Black, so the best thing he can do is prioritise his development.} Qd7 12. Bd3 $13 {A complicated but objectively equal middlegame has taken shape in Lars Milde - James Vaughan, corr 2020. With the text move, we prepare to retreat the queen back to e2 to avoid harassment on the long diagonal. Followed by Rhe1, all of our pieces are beautifully placed, ready for a potential opening of the centre. It's no surprise that the game eventually ended peacefully.} *

