1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 {)} (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nb4 $5 {Reasoning that our bishop is vulnerable on d3, Black immediately go for it.} 7. Bb5+ (7. Be4 $2 {looks natural, but the thrust} f5 $1 {is extremely effective when compared to the 5...a6 6. Bd3 Nb4 line [/variation/17615913], as Black has played Bc5, which is much more useful than a6 would have been. Among the alternatives, we like the text move the most as it's very direct and limits Black's option. As retreating isn't an option, Black is forced to interfere with either the bishop or the pawn.}) 7... c6 {Attacking our bishop is certainly a valid option. However, there is no need for us to retreat just yet!} 8. a3 $1 {As our bishop is short of breathing space, we should give it away for the active Giri knight. Moreover, axb4 will hit the c5-bishop and as a consequence, release our Horwitz monster.} cxb5 ({If Black goes for} 8... Nd5 {instead, the strongest option we have is the paradoxical} 9. Bf1 $1 {and the idea is revealed: our bishop can no longer be chased on f1, while the d4-pawn is hanging. The text move is surely more natural: Black grabs the bishop pair, even at the cost of doubling his b-pawns.}) 9. axb4 Bxb4 (9... Bb6 {is a pleasing image: the b-file is full of pawns and pieces! However, we have the powerful} 10. Na3 $1 {available, threatening the b5-pawn. Afterwards, c3/c4 would follow, with a strong initiative for our side.}) 10. Nxd4 $14 Z0 ({The board has cleared up rapidly and it's time for some strategic discussions. The bishop pair is a long-term trump for Black, even though the French bishop is currently a modified, tall pawn. It's important to know that the initiative is on our side with a mobilized knight on d4. The b5-pawn is hanging while the typical French resource Qg4 is coming, hitting the g7-pawn and eyeing the bishop. Overall, White's advantage might not be much, but it's not easy to handle Black's position as we have no weakness. A sample line is} 10... Bd7 11. Nc3 {and we can follow the plans outlined above.}) *

