1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nb4 $5 {Reasoning that our bishop is vulnerable on d3, Black immediately go for it.} 7. Bb5+ (7. Be4 $2 {looks natural, but the thrust} f5 $1 {is extremely effective when compared to the 5...a6 6. Bd3 Nb4 line [/variation/17615913], as Black has played Bc5, which is much more useful than a6 would have been. Among the alternatives, we like the text move the most as it's very direct and limits Black's option. As retreating isn't an option, Black is forced to interfere with either the bishop or the pawn.}) 7... Bd7 ({After witnessing that Black gets nowhere with} 7... c6 {, it's time to check other alternatives. As neither retreating the knight nor Bongclouding the king are reasonable options, that leave the second player with one move - block the check with the bishop.}) 8. a3 $1 {We urge you to keep this in-between resource carefully in the memory bank! The idea is that we force an exchange of the b4-knight and in case it retreats, c6 isn't a good square anymore.} Bxb5 $1 ({Black has no good choice but to accept the challenge. In case your opponent goes down a different path, here is some information to be aware of: A)} 8... Nd5 $6 9. Qe2 $1 {is no good for Black, since the d4-pawn is hard to defend and our b5-bishop is fully protected. B)}) (8... Nc6 $2 {can be refuted instructively with} 9. b4 $1 Bb6 10. c4 $1 {and it turns out that Black's dark-squared bishop lacks breathing space. A logical sequence is} a6 11. Ba4 Nge7 12. O-O {with a huge positional advantage for White. Black lacks resources to attack the e5-pawn since Re1 is coming. Meanwhile, c4-c5 will bury the tall pawn on b6 for an infinite amount of time.}) 9. axb4 Bb6 (9... Bxb4 10. Nxd4 Be7 {would transpose to 7...c6, covered here. [/variation/17615916]}) 10. Na3 $1 {Another advantage of 8.a3 is shown: we gain a great square for the knight where it threatens the bishop and can be brought into the game via c3-Nc2 or Nc4.} Qd5 ({Centralizing the queen and defending the bishop. However,} 10... Bc6 {is a good alternative we must consider. The correct reaction is} 11. b5 Bd5 12. c4 $1 {, not giving the bishop a respite. Following} dxc3 13. dxc3 Ne7 14. O-O {, we reach an unbalanced but fundamentally equal position. It's true that Black is enjoying the bishop pair, but they might be a huge target to our ideas connected with c4-c5. We have doubled b-pawns, but they're cramping Black's position a lot. Our threat is to play Nd2 (preventing Bxf3) followed by c4, b4 and finally c5 to win the trapped bishop.}) 11. Nxb5 {Let's get rid of the bishop that is preventing us from castling.} Qxb5 12. c4 $1 {Not the first time you see this energetic resource as a crucial resource in White's position! Using the fact that the b4-pawn is poisoned and c4-c5 would be lethal, we force a central exchange that would ease our cramped position.} dxc3 ({Forced, as} 12... Qxb4 $4 13. Ba3 $1 Qa5 14. Bd6 $1 {is a resignable position for Black.}) 13. dxc3 {Black's position looks quite attractive at first, but appearances are deceptive. Black's queen is active on b5, but we can neutralize it easily with Qe2 since castling isn't mandatory in this position. The bishop is 'eyeing' the f2-pawn, but in fact it's a bad piece once the queens get off the board as c4-c5 is always a threat. We have a handy space advantage provided by the e5-pawn, which restricts Black's kingside development. The only defect in our position is the inactivity of the Horwitz bishop, but once c3-c4 is played it'll defend the key e5-pawn. To conclude, White can push for a small edge here due to our positional superiority and Black is the side trying to equalize.} Ne7 14. Qe2 $1 {The key resource. We swap off Black's most active piece and accelerate our own development.} c6 ({We believe that the text move is the most precise, delaying Qxe2+ which would connect our rooks.} 14... Qxe2+ {isn't exactly a mistake, but White has a pleasant edge following} 15. Kxe2 {+=.}) 15. Ra4 $1 (15. Qxb5 cxb5 {is a strange structure, but one which poses no problems for Black due to our c3 target. The text move is the most accurate: all of a sudden, c4 is coming to trap Black's queen. Hooray!}) 15... Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 {The endgame is objectively equal but it's certain there is a lot of play left. With so many pieces on the board, our queenside majority benefits us, with the open a-file to work on. We should make sure not to exchange many pieces, as that would saddle us with a poor structure long-term. We'll play c4 to prevent Nd5 before expanding on both sides with Raa1, Rhd1, g3 followed by h4-h5 and such ideas. Bd4 to weaken Black's defence of a7 and Ng5-e4 to jump into the tasty d6 square are also plans worth considering.} *

