1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Nd5 {Black prepares Nf4 to harass our bishop further. However, a drawback of the text move is that Black weakens the defence of the d4-pawn, which allows us to strike on it immediately.} 8. c3 {Our play so far in this variation has been both instructive and thematic: after making sure nothing bad could happen with e4, we turn our attention to dismantling Black's tower of strength on d4. True, the task isn't easy but oh, if we manage to open the long diagonal for the Horwitz bishop the reward can be so sweet!} Nf4 (8... dxc3 $6 {gives up the fight way too easily and White can claim an opening success with} 9. Nxc3 $1 {As the king's knight has committed to d5, we should capture with the knight.} Nf4 {avoids the trade but} 10. Be4 {leaves us with a huge positional advantage. Bxc6+ is a great threat in particular. The text move is surely more logical. Ignoring the tension, Black forces our bishop to move.}) 9. Be4 ({The right square for the bishop. It cannot be chased easily here, while the big threat of expanding on the queenside with b4-b5 and c4 is there.} 9. Bb5 $6 {is unplayable, this time due to} Bd7 $1 {and we'll be forced to hand over the bishop pair very soon.}) 9... O-O ({The most sensible course of action. Instead,} 9... d3 $6 {is too committal and we can punish it with} 10. Ba3 $1 {, exchanging the bishops and bringing our knight out. It turns out after} Bxa3 11. Nxa3 {that Black's threat of Ne2+ is stronger than the execution since we would face absolutely no problem against that lonely horse. On the agenda is Re1, Nc4 and g3, when the d3-pawn is bound to fall eventually.}) 10. b4 {We shouldn't release the tension on d4 just yet, since that would break our structure for nothing. Instead, our plan is to drive Black's pieces away from that crucial stronghold while bringing the other knight into play with Na3. Eventually, Black would be forced to release the tension. Smart strategy, that is!} dxc3 ({Black decides to release the tension immediately and accept a static disadvantage with less space. Black is worse anyhow, but we'll show you some alternatives: A)} 10... Be7 11. b5 {gives White a slight pull as the d4-pawn is weaker than ever. Na3-c2 will follow to force a reaction from Black. B)}) (10... Bb6 $2 {is a strategical blunder due to} 11. a4 $1 {and the bishop is nearly trapped.} a6 {is mandatory but} 12. Na3 {leaves White with a nagging positional advantage. Qb3 and Nc4 are coming, hunting down the bishop. Furthermore, a timely b4-b5 will crush the queenside.}) 11. dxc3 $1 {The correct recapture! From the outset, the game looks rather dull, since the structure is symmetrical. However, we have several positional advantages. Firstly, the bishop is attacked, so Black has to move it again. Secondly, our queenside structure is aggressive, ready to run over Black's position with b5 or c4-c5. Thirdly, our e5-pawn is restricting Black's pieces, most notably the sad French bishop.} Qxd1 $1 ({Practically forced as} 11... Be7 $2 12. Qc2 $1 {is depressing for Black. Because we have a huge space advantage, Black should prioritise the exchange of queens, as in the text.}) 12. Rxd1 Be7 $1 (12... Bb6 $2 {falls into a positional trap:} 13. a3 $1 {and all of a sudden, both of Black's bishops are dead. As long as we can maintain a grip on d4 and control of the d7 square, the fate of Black's bishop pair is decided. The text move is way more accurate: the bishop cannot be trapped on e7!}) 13. a3 $5 {White has a bunch of alternatives that keep an edge, but the text move is our preference. Our positional trumps aren't going to disappear themselves, so we take a tempo to strengthen the queenside. c4 is an idea now that the b4-pawn is safely defended.} Nd5 {A plan suggested by the engine is to bring the knight around to b6 with the idea of jumping into our light squares. However, this is surely time-consuming considering that Black has made 4 moves with the same knight so far.} 14. Nbd2 Nb6 15. Bc2 $14 {Once more, our motto in this position is: no need to rush! With the last two moves, we take control of the a4 and c4 square, thus rendering Black's tricky knight manoeuvre harmless. Once we've taken care of Black's counterplay, everything is safe and we can resume our plan of expanding. Next, we'll play c4, Bc3 to strengthen the queenside even further before starting a kingside initiative with h4-h5 and g4-g5. We have a nagging space advantage that isn't easy to deal with, as Stockfish confirms with its favourable evaluation for White. In practice, it's a nightmare for Black to suffer in such a passive position.} *

