1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Ng6 {A better square for the knight where it targets the e5-pawn. We cannot let it fall as it would leave Black with a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} a6 $5 {This is Stockfish's deep attempt at prophylaxis. Black prevents Bb5 in advance and thus indirectly overprotects the d4-pawn.} 9. c3 $1 {However, Black made no attempt to prevent the liberating c3 break and we should take the chance to free ourselves! If Black releases the tension we'd be reasonably happy and in case he avoids it, we'll force him into doing so with Be4, Ba3 or Na3-c2.} Nf4 {A possible way to create some complications.} 10. Be4 {The threat of Bxc6+ is lingering so Black must treat the position with care.} d3 $1 (10... O-O $6 {would be way too meek and White gains an advantage with the powerful} 11. Ba3 $1 {. The idea of this move is twofold: firstly, we remove a crucial defender of the d4-pawn and secondly, prepare to bring the knight into the game via a3. The text move is objectively the best and certainly a dangerous try. Black temporarily shuts down our Horwitz bishop, which is sitting like a tall pawn, to be honest. Moreover, the aggressive bishop and knight are hovering around our king. Don't despair my friend, we have several trumps in our favour too. The d3-pawn risks being a long-term weakness while the e4-bishop is incredibly active, at least compared to its counterpart on c8.}) 11. b4 (11. Bxc6+ {is the natural reaction, but we couldn't make it work after} bxc6 12. c4 g5 $1 {Out of nowhere, Black has whipped up a dangerous attack on the kingside and it'll be a tough job for us to survive. The absence of the light-squared bishop will be felt. The text move is the strongest blow, regaining the initiative by kicking Black's active bishop back. We have a lot of tactical ideas in this position, which will be shown via some sample lines: A) 11...Bb6? is met with the powerful 12.c4! and Black will suffer for a long time since c4-c5 will bury the bishop for a long long time. Note that 12...Nxb4?? is losing outright due to the pretty tactic 13.Qa4+! Nc6 14.Bxc6+ bxc6 15.c5! and all of a sudden, Black's underdevelopment is the reason behind his loss. The f4-knight is attacked as well as the bishop and Black loses a full piece. B) 11...Ba7 is better, but we still have the upper hand with 12.c4! . Our threat is Bxc6+ followed by c4-c5 when we'd be completely winning due to the extra piece. Once more, 12...Nxb4?! isn't working, this time due to 13.Qa4+ Nc6 14.Bxc6+ bxc6 15.Nc3! and Black's counterplay with Ne2+ has been prevented. Next, we'll play Ba3 to prevent castling and/or prepare c5 to bury the bishop once again.}) *

