 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Ng6 {A better square for the knight where it targets the e5-pawn. We cannot let it fall as it would leave Black with a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} a6 $5 {This is Stockfish's deep attempt at prophylaxis. Black prevents Bb5 in advance and thus indirectly overprotects the d4-pawn.} 9. c3 $1 {However, Black made no attempt to prevent the liberating c3 break and we should take the chance to free ourselves! If Black releases the tension we'd be reasonably happy and in case he avoids it, we'll force him into doing so with Be4, Ba3 or Na3-c2.} dxc3 {Seeing that the complications don't necessarily favour Black, it makes sense for him to bail out into an endgame that is fundamentally equal.} 10. dxc3 {Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, there is still chances for both sides to press here. Our huge positional threat is Qc2, avoiding the queen exchange which would leave us with a nagging positional advantage. Yes, Black can equalize, but he must find a precise move to achieve his goal concretely.} Nf4 $1 {Only this knight jump will do! The ladies are leaving the board soon, which would ease Black's defensive task considerably. As we mentioned, in case Black plays something else, just go for Qc2 and enjoy a crushing advantage!} 11. Bf1 (11. Be4 $5 {is another sensible try but we think the text move is the most solid. Indeed, if we're going to play for the win then our advantage should be revolved around the extra space, not development lead!}) 11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {White has an edge according to the engine, but if Black defends precisely they should hold without much trouble. Our plans include g3-Bg2 to prevent Black's fianchetto with b6-Bb7, c4 to free the Horwitz beast followed by jumping the knight into the dominant e4 square via either c3 or d2. Doubling on the d-file is certainly an option as well. To conclude, it's a draw but Black is the side working for it. In a practical game, we'd imagine all three results are possible with a bunch of pieces left on the board.} *

