h a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} f6 $5 {Black's strategy is consistent, critical and forcing. Right after we defend the e5-pawn, he attacks it once more for central dominance. However, the text move has a significant drawback: it weakens Black's kingside and opens the e-file for our rook.} 9. c3 $5 Ncxe5 ({Energetically blow the position wide open! We need great confidence to play like this since the consequence is potentially severe with the e5-pawn hanging. However, we've dug deep in this position and the concept seems to be working. As} 9... dxc3 $6 {allows us to insert the jarring check} 10. Bxg6+ hxg6 {before} 11. Nxc3 {with a harmonious position, Black has a choice between knight captures on e5.}) 10. Nxe5 fxe5 $5 ({As} 10... Nxe5 {would transpose to the next line [/variation/17615922], the only extra option Black has at his disposal is the text move. The second player has an extra pawn, but there's no doubt the structure is as ugly as it can get.}) 11. cxd4 {You might be tempted to capture on g6 right away, but please don't rush! Bxg6+ is a forcing option we can decide when to insert and we don't want to prematurely give up that bishop, right? The text move is best, opening the long diagonal and forcing a reaction from Black.} Bxd4 ({Are you able to spot the tactical refutation of} 11... exd4 $2 {It's} 12. Qh5 $1 {and Black cannot avoid the loss of a piece. Note how Black has opened the 5th rank for our queen to participate in the game.}) 12. Bxg6+ $1 {This is the right time to spoil Black's already miserable structure even further.} hxg6 {David Smerdon once coined the term 'Celeriac' for a variation that is visually ridiculous in his excellent work on the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian, Huy's favourite weapon in faster time controls. Black's pawn structure in this position isn't worth a celeriac in our opinion, so we'll take the chance to call it a 'blobfish', widely regarded as the ugliest creature in the world.} 13. Bxd4 {Another of Black's active pieces is removed - his remaining bishop is simply horrendous.} Qxd4 (13... exd4 $6 14. Qg4 $1 {would be tough for Black to deal with as Na3-c4-e5 is coming and the g6-pawn is a chronic weakness. At the very least, the text move covers the g4 square and attacks our rook.}) 14. Nc3 $13 {After the text move, we still have tremendous compensation for the pawn. The e5 and g6 pawns are long-term weaknesses that aren't going to disappear for the next twenty or thirty moves, giving us great chances to grind. Our great threat is to play Re4 followed by Qg4 and Rae1, achieving perfect coordination. Black must be very, very careful not to be left in a positional mess, despite the engine's 0.00 evaluation.} *

