1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Ng6 {A better square for the knight where it targets the e5-pawn. We cannot let it fall as it would leave Black with a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} f6 $5 {Black's strategy is consistent, critical and forcing. Right after we defend the e5-pawn, he attacks it once more for central dominance. However, the text move has a significant drawback: it weakens Black's kingside and opens the e-file for our rook.} 9. c3 $5 Ngxe5 ({Energetically blow the position wide open! We need great confidence to play like this since the consequence is potentially severe with the e5-pawn hanging. However, we've dug deep in this position and the concept seems to be working. As} 9... dxc3 $6 {allows us to insert the jarring check} 10. Bxg6+ hxg6 {before} 11. Nxc3 {with a harmonious position, Black has a choice between knight captures on e5.}) {Black sidesteps Bxg6+ ideas once and for all. However, the knight has left the kingside which leaves some weak spots behind.} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 ({Forced, as} 10... fxe5 $4 11. Qh5+ {followed by b4-b5 is a nightmare for Black.}) 11. Qh5+ {Exploiting Black's hanging pieces on the 5th rank and his vulnerable king, we include an annoying check, forcing Black's king to move, which is obviously not a nice thing you'd like to do every day.} Kf8 $1 (11... g6 $2 12. Bxg6+ $1 {is the point of our previous play. It's tough, but Black must accept the fact that both pieces that are technically capable of capturing the bishop are pinned. In short, His Majesty must move and f8 is the best square for it.}) 12. Bf1 $13 (12. Rxe5 $5 {is interesting and practical exchange sacrifice, but we doubt whether White would be able to retain equality with best play. The text move seems to be the most accurate, avoiding Black's obvious threat of Nxd3. Black is a pawn up while our queenside development is hampered, but the awkward placement of the king gives us full compensation for the pawn. If we get our pieces out quickly, Black will be destroyed, since he'd literally be playing a rook down. Our ideas include Na3, b4-b5 and a4 to target the dark-squared bishop.}) *

