 5. Nf3 Bc5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) {Another alternative to be considered. Black wants to play Nge7-g6 in order to attack the e5-pawn, but that would cage the g8-bishop. Therefore, he brings the bishop out first before developing the knight. We should be quick with defending e5, or else Black would be able to grab it easily.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5 $6 {is a tempting move to play, but it's not effective due to} Nge7 $1 {and Black has achieved dream coordination. Next, a6 would follow when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. A rule of thumb: be careful with Bb5 when Black can support the Giri horse with another knight!}) ({The text move's idea is twofold: We're preparing O-O followed by Re1, supporting the e6-pawn. At the same time, the bishop is rather useful on d3, making sure that a future c3 break cannot be met with ...d3. It's worth mentioning that at this point, after} 6. Bd3 {, f5 is the continuation advocated by Vallejo in his French Defence ebook on Chess24. We do not consider the continuation dangerous and we can simply follow our usual plans after 7.c3!}) 6... Nge7 {The most consistent continuation. Black prepares castle and Ng6, hitting the e5-pawn.} 7. O-O (7. Be4 $5 {is an unusual idea to prevent Ng6, but we prefer keeping things simple this time, especially since the text move gives White quite a promising game. Next, we'll combine fortifying the e5-pawn (Re1) and destroying Black's grip on d4 (c3). Black is at a crossroad: he can choose either to put a knight on d5 or g6. The closed nature of the position means that there are a lot of crossover ideas and transpositions, so don't worry in case your opponent uncorks something not covered in this course!}) 7... Ng6 {A better square for the knight where it targets the e5-pawn. We cannot let it fall as it would leave Black with a commanding centre. Therefore, let's defend that pawn once more.} 8. Re1 $1 {The first step of our grand plan is achieved: after bringing His Majesty to safety, we've put Black's counterplay on the e5-pawn under control. The next step is to break up Black's centre with c3, then our opening strategy would be a success! However, it's Black's turn and the first player has plenty of ways to try to combat our plan.} O-O {Simple chess, Black castles to see what we do before reacting to our plan. As easy as it seems, the text move proved to be a real nuisance to find something interesting against. After many hours of exhausting analysis, we have found a promising continuation for White.} 9. Ba3 $5 ({A switch of plans.} 9. c3 {is what we normally play here, but we couldn't make White's position work after the useful prophylaxis} a5 $5 {, although some other lines are satisfactory for White at least. However, if you're not tempted by the option we're recommending, then} 10. Na3 $5 {followed by Nc2 is the way to handle the}) (9. c3 {line. The text move aims to trade off our passive Horwitz bishop right away, instead of slowly undermining the d4-pawn with c3. A drawback is that Black will win some time with Bxa3, but the closed nature of the position gives us enough time to re-route the knight. As mentioned before, we concluded that}) (9. Ba3 {is the most promising try for White after a long analysis.}) 9... Bxa3 10. Nxa3 f5 $5 ({After the exchange, we should be reasonably happy with our position. c3 is coming to resume the battle about the d4-pawn, while the d3-bishop outweighs its counterpart. We'll examine two different ways for Black to handle this line: active mode with} 10... f5 $5 {or the calm}) (10... b6 {.}) {A concrete approach, gaining space on the kingside at the cost of potentially weakening Black's position.} 11. exf6 {) We shouldn't allow Black to occupy kingside space for free; thus, en passant is the way to go. On one hand, we've removed the bridgehead on e5 but on the other, the e5 square is now cleared for our knights.} gxf6 $1 (11... Qxf6 $2 {is a tragic positional blunder due to} 12. Bxg6 $1 {removing a defender of the dark squares} Qxg6 13. Nc4 {and White enjoys a crushing advantage with Ne5 to come. The light-squared bishop isn't getting out while Black's position is full of holes. The text move is better, covering the e5 square.}) 12. Nh4 $5 ({The most radical way of handling the position. White sacrifices a full (!) knight, but Qh5 is coming to add fuel to the fire. Our chosen option does allow a forced draw with best play, but it requires precision from the dark side, so please don't freak out just yet. We sincerely understand that a forced draw might not be what you wished for after all, so an alternative will be provided:} 12. Bxg6 $5 hxg6 13. c3 {with the idea of undermining the d4-pawn. However, we prefer Black's position slightly after the promising pawn sacrifice} e5 14. cxd4 Bg4 $1 {, with a huge initiative for the small material investment. We don't have enough trust in that line, but you may. Our job is to provide recommendations that we believe in ourselves and it would be a crime for us to do otherwise.}) 12... Nxh4 {There is no good alternative for Black since g6 was hanging.} 13. Qg4+ $1 ({This check is the thing to remember!} 13. Qh5 {looks natural enough, but Black parries both threats with} f5 $1 {and good luck surviving, being a piece down! The text move forces Black's knight back, after which we can force a perpetual.}) 13... Ng6 $1 ({The last chance for Black to play on realistically is} 13... Kh8 $2 {, even though we own an advantage after} 14. Qxh4 {. Mate is being threatened on h7 and we'll continue with Be4, Nc4/c3-Nc2 and setting up a kingside clamp with g3 and f4. We're objectively better according to the engine, so pocketing the draw is Black's best choice.}) 14. Bxg6 hxg6 (14... Kh8 $2 15. Qh4 $1 Qe7 16. Be4 {leads to an advantage with the white plans mentioned above.}) 15. Qxg6+ Kh8 {We may take the draw immediately with Qh6+ and so on, but let's try a final cheapo :)} 16. Re4 $5 {99% is that our opponents won't fall into Rh4+ and mate, but why shouldn't we show them our desire to fight and let them show off their defensive skill?} f5 {Opening the d8-h4 diagonal is crucial.} 17. Qh6+ {Take out your pen, sign the scoresheet, leave the board and enjoy yourself. The day has ended in under 20 moves, not the most exciting one, but a truth that modern chess is facing: the increase in early draws.} *

