1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Qe2 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {Another playable alternative as suggested by both Leela and Stockfish. It's indeed artificial to put our queen on e2, but if you're a fan of the e5-pawn and would like to protect it, the text move is mandatory.} 6... b6 {Giri's recommendation, with the comment that Black has got the happy queenside fianchetto. However, we have an interesting surprise in store.} 7. Qc4 $1 ({The tempting} 7. c4 $6 Qd7 $1 {=+ is favourable for Black, as both of our bishops are stuck. The text move removes Black's active queen and renders the d4-pawn a weakness.}) 7... Qxc4 8. Bxc4 {Our threat is clear: capturing the d4-pawn. Black's ...b6 might also be a weakening move with Bb5 as an idea for White. Therefore, the second player should create counterplay elsewhere.} Bb7 ({Black's idea is to get the g2-pawn in return for the d4-pawn. Instead,} 8... Bc5 9. a3 $1 {would give us a slight edge with b3-b4 as well as c2-c3 coming, breaking up the centre.}) 9. Nxd4 {The exchange isn't unfavourable for us since we'd get the central majority as well as the g-file for the rook. Moreover, the Horwitz bishop is released from the cage.} Nxd4 (9... Nxe5 $6 {is refuted by the pretty trick:} 10. Nxe6 $1 {and the e5-knight is hanging. Our chief point is} Nxc4 11. Nxg7+ $1 {followed by bxc4 with an extra pawn.}) 10. Bxd4 Bxg2 11. Rg1 (11. Bb5+ $5 {is also an idea, but the text move is the most straightforward. We reach a balanced and rich middlegame position, with lots of plans for both sides. For our part, we'll try to set the central majority in motion as well as exploit Black's lag in development. However, Black's structure is nicer, as our h2-pawn is a long-term weakness. Therefore, we should play directly, concretely and avoid exchanging too many pieces.}) 11... Bc6 $1 ({The most accurate square for the bishop. Against} 11... Bb7 {, we have a subtle manoeuvre ready:} 12. Bb5+ c6 13. Bd3 {and it 'looks' like we've just wasted a tempo. However, the whole idea behind the operation is that we've locked Black's bishop in a cage and Be4 is coming.}) 12. Be3 {Retreating the bishop to a secure square and putting the d-pawn in motion. Next, we'll continue with Nc3, perhaps inducing some weaknesses with a4-a5 as well as connecting the rooks with the Bongcloud move Ke2. We believe White has great chances here since Black has only developed one piece.} *

