1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 b6 $5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) ({An interesting and French-style positional move, preparing to fianchetto the bishop on the long diagonal. Compared to} 7... Nxe5 {, the structure is much more closed, with lengthy manoeuvring for both sides. However, the #1 advice is that you should be on the guard for concrete possibilities!}) 8. d3 $5 (8. O-O {is also recommended by the engine, but we think it's way less promising. The text move kicks the active queen back and gives the knight a square on d2. The drawback is that the e2-bishop is locked in, but you'll see later that we've prepared another juicy diagonal for it.}) 8... Qd5 (8... Qf5 $5 {is a surprising alternative, but it's so risky that we doubt your opponents would love to play it. The remedy is} 9. Nxd4 Qxe5 {and now} 10. f4 $1 {is the crucial detail, followed by Bf3 when we win the exchange. With some accurate moves, Stockfish proved Black has a perpetual somewhere in the line, but we believe 10.f4 is a good point to stop the memorization work. The text move retreats the queen to a safer square and therefore is the more human choice. Black has moved his queen three times but after our next move, it'll have to move for the fourth time...}) 9. c4 $5 {Radical, commital, but strong! We're betting on our development lead to kick Black's queen back and gain valuable time. Moreover, the d4-pawn will now be a target. The cost is that we've lost the possibility of c2-c3, so the Horwitz bishop might lack breathing space. Therefore, our plan is to undermine the d4-pawn in the near future.} dxc3 $5 {Black radically changes the pawn structure. We'll be left with a slightly weak d-pawn, but the opening of the position suits us much better with our superior development.} 10. Nxc3 {Of course, hitting the queen is our go-to choice.} Bb4 {Black tries to avoid the loss of the tempo by retreating the queen. However, the cost is that we enjoy the healthy bishop pair.} (10... Qd7 $5 {is perfectly viable as well and we suggest} 11. d4 Bb7 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Qc1 $1 {with an initiative on the queenside. Our ideas include Rd1 to solidify the centre as well as a3-b4 to gain further space.}) 11. Rc1 $5 (11. O-O Bxc3 12. Bxc3 {is also fine for White, but we aren't really satisfied with it since the Horwitz bishop isn't doing much on c3. Instead, our idea is to lift the rook along the 4th rank to create dangerous ideas along the c-file.}) 11... Bxc3+ (11... Nh6 $6 {is a try suggested by one of our Chessable friends, but} 12. d4 $1 {is simple and strong in this case. White is clearly better as Bc4 is coming and Black isn't in time to blockade the d5 square. Hence, we see that the correct placement for Black's knights in this line is c6 and e7.}) 12. Rxc3 Nge7 {Black prepares to drop the queen back, creating an outpost for the knight on d5. However, we have our play on the c-file as well as the bishop pair to compensate for it.} 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rc4 {The rook is a real powerhouse! With the text move, we open the long diagonal for the Horwitz bishop and put the rook at a reasonably safe square. White holds the initiative and it's tough handling Black's position.} Z0 (14... O-O-O $6 {is a natural move to consider, but in fact, it's a mistake to give us a clear target on the c-file. We should play} 15. Qc2 $1 {followed by Rfc1 with a powerful battery and a better position. If} Ba6 {we have the resource} 16. Ng5 $1 Bxc4 17. bxc4 {the only recapture which works because if 17.dxc4 Black has 17...Qd2 . After 17.bxc4 Qa5 we win back the exchange + interest with 18.Nxf7 .}) *

