ly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) ({An interesting and French-style positional move, preparing to fianchetto the bishop on the long diagonal. Compared to} 7... Nxe5 {, the structure is much more closed, with lengthy manoeuvring for both sides. However, the #1 advice is that you should be on the guard for concrete possibilities!}) 8. d3 $5 (8. O-O {is also recommended by the engine, but we think it's way less promising. The text move kicks the active queen back and gives the knight a square on d2. The drawback is that the e2-bishop is locked in, but you'll see later that we've prepared another juicy diagonal for it.}) 8... Qd5 (8... Qf5 $5 {is a surprising alternative, but it's so risky that we doubt your opponents would love to play it. The remedy is} 9. Nxd4 Qxe5 {and now} 10. f4 $1 {is the crucial detail, followed by Bf3 when we win the exchange. With some accurate moves, Stockfish proved Black has a perpetual somewhere in the line, but we believe 10.f4 is a good point to stop the memorization work. The text move retreats the queen to a safer square and therefore is the more human choice. Black has moved his queen three times but after our next move, it'll have to move for the fourth time...}) 9. c4 $5 {Radical, commital, but strong! We're betting on our development lead to kick Black's queen back and gain valuable time. Moreover, the d4-pawn will now be a target. The cost is that we've lost the possibility of c2-c3, so the Horwitz bishop might lack breathing space. Therefore, our plan is to undermine the d4-pawn in the near future.} Qd7 {This simple retreat has proved quite tough for us to come up with an antidote. Black prepares to reach his perfect set-up with Bb7, Ne7-g6, Be7 and O-O after which he would be at least equal. If we play a3, he should reply with ...a5, preventing our queenside counterplay. Meanwhile the e5-pawn is a constant worry for us. Okay, that's a fairly dark picture of our chances from the current position. We do have a few trumps up our sleeve, most importantly the development lead. Let's set it in motion immediately!} 10. a3 $1 {An accurate and little pawn move, preparing b4-b5 to dislodge the Giri knight. Black can either ignore that plan or prevent b3-b4 immediately. Both plans will be checked, so let's go!} Nge7 11. b4 ({What a clever plan!} 11. b4 {will be met with} Ng6 {and Black wins a pawn. However, it's apparent that we've wasted a tempo on a3 and can no longer defend the e5-pawn. Strategically, it looks alright for the second player. However, his whole plan has a tactical flaw, which isn't easy to spot. Note that the more accurate ...a5 will be covered next.}) {Following our previous move!} 11... Ng6 12. b5 $1 {Still, Barry the b-pawn is pushed forward. We hope you've spotted how we can punish the greedy capture on e5!} Na5 {A sad move, putting the knight on the rim of the board. True, the knight may be relocated to c5 via b7, but that would take away the only developing square for the French bishop. Moreover, the c5 square is needed for the dark-squared bishop to defend d4. So, what's wrong with} (12... Ncxe5 $2 {The chief idea is} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. f4 $1) {followed by Bf3, when we win at least a piece.} 13. h4 ({We shouldn't capture the pawn immediately, as} 13. Bxd4 {gives Black the unexpected tactical possibility of} Nh4 $1 {, undermining our f3-knight with a good game. Having seen the above line, it makes sense to control the h4 square ourselves with a pawn. Moreover, Harry is responsible for kicking the knight back in the near future with h4-h5. Our threat is capturing the free d4-pawn while Nbd2 is also an idea. The concrete evaluation of the position is that White has an edge, but a lot of play remains.}) *

