by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O c5 ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) {Black overprotects the d4-pawn. However, every pawn move is a tempo wasted and we can exploit our lead in development.} 9. Re1 {Lining up with the queen on the e-file and creating the deadly threat of Bb5+.} (9. Na3 $5 {is a decent choice as well, but the text move is the most thematic.}) 9... Nxf3+ $6 {Thanks for the free gift! Can you believe it, Black has chosen to accelerate our development! His queen will be a target now, while all other pieces are standing on the back rank.} 10. Bxf3 Qh4 11. c3 $5 {There are stronger alternatives objectively, but the text move fits the most with our grand plan of opening up the position (particularly the long diagonal). Moreover, it forces Black to play precisely not to fall into immediate disaster.} Bd6 $1 ({The most precise choice, Black develops with a counter-threat on the h2-pawn. Some alternatives: A)} 11... dxc3 $2 12. Nxc3 {is simply a dream middlegame. Black will be crushed with Rc1, Nb5 and d4 to come. B)}) (11... d3 $6 {is also not precise due to} 12. Re3 $1 Qd8 13. c4 $1 {, opening the long diagonal for the Horwitz bishop. Next up is the crucial resource Qd1-f1, winning the d3-pawn cleanly.}) 12. g3 {Let's kick the queen back while preventing Qxh2+} Qd8 13. cxd4 cxd4 14. Na3 $13 ({Black has left the d4-pawn hanging, but it turns out that it's an intentional decision and the pawn is poisoned. If we capture it immediately with} 14. Bxd4 $2 {, Black would have the neat trick} Bxg3 $1 15. Bxg7 Bxh2+ $1 16. Kxh2 Qh4+ {followed by Qg5+ and Qxg7, winning back the sacrificed bishop with a few extra pawns. Lesson learned: don't accept gifts without thinking! Fortunately, we have many good alternatives here to choose from.}) *

