1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O c5 ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) {Black overprotects the d4-pawn. However, every pawn move is a tempo wasted and we can exploit our lead in development.} 9. Re1 {Lining up with the queen on the e-file and creating the deadly threat of Bb5+.} (9. Na3 $5 {is a decent choice as well, but the text move is the most thematic.}) 9... Bd7 {The more accurate choice, preventing Bb5+ and not allowing us to attack the queen just yet.} 10. d3 $1 ({The most precise continuation, winning a wonderful and valuable tempo before exchanging on e5.} 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 {would reach the exact position as in the mainline without the inclusion of d2-d3, and it definitely favours us since d2 is a square for the other knight now.}) 10... Qd5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Bf3 {Attacking both the queen and the b7-pawn at once. Black can retreat to c7 and defend against both threats, but more unpleasant surprises are awaiting him!} Qc7 13. c3 $13 Z0 ({Black is never given a moment of respite! Blow after blow, we continue to undermine his centre. Right now, the second player should bail out and give up the d4-pawn, since} 13... dxc3 $6 14. Nxc3 Nf6 {is inaccurate due to} 15. Ne4 $1 {followed by Rc1 and d4. Despite being a pawn down, White's huge lead in development amounts to a large advantage.}) *

