 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O d3 $5 ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) {The most dangerous try Black has at his disposal. Despite his lag in development, he opens up the centre with the concrete idea of creating a monster knight on the d3-square. Moreover, the text move is the first choice of the engine - quite an achievement for such a risky move! Both sides have to be precise not to fall into immediate trouble, so do study the theoretical nuances carefully!} 9. cxd3 {There was no other choice since the bishop was hanging. We're at a fork in the road: Black can either capture on f3 or d3.} Nxf3+ {Not a good choice. Black wins a pawn, true, but he allows our bishop pair to see the daylight. Meanwhile, his whole army except for the courageous lady is sitting at home.} 10. Bxf3 {)} Qxd3 11. Re1 {Black faces huge pressure on the e-file as well as the long diagonals. From a strategic point of view, Black's position is highly suspicious. Luckily for him, the extra pawn grants him approximate equality through accurate play.} Nf6 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Ne4 $13 {An important move, activating the knight as well as preparing the removal of its counterpart, a key defender. Black faces an unpleasant choice: castling would allow us to capture twice on f6 when Black's king cover has been crippled. On the other hand, we're going to proceed energetically with Rc1, Qc2 (after Black retreats the queen) and d4, with sufficient activity to compensate for the pawn.} *

