 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O d3 $5 ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) {The most dangerous try Black has at his disposal. Despite his lag in development, he opens up the centre with the concrete idea of creating a monster knight on the d3-square. Moreover, the text move is the first choice of the engine - quite an achievement for such a risky move! Both sides have to be precise not to fall into immediate trouble, so do study the theoretical nuances carefully!} 9. cxd3 {There was no other choice since the bishop was hanging. We're at a fork in the road: Black can either capture on f3 or d3.} Nxd3 $1 {Black takes up the gauntlet and occupies the most active position for the knight.} 10. Qc2 $1 {A strong but hard-to-spot nuance when you haven't seen it before. We pin Black's knight at the cost of losing the e2-bishop. However, you'll see that we'll utilize concrete tactics to trap Black's queen in our camp, reaching an unclear position. The alternatives lead nowhere with an annoying knight on d3. You can check yourself that the text move is the only move to yield enough compensation for the pawn.} Qxe2 $1 ({Black must bite the bullet, grab the offered piece and enter a deep dark forest when 2+2=5, à la Tal. Otherwise,} 10... Nc5 $2 {would prematurely retreat the cramping knight and we can punish him with} 11. d3 $1 Qf5 12. b4 $1 {and Black's house is falling. After the text move, aren't we simply a whopping piece down? However, we can prove we have a trick or two up our sleeves.}) 11. Qc4 $1 (11. Nc3 $2 {would be met with} Nb4 $1 {and Black hits our queen, thus escaping with an extra piece. After Black's last move, the only escape square for the queen is e4 , so we control it and prepare Nc3 , shutting the cage. Moreover, the queen pins the d3-knight, thus not allowing Nb4 tricks as it would hang the queen. Black has two approaches to consider: he might try to get the queen out and sac the knight back, or he can trade the queen on f3 followed by Nxb2 , with three minor pieces for the queen. The b2-knight would be trapped in that case, but our wrecked structure (4 pawn islands) surprisingly give Black enough compensation.}) 11... Nf4 $5 {Black bails out and gives back the knight, in hopes of bringing the queen back.} (11... Nc1 $5 {is a similar concept, but it has the added benefit of luring our queen to the passive c1 square. This is the recommendation of FM Kamil Plichta in his Lifetime Repertoires on the French. However, the drawback is that White can snatch a pawn with} 12. Qxc7 $1 {when Black is unable to rescue the knight, since} Nd3 $2 13. Nc3 {traps the queen. Best is 12...Qa6 13.Rxc1 Bd6 as given by Kamil, with a dynamic but balanced position. 14.Qc2 f6 15.Nc3 Ne7 16.Ne4 O-O 17.a4 White has pressure on the c-file and the a3-f8 diagonal. 14.Qc4!? is another option 14...Qxc4 15.bxc4 Nf6 16.Na3 O-O 17.Nb5 Bb8 18.Be5 after exchanging the bishops White can play c4-c5 and plant an octopus knight on d6.}) 12. Qxf4 {) The ever-powerful Horwitz bishop exerts tremendous pressure along the long diagonal, making it tough for Black's dark-squared bishop to develop. Moreover, our queen and knight are also active, yielding us full compensation for the pawn. On the other side of the board, Black is poorly underdeveloped, with only a queen in the game. No relief is brought by that since Re1 will gain a crucial tempo.} Bd6 {Black chases our queen and protects the c7-pawn at once. However, the text move weakens the g7-pawn.} 13. Qg5 {We can immediately pounce on the holes. Despite being a pawn down, White has sufficient pressure to fully compensate for it. The loss of the g7-pawn is inevitable, after which Black would be the side scrambling for compensation. As often, Stockfish delivers a cold dead equal evaluation, but one thing is certain: the position is full of life and all three results are possible.} *

