as emerged with a material advantage, but that's hardly relevant since the b2-knight won't escape from the cage.} 14. Qe2 $13 {The position is incredibly complex with a strange material imbalance. Next, we'll play d4 and the b2-knight inevitably falls. At depth 56, Stockfish announces the position is dead equal, objectively. However, we must reveal the truth that playing the dark side should be an easier task in practice according to us. His minor pieces have plenty of good squares to settle on and Black has a clear plan: to target our weaknesses on d2 and f3. This position is the chief reason we found 8...d3!? to be an annoying and dangerous try, probably Black's best bet in the whole Giri variation against our antidote. You have three choices: simply hope your opponents wouldn't go down this road, do an extensive study of the position or go for one of the alternatives we analyzed along the way.} *

