y any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O Nxf3+ ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) ({Black releases the tension and prepares a retreat of his queen. However, he gives us some free tempos and no particular problem in our camp. The text move is the most principled one, but Black risks a lot and our play flows remarkably easily. After diving our head into other variations as well, we concluded that annotating the} 8... Nxf3+ {variation is heaven compared to}) (8... d3 {knightmares (we mean the knight on d3...).}) 9. Bxf3 {This recapture is the only sensible option and it's Black's turn to move. His queen is attacked and choosing a square isn't easy. We'll examine two moves Black can try.} Qh4 {The lesser evil. Black prepares to retreat to d8 in one go while maintaining the connection with the d4-pawn.} 10. Qe2 $5 {We have a pleasant choice since there is a wide range of alternatives to choose from. We believe the text move is the most direct and annoying one to face since it keeps the momentum of the initiative. Our threats are Bxb7 and Qb5+, winning the house. We're going to continue with Na3-c4 and bring the rook to the central files. By this point, we can already stop the line and claim that White has powerful and more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. However, let's take a look at some sample lines.} c6 {Black prevents our threat but wastes yet another tempo for development.} 11. Na3 {The knight is brought into the game and Black struggles to defend all of his weaknesses.} Qd8 {The best move, retreating the queen to a safe spot before getting the king's knight out via f6.} (11... Nf6 $6 {is refuted instructively with} 12. Nc4 Nd5 13. g3 $1 Qf6 14. Ne5 $1 {and through some accurate manoeuvring, the d4-pawn is caught. White has a huge advantage after the Horwitz bishop is released.}) 12. Nc4 Nf6 13. Qe5 $5 (13. a4 $5 {followed by a5-a6 is a nice positional plan, but we feel the text move is most energetic. We attack the d4-pawn while centralizing our queen and Black must be very precise, or else we'd get a crushing positional stranglehold.}) 13... c5 $2 {As natural as it is, this move is a huge mistake! It opens the h1-a8 diagonal for our light-squared bishop and gives us a target on c5. The elegant refutation of Black's concept is} 14. c3 $1 {Firstly, we undermine the d4-pawn.} d3 {Black cannot afford to open the long diagonal for the Horwitz bishop since it'd be overwhelming.} 15. Ba3 $16 {Through a series of strong moves, we've made Black powerless to stop the capture of the c5-pawn. Our pieces completely dominate their counterpart and Black is positionally lost.} *

