1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Nc6 $5 ({'Giri's Papoo' sounds like anything but a fancy name for this chapter! The origins of this exquisite name come from a funny comment by the user MuZero in the chessable forums, and we think this name is fitting: so welcome to the chapter on the Papoo! We'll take you on a ride through all the intricacies of the move} 3... Nc6 {, a modern try from Black. The idea is to make a useful waiting move and wait for us to commit before deciding on a particular set-up. High attention is required when}) (3... Nc6 {is the recommendation of Mr Anish Giri, the Twitter King of Chess. When one of the best theoreticians in the world recommends such a rare variation with confidence, we know a tough challenge awaits us. From the moment Giri's course was released, many have followed him, including the 'Play the French' series on Chess24 by GM Romain Edouard. Therefore, we expect it to become the height of fashion in no time and will therefore devote a chunky chapter to hammer the tricky knight jump. On a final note, Giri only gives 4 lines to combat 2.b3 and he stops as early as move 6 against our recommended lines. His work has proved troublesome for White players but after hard working days of analysis, we've managed to pass the ball back to Black's court!}) 4. e5 ({Apart from} 4. exd5 {which will be examined soon, the text move is the only continuation that keeps equality for White with best play. At the cost of blocking the Horwitz bishop, we gain space in the centre and would like to play d2-d4 next. Black has a variety of choices at this point:} Nge7 {as well as 4...f6!? are tried from time to time in practice, while 4...d4! is the critical reaction, recommended by Giri.}) 4... d4 {GM Anish Giri's recommendation in his notorious work Lifetime Repertoires: French Defense. He claims the Horwitz bishop is misplaced due to the influence of the d4-pawn, but we'll prove that things are far from simple and that the Horwitz has been underestimated by him.} 5. Nf3 Qd5 $5 ({Developing our knight and protecting the e5-pawn. Black has a bunch of playable alternatives here and we'll cover five of them in detail. Speaking of Giri, his choice of} 5... Qd5 {will be addressed last.}) 6. Bc4 $5 ({Woohoo! We sincerely hope you're still reading these words, especially after an exhausting journey through all of the 5th move alternatives Black has. 5...Qd5 is a rare but inspired attempt at a refutation of our beloved opening by none other than the infamous Anish Giri. Black centralizes his queen in Scandinavian style, aiming to greedily snatch the e5-pawn and get away with it. The fact that the text move got Giri's approval means that we'll cover it deeply, deeper than the alternatives. It has also been recommended by Yuriy Krykun in his course ‘The Unexplored French Defense’, who does not cover our} 6. Bc4 {line. For variety, two different White moves will be covered:}) (6. Qe2 {is a boring attempt, while the enterprising}) (6. Bc4 $5 {gambit is our main recommendation.}) {A promising gambit we've spent a lot of time on. True, Black can win a pawn with a check on e4, but playing only with a queen is rarely a recipe for success. Initially, Stockfish liked Black's chances more, but after exhausting investigation, it was proved that Black has no advantage whatsoever - furthermore, we've several twists ready in the mainline!} 6... Qe4+ ({The only critical try, forcing us to react to the check. Black will capture the e5-pawn next, with a material advantage. It's notable that Giri ends his clickable with} 6... Qe4+ {, no annotations provided. Hopefully, the lines presented here would convince you that Anish has underestimated the potential of White's concept.}) 7. Be2 $1 Nxe5 ({A clever backward move with the bishop. Next, we'll bring the king to safety via O-O and blast open the centre. We'll check two alternatives Black can try: the solid} 7... b6 {or outright greediness via}) (7... Nxe5 {. We're already in fresh territory with hardly any games played. However, we decided to give you a lot of lines for a proper understanding of this complex position, and because this line may well become the acid test of the Horwitz in the future.}) {The critical challenge to the viability of our whole concept starting with the provocative gambit 6.Bc4 . Black grabs the poisoned pawn and will try to get his queen back to safety while keeping the extra material. On our part, we'll aim to blast open the centre as soon as possible while Black tries to get his pieces out. An important factor of this position is the activity of our Horwitz bishop. If Black can maintain the wedge on ( d4 without making too many concessions he'd be fine, but that's easier said than done. To conclude, the position is rich, often wildly unclear but objectively equal.} 8. O-O Nxf3+ ({Bringing our king to safety and preparing Re1. We'll cover three moves Black can try here:} 8... c5 {is the solid choice,}) (8... d3 $5 {is quite tricky while}) (8... Nxf3+ {is the ambitious mainline.}) ({Black releases the tension and prepares a retreat of his queen. However, he gives us some free tempos and no particular problem in our camp. The text move is the most principled one, but Black risks a lot and our play flows remarkably easily. After diving our head into other variations as well, we concluded that annotating the} 8... Nxf3+ {variation is heaven compared to}) (8... d3 {knightmares (we mean the knight on d3...).}) 9. Bxf3 {This recapture is the only sensible option and it's Black's turn to move. His queen is attacked and choosing a square isn't easy. We'll examine two moves Black can try.} Qh4 {The lesser evil. Black prepares to retreat to d8 in one go while maintaining the connection with the d4-pawn.} 10. Qe2 $5 {We have a pleasant choice since there is a wide range of alternatives to choose from. We believe the text move is the most direct and annoying one to face since it keeps the momentum of the initiative. Our threats are Bxb7 and Qb5+, winning the house. We're going to continue with Na3-c4 and bring the rook to the central files. By this point, we can already stop the line and claim that White has powerful and more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. However, let's take a look at some sample lines.} c6 {Black prevents our threat but wastes yet another tempo for development.} 11. Na3 {The knight is brought into the game and Black struggles to defend all of his weaknesses.} Qd8 {The best move, retreating the queen to a safe spot before getting the king's knight out via f6.} (11... Nf6 $6 {is refuted instructively with} 12. Nc4 Nd5 13. g3 $1 Qf6 14. Ne5 $1 {and through some accurate manoeuvring, the d4-pawn is caught. White has a huge advantage after the Horwitz bishop is released.}) 12. Nc4 Nf6 13. Qe5 $5 (13. a4 $5 {followed by a5-a6 is a nice positional plan, but we feel the text move is most energetic. We attack the d4-pawn while centralizing our queen and Black must be very precise, or else we'd get a crushing positional stranglehold.}) 13... d3 $1 {How else Black is going to defend the d4-pawn, after witnessing the previous line? The solution is to advance the brave pawn a step further. However, Black has opened two long diagonals for our powerful bishop pair and will face a fierce assault.} 14. Rfe1 $1 {There's no need to worry about the c2-pawn since Black cannot promote anyway. Instead, it's recommended to develop all of our pieces to commanding posts and strike! We believe the text move wouldn't be an easy one to memorize, but it's a truly strong idea. Make sure to understand it fully or you'll forget it easily :).} dxc2 15. Rac1 $13 {An elegant and incredibly beautiful picture of domination. There isn't a single weakness in our camp, White's whole army is coordinating well with each other and Black is stuck on the first three ranks, despite the extra pawns. Next, we'll capture the c2-pawn and proceed with either a4-a5 to complete the queenside domination or Re3, lifting the rook along the third rank. f4-f5 is also a potential future idea, hitting the e6-pawn. However, Black's Capablanca formation is quite solid, and although they have the typical French bishop (which doesn't appear on other lines with this structure, such as the Caro or Scandi) , Black has good compensation for it with the material advantage and it is hard for White to break with d5 since the d-pawn is isolated. After writing these words, we're proud that a convincing solution has been found (at least for now), against Giri's recommended option of 3...Nc6. More and more players are moving away from the mainlines of 3...Nf6 and 3...dxe4, therefore, we expect 3...Nc6 to be at the height of fashion (it is already!) in the future. Our solution is a cheeky gambit that is underestimated by Anish and will likely blow your opponent away. In the future, improvements to our analysis will surely be found and one of Chessable's unique features is the continuous updating of courses. We'll make sure to take full advantage of that! Congratulations on reaching the end of this chapter!} *

