{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 f5 $2 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A horrendous mistake, yet there are many players who have played this move. Black weakens the shelter of their king and deserves a harsh punishment.} 4. exd5 {Opening the e-file and releasing the tension. Note that capturing the f-pawn will lead to the same position so it makes no difference which pawn you capture.} exd5 (4... Qxd5 {is an ugly version of the Scandi. However, since Black's position is hardly playable anyway, all moves look bad. We will continue in the same vein as the text with} 5. Qh5+ {. After the text move, we have a nice trick that highlights Black's fragile position.}) 5. Qh5+ $1 {A killer check. Black is unable to block it with ...g6 due to the opening of the long diagonal, and the sad king is forced to Bongcloud itself.} Ke7 (5... g6 $4 6. Qe2+ {followed by Bxh8 is resignable for Black.}) 6. Nf3 {We have three pieces developed against Black's bare king in the centre. Our threats are Ba3+, Nc3 and Ng5. If you cannot bring such a strong initiative home, frankly, you have to blame yourself :).} *

