{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 d4 $5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {An interesting try our opponent may throw at us. They block the Horwitz bishop at the cost of spending a valuable tempo. It wouldn't be a sensible approach to leave the pawn there, hence our job - attack it! Ranging from the direct Nf3 and c3, we can add further pressure with Bb5 and O-O.} 4. Nf3 {Starting the music by attacking the important d4-pawn, the factor which the entire battle revolves around.} c5 ({In Vietnam, the saying goes: 'Once you've thrown the javelin, you must follow it!'. Indeed, Black must commit another pawn move to hold their centre together. Otherwise,} 4... Bc5 $6 5. c3 {would be great for us, while}) (4... Nc6 $6 5. Bb5 $1 {also leaves Black struggling to defend the pawn.}) 5. c3 $1 dxc3 $6 ({Breaking open the centre with furious force. We'll examine two continuations for Black:} 5... dxc3 {and}) (5... Nc6 {, but both of them have their own drawback. In general, the rare 3...d4 variation is quite risky since Black's d4-pawn often comes under a fierce assault, and they must play very accurately to equalise (if equality is attainable at all).}) ({A poor move - Black gives up the centre without a fight. If we can get the d4 break in after our next move, Black would suffer from their incomplete development. It's worth mentioning that} 5... d3 $2 6. Ne5 {would be even worse - White already has a decisive advantage, and we will pick up the d3-pawn next.}) 6. Nxc3 {Naturally, we develop our knight. Next on the agenda are Bb5 and d4.} Nc6 {Black tries to stop d4. However, they will be placed in a bad pin as a punishment!} 7. Bb5 $1 {A powerful pin. The huge positional threat of Bxc6+ is looming, while we also have ideas of targeting Black's weaknesses with Ne5 and Na4.} Bd7 8. Rc1 {A useful centralising move, preparing Na4 as well as a potential d4. There are a lot of ways to claim a pleasant advantage as White already, since Black is falling dangerously behind in development.} Nge7 ({Black tries to support the other knight. If they play} 8... a6 {immediately, we could take with} 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 {and now simply} 10. O-O {followed by the d4 break, which would give us a strong initiative. Black's bishop is hitting an impregnable wall, therefore, the knight is the piece that should land on c6.}) 9. O-O a6 ({The point of their previous move is to force the exchange and the bishop pair. Otherwise,} 9... Nd4 $5 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Ne5 $1 {would give White a strong initiative. The f7-pawn is a weak spot, while we can also increase the pressure with f4-f5.}) 10. Bxc6 $1 {Don't be afraid to give up the bishop pair! The mighty bishop has forced Black to make many passive and weakening moves. It's time to get it off the board for a useful tempo!} Nxc6 11. Na4 {Continuing our energetic play by hitting the c5-pawn, thus forcing another weakness. Do note that the wonderful Horwitz bishop is taking aim at the g7-pawn, not allowing the dark-squared bishop to move.} b6 12. d4 $16 {We're impressed with the fashion in which White has opened up the centre. By forcing many weakening moves on the queenside, White gave Black no other option than to put pieces on bad squares, and it's time to reap the harvest! White has a large advantage due to Black's laggy development and the vulnerable b6-pawn.} *

