{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 d4 $5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {An interesting try our opponent may throw at us. They block the Horwitz bishop at the cost of spending a valuable tempo. It wouldn't be a sensible approach to leave the pawn there, hence our job - attack it! Ranging from the direct Nf3 and c3, we can add further pressure with Bb5 and O-O.} 4. Nf3 {Starting the music by attacking the important d4-pawn, the factor which the entire battle revolves around.} c5 ({In Vietnam, the saying goes: 'Once you've thrown the javelin, you must follow it!'. Indeed, Black must commit another pawn move to hold their centre together. Otherwise,} 4... Bc5 $6 5. c3 {would be great for us, while}) (4... Nc6 $6 5. Bb5 $1 {also leaves Black struggling to defend the pawn.}) 5. c3 $1 Nc6 ({Breaking open the centre with furious force. We'll examine two continuations for Black:} 5... dxc3 {and}) (5... Nc6 {, but both of them have their own drawback. In general, the rare 3...d4 variation is quite risky since Black's d4-pawn often comes under a fierce assault, and they must play very accurately to equalise (if equality is attainable at all).}) {The right way to proceed, maintaining the bridgehead on d4. Black must hold on to that pawn, or they will be worse as our Horwitz bishop is released. However, the drawback of the text move is that a pin with Bb5 may be quite annoying.} 6. Bb5 {Here we come! Black's position already looks quite fragile.} Bd7 $1 7. O-O ({There is no other good way to stop the threats of cxd4 and Bxc6. At this point,} 7. Bxc6 {can be met with} Bxc6 {and Black regains the e4-pawn. Therefore, we should focus on development first and only take on c6 when provoked.}) 7... Nf6 ({What can be more natural than castling? The d4-pawn is under heavy fire with Bxc6, d3 (to protect the e4-pawn) and cxd4 to come. We'll examine two approaches Black may try to defend their centre:} 7... Nf6 {attacks the e4-pawn, while}) (7... Nge7 {supports the other knight.}) {An interesting idea. Black prepares to meet cxd4 with ...Nxe4, thus regaining the pawn. It is in our favour to delay the exchange since we wouldn't want to be left with an isolated d-pawn. However, the drawback of this move is that after we protect the e4-pawn, Black won't have enough firepower to keep the pawn on d4 and must commit to ...dxc3. Generally, the resulting structure would favour us, with one more central pawn and the possibility of d4 at a later point.} 8. Qe2 $1 ({The most accurate way to protect the e4-pawn and simultaneously defend the b5-bishop. It turns out that the rook may stay on f1, since it's not clear what would be the best file for it. Instead,} 8. cxd4 {is another attempt to fight for an edge. We'll look at a few lines: A)} Nxe4 $2 9. dxc5 $1 {is excellent for White. The Horwitz bishop ties down its counterpart, and d4-d5 will come, destroying Black's position. B) 8...Nxd4! is the accurate choice. After the forcing sequence 9.Nxd4 cxd4 10.Bxd7+ Qxd7 11.d3 , we were convinced Black's prospects are fine and White cannot claim anything serious.}) 8... a6 ({Black should get rid of the tension, since something like} 8... Be7 $2 9. cxd4 {is a free pawn for White.}) 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 {This is the point of Black's previous play. They have won the bishop pair at the cost of delaying the kingside development. The d4-pawn is hanging, but so is our e4-pawn. However, Black's concept seems flawed, as there is a strong resource that gives White an advantage and a pleasant middlegame.} 10. d3 $1 {A great positional decision. White recognises that it's worth protecting the e4-pawn, and at this point Black is forced to surrender the centre.} dxc3 11. Nxc3 {Our d3-e4 pawn chain is taking many useful squares from Black's pieces, especially the hitting-at-a-wall bishop on c6. Black's bishop pair is meaningless in this position, since they're both blocked in.} Be7 12. Ne5 {White can also prepare the d3-d4 break to exploit Black's lag in development, but the text move is even better in the present situation. Our knight is an absolute monster on e5, completely dominating the c6-bishop. We have several ideas to proceed (after Black protects the c6-bishop), like f4 followed by Rf3 with a strong kingside attack. Moreover, Nd1-e3 is often a clever regrouping in this structure. It will be a chore for Black to neutralise our initiative, and White's position is much easier to play.} *

