{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 d4 $5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {An interesting try our opponent may throw at us. They block the Horwitz bishop at the cost of spending a valuable tempo. It wouldn't be a sensible approach to leave the pawn there, hence our job - attack it! Ranging from the direct Nf3 and c3, we can add further pressure with Bb5 and O-O.} 4. Nf3 {Starting the music by attacking the important d4-pawn, the factor which the entire battle revolves around.} c5 ({In Vietnam, the saying goes: 'Once you've thrown the javelin, you must follow it!'. Indeed, Black must commit another pawn move to hold their centre together. Otherwise,} 4... Bc5 $6 5. c3 {would be great for us, while}) (4... Nc6 $6 5. Bb5 $1 {also leaves Black struggling to defend the pawn.}) 5. c3 $1 Nc6 ({Breaking open the centre with furious force. We'll examine two continuations for Black:} 5... dxc3 {and}) (5... Nc6 {, but both of them have their own drawback. In general, the rare 3...d4 variation is quite risky since Black's d4-pawn often comes under a fierce assault, and they must play very accurately to equalise (if equality is attainable at all).}) {The right way to proceed, maintaining the bridgehead on d4. Black must hold on to that pawn, or they will be worse as our Horwitz bishop is released. However, the drawback of the text move is that a pin with Bb5 may be quite annoying.} 6. Bb5 {Here we come! Black's position already looks quite fragile.} Bd7 $1 7. O-O ({There is no other good way to stop the threats of cxd4 and Bxc6. At this point,} 7. Bxc6 {can be met with} Bxc6 {and Black regains the e4-pawn. Therefore, we should focus on development first and only take on c6 when provoked.}) 7... Nge7 $1 ({What can be more natural than castling? The d4-pawn is under heavy fire with Bxc6, d3 (to protect the e4-pawn) and cxd4 to come. We'll examine two approaches Black may try to defend their centre:} 7... Nf6 {attacks the e4-pawn, while}) (7... Nge7 {supports the other knight.}) 8. Na3 $5 ({The most precise approach, which seems to allow Black to equalise with further accuracy. The idea is that} 8. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 {gives up the b5-bishop, and the e7-knight will eventually find a great home on c6. With that in mind, we should prevent Black from activating the e7-knight! The position contains many subtleties, and we'll try to explain them as clearly as possible.}) {A sophisticated waiting approach. The point is that if we were to release the tension on d4 too early, Black would get the c6-square for the other knight. Meanwhile, it's not time for Bxc6 either, since Black hasn't committed to ...a6. With that in mind, it's clear that White should play a useful waiting move to force Black to 'commit' to some kind of weakening. The text move is an excellent idea - we're threatening the brutal Nc4-d6# with mate, so Black should strive to bring their pieces out!} 8... Ng6 ({Black prepares Be7 to finish their development smoothly. However, they have lost the possibility of Ne7-c6, and we can happily release the tension now. Let's check some plausible alternatives as well: A)} 8... dxc3 9. dxc3 {gives us a tangibly better position due to the space advantage. B)}) (8... a6 9. Nc4 $1 {is a clever point behind our last move. Checkmate is threatened, so Black should play} Ng6 {. The second player has committed to ...a6, so it's high time to deliver} 10. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 11. Re1 $1 {with a a huge advantage for White. The g6-knight turns out to be misplaced and we've broken down the d4-pawn. With those clickable lines, we hope you've appreciated how tricky the position actually is. As GM Giri said (ironically, in his coverage of the 2. b3 French), 'Move order subtleties. Get some!'}) 9. Nc4 {A useful inclusion before cxd4.} Be7 10. cxd4 $5 (10. Re1 $5 {is perhaps an even better attempt to fight for an edge. However, we prefer clarity and follow our previous positional idea of releasing the tension once Black's knight reached g6.}) 10... Nxd4 $1 ({The correct recapture! The other choice is} 10... cxd4 $2 {which allows the cunning} 11. d3 $1 {and White wins a pawn in all lines with Bxc6 to come.}) 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. a4 $13 ({Protecting the b5-bishop is a slight improvement to the immediate} 12. Bxd7+ {, since the exchange on b5 would favour us due to the activation of the a1-rook. An interesting strategic situation has arisen. Black has a bad knight on g6, which we'll aim to exploit with a quick f4-f5. The d4-pawn is restricting our Horwitz bishop for now, but in the future, it will lack static protection from Black's army. We're pretty sure White has no advantage here, but the onus is on Black to prove clear equality and solve the problems White is proposing.}) *

