{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 a6 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A strange move to say the least, but it has been employed by several French masters such as Atalik, Bluebaum and Meier. Moreover, it's mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black' as well as being recommended by Kryakvin in his recent French repertoire for Chess Stars. What's the idea behind this little pawn move? Well, it's purely prophylaxis against Bb5, which is often an annoying resource. However, the drawback is that if we open up the position with the lines we recommend, the move a7-a6 seems to be at least partially wasted.} 4. exd5 $5 (4. Nc3 $6 d4 {wouldn't do it! We believe the text move is the most promising way to fight for the initiative. Black has wasted a lot of time on pawn moves, and it's principled that we should strive to open up the battle.}) 4... exd5 {We don't believe, for a second, that the alternatives are worth considering. The text move is the only way to make sense of Black's previous play.} 5. Nf3 {Staying flexible with the kingside. We may insert an annoying Qe2+ at times, and our king's bishop has many good places to go, ranging from e2 to g3-Bg2. The idea of c4 is also viable in this structure, provided Black couldn't reply with ...d4.} Nf6 {A natural developing move that hardly requires explanation. At this juncture, White has many playable moves to choose from. The one we propose seems to be the most strong and dangerous.} 6. g3 $146 {A powerful novelty, although not a crushing one. Previously, the bishop was mainly developed to the e2 and d3 squares, although it has less of a future there. It should be recognised that the presence of our double fianchetto makes it especially difficult for Black to advance the central pawns - every pawn move leaves behind a weakness!} Be7 7. Bg2 {We aim to finish our kingside development next with O-O before bringing the b1-knight to life.} O-O 8. O-O Bf5 9. d3 $5 (9. d4 $5 {is also a reasonable alternative. Next, we will bring our b1-knight to life with Re1 and Nd2-f1.}) *

