{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 a6 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A strange move to say the least, but it has been employed by several French masters such as Atalik, Bluebaum and Meier. Moreover, it's mentioned by Eingorn in his book 'A Rock-Solid Chess Opening Repertoire for Black' as well as being recommended by Kryakvin in his recent French repertoire for Chess Stars. What's the idea behind this little pawn move? Well, it's purely prophylaxis against Bb5, which is often an annoying resource. However, the drawback is that if we open up the position with the lines we recommend, the move a7-a6 seems to be at least partially wasted.} 4. exd5 $5 (4. Nc3 $6 d4 {wouldn't do it! We believe the text move is the most promising way to fight for the initiative. Black has wasted a lot of time on pawn moves, and it's principled that we should strive to open up the battle.}) 4... exd5 {We don't believe, for a second, that the alternatives are worth considering. The text move is the only way to make sense of Black's previous play.} 5. Nf3 {Staying flexible with the kingside. We may insert an annoying Qe2+ at times, and our king's bishop has many good places to go, ranging from e2 to g3-Bg2. The idea of c4 is also viable in this structure, provided Black couldn't reply with ...d4.} c5 {Black controls the important d4-square at the cost of neglecting piece development. Actually, we've transposed to a Sicilian sideline, which normally arises after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.b3 the Cowboy chess! 3...a6!? 4.Bb2 d5 5.exd5 exd5 and the two branches join together.} 6. d4 (6. Qe2+ {is Adhiban's recommendation in his excellent 1. e4 Lifetime Repertoires. As he calls it, this is a 'sneaky' intermediate move to disrupt Black's coordination. However, the text move fits best with the principles we've tried to emphasise throughout the repertoire: active, sound lines that set small, annoying problems for Black early in the game. We now have the ability to create an isolated pawn on d5, but more often, we'd like to focus on development first.}) 6... Nf6 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 {is the most popular move, but possibilities like} Bg4 $5 {are annoying, and White has done poorly in practice. Our chosen option is Carlsen's recipe, with which the famed champion won a game against Peter Svidler. We develop our pieces modestly and avoid Bg4 pins.}) 7... Nc6 {A natural developing move.} 8. O-O cxd4 {Generally, Black shouldn't exchange on d4 in this structure since it'd activate our army. However, a possible justification behind Svidler's choice is that he would like to avoid dxc5 (after moving the f8-bishop), and Black would have to spend further time. 8...Be7 can be met in many ways, the most interesting being 9.c4!? when we can count on a slight development lead.} 9. Nxd4 Bc5 ({The point of Black's last move is to clear the c5-square for the bishop, so the text move should be played.} 9... Bd6 {can be met with} 10. c4 $1 {, similarly to the mainline.}) 10. Nxc6 {Black's pressure is mounting on the d4-knight, so let's get rid of it with tempo. Note that the Horwitz bishop now gets opened up. Moreover, Black's structure would still be weak with three pawn islands compared to our two.} bxc6 11. c4 $14 Z0 ({Start chopping off the weak d5-pawn. Next, we'll follow up with Bf3 and Nc3, increasing the pressure. A sample line is} 11... O-O 12. Nc3 {is an improvement to Carlsen - Svidler} Re8 13. Bf3 {with a certain edge for White, since it's not easy to defend the d5-pawn.}) *

