{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 c5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A decently popular move at the master as well as amateur level. Black combines the French with the Sicilian and ambitiously grabs space in the centre. They are preparing d4 to steamroll our Horwitz bishop. However, a clear drawback of this move is that it fails to develop any piece. Black's thrust is also premature in the sense that the strong Bb5+ resource is now available as Black can no longer play ...c6. Huy faced this line once in a rapid game and launched a sudden attack in the middlegame to win. And after doing a lot of analysis, we're convinced you don't need to be worried at all about this option.} 4. exd5 {Similar to the pawn move 3...a6 , we decide to recommend the exd5 approach, which opens up the centre in a principled manner while our opponent is lagging in development. This is an even better option for us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} Qxd5 $2 {No, #TeamScandi, your boat is definitely sinking with this move! You cannot start with the French and then capture on d5 with the queen!} 5. Nc3 $1 {Development is our top priority, and it would be great if we could develop with a threat. Black's queen is currently short of squares.} Qd8 ({Let's look at the alternatives to this meek retreat: A)} 5... Qd6 {can be refuted in many ways, the easiest and simplest one being} 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Nb5 $1 {followed by Be5 and Bc4. Black is suffering from so many holes in their position, like the c7-square. B) One of our favourite Chessable courses is 'The Scandinavian Supercharged', in which the author mapped out a reliable repertoire based on the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian. Here, not only is the c8-bishop unable to get out of the pawn chain, but the unfortunate c5-pawn makes it tougher than ever for Her Majesty to get to a5. Heartbroken!}) 6. Qe2 {Simple development with Nf3 and natural developing moves should also guarantee an edge. We are Horwitz players, though! Our goal is to deliver an attack whenever possible, and castling queenside is the way to spice things up. The text move isn't just the engine's recommendation, it's also the most spirited way to go about it - Black's undeveloped forces will have a hard time dealing with our menacing pieces.} Nc6 7. O-O-O $16 {We have a commanding lead in development, which can be transformed into a lethal initiative. We'll follow up with f4-f5 and Nf3 as well as Ne4 to turn up the heat on Black's weak pawns on c5 and g7.} *

