 us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} exd5 {An obviously better choice compared to the Scandi-French hybrid we've just seen. Black captures the centre with their c5-d5 duo, but the legends have it that White will strike back furiously!} 5. Nf3 {A natural move, bringing the king's knight into play in the most active fashion out there. There are many hidden subtleties in the position, like whether Black develops the knight to c6 or f6 and the ways they could react to Bb5+. We'll try to explain them all as convincingly as possible!} Nc6 ({We tend to believe this is less accurate compared to} 5... Nf6 {, although both options should be fine. The reason is that Black should develop their kingside first in order to avoid us from disrupting their development with a timely Qe2+.}) 6. Bb5 Nf6 ({A powerful pin indeed! We've developed three pieces compared to Black's one. Needless to say the second player must play precisely to stay afloat, since the threat of O-O followed by Re1+ is very strong. We're at a tabiya of the 3...c5 variation and will analyse two branches: the ordinary} 6... Nf6 {and the tricky}) (6... Qe7+ $5) {Developing the knight first is logical. This position may be reached from many different move orders, so it's important to study this line carefully. It turns out that the capture on c6 isn't dangerous, since the bishop pair fully compensates for Black's structural weakness. Therefore, we should play on the e-file instead.} 7. Qe2+ $1 (7. O-O {is the main choice in practice, but it is too tame and gives Black the necessary time to complete their development with} Be7 {followed by O-O and Bf5. The second player has equalized and won in Elgersma - Jobava. The text move is a cunning and hard-to-meet idea. As usual in this variation, as soon as Black plays Nf6, we throw in the check, in order to meet ...Be7 with Bxf6.}) 7... Be7 ({The most sensible move, although allowing Bxf6 is a clear concession. Alternatives:} 7... Qe7 8. Ne5 $1 {gives White a large initiative, while}) (7... Be6 8. Ng5 $1 {isn't pleasant for Black either.}) 8. Bxf6 $1 {With some clever subtleties, we've gained a small but clear edge out of the opening. Black will never be safe with this broken structure!} gxf6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 $14 {Developing the last minor piece. White is a lot more comfortable here due to the better structure. We'll continue with Bxc6 to weaken Black's structure further, Rae1, as well as Nh4 to exploit the kingside holes. Historically, this position first appeared in Aronin - Taimanov, which ended in a draw.} *

