{In this chapter, we'll cover the alternatives Black can try on the third move. Some of them are outright refuted, some are dubious, but there are some poisonous variations that can be dangerous.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 c5 ({Except for} 3... Nc6 {(Giri's line),}) (3... Nf6 {(Closed Horwitz) and}) (3... dxe4 {(Open Horwitz), which were covered in previous chapters, there are many moves Black can try on the third move. An interesting fact we discovered when working on this course is that in the present position, White is in a strange kind of zugzwang, as early as move 3!}) (3... Nf6 {gives us a tempo with} 4. e5 {, while}) (3... dxe4 {allows us to finish queenside development smoothly via} 4. Nc3 {followed by Qe2. Even if it's White to move here, there aren’t many useful moves we have at our disposal. Nc3 would run into ...d4, while e5 is a shot into thin air. Meanwhile, we cannot get the king's knight out yet with Nf3 due to dxe4. Therefore, Black can try a wide range of useful waiting moves at this point to force us to commit first. Giri's Nc6 sortie is the most important among them and deserves its own chapter. We'll examine the rest of them here.}) {A decently popular move at the master as well as amateur level. Black combines the French with the Sicilian and ambitiously grabs space in the centre. They are preparing d4 to steamroll our Horwitz bishop. However, a clear drawback of this move is that it fails to develop any piece. Black's thrust is also premature in the sense that the strong Bb5+ resource is now available as Black can no longer play ...c6. Huy faced this line once in a rapid game and launched a sudden attack in the middlegame to win. And after doing a lot of analysis, we're convinced you don't need to be worried at all about this option.} 4. exd5 {Similar to the pawn move 3...a6 , we decide to recommend the exd5 approach, which opens up the centre in a principled manner while our opponent is lagging in development. This is an even better option for us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} exd5 {An obviously better choice compared to the Scandi-French hybrid we've just seen. Black captures the centre with their c5-d5 duo, but the legends have it that White will strike back furiously!} 5. Nf3 {A natural move, bringing the king's knight into play in the most active fashion out there. There are many hidden subtleties in the position, like whether Black develops the knight to c6 or f6 and the ways they could react to Bb5+. We'll try to explain them all as convincingly as possible!} Nc6 ({We tend to believe this is less accurate compared to} 5... Nf6 {, although both options should be fine. The reason is that Black should develop their kingside first in order to avoid us from disrupting their development with a timely Qe2+.}) 6. Bb5 Qe7+ $5 ({A powerful pin indeed! We've developed three pieces compared to Black's one. Needless to say the second player must play precisely to stay afloat, since the threat of O-O followed by Re1+ is very strong. We're at a tabiya of the 3...c5 variation and will analyse two branches: the ordinary} 6... Nf6 {and the tricky}) (6... Qe7+ $5) {Black attempts to exploit the e-file himself! As strange as this move looks, it's quite popular and has been tried by David Navara. Black's intention is to force an exchange of queens, which would greatly ease their position. We won't allow that!} 7. Be2 $1 {A clever switchback with the bishop. We're violating the rule of not moving pieces twice in the opening, but this time our idea is fully justified: the e7-queen is clumsy and will have to move again in the near future. Our next moves are O-O and d4 when Black isn't in time to castle kingside.} Nf6 {Okay, let them develop the knight. How is that bishop coming out without paying a huge cost, though?} 8. O-O {We've reached the tabiya of the 6...Qe7+ variation. Black has many approaches to choose from to untangle their pieces, and we'll check three of them.} g6 $6 {A creative plan that proves to be too slow. Black wants to fianchetto the f8-bishop to oppose our legendary Horwitz gun, but the problem is that the e-file is now wide open.} 9. Re1 {How does it feel to line your rook up in the same file as your opponent's queen AND king? It tastes sweet!} Be6 ({Careful play from Black. Instead,} 9... Bg7 $2 10. Bc4 $1 Be6 11. Bxd5 $3 {crushes Black in the deadly pins.}) 10. Bb5 $1 {An important positional motif to remember. We prepare Bxc6 to damage Black's structure, since the f8-bishop will be fianchettoed. Here's the trick: the c5-pawn will be weaker, with Nc3-a4 and Ba3 to follow. Eureka!} Bg7 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Nc3 $16 {We have a solid positional advantage, with Na4 and Ba3 to follow. While Black may be able to defend the c5-pawn, their forces would be so tied up.} *

