 us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} exd5 {An obviously better choice compared to the Scandi-French hybrid we've just seen. Black captures the centre with their c5-d5 duo, but the legends have it that White will strike back furiously!} 5. Nf3 {A natural move, bringing the king's knight into play in the most active fashion out there. There are many hidden subtleties in the position, like whether Black develops the knight to c6 or f6 and the ways they could react to Bb5+. We'll try to explain them all as convincingly as possible!} Nc6 ({We tend to believe this is less accurate compared to} 5... Nf6 {, although both options should be fine. The reason is that Black should develop their kingside first in order to avoid us from disrupting their development with a timely Qe2+.}) 6. Bb5 Qe7+ $5 ({A powerful pin indeed! We've developed three pieces compared to Black's one. Needless to say the second player must play precisely to stay afloat, since the threat of O-O followed by Re1+ is very strong. We're at a tabiya of the 3...c5 variation and will analyse two branches: the ordinary} 6... Nf6 {and the tricky}) (6... Qe7+ $5) {Black attempts to exploit the e-file himself! As strange as this move looks, it's quite popular and has been tried by David Navara. Black's intention is to force an exchange of queens, which would greatly ease their position. We won't allow that!} 7. Be2 $1 {A clever switchback with the bishop. We're violating the rule of not moving pieces twice in the opening, but this time our idea is fully justified: the e7-queen is clumsy and will have to move again in the near future. Our next moves are O-O and d4 when Black isn't in time to castle kingside.} Nf6 {Okay, let them develop the knight. How is that bishop coming out without paying a huge cost, though?} 8. O-O {We've reached the tabiya of the 6...Qe7+ variation. Black has many approaches to choose from to untangle their pieces, and we'll check three of them.} Be6 {There's nothing wrong with this move objectively, but the queenside castling plan is quite dubious. Why? Black has advanced the c-pawn rather prematurely, and the king won't have much cover. Moreover, Black is far too slow in organising anything against the white king.} 9. d4 $1 {Breaking open the centre to utilise our development lead! The positional threat is dxc5 to force Black to recapture with the queen and create a target for our pieces.} O-O-O $6 ({Let's see what happens if Black just ignores our plan. We must note that} 9... Qc7 {is the best move, transposing to 8...Qc7 [/variation/18434603].}) 10. dxc5 $1 {Not just weakening Black's structure, we also open the d4 square for our pieces and force Qxc5, which is a move Black wouldn't like to make.} Qxc5 ({If Black does not attempt to capture back the pawn, we'd continue with a3-b4, with a free extra pawn. However,} 10... Ne4 $5 {is a tricky try worth mentioning. We believe White can play} 11. a3 $5 {to force} Nxc5 {and here} 12. Nd4 $1 {with a promising advantage. Black can no longer fight for control of the d4 square, and the c5-knight turns out to be a target with b4 to come. We're also preparing Nc3 and Qd2 to hit the isolated d5-pawn. After the text move, we could imagine a few players wanting to chop the f6-knight off. Don't do it! It would open the g-file for Black's major pieces and create severe trouble in our camp. Instead, our suggestion is much more powerful.}) 11. a3 $1 {A typical idea in these structures. We prepare b4 to kick Black's queen back and gain space on the queenside.} Be7 12. b4 Qb6 13. Nc3 $16 {The next step is to fight for control of the d4 square, which can be achieved with Nb5-d4. Black's queen is running out of squares as well. White stands much better here, concluding that the queenside castling plan is ineffective.} *

