 us compared to the a6 lines, since Black cannot prevent the tempo-gaining Bb5+ and the c5-pawn can be undermined with d2-d4 later, creating an isolated pawn on d5.} exd5 {An obviously better choice compared to the Scandi-French hybrid we've just seen. Black captures the centre with their c5-d5 duo, but the legends have it that White will strike back furiously!} 5. Nf3 {A natural move, bringing the king's knight into play in the most active fashion out there. There are many hidden subtleties in the position, like whether Black develops the knight to c6 or f6 and the ways they could react to Bb5+. We'll try to explain them all as convincingly as possible!} Nc6 ({We tend to believe this is less accurate compared to} 5... Nf6 {, although both options should be fine. The reason is that Black should develop their kingside first in order to avoid us from disrupting their development with a timely Qe2+.}) 6. Bb5 Qe7+ $5 ({A powerful pin indeed! We've developed three pieces compared to Black's one. Needless to say the second player must play precisely to stay afloat, since the threat of O-O followed by Re1+ is very strong. We're at a tabiya of the 3...c5 variation and will analyse two branches: the ordinary} 6... Nf6 {and the tricky}) (6... Qe7+ $5) {Black attempts to exploit the e-file himself! As strange as this move looks, it's quite popular and has been tried by David Navara. Black's intention is to force an exchange of queens, which would greatly ease their position. We won't allow that!} 7. Be2 $1 {A clever switchback with the bishop. We're violating the rule of not moving pieces twice in the opening, but this time our idea is fully justified: the e7-queen is clumsy and will have to move again in the near future. Our next moves are O-O and d4 when Black isn't in time to castle kingside.} Nf6 {Okay, let them develop the knight. How is that bishop coming out without paying a huge cost, though?} 8. O-O {We've reached the tabiya of the 6...Qe7+ variation. Black has many approaches to choose from to untangle their pieces, and we'll check three of them.} Qc7 {The recommendation of our silicon frenemies. Black frees the e7-square for the bishop and puts the queen on an active square.} 9. d4 $1 {No comment is required if you've studied the previous lines. It's all about the initiative, and opening the centre is the way to do so! We must mention that both sides are in some kind of crisis regarding the d4-c5 tension. Black obviously doesn't want to give White a free tempo and open the centre with cxd4. However, White wouldn't like to play dxc5 either since Black would be able to capture on c5 in one go. Therefore, it's a battle of waiting moves. While we can come up with all sorts of ideas like Nc3 and Re1, Black can't afford such luxuries.} Be6 10. Nc3 ({As discussed Black wants to delay . If they play it anyway, we'd reply with} 10. dxc5 $1 {and we have a branch: A) O-O a3} Bxc5 {is bad due to} 11. Bxf6 $1 {. Black has castled kingside, so the idea of Bxf6 IS now serious, compared to a few moves before. B) 10...Bxc5 is a clear waste of time, which we can refute concretely with 11.Bxf6 gxf6 12.Nc3! and White wins the d5-pawn.}) {Creating the strong threat of Nb5 to chase Black's queen. Meanwhile, dxc5 is still on the radar.} 10... a6 $1 ({The only good move, in our opinion. The threat must be stopped! Black has some alternatives we should consider: A)} 10... Rc8 11. Nb5 $1 {gives White a powerful initiative with c4! to come. B) 10...Be7 is inaccurate due to 11.Nb5! Qd8 12.dxc5 and now: B1) 12...Bxc5 isn't ideal due to 13.Bxf6! and Black cannot recapture with the queen due to the Nc7+ fork. B2) 12.dxc5 O-O allows the clever 13.Nd6! when we give back the pawn in order to obtain a bishop pair and therefore, a risk-free middlegame.}) 11. Na4 {Nevertheless, we can still hit the c5 weakness! We've succeeded in our goal of provoking cxd4. Moreover, the b6 square is now a juicy weakness.} cxd4 12. Nxd4 {Since the threat of Nxe6 is rather strong, Black should exchange a pair of knights.} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 $14 {We've ended up in a highly comfortable middlegame. We're leading in development with rather active pieces. Perhaps the only drawback is that our pieces aren't well placed strategically - for example, the a4-knight would love to be on d4! However, the pluses outweigh the minuses, and White can press for an advantage in this position. Stockfish's evaluation swings between equality and a slight edge for White, which is good enough for us. Continuing with Bf3, c4, and perhaps even Bb6-c5 to exchange the bishops, we are sure to mount a lot of pressure on Black's position. Congratulations on reaching the end of the 3rd move alternatives chapter! Needless to say, the options presented in this chapter aren't the most critical ones against the Horwitz, and we've found fresh ideas in most of the lines to swing the balance in White's favour.} *

