{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Qf6 $6 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) 3. d4 ({The cheap and objectively horrible queen sortie is quite popular online, where many players premoved} 3. Bb2 {after 2. b3 (it reminds us of the famous Lefong trap). Well, is it even ethical for black players to win in such a dirty manner? We aren't sure, but we do feel sympathy for +100 players that have fallen for the 'trap' in the Lichess Database. 2...Ba3!?!? is officially the Lefong 'Gambit' and is directed against unsuspecting online players. For the purpose of a serious opening course, 3.Bxa3 ends the story.}) {Seizing the centre, the text move is the most principled refutation of Black's cheeky concept.} 3... Qg6 ({This tricky move has given Black a win in a random game in the database. Black attacks the e4-pawn and makes it annoying for us to protect it with the pressure on the g2-pawn. There are some other moves we may look at for the sake of completeness: A)} 3... c5 $5 4. e5 $1 {is rather strong, the point being} Qd8 5. d5 $1 {and Black will be saddled with a backward d-pawn. B)}) (3... e5 $5 {is another way to justify Black's last move. We can refute it with the seemingly illogical} 4. Nc3 $1 {to jump onto d5.} Bb4 5. Bd2 $1 {is the key detail when we're clearly better.}) 4. Nd2 $16 Z0 ({This time around, d2 is the best square for the knight, since Bb4 pins are no longer that dangerous. We want to follow up with Ngf3 or even Qf3 followed by Bb2. For example,} 4... Bb4 5. Qf3 $1 {is very strong, covering the c3 square and preparing to advance with c3 next. Moreover, the e4 and g2 pawns are both defended, leaving the f1-bishop free to move to d3. Refuting 2...Qf6? is a piece of cake, we dare say. Move 4 is the proper moment to end the whole line :)}) *

