{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Nf6 $5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {A weird Alekhine Defence. Black argues that the extra moves b3 and e6 favour him, since the knight would be more stable in the centre. However, Black's break in the Alekhine structure is ...d6, and our gifted Horwitz bishop would be able to steal the show on b2!} 3. e5 Ne4 $6 ({Kicking the knight away is principled and strong. We'll check two squares he can try:} 3... Ne4 {and}) (3... Nd5 {.}) {A dubious move. The knight is really running out of squares here, and it risks being trapped. In return for it, Black threatens some dubious cheapos on f2. The refutation of this line offered by us is a magnificent KOTH (King of the Hill) idea that is unique and strong. However, given the rarity of this line, you'll probably never have the chance to execute it on the board. Regardless, what'd you lose by enjoying an entertaining variation?} 4. a3 $146 Nxf2 $5 ({A powerful novelty in order to cover the b4 square and thus preparing d3 to kick the annoying knight back. If Black just plays something meek like} 4... d5 {, we'd play} 5. d3 $1 Nc5 6. d4 $1 Ncd7 7. Bd3 {with an easy advantage due to the time wasted by Black's knight. However, the second player may have some nasty tricks in mind...}) {Starting the fireworks! Black exploits the vulnerabilities of our king and rook and sacrifices a knight in order to play Qh4-d4+, forking the rook. Say no to panic! Black's sacrifice is more smoke than fire, and with an amazing sequence we'll come out on top.} 5. Kxf2 Qh4+ {The point.} 6. Ke3 $1 ({Otherwise we'd be losing after} 6. g3 $4 Qd4+ {or}) (6. Kf3 $4 Nc6 $1 {. The text move is the only way to keep the game going! Our threat now is to play Nf3 and Bb2, so Black's best bet is to beg for repetition with}) 6... Qg5+ {And have you spotted the mindblowing resource to bring our king to safety?} 7. Kd4 $3 {A-M-A-Z-I-N-G! No adjective is enough to describe this move, which is one of the most outlandish ideas that actually works - that we've ever seen. Eschewing the repetition, the brave king protects the e5-pawn for a decisive tempo, and the devastating threat is Kc3-b2! when we'd be simply a piece up. Have you ever played King of the Hill, an interesting variant of chess? Well, the rule is that when the king gets to a central square (e4, d4, e5, d5), that side wins. However, that's not the case in standard chess, and the game is still going :)} c5+ (7... Nc6+ $2 {is even worse due to} 8. Kc3 $1 {and Black has no compensation for the piece.}) 8. Kc3 $1 {Following the plan!} Qxe5+ 9. d4 cxd4+ 10. Kb2 $16 {What a journey for the king! Next, we'll follow up with Nf3 to capture the d4-pawn. c3 and Ka2 are also possible ideas to improve White's position. Black has his three pawns for the knight but falls behind in development with a weak pawn on d4. All in all, White stands clearly better.} *

