{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Nf6 $5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {A weird Alekhine Defence. Black argues that the extra moves b3 and e6 favour him, since the knight would be more stable in the centre. However, Black's break in the Alekhine structure is ...d6, and our gifted Horwitz bishop would be able to steal the show on b2!} 3. e5 Nd5 ({Kicking the knight away is principled and strong. We'll check two squares he can try:} 3... Ne4 {and}) (3... Nd5 {.}) {A more solid square for the Alekhine horse, where it is supported by the e5-pawn. Black plans to undermine our cramping e5-pawn with d7-d6 and thus equalising the chances.} 4. c4 $5 Nb6 $6 ({The mainline in the ChessBase Database and one which has scored a great 87% for White. We think this is mainly because out of 25 games, only one Black player has chosen the correct} 4... Nb4 $1 {, after which White should be careful due to his slow development. In any case, the avalanche of white pawns in the centre can be threatening. And if Black wishes to reach a balanced position, he is often forced to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative.}) {The most popular move, played in 65% of the games that reached this position at the moment we write these words. However, there is no wonder that this is a suspicious move: the knight on b6 simply has no future, being completely restricted by the c4-pawn.} 5. Bb2 {Logical development with Nf3 and d4 next, and White has a pleasant advantage!} d6 6. exd6 cxd6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. d4 $16 {White has a clear advantage and won all three games from this point. Black is struggling to find good squares for his pieces. In an ideal world, we'll proceed with Nc3, Bd3, O-O, Qe2, Rad1, Rfe1 and Bb1, reaching the perfect set-up. It's worth noting that after Black breaks with ...d5, it's advisable to keep the tension, since after ...dxc4 the hanging pawn structure is highly favourable for White, given Black's horrible b6-knight.} *

