{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Nf6 $5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {A weird Alekhine Defence. Black argues that the extra moves b3 and e6 favour him, since the knight would be more stable in the centre. However, Black's break in the Alekhine structure is ...d6, and our gifted Horwitz bishop would be able to steal the show on b2!} 3. e5 Nd5 ({Kicking the knight away is principled and strong. We'll check two squares he can try:} 3... Ne4 {and}) (3... Nd5 {.}) {A more solid square for the Alekhine horse, where it is supported by the e5-pawn. Black plans to undermine our cramping e5-pawn with d7-d6 and thus equalising the chances.} 4. c4 $5 Nb4 $1 ({The mainline in the ChessBase Database and one which has scored a great 87% for White. We think this is mainly because out of 25 games, only one Black player has chosen the correct} 4... Nb4 $1 {, after which White should be careful due to his slow development. In any case, the avalanche of white pawns in the centre can be threatening. And if Black wishes to reach a balanced position, he is often forced to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative.}) {The strongest move. Black moves the knight to an active square and prepares to blast open the centre with ...d6. The sole drawback is that he can no longer give a check on b4 after we move the d-pawn.} 5. d4 (5. Bb2 {looks like a logical move, but Black has the powerful antidote} d6 $1 6. exd6 Bxd6 $1 {and it turns out we cannot capture on g7 without giving Black sufficient compensation. The break ...e5 is hard to stop and Black has already equalized. The text move is the fifth pawn move in a row for White! However, we believe it's the best way to keep control. Moreover, we're not that behind in development: Black has just developed one piece, and that piece has moved three times so far.}) 5... d6 {As usual, the only way for Black to drum up counterplay in the 2...Nf6 variation is the d6 break.} 6. exd6 Bxd6 $1 {The correct recapture. Black prepares the e5 break with a dangerous initiative, and it seems the break is impossible to prevent. Because of this reason, we decided to recommend 4. c4 as an alternative and not the main choice.} 7. Nf3 ({Trying to stop the ...e5 idea with} 7. Bb2 {can be met with} e5 $1 {anyway and then} 8. dxe5 Bf5 $1 {with a powerful attack for the invested material. The text move is no improvement either, due to}) 7... e5 {and White's prospect is not pleasant at all with ...Bf5 coming. We've analysed this position in some detail and came up with some computer lines, only to conclude this is simply no fun for White. After seeing why 4. c4 is so risky, you can appreciate why we don't want all of us to die on that hill.} *

