{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Nf6 $5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {A weird Alekhine Defence. Black argues that the extra moves b3 and e6 favour him, since the knight would be more stable in the centre. However, Black's break in the Alekhine structure is ...d6, and our gifted Horwitz bishop would be able to steal the show on b2!} 3. e5 Nd5 ({Kicking the knight away is principled and strong. We'll check two squares he can try:} 3... Ne4 {and}) (3... Nd5 {.}) {A more solid square for the Alekhine horse, where it is supported by the e5-pawn. Black plans to undermine our cramping e5-pawn with d7-d6 and thus equalising the chances.} 4. Bb2 ({The safest move, according to our investigation. We develop a piece and protect the crucial e5-pawn. However, there's a sharper approach starting with} 4. c4 $5 {which we've given as an alternative.}) 4... Nc6 $6 {Apparently, this move is tried quite often. However, the knight is badly placed on c6, where it blocks Black from playing the c7-c5 break once we put our pawn on d4.} 5. Nf3 d6 6. d4 $146 {Surprisingly, this obvious move is a novelty - and a strong one! The point is that Black's slow play has allowed us to keep a pawn on e5 without being punished. Therefore, we're able to restrict the French bishop as well as cramping Black's position.} dxe5 7. dxe5 $16 {The right recapture, maintaining our space advantage. We have a huge positional advantage and the important thing is to prevent Black's counterplay with the evil Nf4/Nb4 jumps. It's often recommended to play a3 and g3 to shut down those ideas. Generally, we'll develop with Bg2, Qe2 and O-O followed by c4 to kick Black's strongest piece next. To conclude, Black is just suffering here and the 4...Nc6 variation is totally out of business.} *

