{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 Nf6 $5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {A weird Alekhine Defence. Black argues that the extra moves b3 and e6 favour him, since the knight would be more stable in the centre. However, Black's break in the Alekhine structure is ...d6, and our gifted Horwitz bishop would be able to steal the show on b2!} 3. e5 Nd5 ({Kicking the knight away is principled and strong. We'll check two squares he can try:} 3... Ne4 {and}) (3... Nd5 {.}) {A more solid square for the Alekhine horse, where it is supported by the e5-pawn. Black plans to undermine our cramping e5-pawn with d7-d6 and thus equalising the chances.} 4. Bb2 ({The safest move, according to our investigation. We develop a piece and protect the crucial e5-pawn. However, there's a sharper approach starting with} 4. c4 $5 {which we've given as an alternative.}) 4... d6 $146 5. Nf3 ({A crucial improvement to rescue the variation for Black. He immediately challenges the bridgehead on e5 and seeks to remove it at the earliest 'convenience'. We suspect the reason this move is still a novelty is that most players didn't realize that} 5. exd6 Bxd6 $1 {is actually quite okay for Black since it would be risky to grab the poisoned pawn on g7. As often, we recommend that you go the pleasant route, instead of plunging the head of the Horwitz bishop into the complications.}) ({First of all, you may wonder why} 5. d4 $6 {, a move which usually support our structure very well, is ineffective here. The solution is the break} c5 $1 {and our centre is shamefully dismantled. Therefore, we advise you not to create a d4-e5 pawn duo so early in the game while Black already has a pawn on d6, since the ...c5 break would be powerful. Next, we're going to explain why we chose the text move. White develops the knight in the healthiest way possible and prepares to recapture on e5 with the knight. Since the bishop is a long-range piece, it's a very strong piece in this position. If it comes to e5, Black would be able to hit with the knight and an exchange is not in our favour, as Bobby Fischer confirmed years ago.}) 5... dxe5 {Black is advised to release the tension instantly to avoid the prospect of d4. Also, annoying exd6 tricks are ruled out.} 6. Nxe5 {White has a comfortable edge with a lead in development and a strong knight on e5. If not disturbed, we'll proceed with Nc3, g2+Bg2 and just finish development. More aggressive plans to consider are Qf3 or even Qh5 to play for that glorious checkmate :) In any case, let's look at a sample line.} Bd6 ({A natural move to come up with. Black hits the e5-knight and prepares smooth castling. Nevertheless, we believe this is a slight inaccuracy since it gives White the bishop pair after our next move. Besides the text move, we should also check some other continuations: A)} 6... Nd7 {is the recommendation of Stockfish. We think} 7. Nc4 $5 {is a good reply, maintaining control of the e5 square and keeping Black cramped. B)}) (6... Be7 {can be met with} 7. Nc3 O-O {and now} 8. Qh5 $1 {is an admittedly weird but strong idea offered by the silicon machines. The idea is to clear the way for castling while maintaining control over the crucial e5 square, since} f6 $2 9. Bd3 $1 {would be deadly.}) 7. Nc4 $14 Z0 ({Seizing the bishop pair since the g7-pawn is hanging. White has a pleasant strategic advantage due to the bishop pair. Nevertheless, we must tread with care and not allow Black to achieve the ...e5 break, which would release the French bishop. After something like} 7... O-O 8. Nxd6 cxd6 {, this can be done by} 9. d4 $1 {followed by Qd2 (prophylaxis against Qa5+) and c4, conquering the centre. That's the end of our dense coverage of the 2...Nf6 variation. We sincerely hope the two options provided against 3...Nd5 will give you a lot of success. Of course, do not forget the heroic king's journey against 3...Ne4!}) *

