{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 b6 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {The Copycat variation, championed by John Watson in his legendary book 'Play the French' - a should-have manual for aspiring French players. Black wants to prove that our e4-pawn is a liability by hitting it with Bb7. However, Black does not fight for the centre directly and we can often seize it ourselves with d4 - although objectively speaking we should have done so on the 2nd move ;). We're proud to announce we've found many bright ideas over previous theory (Watson's book for example), and the ideas are as original as they can be.} 3. Bb2 {The point of our previous move. Need we add some more explanations?} Bb7 {No choice for Black either. He threatens the e4-pawn, and now there is more than one way to protect it. We recommend the most logical one, which is} 4. Nc3 {and the pawn is well protected. First of all, we would like to push d2-d4, which is why the various moves Black has tried in this position are directed against it. Secondly, there are also ideas to move our queen and pave the way for queenside castling. The e4-pawn does an awesome job of restricting the poor bishop on b7! In the Owen ( 1.e4 b6 ), it's true that the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop is not the most convenient of ways to gain an edge. However, it's certainly quite a venomous one against the opening that Kramnik considered to be 'no better than 1.e4 a6 '! This is the critical tabiya of the Copycat variation, from which we'll analyse two moves. Grab your popcorn and watch in delight as Black's kingdom falls apart everywhere!} Nf6 ({Firstly, we'd like to mention briefly that} 4... d5 $6 {fails to} 5. exd5 exd5 6. Qe2+ $1 {and Black's coordination is disrupted. There are a lot of details to gain an advantage with White though, and we don't feel it's practical to learn all of them given the rarity of that sideline. With the text move, Black hits the e4-pawn and it's not so convenient to defend it with pawn moves, while 5.Bd3 or 5.Qe2 would block our future development. This concept was played recently by Wesley So against none other than Magnus Carlsen in a game that starts with the unusual move order 1.b3 b6 2.e4 Bb7 . At this point, 5.e5 Nd5 is the mainline, a possible continuation being 6.Nxd5 Bxd5 7.Qg4 h5!? with highly unclear play in Carlsen, M - So, W, Meltwater Tour Final 2021. What we will be proposing instead is a rare but venomous continuation, let's see it!}) 5. Qf3 $5 {According to our database, this move is a theoretical novelty. Despite the peculiar appearance, it does protect the e4-pawn and is a challenging option due to: - We may transpose to the 4...d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Qf3!? variation as covered previously. - The queen often exerts uncomfortable pressure down the long diagonal while not blocking the f1-bishop. Moreover, Her Majesty supports g4-g5 to dislodge the black knight. - We are now ready to castle queenside! What a multipurpose move! Pretending Black does nothing, we'll play O-O-O and take the whole centre with d4. Black has several playable continuations here, but to our eyes, the most natural ones are 5...c5 and 5...d5 , fighting for the centah!} d5 {Black opens the centre in order to 'exploit' our queen's placement on the same diagonal as his bishop. Well, soon enough, he'll find himself on the wrong end of the food chain :)} 6. exd5 {It turns out there's nothing to fear, since the opening of the h1-a8 diagonal benefits White!} Nxd5 (6... exd5 7. O-O-O {transposes to a line we covered before. The text move is the only sensible alternative, but it leaves Black's knight in an awkward pin.}) 7. Bc4 $1 {A powerful resource, tying Black down completely. The f8-bishop is unable to move since the g7-pawn would hang after an exchange on d5, while the b8-knight will obstruct the defence of the d5-knight from either c6 or d7. Lastly, there is no good 'discovered attack' with the d5-knight since we'd simply take on b7. At this point, there's no doubt the hunter has become the hunted prey!} c6 ({A sad move, but there's nothing better actually. For example,} 7... Bc6 {can be met with} 8. Qg3 $1 {, pressurizing the g7-pawn while clearing the f3-square for our other knight.}) 8. O-O-O Nd7 9. Qg3 {White's pieces are excellently developed and coordinate very well. Next, we'll play Re1 followed by f4-f5, blasting open the e-file and getting to that sitting duck on e8. Black is unable to castle kingside due to the threats to the g7-pawn, while the b7-bishop looks no better than a glorified pawn. To conclude, 5...d5 looks like a premature opening of the centre and we can refute it with energetic play.} *

