lack is fighting for control of the d4 square as well as gaining space on the queenside. His next moves will likely be Nc6 and a6.} 6. O-O-O {We see no reason to delay this natural move. We have two basic plans here: Nge2 followed by d4, and g4-g5.} Nc6 {Black threatens to jump his knight onto the juicy d4 square and dislodge our queen. However, the drawback is that we can play} 7. e5 $146 {An obvious and strong improvement to Gelashvili - Ehlvest. Our queen proves its worth on f3, pinning the c6-knight and thus not allowing ...Nxe5. Black's well-placed horse on f6 must move now, granting us the initiative. The sole drawback of the text move is that the e5-pawn is a potential weakness in the long term, but for now, it is doing an excellent job of cramping Black's pieces.} Ng8 ({Not the most pleasant move to make but there is no other good option for Black. For example,} 7... Na5 $2 8. Qf4 Nd5 {is met by} 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Ne2 $1 {and Black is too undeveloped to face d2-d4.}) 8. Ne4 {Activating our knight and protecting the important e5-pawn. It's quite hard to suggest a good plan for Black to develop his kingside given our space advantage. Meanwhile, White has many plans, like Nd6+, Qf4, Nf3 and possibly d4. It cannot be ruled out that we'll cramp Black further with g4 and h4 as well! We'll show you a sample line to demonstrate the ideas we have here!} Nh6 {The best way to get Black's kingside developed. His knight is on a journey to reach d4, while the f8-bishop will come to e7.} 9. Qf4 Z0 ({A prophylactic idea, ensuring that ...Nf5 and ... Nfd4 won't come with a tempo. Moreover, we overprotect the e5-pawn and clear the f3-square for our king's knight to stand on. Re1 is a potentially good idea, while g4 is also possible, taking away the f5 square for Black's knight on the rim. The game may proceed with} 9... Nf5 {Black's threat is surprisingly Nce7-g6 to force our queen elsewhere! We can meet it with the strong} 10. h4 $1 {, preparing h5 and g4 and Black is having extreme difficulties developing his kingside. A gorgeous line discovered by Stockfish is} Be7 $2 11. g4 $1 Nxh4 12. Rxh4 $1 {a bombshell!} g5 13. Qf3 gxh4 {is forced, and now} 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 Rg8 16. Nh3 $1 {followed by Bd3-xh7, Re1 and g5 would give White overwhelming compensation for the exchange. Nice stuff!}) *

