6 '! This is the critical tabiya of the Copycat variation, from which we'll analyse two moves. Grab your popcorn and watch in delight as Black's kingdom falls apart everywhere!} Nf6 ({Firstly, we'd like to mention briefly that} 4... d5 $6 {fails to} 5. exd5 exd5 6. Qe2+ $1 {and Black's coordination is disrupted. There are a lot of details to gain an advantage with White though, and we don't feel it's practical to learn all of them given the rarity of that sideline. With the text move, Black hits the e4-pawn and it's not so convenient to defend it with pawn moves, while 5.Bd3 or 5.Qe2 would block our future development. This concept was played recently by Wesley So against none other than Magnus Carlsen in a game that starts with the unusual move order 1.b3 b6 2.e4 Bb7 . At this point, 5.e5 Nd5 is the mainline, a possible continuation being 6.Nxd5 Bxd5 7.Qg4 h5!? with highly unclear play in Carlsen, M - So, W, Meltwater Tour Final 2021. What we will be proposing instead is a rare but venomous continuation, let's see it!}) 5. Qf3 $5 {According to our database, this move is a theoretical novelty. Despite the peculiar appearance, it does protect the e4-pawn and is a challenging option due to: - We may transpose to the 4...d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Qf3!? variation as covered previously. - The queen often exerts uncomfortable pressure down the long diagonal while not blocking the f1-bishop. Moreover, Her Majesty supports g4-g5 to dislodge the black knight. - We are now ready to castle queenside! What a multipurpose move! Pretending Black does nothing, we'll play O-O-O and take the whole centre with d4. Black has several playable continuations here, but to our eyes, the most natural ones are 5...c5 and 5...d5 , fighting for the centah!} c5 {Stockfish's favourite move and there are suddenly many games in the database. The reason is that now we've transposed into a sideline of the Sicilian! It starts with 1.e4 c5 2.b3 b6 3.Bb2 Bb7 4.Nc3 e6 5.Qf3 Nf6 and we're back in this position! Black is fighting for control of the d4 square as well as gaining space on the queenside. His next moves will likely be Nc6 and a6.} 6. O-O-O {We see no reason to delay this natural move. We have two basic plans here: Nge2 followed by d4, and g4-g5.} a6 {The most popular move in practice, played by Alberto David and Saric. Along with covering the sensitive b5 square, he is threatening ...b5-b4 to push our knight back, win the e4-pawn and enforce ...d5. However, it is too slow a plan in the 21st century, with the chance of succeeding equal to the chance the French Defence gets refuted :) Indeed, our silicon friends insist that White is better at high depths. However, you can't refute a line with a sarcastic evaluation. You've got to do it with concrete moves, and the powerful idea that guarantees White a strong initiative is} 7. g4 $1 {The g-pawn steps up and kicks off the battle. The strong and hard-to-stop threat is g4-g5, driving the knight back to the sad g8 square. Later, we may even support Garry with Huy the h-pawn via h2-h4, while our kingside pieces will come out with Bg2 and Nge2. The queen is well placed on f3 to prevent d7-d5 but in the future, Her Majesty may sidestep to pave the way for the launch of Freddie the f-pawn. Oh, we haven't forgotten Black's plan of b5-b4. However, let us remind you that it is too slow, while our kingside expansion will be as fast as an F1 racing car. Given the non-forcing nature of the position, Black has several possibilities here. We hope you'll not object to our decision of giving one trainable and the alternatives as clickable.} b5 ({Continuing to expand on the queenside and threatening ...b4, forcing us to react immediately. Apart from the text move, Black has a wide choice of moves. Here is a brief summary of our analysis: A)} 7... Nc6 8. g5 $1 Ng8 9. h4 {gives White a strong initiative on the kingside with Nge2, Qe3/g3 and f4 to follow. Clearly, Black is not advised to move his knight back to the original square! B) 7...d6 is a relevant move as it was played by Nevednichy, a strong grandmaster. It appears that his idea is to make a square for the knight on d7, but after Paichadze's 8.g5 Nfd7 9.Qe3! White had a typical position for this variation. Black is slow in development while we're preparing Nf3, h4 and even f4-f5! to blow up Black's position. C) 7...d5 follows the rule of striking back in the centre while your opponent plays on the flank. The only problem is that Black is caught in a horrible pin after 8.exd5 Nxd5 9.Bg2! and it's really hard to untangle his pieces. We'll follow up with Nge2 and if Black castles kingside, g5 (even as a pawn sac!) and Rhg1 would follow. A brutal attacking scenario! Note that Ne4 is often a good resource, releasing the tension on the d5-knight and bringing one more piece to the kingside.}) 8. g5 {The knight is a 'persona non grata' on the f6-square...} Ng8 {...so it is shamefully departed to the original square!} 9. Qe3 {On this active square, the queen protects the g5-pawn as well as prepares f4. Moreover, it's harder than ever for the evil dark knight on g8 to get back into the game given White's queen pressure on the c5-pawn.} Nc6 10. f4 Qc7 11. Nf3 $16 Z0 ({The knight is just excellently placed here. Next, White will follow up with Kb1 and a4! is a powerful resource, saying that Black's a6+b5 plan has done nothing other than give us a hook. White is clearly better with an overwhelming space advantage, superior development and better pieces! A sample line is} 11... O-O-O 12. a4 $1 b4 13. Ne2 {note that we'll reply to ...d5 with an exchange followed by d4, blockading.} Kb8 14. Bg2 {and with d4 to follow, Black is going to be outnumbered on the queenside and in the centre.}) *

