{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 b6 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) {The Copycat variation, championed by John Watson in his legendary book 'Play the French' - a should-have manual for aspiring French players. Black wants to prove that our e4-pawn is a liability by hitting it with Bb7. However, Black does not fight for the centre directly and we can often seize it ourselves with d4 - although objectively speaking we should have done so on the 2nd move ;). We're proud to announce we've found many bright ideas over previous theory (Watson's book for example), and the ideas are as original as they can be.} 3. Bb2 {The point of our previous move. Need we add some more explanations?} Bb7 {No choice for Black either. He threatens the e4-pawn, and now there is more than one way to protect it. We recommend the most logical one, which is} 4. Nc3 {and the pawn is well protected. First of all, we would like to push d2-d4, which is why the various moves Black has tried in this position are directed against it. Secondly, there are also ideas to move our queen and pave the way for queenside castling. The e4-pawn does an awesome job of restricting the poor bishop on b7! In the Owen ( 1.e4 b6 ), it's true that the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop is not the most convenient of ways to gain an edge. However, it's certainly quite a venomous one against the opening that Kramnik considered to be 'no better than 1.e4 a6 '! This is the critical tabiya of the Copycat variation, from which we'll analyse two moves. Grab your popcorn and watch in delight as Black's kingdom falls apart everywhere!} c5 5. d4 $1 ({The Sicilianesque option, taking control of the d4-square. Black is preparing Nc6 to grip d4 further and Nf6 to hit the e4-pawn. It's worth mentioning that} 5. Nf3 {would transpose to some sort of Anti-Sicilians with b3; however, transpositions to explored grounds aren't what we look for! In the ChessBase Database there are roughly 400 games that have reached this position. To cut it short, after our next move the number decreases to a mere 10 games.}) {An energetic and principled reaction, challenging Black's foothold in the centre. We'll recapture the d4-pawn with our queen, thus paving the way for queenside castling. An important difference compared to 2.Nf3 e6 3.b3 lines in the Sicilian is that our f-pawn is free to move forward, creating a ruckus in Black's camp. White often has a straightforward plan of attacking on the kingside, while the fianchettoed b2-bishop performs a great job of shielding our king. Our recommendation is very rare, but it is the first recommendation of Stockfish 16. Therefore, we expect it to gain popularity soon.} 5... cxd4 {Allowing d4-d5 is far from ideal since the b7-bishop would feel silly. The text move is almost forced from a positional point of view.} 6. Qxd4 {We'll castle queenside in the near future. Meanwhile, Black is having a difficult time freeing his kingside. The dark-squared bishop can't move yet due to our pressure on the g7-pawn, while ...Nf6 often runs into the powerful e4-e5 thrust. Against ...Nc6, we'll retreat the queen to e3, keeping the possibility of e5 while preparing to switch the queen to g3, pressurising the g7-pawn. To summarise, Black is facing minor problems as early as the 6th move regarding development.} Nf6 {Black safeguards the g7-pawn and prepares the development of his king's bishop.} 7. O-O-O ({Safety for the king, activity for the rook! We like this approach best, developing one more piece before committing to anything in the centre.} 7. e5 $5 {is the sharpest approach, forcing both sides to play very precisely. The best line continues} Nc6 8. Qf4 $1 Nh5 $1 9. Qg4 g6 10. Nf3 {(note that 10.Ne4? fails to 10...Bb4+ ) 10...f5! with level chances. In our opinion, the text move is more thematic and also easier to learn.}) 7... Bc5 ({Hitting our queen with tempo and opening the route for castling. Besides the text move, there are also some alternatives for Black that we shall consider: A)} 7... Nc6 8. Qe3 {transposes to 6...Nc6, as covered here [/variation/22844367]. B) 7...Be7 is way too slow, and the refutation is 8.e5! Nc6 9.Qf4 Nh5 10.Qg4 g6 and now White has 11.Ne4! , a resource that is not available in the 7. e5 variation. White has full control of the weak dark squares around Black's king. After the text move, it appears our life is grim: the f2-pawn and the e4-pawn cannot both be defended. It's much more important to protect the e4-pawn, since Black cannot get away with snatching on f2 anyway.}) 8. Qd3 $1 Bxf2 $2 ({A nice retreat, maintaining contact with the e4-pawn. Moreover, Qg3 is on the agenda. A sample line is} 8... O-O 9. Qg3 $1 {, and the exchanges on e4 will result in an embarrassing mate on g7. Black better respects our Horwitz bishop and follows up with} Nc6 {, when} 10. e5 $1 Nh5 11. Qg4 {followed by Nf3 gives us a strong initiative. We can go deeper to prove how White shall exploit the glaring holes around Black's king, but we think it's enough to say that the f2-pawn is irrelevant, and we'll follow up with Ne4 and Kb1.}) {The supposedly critical reply, eating the poisoned apple. It's instructive to see how we should refute such greediness.} 9. e5 $1 {Chasing the well-placed knight as well as clearing the e4 square for our horsey.} Nd5 (9... Ng4 {meets a similar fate:} 10. Ne4 $1 Bc5 11. Nxc5 {followed by Qg3, and Black is bamboozled.}) 10. Ne4 {Eyeing the d6-square while threatening the f2-bishop, things look like a knightmare for Black.} Bc5 11. Qg3 $16 {White is completely dominating despite the one-pawn deficit (which is not even felt in this position!). The threat of Qxg7 must be stopped, and in case Black castles, we'll proceed with Nh3 followed by a timely Nf6+ stroke. For the record, Stockfish evaluates our advantage as +2, and in practice, White's attack should play itself.} *

