6 '! This is the critical tabiya of the Copycat variation, from which we'll analyse two moves. Grab your popcorn and watch in delight as Black's kingdom falls apart everywhere!} c5 5. d4 $1 ({The Sicilianesque option, taking control of the d4-square. Black is preparing Nc6 to grip d4 further and Nf6 to hit the e4-pawn. It's worth mentioning that} 5. Nf3 {would transpose to some sort of Anti-Sicilians with b3; however, transpositions to explored grounds aren't what we look for! In the ChessBase Database there are roughly 400 games that have reached this position. To cut it short, after our next move the number decreases to a mere 10 games.}) {An energetic and principled reaction, challenging Black's foothold in the centre. We'll recapture the d4-pawn with our queen, thus paving the way for queenside castling. An important difference compared to 2.Nf3 e6 3.b3 lines in the Sicilian is that our f-pawn is free to move forward, creating a ruckus in Black's camp. White often has a straightforward plan of attacking on the kingside, while the fianchettoed b2-bishop performs a great job of shielding our king. Our recommendation is very rare, but it is the first recommendation of Stockfish 16. Therefore, we expect it to gain popularity soon.} 5... cxd4 {Allowing d4-d5 is far from ideal since the b7-bishop would feel silly. The text move is almost forced from a positional point of view.} 6. Qxd4 {We'll castle queenside in the near future. Meanwhile, Black is having a difficult time freeing his kingside. The dark-squared bishop can't move yet due to our pressure on the g7-pawn, while ...Nf6 often runs into the powerful e4-e5 thrust. Against ...Nc6, we'll retreat the queen to e3, keeping the possibility of e5 while preparing to switch the queen to g3, pressurising the g7-pawn. To summarise, Black is facing minor problems as early as the 6th move regarding development.} Nc6 ({A tad more accurate than} 6... Nf6 {, since Black forces us to reveal the destination of our queen immediately.}) 7. Qe3 {This move should come as no surprise if you've read our detailed notes above! Let us repeat: the queen is very useful here, having access to g3 and supporting e4-e5.} Nf6 ({There's simply nothing more natural on earth:} 7... Bc5 $6 8. Qg3 $1 {followed by the f4+e5 combo will seal the deal in White's favour.}) 8. O-O-O {After all, White has successfully managed to castle queenside! Black's life will be uneasy with e4-e5 as a constant worry. We can often prepare that break with f4, while Kb1 is a useful prophylactic move. It's also worth noting that Nd5 is often an attractive idea as well. This structure resembles the Sicilian more than the French, and with the super Dragon bishop on b2 fulfilling both attacking and defensive roles, White will be much faster in the attacking race. We believe this is a good enough point to stop, since our following play will be relatively intuitive and natural. However, during analysis, an astonishing idea was found by the engine, and we'd like to show it!} Rc8 9. e5 $1 {Dropping a huge bomb on the board! It appears that we're losing a pawn after the obvious fork on g4; however, things are more sophisticated. White's idea is to lure one of Black's knights to e5, where it will be a huge target!} Ng4 ({Black must go down the rabbit hole, since} 9... Nh5 {fails to} 10. Kb1 $1 {avoiding a potential check on g5, which would be the case after 10.g4? Bc5! . Now we're threatening g2-g4 to trap the knight, and 10...Bc5 11.Qf3! would leave Black busted. The text move is the critical reaction, forking our queen and the e5-pawn, thus temporarily winning a pawn.}) 10. Qg3 {The queen is sound and safe on the g3-square, where it cannot be attacked by Black's evil forces.} Ngxe5 11. f4 {Freddie let's go! Black's knight is well placed on e5, so we chase it back and prepare f4-f5 to open the e-file, where Black's king is like a sitting duck waiting to be shot at.} Ng6 12. f5 Z0 ({The culmination of our conception. We'll have tremendous play no matter how many pawns we sacrificed. Our pieces coordinate wonderfully, and Black struggles to get his king to safety. Let us show a few lines: A)} 12... exf5 {allows} 13. h4 $1 {followed by h4-h5-h6 and Re1+. Black's knight must run for his life! B)}) (12... Nh4 {is suggested as the most resilient by the engine, but it weakens the king's protection. We can exploit this with} 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Be2 $1 {followed by a jarring check on h5. Opening the long diagonal with ...g6 would be extremely risky due to the Horwitz bishop's influence.}) *

