{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 c5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) 3. Bb2 ({Black grabs his share in the centre and offers White a transposition to an Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Nf3 {. We believe that objectively,}) (3. Nf3 {is the best move; but it wouldn't be wise for us to transpose into a theoretical branch of the Sicilian, which is well-explored already. Let's keep things in uncharted territory!}) ({Mobilising the Horwitz bishop with} 3. Bb2 {is the most logical. In this position, Black has tried} Nf6 {often, but 3...Nc6 is clearly the mainline (according to Lichess Database) and what we will focus on. There are a lot of transpositions here to keep in mind and we'll make sure to highlight them. For a start, 3...d5 is the second most popular move and it brings us to the 2...d5 3.Bb2 c5 variation, a chicken we've roasted in the 3rd move deviations chapter [/course/82991/8].}) 3... Nf6 4. e5 ({Attacking the e4-pawn and forcing} 4. e5 Nd5 {, a structure that is clearly better for White.}) 4... Nd5 {Black's knight is unstable on d5 - a timely c4 will force the horse to move for the third time. The structure is also suspicious for Black since there's a big hole on d6 we can exploit. If Black frees himself with ...d6, our Horwitz bishop would become a blazing gun. Almost any sensible move gives White a nice edge here, including our recommendation.} 5. g3 {The long diagonal is the optimal place for the light-squared bishop to exert pressure on Black's position. We'll follow-up with Bg2 and Nf3, taking control of the game. 5.Nc3 , 5.Nf3 and 5.c4 are good alternatives as well. We feel that our approach is the most solid while also packing a punch.} Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O $14 Z0 ({The e5-pawn is an annoying thorn in Black's position, preventing him from activating his pieces. Therefore, we should maintain a grip on the e5 square with Re1 and even Na3-c4. If Black doesn't act fast, we can drive the d5-knight away with c4, followed by d4, taking the initiative. White has a comfortable advantage, as illustrated by the following lines: A)} 8... f6 {is rather risky because of} 9. c4 Nc7 10. d4 $1 {and the opening of the position favours White since we have two powerful bishops. B)}) (8... d6 {is most popular when} 9. Re1 {is simple and good. Following exchanges on e5, our light-squared bishop is clearly better than its restricted counterpart.}) *

