{We're arriving at the deep end... This chapter covers all of Black's alternatives to 2. b3 d5. Although these rare lines do not appear that often in practice, it's useful to have an idea of how to counter them.} 1. e4 e6 2. b3 c5 ({We will take a look at four moves in this chapter:} 2... Qf6 {,}) (2... Nf6 {,}) (2... b6 {and}) (2... c5 {. Some of them are garbage chess while others are more logical attempts to create a tense fight. We are confident that the readers will be able to deal with moves like}) (2... a6 {,}) (2... c6 {,}) (2... h6 {and other similar, funny-looking 'variations' at the board by themselves. Don't let us down!}) 3. Bb2 ({Black grabs his share in the centre and offers White a transposition to an Anti-Sicilian with} 3. Nf3 {. We believe that objectively,}) (3. Nf3 {is the best move; but it wouldn't be wise for us to transpose into a theoretical branch of the Sicilian, which is well-explored already. Let's keep things in uncharted territory!}) ({Mobilising the Horwitz bishop with} 3. Bb2 {is the most logical. In this position, Black has tried} Nf6 {often, but 3...Nc6 is clearly the mainline (according to Lichess Database) and what we will focus on. There are a lot of transpositions here to keep in mind and we'll make sure to highlight them. For a start, 3...d5 is the second most popular move and it brings us to the 2...d5 3.Bb2 c5 variation, a chicken we've roasted in the 3rd move deviations chapter [/course/82991/8].}) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 $5 ({Black controls the important d4 square, thus making the d4 break ineffective for us. Over 1300 games have reached this critical tabiya, and the majority of white players are headed for} 4. Nf3 {, moving to Sicilian waters. We have something different up our sleeve!}) 4... Nf6 $6 ({Creating the lethal positional threat of Bxc6, which seems to be tolerated by Black players all the time!} 4... a6 $2 {is surprisingly the most popular move, and we will demonstrate the punishment. Our recommendation has happened in only 15% of the games, so there's a high chance your opponents will be out of book here, even if 2. b3 didn't surprise them. The drawback of 4.Bb5 compared to 4.Nf3 is that Black has 4...Nd4! available, forcing White to move the bishop again. An observation is that in the first four moves of the game we have broken two classical opening principles: 'Occupy the centre with pawns' and 'knights before bishops'. However, in the 21st century, even the Bongcloud and 1.e4 g5 stuff has entered the rank of legendary openings, so we can chill :)}) ({This isn't a huge improvement on the} 4... a6 {line we've just covered. Black unwisely allows his pawns to be doubled.}) 5. Bxc6 $1 {We take the opportunity to punish Black for his positional sins.} bxc6 ({The lesser evil.} 5... dxc6 $6 6. Qe2 $1 {would be even worse for the second player, since both diagonals for the c8-bishop are occupied by Black's pawns. Here, we may continue with 6.d3 with a clear advantage due to the better structure. However, exploiting the fact that Black has played ...Nf6 instead of ...a6 compared to the previous line, we can do even better.}) 6. e5 $1 {Cutting across Black's position with the e5-pawn. Now, d6 is a weak square and a potential outpost for our knights.} Nd5 7. d3 $16 {Preparing Nd2-c4, Ngf3, Qe2 and we can choose to castle on the kingside or queenside. Black's structure is a horrible image - the c5-pawn is easily attacked by our pieces and can't be easily defended by another pawn. Counterplay with ...a5 will be stopped in the tracks with a4, so to open up the position, Black has to try ...d6 at some point, which will further weaken his dismal structure and activate the b2-bishop. To conclude, White has a large positional advantage.} *

