y 15% of the games, so there's a high chance your opponents will be out of book here, even if 2. b3 didn't surprise them. The drawback of 4.Bb5 compared to 4.Nf3 is that Black has 4...Nd4! available, forcing White to move the bishop again. An observation is that in the first four moves of the game we have broken two classical opening principles: 'Occupy the centre with pawns' and 'knights before bishops'. However, in the 21st century, even the Bongcloud and 1.e4 g5 stuff has entered the rank of legendary openings, so we can chill :)}) 5. Bd3 ({The most challenging option Black has, which appears frequently in master-level games but is not as popular in casual online chess. Black avoids the dangerous threat of Bxc6 and counter-attacks our b5-bishop.} 5. Bxd4 $6 {is ill-advised, since our Horwitz bishop is a great piece and shouldn't be exchanged for the knight like that. Therefore, we should retreat the bishop. This isn't a loss of time since we'll proceed with Nf3, gaining a tempo on Black's knight. The question is: where should we put the bishop?}) {It's most accurate to put the bishop on d3, where it's free from harassment. Our next move is certainly Nf3, challenging the strong and centralised knight. White scores 66% from a reasonable sample size (around 30 games) in the ChessBase Database, which is an encouraging result.} 5... Nf6 $6 ({A natural-looking move. However,} 5... Nf6 {is flawed because it doesn't address White's idea of Nf3. In the resulting positions, the knight is out of place and can be kicked away with e5.}) 6. Nf3 $1 Nxf3+ ({Challenging the dominant knight is White's main priority. Black has two options here:} 6... Nc6 {is an embarrassing retreat, while}) (6... Nxf3+ {further accelerates White's development. In both cases, we can be happy with a strong development lead.}) (6... Nc6 {allows} 7. e5 $1 Nd5 8. Be4 {with better chances for White. We have a strong development lead, a healthy pawn structure and can be happy.}) 7. Qxf3 d6 8. O-O $14 {We've developed both bishops and castled, while Black has only developed his knight. Next, we'll break through with e4-e5, opening both diagonals to Black's king. The queen's knight may travel through a3-c4 to reach e5, or just Nc3-e4 after the centre opens up. To sum up, White has a clear and comfortable advantage.} *

