y 15% of the games, so there's a high chance your opponents will be out of book here, even if 2. b3 didn't surprise them. The drawback of 4.Bb5 compared to 4.Nf3 is that Black has 4...Nd4! available, forcing White to move the bishop again. An observation is that in the first four moves of the game we have broken two classical opening principles: 'Occupy the centre with pawns' and 'knights before bishops'. However, in the 21st century, even the Bongcloud and 1.e4 g5 stuff has entered the rank of legendary openings, so we can chill :)}) 5. Bd3 ({The most challenging option Black has, which appears frequently in master-level games but is not as popular in casual online chess. Black avoids the dangerous threat of Bxc6 and counter-attacks our b5-bishop.} 5. Bxd4 $6 {is ill-advised, since our Horwitz bishop is a great piece and shouldn't be exchanged for the knight like that. Therefore, we should retreat the bishop. This isn't a loss of time since we'll proceed with Nf3, gaining a tempo on Black's knight. The question is: where should we put the bishop?}) {It's most accurate to put the bishop on d3, where it's free from harassment. Our next move is certainly Nf3, challenging the strong and centralised knight. White scores 66% from a reasonable sample size (around 30 games) in the ChessBase Database, which is an encouraging result.} 5... d5 $1 6. Nf3 ({The strongest move, taking a foothold in the centre. We looked at different options for White here, but were not satisfied by} 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Nf3 Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 d4 {, or}) (6. exd5 exd5 7. Bxd4 $5 {with dry equality. Let's challenge the d4-knight with our thematic move then!}) {Putting pressure on Black's proud horse. White has three troops in action, compared to the lonely knight on d4. In the ChessBase Database, only one game has reached this position, so we don't think it's likely that you will get this on the board. Therefore, we'll limit its coverage to a single trainable line.} 6... dxe4 ({The best move. Black should force our bishop to e4 and gain time on it with ...Nf6. Instead,} 6... Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 {just accelerates White's development.}) 7. Bxe4 Nf6 8. Nxd4 {Freeing the f3 square for our pieces. We don't mind losing the bishop pair at all.} Nxe4 (8... cxd4 9. Qf3 $1 {is our idea, hitting the b7-pawn. A nasty point is that} Nxe4 $2 10. Qxe4 {wins a pawn, thanks to} Bc5 11. Qe5 {.}) 9. Nf3 $13 {We like White's chances a lot here. Suddenly, it looks like a typical Open Horwitz position with Qe2, Nc3 and O-O-O coming! We don't have the bishop pair, but both of Black's bishops are passive. The position is dynamic and certainly playable for both sides. Conclusion: In this chapter, we've gone through everything Black can try apart from the mainline, 2. b3 d5. Among the alternatives, 2...c5!? has occurred frequently in practice and knowledge of this line will prove useful for you. For the sake of completeness, we've covered some funny lines as well at the beginning of the chapter. Hopefully they made you laugh! By the way, this just so happens to be the final variation of the course. Your time is limited and you can’t get it back, and we sincerely thank you for trusting us with some of that time. If you made it this far, you are among the elite, one of the world’s most knowledgeable in this wonderful opening. We’d love to hear from anyone who has put up with us for so long, so please do reach out! �} *

